<FIRST>r w PM-TaintedFood Bjt   01-19 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tainted Food, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Internal Report Hits Controls on Pesticides in Food</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: stands for PM-Farm Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal programs to curb illegally high amounts
of pesticides and other chemicals in the nation's meat supply have
been slipshod and sometimes allowed adulterated food to reach store
shelves, according to an internal audit.
   The report by the Agriculture Department's inspector general's
office said the department's inspection agency _ the Food Safety and
Inspection Service, or FSIS _ has little authority to prevent
pesticide residues from showing up in meat and poultry.
   Accordingly, FSIS has turned to the food industry itself for
cooperation in monitoring levels of chemicals and ferreting out
violations.
   But Agriculture Department investigators found that in some cases
meat and poultry containing too much of these chemical residues were
allowed into the consumer pipeline.
   ``Even when animals were presented to inspectors, (agency)
administrative controls and current policies did not ensure timely
and effective response when pesticide residue was suspected or found
in meat and poultry products,'' the report said. ``As a result, some
adulterated products were allowed to enter commerce.''
   The chief responsibility of FSIS is to ensure that USDA-inspected
meat and poultry products are safe, wholesome and free of
adulterating chemicals. As part of its responsibility, the agency
samples and analyzes edible tissues to see if they meet the federal
standards.
   But the system is far from foolproof, and the agency also
includes efforts to enlighten farmers and processors about the
federal standards and how to comply with them.
   The report, which was completed last November but not given wide
distribution by the department, said FSIS was ``unable to
successfully investigate pesticide violations in 79 percent of the
cases'' reviewed by the auditors. A violation was defined as an
illegal level of chemical residue found in a sample of meat or
poultry.
   Some of the reasons for the lack of success in investigating
violations included:
   _Tracing the illegal residue to the original producer was not
always successful.
   _Follow-up samples from suspected meat were seldom taken, or else
the suspected animals or carcasses were not always retained for
further checking.
   _Documentation of regulatory actions was insufficient.
   Starting in June 1986, when a company signed a memorandum of
understanding with FSIS, it agreed to upgrade its own quality
control procedures, was exempted from routine monitoring by the
agency and placed under a less-intensive monitoring program.
   ``In addition, these companies became eligible to make certain
claims on their product labels concerning (chemical) residue levels
or superior quality control procedures,'' the report said.
   By 1988, this ``verified production control'' program included 11
companies and 34 slaughter plants out of a U.S. total of 1,800
plants. The participating plants had an annual slaughter of about 5
billion pounds, or about 8 percent of all animals slaughtered last
year.
   In all, the agency is responsible for inspection in more than
7,000 meat and poultry slaughter and processing plants.
   The USDA investigators visited 96 federally inspected meat and
poultry plants and conducted research at the agency's national
office, three regional offices, three field laboratories and five
USDA-accredited laboratories.
   One of the major problems uncovered was in identification of the
original farmer, feedlot operator or other livestock producer that
have been found to be in violation of the federal residue levels.
   Investigators found that FSIS was unable to locate producers in
12 of 28 pesticide violation cases reviewed.
   In one case, regional office personnel did not act on all the
information that was available, not even when tags on a 6-year-old
cow provided information on the name of the livestock auction market
where the cow was sold.
   The agency contacted the auction market and was told cow's
previous owner was unknown, so the case was closed, the report said.
Federal regulations, administered by another USDA agency, the Animal
and Plant Health Inspection Service, require such cows to be
identified and records maintained.
   But FSIS ``made no attempt to contact'' the other agency, and the
regional official in charge of residues said that staff people
didn't take time to check further.
   The report recommended that the agency seek legislation for
mandatory identification of the source of all animal species
slaughtered for domestic food consumption. However, FSIS responded
that such a move should be directed to policy-makers, not the
regulatory agency itself.
   Lester M. Crawford, FSIS administrator, said that historically
the agency has pursued animal identification as a related part of
the residue testing program.
   ``We recently were successful in obtaining a swine identification
program outside of the legislative route, and would strongly support
similar identification for the other species which come under our
jurisdiction,'' Crawford said in a response to the report.
</TEXT>
