<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Cabinet-1stAdd     01-19 1108</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Cabinet - 1st Add,1151</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Hebert</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, the only black in Bush's Cabinet, brings
to HHS a long-time desire to improve health care for the poor.
Sullivan has focused his efforts as president of the Morehouse
School of Medicine in Atlanta on training doctors, especially
minorities, who are willing to establish family practices in rural
and inner-city areas.
   The 55-year-old doctor is a personal friend of Bush and his wife,
Barbara, who was named to the medical school's board of trustees in
1983.
   Sullivan's selection was nearly derailed after he was quoted in
an Atlanta newspaper as saying he supported a woman's right to seek
an abortion, though he opposed federal funding for the procedure.
   His statement inflamed anti-abortion groups and he later said he
opposed abortion in all cases except in cases of rape, incest and
when the mother's life is in danger, mirroring Bush's view.
   Since the abortion flap, Sullivan has said little about his
priorities for HHS, the largest of all the federal departments. HHS
includes Medicaid, Medicare and Social Security as well as the
Public Health Service and the Food and Drug Administration.
   Sullivan graduated with honors both from Morehouse College in
1954 and Boston University Medical School in 1958. He has taught
medicine at Harvard, Morehouse, the New Jersey College of Medicine
and Boston University.
   In the 1970s, Sullivan worked to establish the Morehouse medical
school and when it separated from Morehouse College in 1981, he
became president. It is one of the three predominantly black medical
schools in the country.
   _By Deborah Mesce
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENERGY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The top issue on James D. Watkins' agenda as energy
secretary-designate _ repairing and cleaning up the nation's nuclear
defense plants _ is one for which his military background gives him
special preparation.
   Watkins, 61, studied nuclear reactor engineering in 1958 at the
Oak Ridge, Tenn., National Laboratory. He taught at naval nuclear
training centers in 1960, and four years later took command of the
nuclear-power attack submarine Snook.
   The Oak Ridge lab is one link in the Energy Department's
nationwide network of nuclear weapons plants. The system has been
crippled recently by safety and technical problems that forced the
shutdown of the only reactors that make tritium, a radioactive gas
vital to the production of nuclear warheads.
   Watkins capped a 41-year Navy career with a four-year stint as
chief of naval operations, the service's top job. He retired in 1986.
   In October 1987, Watkins took over as chairman of the
presidential commission on AIDS that recommended legislation to
prohibit discrimination against victims of the deadly disease.
   Watkins graduated from the Naval Academy at Annapolis, Md., in
1949, earned a master's degree at the Naval postgraduate school and
then decided to specialize in nuclear submarines.
   Watkins was a protege of the late Adm. Hyman Rickover, the father
of the modern nuclear Navy. He became commander of the Pacific
Fleet, based in Honolulu, and in March 1982 was named chief of naval
operations by President Reagan.
   _By Robert Burns
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DRUG CZAR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Early in William J. Bennett's tenure as secretary of education,
the National Education Association asked him what he would do if he
had a magic wand to wave over American schools.
   ``No drugs _ none, zero, out, gone, disappear,'' replied the
blunt-spoken educator.
   As Bush's choice to be the nation's first drug czar, it will fall
to Bennett to find a way to win the war on drugs.
   Bennett, 45, was a headline-grabbing education secretary who
railed against rising college costs and slipshod standards. He also
spoke out on topics from defense of Western civilization courses to
AIDS.
   He left Reagan's Cabinet in September to write, open a small
policy shop called the Madison Center, and deliver lectures at
reported fees of up to $15,000-per-appearance.
   Bennett obtained a Ph.D in philosophy from the University of
Texas at Austin and a law degree from Harvard. He taught at several
campuses and eventually ran the National Humanities Center in
Research Triangle Park, N.C.
   _By Christopher Connell
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. TRADE REPRESENTATIVE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carla Hills won swift praise when she was named as the nation's
top trade negotiator. But there also was grumbling.
   ``I had hoped that we'd have someone from the business world who
had extensive international experience,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, said after the 54-year-old Washington lawyer was named U.S.
trade representative.
   But Hills' fans say she is fully up to whatever comes her way.
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., calls her ``a tough negotiator'' and
Clayton Yeutter, the outgoing trade representative, praised her
``strong international background.''
   Hills has been underestimated before.
   Her 1975 nomination by President Ford as secretary of housing and
urban development quickly came under fire.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., groused that experience is too
seldom valued in the nation's capital, chortling that the Washington
Redskins had once lost 16 yards on a play devised by Richard M.
Nixon.
   ``I can promise you that I won't be sending in any football
plays,'' Hills shot back. She went on to win wide plaudits in the
post.
   She graduated with honors from Stanford, where she captained the
tennis team, and was 20th in her class of 167 at Yale Law School.
She served as an assistant attorney general for a year in the Ford
administration and has practiced law in Los Angeles, where she
co-founded her own law firm.
   _By Mike Robinson
</TEXT>
<NOTE>COMMERCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oilman Robert A. Mosbacher Sr. takes over the Commerce
Department without any government experience but pledging to keep
communication between Washington and the business community ``open
and continuing and even building.''
   Bush turned to a longtime friend and stalwart GOP fund-raiser in
selecting Mosbacher to round out his economic team, saying the
61-year-old businessman would ``bring his tremendous energies to the
task of promoting U.S. exports abroad.''
   Mosbacher has raised money for the president-elect in every
campaign since Bush ran unsuccessfully for the Senate in 1970.
   Mosbacher, whose fortune in oil, real estate and ranching is
estimated at more than $200 million, founded Mosbacher Energy Co.
and is an avid sailor in his off-hours.
   He amassed his fortune after leaving his home in White Plains,
N.Y., in 1948 at age 21 to make his way in Texas. He first met Bush,
who also ventured out from New England to Texas as a young man, in
the late 1950s.
   Mosbacher's primary responsibilities at Commerce will include
work on opening foreign markets to U.S. goods, administering the new
U.S.-Canada free trade agreement and presiding over the 1990
national census.
   Mosbacher received a bachelor's degree in economics from
Washington and Lee University in 1947.
   _By Nancy Benac
</TEXT>
