<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Cabinet-4thAdd     01-19 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Cabinet - 4th Add,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Brumley</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGRICULTURE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Clayton Yeutter, Bush's designated new agriculture secretary,
moves to his new job after serving 3{ years as the U.S. trade
representative where he was the nation's No. 1 negotiator on
agricultural and other international trade issues.
   He is widely respected for his aggressive push to make foreign
markets more open to U.S. products and for his ability to soften
harsh protectionist legislation in Congress.
   Yeutter, who grew up on a farm in Nebraska and still manages
2,500 acres of property near the town of Cozad, served in the Nixon
and Ford administrations as an assistant secretary of agriculture,
running some of the regulatory programs.
   President Reagan considered Yeutter, 58, for the position of
agriculture secretary in 1980, but he was passed over because of
objections from some members of Congress. He was later named trade
representative.
   Yeutter, a man who runs on very little sleep and always appears
affable, will oversee the fight with the European Economic Community
over U.S. demands that subsidies be eliminated.
   _By Joan Mower
</TEXT>
<NOTE>VETERANS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Edward J. Derwinski will be the first head of the Department of
Veterans Affairs, which Congress has upgraded to the level of a
Cabinet job.
   A Chicago native, Derwinski served in the Army in the Pacific
during World War II. He was a member of Congress from 1959 until
1983. Although he did not serve on any veterans committees,
Derwinski, 62, brings to his new job vast experience on Capitol Hill.
   After leaving Congress, Derwinski garnered foreign policy
experience, serving first as the counselor of the State Department
and a special adviser to the secretary of state. He later became
undersecretary of state for security assistance, science the
technology, a post he assumed in April 1987.
   Derwinski is known for his trademark crew cut and loud
sportscoats and for his puckish humor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OFFICE OF MANAGEMENT AND BUDGET</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Darman, the wealthy son of an industrialist with
undergraduate and graduate degrees from Harvard, has spent much of
his career in the bureaurcratic trenches. From 1970 until 1977, he
served in the Nixon and Ford administrations in policy positions in
the departments of defense, justice, commerce, state and health,
education and welfare.
   Darman, 45, entered the Reagan administration in 1981 as a top
aide to James A. Baker III, who was then the White House chief of
staff and is now Bush's choice for secretary of state. He followed
Baker to the Treasury Department when Baker moved there in 1985.
   At treasury, Darman was a key figure in developing a plan to
drive the value of the dollar lower as a way of reining in the huge
budget deficits.
   Known for his keen intellect and his political skills, Darman
resigned the No. 2 job at treasury in 1987 to take a position with
Shearson, Lehman Bros. investment banking division.
   Last summer, he joined the Bush campaign, serving as a stand-in
for Michael Dukakis during Bush's practice debates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
