<FIRST>u a AM-HallofFame 2ndLd-Writethru a0843 01-19 0972</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hall of Fame, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0843,0993</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Inducted Into Rock and Roll Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Jagger quotes; picks up 12th
graf pvs: `To be inducted ...; minor editing 13th graf, `The Rolling Stones'
..., to, conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's five inductees into the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame _ Dion, Otis Redding, the Rolling Stones, the
Temptations and Stevie Wonder _ are a gathering of the soulful side
of the '60s.
   ``Tonight we're all on our best behavior,'' said the Stones' lead
singer, Mick Jagger. ``And we're being rewarded for 25 years of bad
behavior.''
   Jagger was among four present and former Stones who attended
formal induction ceremonies Wednesday night at the Waldorf-Astoria,
where the three previous induction banquets have been held.
   ``I got in! I got in!'' an exuberant Dion exclaimed. ``This is a
major moment for me. I'm conscious and breathing and right here with
you and enjoying every minute.''
   Dion said music to him was a way to ``share my feelings, love,
hates, thoughts, perceptions. It is a way of connecting.''
   Pete Townsend, who presented the award to the Rolling Stones,
said the Stones had influenced his own British band, The Who.
   ``The Stones were a rock band to begin with. The Who became a
rock band partly because of the Stones,'' Townsend said.
   He dismissed suggestions that the Stones are outdated.
   ``I think the debate between Mick and Keith (Richards) is the
same debate we're (The Who) having _ are we capable of doing
anything new of consequence? Whether the Stones do anything new
doesn't matter to me. They have a fantastic collection of stuff.''
   Jagger and Richards, who have fallen out in recent times,
attended the ceremonies along with ex-Stone Mick Taylor and his
replacement, Ron Wood.
   In accepting the award, Jagger hinted that there may be more
Rolling Stones music to come.
   ``Jean Cocteau said Americans are a funny people,'' Jagger said.
``First you shock them, then they put you in a museum. We're not
quite ready to hang up the number yet.''
   Right now, the 20 artists or groups named to the Hall of Fame
since 1986 are honorees without a home _ ground has not yet been
broken for the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame archives and museum in
Cleveland, scheduled to open in 1992.
   ``I hope they can get down to building the phantom temple of
rock,'' Jagger said.
   David Ruffin, former lead singer with the Temptations, said he
will always consider himself a part of the group.
   ``That's something I'm very proud of _ to have been a part of the
group and I always will be,'' Ruffin said.
   To be inducted, artists must have recorded more than 25 years
ago. All of this year's fourth honored group had records released
before Jan. 1, 1964. They were elected by more than 150 performers,
producers, writers, record executives and broadcasters for their
contributions to, or influence on, the course of rock 'n' roll.
   The Rolling Stones' induction includes the original five members,
Jagger, Richards, the late Brian Jones, Bill Wyman and Charlie
Watts, plus Taylor who replaced Jones, Wood who replaced Taylor and
the late pianist-arranger Ian Stewart, who made an important
contribution to the group's sound. At the beginning, the Stones were
immersed in ``raunchy'' American blues and rhythm 'n' blues.
   The group went on to record songs by Jagger and Richards and had
major hits including ``Satisfaction,'' ``Jumpin' Jack Flash,''
``Street Fighting Man'' and ``Honky Tonk Women.'' They have been
hailed as the world's greatest rock 'n' roll band.
   The soul group the Temptations have original members Otis
Williams, Melvin Franklin, Eddie Kendricks, the late Paul Williams
and David Ruffin inducted, plus Dennis Edwards, who replaced Ruffin
in 1968. Later replacements are not included. The Temps' major
breakthrough was in 1965 with ``My Girl.'' Later hits include
``Cloud 9'' and ``Papa Was a Rolling Stone.''
   Stevie Wonder was born Steveland Morris Hardaway on May 13, 1950,
in Detroit. His first record, ``Fingertips, Part 2,'' became a hit
when he was just 13. Wonder, who was born blind, has written one
imaginative piece of music after another in his soulful, pop and
experimental concept albums. He opened for the Stones on their 1972
tour. His hits include ``My Cherie Amour'' and ``You Are the
Sunshine of My Life.''
   Soul singer Otis Redding was born Sept. 9, 1941, in Macon, Ga.,
and died in a plane crash on Dec. 10, 1967. He was traveling with
the group the Bar-Kays to save travel expenses, and the plane
crashed en route to Cleveland, killing everyone aboard. Redding had
interrupted his tour to cut a record which was in the mail to stores
when he died. It was ``(Sittin' on) the Dock of the Bay,'' his
biggest hit.
   Dion was born Don DiMucci on July 18, 1939, in New York City. He
and three friends formed a group in high school in 1958, taking the
name the Belmonts from a Bronx street. After recording such hits as
``A Teenager in Love,'' ``Where or When'' and ``In the Still of the
Night,'' Dion went solo. His biggest hit was ``Runaround Sue'' in
1961.
   The Hall of Fame also honored three early influences on rock 'n'
roll, the late blues singer Bessie Smith, the soft rhythm 'n' blues
vocal quartet the Ink Spots and the gospel singers the Soul Stirrers.
   Sam Cooke didn't change his style, just the type of lyrics, when
he went into secular singing in 1956 after six years singing lead
with the Soul Stirrers. He was replaced by Johnnie Taylor, who also
went on to soul stardom.
   Producer Phil Spector, famous for his ``wall of sound,'' is being
inducted in a non-performing category.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
