<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Eggs     01-19 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Eggs,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Rules For Safer Eggs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scare in Britain over food poisoning from eggs
has led Agriculture Minister John MacGregor to announce new controls
for the poultry industry that he said will be the world's strictest.
   Inspections of stockfeed plants will be doubled and plants with
contaminated premises will not be allowed to ship their feed, he
said Wednesday in a House of Commons written reply.
   MacGregor promised new laws to give greater control over imported
feed and British hatcheries and breeding flocks. Producers will have
to register and submit their flocks, products and premises to
regular bacteriological checks.
   MacGregor also announced a national campaign to educate the
public in food hygiene in the home ``to reduce the incidence of food
poisoning generally.''
   After reports that eggs had caused food poisoning, with
slaughterhouse waste used in stockfeed a possible suspect, junior
Health Minister Edwina Currie said most egg production was infected
by salmonella bacteria.
   Eggs sales slumped, farmers began killing chickens and Mrs.
Currie quit under fire on Dec. 16.
   The government promised farmers $34 million compensation and
launched a national advertising campaign to restore public
confidence in eating eggs.
   The government's chief medical officer, Sir Donald Acheson, said
last week that salmonella in eggs is still a serious health problem
but ``only a very few eggs are infected.''
</TEXT>
