<HEAD>Balkans' Meeting A Post-War First For Albania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since World War II,
Albania is playing host to a meeting of senior diplomats from the
six Balkan countries.
   Albania's holding of the three-day meeting of the countries'
deputy foreign ministers is widely seen as another strong indication
that the country is emerging from its long self-imposed isolation.
   The meeting, which opened Wednesday, was attended by
representatives from Bulgaria, Romania, Yugoslavia, Turkey, Greece
and Albania, the official Albanian news agency ATA said in a report
monitored in Vienna.
   The gathering comes a year after six Balkan foreign ministers
pledged in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, to boost economic cooperation and
work toward resolving ethnic disputes in the region.
