<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Jaywalkers     01-19 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jaywalkers,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Police Plan Jaywalking Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are going to crack down on pedestrians
who walk on the wild side.
   But the city's public safety chief, Glenn Cannon, isn't certain
how successful the new enforcement program will be, since jaywalking
``is almost like a birthright'' to many pedestrians.
   ``I don't think we're going to start locking people up for
jaywalking,'' said Cannon, who admitted Wednesday he has ignored a
crosswalk or two.
   ``Our efforts are aimed at education, not enforcement.''
   Cannon said he has ordered officers to issue warnings to
jaywalkers as part of a program to educate pedestrians that the
practice can be dangerous.
   Motorists who block intersections at traffic lights will be
issued written warnings, and the program will include tighter
enforcement of illegal parking violations.
   Violators could face fines of $32.50.
