<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-IranArmsArrest     01-19 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran Arms Arrest,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Charged with Conspiring to Sell Plane Parts to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTHAMPTON BEACH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two businessmen were arrested
Wednesday and charged with conspiring to sell spare parts for the
F-14 Tomcat fighter jet to Iran, the U.S. Customs Service said.
   George DeMar, 58, an independent pilot from East Quogue, and Paul
Amara of North Babylon, an aircraft parts broker, were accused of
negotiating with an undercover Customs agent posing as a
representative of Iran interested in buying spare parts for the
fighter, said Gary Hillberry, special agent-in-charge of Customs'
New York office.
   In exchange for $1 million, the men allegedly agreed to provide
the parts, a plane and pilot and pay the cost of shipping the parts.
   Hillberry said the undercover agent suggested shipping the parts
through Shannon, Ireland, to cover their trail.
   The men were arrested after the agent met with them Wednesday
morning at Suffolk County Airport in Westhampton Beach and verified
that the parts were on the plane.
   ``The plan was to take off today after we gave them a certain
amount of good-faith money,'' Hillberry said.
   Hillberry said the agent approached the men after the Customs
Service learned that they wanted to sell the parts, Hillberry said.
   ``They were interested in brokering the parts. We told them we
were Iranian representatives and they picked the ball up from
there,'' Hillberry said.
   The parts were originally purchased as surplus from the
manufacturer by a middleman, who, in turn, sold them to the men
arrested Wednesday, Hillberry said.
   The middleman was not involved in the scheme to sell the parts to
Iran, Hillberry said.
   Export of spare parts for the F-14 to Iran is illegal without a
license from the State Department, according to the Customs Service.
Moreover, Hillberry said, it is not possible to obtain such a
license because ``we're not dealing with Iran.''
   A complete inventory of the parts or the quantity involved was
not immediately available. Hillberry said the parts on the plane
included equipment for loading ammunition in the jet's 20mm canon
and hydraulic assemblies for the jet's landing gear.
   DeMar and Paul Amara were arrested at the airport, U.S. Attorney
Charles Rose said. They were arraigned in federal court in Brooklyn
on charges of conspiracy and violating the Arms Export Control Act.
   If convicted, they face fines of up to $250,000 and a maximum of
15 years in prison.
   Federal Magistrate Carol Amon released DeMar on $1 million
personal recognizance bond; Amara was released on $250,000 bond.
   Customs agents seized the twin-engine turboprop on which the
parts were loaded. Hillberry said the German-made Hansa plane was
capable of making the flight to Europe. He would not identify the
plane's owner, who he said was unaware of the scheme when he leased
the jet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
