<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Promising mayhem but no bodily injury,
magicians Penn and Teller are bringing their award-winning Broadway
show to Philadelphia, where they performed on the streets during the
late '70s.
   During what Penn Jillette described as ``the world's most
efficient press conference'' Wednesday, he said ``horrific'' things
would occur during the ``Penn and Teller'' show at the Shubert
Theater.
   While he spoke, Teller, his quiet partner of 14 years, was
submerged in a locked tank of water.
   The fast-talking Penn got a little carried away describing the
comedy team's ascent to fame and only took notice of the time when
Teller began banging on the glass tank, splashing reporters,
photographers and his partner.
   ``Time just flies by,'' Penn said as he glanced at his watch. He
assured the reporters, ``It's OK. There's a signal he would give if
he were reallly in trouble.''
   Penn opened the tank after a mere five minutes and 47 seconds had
elapsed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Carter and Jerry Ford say they don't know
why they got such bad press while in office and President Reagan has
played so well in the media.
   ``Presidents Nixon, Johnson, Ford and I had bad relations with
the press. Reagan had good relations,'' said Carter. ``Why, I don't
know.''
   The two former presidents took part in a discussion at Columbia
University on Wednesday on ``The Press, the Presidency and the First
Hundred Days.''
   Carter said he spent weeks trying to deflect attention from a
story that a ``killer rabbit'' had swum out to his boat as he was
fishing and that he had to beat it back with oars.
   ``How can you control something like that?'' Carter asked. The
rabbit story, he said, ``gave an image of an incompetent president
who could not even protect himself against a rabbit.''
   He said Ford ``was the best athlete ever in the White House'' but
he was dogged by stories about his supposed clumsiness. ``It hurt
him politically,'' Carter said.
   Ford said news people who accompanied him on ski trips to Vail
fell as much on the slopes as he did ``but nobody took pictures of
them.''
   The images are hurtful, he said, but ``it's part of what they
think the public wants.''
   Ford and Carter agreed that when it comes to relations with the
news media, George Bush will find Ronald Reagan a hard act to follow.
   Reagan was treated with kid gloves by the press, Ford said. And
Carter thinks Reagan got away with staying aloof from tough issues _
``a tribute to his acuity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
