<FIRST>r w PM-Inaugural-Police     01-19 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural-Police,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inaugural Committee Pays Way For Boston, New York, Springfield Police
Unions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush received a big boost during the
campaign when the Boston police union voted to endorse the
Republican over hometown favorite Michael Dukakis. This week, Bush
is returning the favor.
   Sixty Boston police officers plus spouses arrived in Washington
on Wednesday along with members of the New York Police Department
and Springfield, Mass., police for inaugural activities, compliments
of the Presidential Inaugural Committee.
   The committee paid for an estimated 315 officers and spouses to
come to Washington via Amtrak and stay for two nights at a local
Holiday Inn, according to Michael Dee, a committee official. He said
no estimate was available no how much the travel and accommodations
would cost.
   ``It's payback time,'' said Robert Guiney, head of the 1,500
member Boston Police Patrolmen's Association. ``I know they
appreciate what we did. They wanted the Boston police down here.''
   Delegations from all three departments will march in the
Inaugural Parade on Friday.
   Every officer attending the inauguration also was given the
opportunity to buy coveted tickets to an inaugural ball, Dee said.
   The Boston union voted 51-0 on Sept. 21 to endorse Bush over the
Massachusetts governor. Bush came to Boston the next day and held a
well-publicized news conference during which he hammered away at his
campaign theme that Dukakis was soft on crime. The following week,
Bush went to Springfield to accept the endorsement of the
Springfield police union.
   The Boston police endorsement, which served to point up the
Republican's attack on the state's much-criticized furlough program,
embarrassed Dukakis in his own back yard.
   ``I've been told by a lot of people in the Republican Party that
it was a turning point in the election,'' Guiney said at Union
Station as officers from all three departments arrived in Washington.
   The Inaugural Committee reserved a special Amtrak train, which
Boston and Springfield police boarded at 6:15 a.m. in Boston. New
York City officers joined the ``Presidential Inaugural Express'' at
11 a.m.
   The officers went from Union Station to the Lincoln Memorial for
the opening inaugural ceremonies.
</TEXT>
