<FIRST>r w PM-InauguralNotebook     01-19 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural Notebook,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>President-elect Dodging the Movers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take it from a man who knows, moving never gets
easier _ even when you're president-elect.
   ``It's a real wasteland out there this morning,'' George Bush
told a group of teachers Wednesday, referring to the chaotic scene
he had left behind at the official vice presidential residence in
northwest Washington.
   Later, addressing a Republican National Committee luncheon, Bush
said he was giving his wife Barbara ``a little elbow room'' as she
was in the throes of moving out of the residence.
   ``She's getting tough around the house,'' Bush joked. ``See a
half-filled crate and she puts me to work and she's mean and tough
and ugly about it. She doesn't show any understanding. And so she's
not here today.''
   ``I don't care if I see her for another 48 hours, because I know
there'll be another crate and she'll say: `Move this one over here.'
Getting tired of that. After all, I got big responsibilities being
put on my shoulders,'' he added, to laughter from the crowd of 550.
   The Bushes, their children and grandchildren are spending two
nights at Blair House, the government guest house, before moving
into the White House on Friday. Mrs. Bush, it should be noted,
packed hundreds of boxes herself.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A favorite pastime this week is comparing the Bush style to the
Reagan style, and speculating on what it all means for the nation.
   ``It's the difference between old money and new money. What that
means is that the rug is just as expensive, but now the dog is going
to wet on it,'' humor writer P.J. O'Rourke told CBS reporter Bob
Schieffer.
   Letitia Baldrige, a renowned hostess and etiquette writer,
temporarily forgot her manners when Schieffer asked her about the
consequences of Nancy Reagan's departure. ``Maybe there won't be
quite as many anorexics in this country,'' she said.
   Marge Schott, owner of the Cincinnati Reds baseball team, offered
a somewhat gentler view at an Inaugural Salute to Women in Business.
With Barbara Bush in the White House, she told the primarily female
audience of 400, ``we can age gracefully.''
   The changing of the guard has already claimed its first casualty:
Mrs. Reagan's hairdresser. Robyn Wier is trying to drum up business
via the fax machine, urging prospective inauguration week customers
to call 1-800-GO-2-BUSH. Already signed up: Miss America Gretchen
Carlson and Entertainment Tonight hostess Mary Hart.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   When presidential candidate Bush referred to ``a thousand points
of light'' in accepting the GOP nomination last August, most
Americans shook their heads and wondered what he meant. But
fireworks designers had a different reaction.
   ``We said to ourselves, `That sounds like a great fireworks
show,''' said Philip Butler of Fireworks by Grucci.
   The Gruccis, veterans of two previous inaugurations, got their
chance to display ``an exclusive designer shell in a barrage to
highlight this theme'' at the inaugural opening Wednesday evening at
the Lincoln Memorial.
   While the crowd on the ground waved thousands of flashlights,
points of light repeatedly exploded in the sky, pearl-like flashes
lasting 30 seconds each against the darkening sky. Said Butler with
satisfaction: ``Most shells last no more than four seconds.''
</TEXT>
