<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Bomb-Animal     01-19 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bomb-Animal,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Indicted on Federal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The animal-rights activist who allegedly placed a
bomb on the grounds of a surgical company was indicted Wednesday on
federal charges of possessing two additional pipe bombs.
   Fran Stephanie Trutt, 33, had previously been charged in a
federal complaint. Prosecutors with the U.S. attorney's office in
Brooklyn presented the case to a grand jury, which returned the
indictment.
   Miss Trutt's arraignment on the indictment had not yet been
scheduled, said Ann Driscoll, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Andrew
Maloney.
   Miss Trutt was arrested Nov. 11 in Norwalk, Conn., after police
said she placed a radio-controlled pipe bomb packed with roofing
nails on the grounds of U.S. Surgical Corp. They said she apparently
opposed the company's use of live, anesthetized dogs in surgical
equipment demonstrations.
   Miss Trutt, who was charged with attempted murder and possession
of explosives by Connecticut police, is in custody on $500,000 bail.
   After her arrest, authorities searched her apartment and found
two live pipe bombs inside a suitcase in her bathroom, court papers
allege.
   If convicted of the federal charges, she faces up to 10 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
