<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Workday     01-19 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Workday,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plans To Start The Day Earlier Than Reagan Did</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The day is going to start earlier and last
longer at the White House after President-elect Bush takes over, the
president-elect's spokesman says.
   Marlin Fitzwater, who is President Reagan's chief spokesman and
will also be Bush's press secretary, broke the news Wednesday.
   ``The vice president is going to start his work schedule at 8
a.m., and he also has breakfasts at 7:15 a.m. and things like
that,'' Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater, who was Bush's press secretary as vice president
before becoming Reagan's spokesman, said he expects the new
president's working day to last until 5 p.m. or 6 p.m.
   Reagan usually has his first appointment of the day at 9 or 10
a.m. and seldom stays past 5 p.m., often leaving the Oval Office in
mid-afternoon.
   Fitzwater said John Sununu, who will be Bush's chief of staff,
had indicated he would meet with his senior staff daily at 7:30 a.m.
and meet with the president shortly after that.
   Reagan's meetings with his chief of staff have been ordinarily
either at 9 a.m., 9:30 a.m. or 10 a.m.
   Fitzwater said he, too, will be coming to work a half-hour
earlier than his present 7:30 a.m.
</TEXT>
