<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Plane     01-19 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Plane,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>World War II Plane Intended To Surprise Bush At Inaugural</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A World War II plane hidden under black plastic
sheeting near the Smithsonian Air &amp; Space Museum was intended as a
surprise for George Bush as he views his inaugural parade on Friday.
   Parade organizers said they were disappointed Wednesday that word
got out about the plane through news stories. The newly painted
aircraft is a Grumman Avenger torpedo bomber identical to the one
Bush bailed out of at age 20 after a sortie against the Japanese.
   Organizers had other problems with the aircraft and had to trim
back trees and move a couple of reviewing stands to make way for its
54-foot wingspan.
   The Avenger's wings could be folded back as they would be aboard
an aircraft carrier, but officials said they wanted to ensure that
it would be in full flight position when it passed in front of the
new president. The float will also carry about a dozen members of
Bush's former torpedo squadron, Air Group VT 51.
   The plane's wingspan is so wide, Bush could almost reach out and
touch it from his reviewing stand, said a Navy officer watching over
the plane.
   Bush was rescued from the Pacific Ocean on Sept. 2, 1944, after
he bailed out of his flaming aircraft over the Bonin Islands, 600
miles south of Japan. He won the Distinguished Flying Cross for
heroism during the bombing raid in which his two crew members were
killed.
   The plane in the parade, built in the 1940s by General Motors on
a Grumman design, was flown to Washington by its owner, Cole Stuart
of Valdosta, Ga., after it was spotted by a World War II veteran
working with the USS Yorktown Association in Mount Pleasant, S.C.
   Veterans from the Yorktown arranged for the plane to be in the
parade and also tracked down members of Bush's torpedo squadron,
said Joseph Sharkey, assistant director of the Yorktown veterans
group.
   About 10,000 Avengers were built, according to Grumman historian
Lois Louisolo, with 45 of the old aircraft still registered to fly.
</TEXT>
