<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-WarBuddies     01-19 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-War Buddies,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>War Buddies Gave His Life Direction, Bush Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>PM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an emotional reunion 44 years later, George
Bush paid tribute to the his World War II Navy flying comrades and
the submarine crewmen who nicknamed him ``Ellie'' after pulling him
from the drink.
   Fireworks lit up the sky over the Lincoln Memorial as Bush, about
to become the nation's 41st president, spent half an hour of quiet
reflection Wednesday night with about three dozen of his war buddies.
   ``He spoke with great feeling about what the squadron and the
Finback's crewmen meant to him,'' said retired Rear Adm. Lawrence
Heyworth of Virginia Beach, Va. ``Mrs. Bush's eyes kind of teared up
a little. It was very intimate.''
   Heyworth was gunnery and torpedo officer aboard the USS Finback
in September 1944 when Bush was one of five young Navy aviators
rescued by the submarine after being shot down by the Japanese over
the Pacific.
   Bush has accorded the Finback veterans, the widows of a few
others and an equal number of members of his aircraft carrier
Torpedo Squadron VT-51 from World War II the choicest seats at
several inaugural events.
   But first he welcomed them to his temporary quarters at the Blair
House across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House for a private
reunion.
   ``It was very emotional,'' said Don Kohler, 64, of Rogers, Ark.,
the submarine torpedoman who helped pull Bush out of his bobbing
orange life raft onto the deck of the Finback after he had bailed
out of his flaming torpedo bomber on Sept. 2, 1944.
   ``You have to remember that few of us had seen any of the others
from the Finback for 44 years,'' Kohler said. ``And meeting under
these circumstances where the president-elect personally welcomes
us, it was pretty moving.''
   Kohler said Bush told the group that ``the youngness that was
there all those years ago and the things we were fighting for had a
great deal to do with directing his life and ideas.''
   Bush spent a few moments with each of the veterans, signing
pictures, looking at their scrapbooks, swapping remembrances.
   Heyworth quoted Bush as saying: ``If it weren't for you people in
this room, I wouldn't be here and I certainly wouldn't have been
elected president of the United States.''
   Hugo Parkman, 69, of Stone Mountain, Ga., the Finback's
communications officer, recalled Bush as ``a very clean-cut young
man.''
   ``I shared my bunk with him,'' Parkman said. ``That is, when I
was on duty, he slept, and when he was on duty I slept. On a
submarine everything's so tight, bunks don't get cold.''
   ``He was a very regular guy,'' said Parkman. ``We never knew that
he came from a distinguished family. He didn't tell anybody anything
about that.''
   W.E. ``Bill'' Edwards of Bay St. Louis, Miss., an insurance agent
and retired Navy commander, recalled that Bush was nicknamed
``Ellie'' by the submarine's crewmen because he would imitate a
braying elephant. But it had nothing to do with his aspiring
politics.
   ``We had a nickname for everyone aboard, and George was a very
smart, fun loving guy,'' Edwards said. ``He was always joking,
mimicking this elephant. I think he'd seen too many Tarzan movies.''
   Then a 20-year-old lieutenant and the Navy's youngest pilot, Bush
was flying a bombing run against a Japanese radio communications
center in the Bonin Islands 600 miles south of Japan when enemy fire
struck his TBM Avenger. He later won a Distinguished Flying Cross
for completing the run before bailing out of the flaming plane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
