<FIRST>r a PM-Miami-DeadlyForce     01-19 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami-Deadly Force,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Chief: `Major Concerns' In Shooting That Triggered Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Miami Riot, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police chief said he has ``major concerns'' in
understanding why a police officer shot to death a black
motorcyclist who was being sought for speeding.
   ``There seem to be some unusual occurrences'' in the shooting of
23-year-old Clement Lloyd, which sparked three days of riots, Police
Chief Perry Anderson said Wednesday night on ABC-TV's ``Nightline.''
   A police officer chased Lloyd because he was speeding.
Colombian-born Officer William Lozano, who fired the shot that
struck Lloyd in the head, was taking a report from a crime victim in
an unrelated incident when Lloyd sped by, authorities said.
   ``There might have been a perception of a (more serious) crime
being committed by the officer (Lozano), but we're looking at that
to determine exactly what transpired,'' the chief said.
   Anderson said the law prevented him from discussing aspects of
the investigation into Monday evening's shooting, but added, ``we
have major concerns in dealing with the reason why the officer fired
the shot.''
   Lozano was relieved of duty with pay pending the investigation.
   The shooting is being investigated by the police internal review
board, the FBI, the State Attorney's Office and a special panel
approved by city commissioners in an emergency session Wednesday.
   The Miami-Dade Police Department has a strict, 20-page policy on
the circumstances under which officers may shoot at a fleeing
suspect.
   It says an officer can use deadly force only to ``prevent death
or substantial harm to the officer or another person'' or ``to
prevent the escape of a fleeing felon who would pose a real threat
of death or substantial harm to the community or police officers.''
   The policy says the department ``places a greater value on the
preservation of life than on the protection of property.'' Officers
will use deadly force ``with great restraint and as a last resort.''
   ``Deadly force shall not be used against misdemeanors and traffic
violators,'' it says.
   The policy also says that ``shooting at or from a moving vehicle
is a dangerous and ineffective practice and is generally prohibited.
   ``However, there may be unique situations or mitigating
circumstances in which an officer may be justified in using
firearms,'' it says.
