<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DroughtOf1988     01-19 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Of 1988,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988 Drought Called Worst Natural Disaster In U.S. Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought of 1988 was the nation's worst
natural disaster on record, causing an estimated $30 billion in
agricultural losses, and its releated heat wave contributed to
10,000 deaths, researchers reported.
   ``If these data are correct, it's the Number One natural disaster
in this country,'' said John A. Dracup, a civil engineer at the
University of California, Los Angeles, who is developing ways to
assess drought severity.
   The second worst was the hurricane that struck Galveston, Texas,
on Sept. 8, 1900, killing 6,000 people, Dracup said.
   Norman Rosenberg of Resources for the Future in Washington, D.C.,
said more bad news is on the way.
   ``The drought of 1988 is not over,'' he said. ``A large portion
of the country still remains vulnerable. If we have a dry spring, we
could have a very serious situation.''
   Rosenberg and Dracup were among a panel of experts who gathered
at the annual meeting of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science to assess the effects of the drought.
   Stanley A. Changnon of the Illinois State Water Survey, who has
tried to tally the damages, said the drought was slightly less
severe in area and intensity than the droughts of 1932-1936 and
1953-1956.
   Nevertheless, 70 percent of the nation experienced ``extensively
warm and dry conditions,'' he said. Wheat, corn and soybean
production fell by 30 percent to 40 percent.
   Agricultural losses throughout the United States totaled $30
billion even though all the damage has not yet been tallied,
including the drought's effect on feed development, the livestock
industry and the consumer, who faces an increase of 2 percent to 4
percent in food prices, Changnon said.
   Summer high temperatures set records for any date in 13 percent
of the country, contributing to an estimated 10,000 deaths related
to heat stress, Changnon said.
   The most long-lasting effects will be losses to the environment,
Changnon said. The populations of certain species of wildlife in the
Mississippi River basin were reduced by 5 percent to 30 percent. The
damage due to forest fires was the greatest on record.
   Changnon and the other researchers did not give details of how
they derived their figures on the drought's severity.
   Falling water levels in the Mississippi River stopped barge
traffic in June and July, greatly disrupting shipments of coal,
grains and petroleum products.
   The researchers agreed it was impossible to say whether the
drought was evidence that the global warming known as the greenhouse
effect was beginning to take hold.
   Stephen H. Schneider of the National Center for Atmospheric
Research in Boulder, Colorado, said that the greenhouse effect could
be expected to increase the severity of droughts but not their
frequency.
   Whether the drought of 1988 was intensified by an underlying
greenhouse effect or was just caused by unusual seasonal weather
variations cannot be determined, he said.
   Schneider said most climatologists believe the immediate cause of
the drought was colder-than-usual temperatures in the tropical
Pacific Ocean, which are known to affect weather in the United
States.
   David R. Rodenhuis, director of the Climate Analysis Center at
the National Weather Service, said 26 percent of the continental
United States received less than half its normal rainfall during
April, May and June, 1988.
   In late July, 40 percent of the United States was covered by
severe or extreme drought conditions, Rodenhuis said.
   ``We still do have a continuing dryness in the northern plains
and the northwest part of the country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TritiumAlternative     01-19 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tritium Alternative,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say Accelerator Could Also Help Neutralize Radioactive
Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear researcher says there is reason to
believe that a linear accelerator could be used to help neutralize
highly radioactive waste in addition to producing tritium, a key
ingredient in atomic warheads.
   Rod Powell, manager of engineering development at the
Westinghouse-Hanford Co. in Washington state, said Wednesday that
high-level radioactive waste could be bombarded with neutrons in an
accelerator and changed into low-level radioactive waste.
   ``It would be a new twist,'' Powell said in a telephone
interview. He cautioned that the technology still needs to be proven
in a pilot project, but added that the Japanese are already studying
the possibility of using an accelerator for such a purpose.
   The federal government is currently grappling with the problem of
disposing of massive amounts of highly radioactive waste, both from
commercial nuclear reactors and from the production of nuclear
weapons.
   Existing plans call for storing the waste in an underground
repository in Nevada, but the project has already been fraught with
problems and delays.
   Scientists at Westinghouse-Hanford and at the Los Alamos and
Brookhaven national laboratories have been studying the idea of
using an accelerator to produce tritium, a radioactive gas used in
nuclear warheads, for more than a year.
   The work comes amid increasing concern about the reliability and
safety at the Energy Department's three tritium producing reactors
at the Savannah River complex in South Carolina.
   Powell said that researchers were convinced that an accelerator
could be used to produce enough tritium to meet demand and also be
used for other purposes.
   The accelerator could also be used to produce special isotopes
for everything from sophisticated medical equipment to a new device
that the Federal Aviation Administration is developing to detect
plastic explosives, he said.
   An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic
particles are whipped at high speeds until they crash into a target,
in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision
produces tritium.
   In using an accelerator to deal with radioactive waste, Powell
said the process is essentially similar.
   As an example, Powell said the most deadly elements could be
separated from spent fuel rods from a nuclear reactor and than
bombarded with neutrons in an accelerator.
   ``The actual word is transmutate,'' said Powell. ``It could be a
way of disposing of (radioactive) waste.''
   The Energy Department provided $300,000 to initially fund
research into using an accelerator for tritium production, but no
funding was provided in the current fiscal year, Powell said.
   According to a copy of a summary report prepared by the
scientists and obtained by The Associated Press last week, an
accelerator could produce tritium more cheaply, quickly and safely
than a nuclear reactor.
   Last July, the Energy Department recommended construction of two
new tritium producing reactors, one at the Savannah River complex in
South Carolina and the other at the Idaho Falls National Laboratory
in Idaho.
   Powell said the researchers were disappointed when the department
didn't decide to pursue the accelerator alternative, but decided to
continue the work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
