<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Use Set Record Last Year; Oil Import Rise Continued</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An energy industry trade group says U.S. oil
imports hit a nine-year high in 1988 as Americans used more energy
than in any year in history.
   The American Petroleum Institute, representing the bigger oil
producers and refiners, said U.S. consumption of all types of energy
rose 4 percent last year, surpassing the previous record set in
1979, the year the last oil crisis struck.
   Oil imports last year jumped nearly 9 percent, to a rate of 7.2
million barrels a day, which was the highest level since 1979.
   The group said its index of energy efficiency _ the amount of
energy used to produce each unit of economic output _ ``suggests'' a
small improvement for 1988 over the previous year, if the figures
are adjusted for seasonal factors such as weather.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Texas Formally Handed Key To New Physics Project</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department has formally crowned
Texas the winner of a seven-state battle to host a proposed $5.9
billion superconducting super collider.
   At a formal ceremony attended by Texas Gov. Bill Clements, John
Herrington, the energy secretary, signed an official ``record of
decision'' Wednesday to build the massive physics installation
around the city of Waxahachie, about 25 miles south of Dallas.
   The collider is envisioned as a 53-mile underground ring that
would use 10,000 magnets to whirl beams of protons into each other
at energy levels 20 times what is possible in today's most powerful
machines.
   Scientists will use the facility, to be called the Ronald Reagan
Center for High-Energy Physics, to explore the nature of matter and
energy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Scientists Suggests Manned Mission To Moons Of Mars</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal government scientist says the best,
cheapest way to explore Mars would be to land astronauts on the
planet's moons rather than on the surface of the planet.
   Fred Singer, an astronomer and the Department of Transportation's
chief scientist, said that putting researchers on either Phobos or
Deimos, would enable engineers to direct mobile robot craft to
explore and collect samples from the Martian surface.
   ``Sending an expedition to the moons of Mars has the advantage of
being the best we could do, the least expensive and the soonest,''
Singer said Wednesday in a luncheon address at the Touchdown Club.
``My hope that the time is right now for us to go in this
direction.''
</TEXT>
