<FIRST>u w PM-InauguralDinners Bjt   01-19 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural Dinners, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Feast While Protesters Highlight Poverty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was toasted with champagne,
serenaded by the Whiffenpoof songsters from Yale and cheered at a
$1,500-a-plate inaugural dinner by Republican fat cats who refused
to let chanting protesters and homeless onlookers spoil their party.
   Outside Union Station on Wednesday night, street people stood
eating a soup-kitchen supper of chili and rice off paper plates
while protesters shouted chants of ``Food for the Poor, Not the
Rich'' and ``What About the Homeless?'' at stretch limousines
delivering black-tie guests to the dinner inside.
   Once the police erected barricades and shooed away several
hundred demonstrators, about 2,500 Republican Party stalwarts and
wealthy contributors settled down at three great halls around town
to feast on Maryland crab and mushroom-stuffed loins of veal washed
down with California wines from crystal goblets.
   Just as the diners were polishing off the apple-cranberry brown
betty with cinnamon ice cream and bourbon custard, President-elect
Bush and Dan Quayle, his vice president-to-be, arrived in the
vaulted main hall of Union Station from visits to other dinners at
the Pension Building and the Corcoran Gallery of Art.
   They were running 25 minutes late _ ``We're exhausted,'' Bush
said _ but the GOP's big spenders finally got what they paid for,
and they went slightly wild. Heraldic trumpets blared from a
balcony. Cameras flashed. Women in sequined gowns and glittering
necklaces left tables decked with floral trees of white roses and
pushed forward. Bush waved and smiled.
   ``I'm gonna try my level best to be a good president of the
United States, and work for all the people of the United States,''
he said.
   ``You've given me a chance, and I'm not going to let you down.''
   Bush and Penne Percy Korth, co-chairman of the inaugural
committee, toasted each other with champagne. Bush waved his arm and
mouthed the words of his school song, sung by the Whiffenpoof glee
club of his alma mater, Yale University.
   Then he plunged into the crowd of well-wishers, shaking hands,
waving and exchanging hugs for the next 10 minutes. Bush thanked
them for the financial support that helped him win the presidency,
and for underwriting the four days of inaugural festivities with
$100,000 interest-free loans.
   Earlier, on the plaza facing the newly refurbished train station,
demonstrators served a ``counter-inaugural banquet'' to several
dozen homeless people from large metal pots steaming in the glare of
television lights, and entertained them with folk singers and
pro-abortion street theater.
   Michael Hasty of the Washington Peace Center said it was ``sick,
decadent'' for the Republicans to eat $1,500 dinners while people
are homeless and starving on the streets.
   ``We've fed over 1,000 people so far tonight with less than a
$200 budget,'' he said. ``I wonder how long it would take for
somebody out on the street to beg for $1,500 in spare change.''
   A half-hour before the dinner inside began at 8 p.m., the crowd
pushed closer to the arriving limousines, and police erected
barricades to prevent a spontaneous surge toward the station's main
entrance. The protesters dispersed peacefully just as their
three-hour permit expired.
   U.S. Park Police also banished from the plaza a half-dozen
conservative Republican activists carrying American flags who said
they wanted to demonstrate against the anti-poverty demonstrators.
Sgt. Robert Kass said the conservatives lacked a permit.
   Grace Stepp, 36, a homeless person, paused between spoonfuls of
chili to say the inaugural diners ``should help us out, too _ they
should get us more shelters and stuff.''
   Roosevelt Carrington, 30, a homeless, unemployed carpenter, said
he thought the black-tie guests should come out and ``eat the same
thing we're having, so they'll know what it's like.''
   But inside, many of the party faithful waiting to pass through
metal detectors at the entrance said they had hardly noticed the
demonstrators and their shouted messages.
   Thomas J. Stewart, a Seattle business executive, termed
``ridiculous'' the protesters' suggestion that the $2.25 million in
proceeds from the inaugural dinners would be better spent helping
the poor and homeless.
   ``They hold these staged events every time Republicans get
together, and it's in very poor taste,'' Stewart said.
   ``The people here tonight have probably contributed more, as
individuals and corporations, to the welfare of this country than
anybody else,'' said Jim Hewgley, a Tulsa, Okla., oilman. ``If they
want to celebrate, then, by God, they're entitled to.''
   Stew Jackson, president of a burglar alarm company in Denver,
predicted that Bush would ``do a lot for the homeless,'' which he
endorses. ``But I also support those who do something to help
themselves,'' Jackson said.
   David Eller of Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., a water pump manufacturer
and weekly newspaper publisher who qualifies as a Republican
``Eagle'' for donating a minimum of $10,000 to party campaigns, said
there were plenty of jobs available for the homeless. ``If they'd
rather protest than do an honest day's work, I don't have too much
sympathy for them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
