<DOCNO> AP890119-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolShooting-Psychology Bjt   01-19 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Shooting-Psychology, Bjt,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass Killers: `Grandstand Suicides' Bent On Revenge Against World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychologists say mass murderers like the
drifter who sprayed rifle fire at his boyhood school are part of a
recent unprecedented wave of ``grandstand suicides'' expressing a
hair-trigger anger at the world.
   But some experts warn that such acts of violence, whether they
represent a copycat trend or are only isolated incidents, should not
turn the nation's schools into ``armed camps.''
   The issue took on new significance as police investigated the
motivations of Patrick Purdy, a drifter who returned to his former
elementary school on Tuesday and opened fire on a crowd of children,
killing five students and wounding 30 people before killing himself.
   ``For these people, it is typically their last chance to show
society how angry they are,'' Michael Mantell, chief psychologist
for the San Diego Police Department,'' said Wednesday. ``Striking
out at children is their way of building up their flagging egos by
taking out their frustration on young victims.''
   ``It's the fad of the last year. We've had more this last year
than ever before,'' said James Alan Fox, co-author of ``Mass Murder:
America's Growing Menace'' and a psychologist and criminology
professor at Northeastern University in Boston.
   During 1988, there were five shooting rampages at public schools
in the United States.
   Fox noted that 19-year-old Jamie Wilson, charged with two counts
of murder in an attack on a Greenwood, S.C. elementary school last
year, was reported to be a ``fan'' of Laurie Dann, the woman who
shot and killed herself after gunning down children at a Winnetka,
Ill., elementary school earlier in 1988.
   But despite the increasing number of school shootings, they can't
all be blamed on copycats, although mass murder locations tend to
cluster, Fox said. After the massacre of 21 people at a McDonald's
restaurant in San Ysidro, near San Diego, in 1984, there was a
similar but less deadly attack on another McDonald's in Detroit.
   ``You do it (mass murder) in a confined place like a restaurant,
a McDonald's, or a school,'' he said, calling such bursts of
violence ``revenge against society'' for a lifetime of frustrations.
   ``And what better way to do it than take it out on children, the
thing that is most dear to us?'' he said.
   Mantell described Purdy's death as a ``grandstand suicide.''
   ``The reason people do that `grandstand suicide' is often to say
to the world, `I am important. Look at me,''' Mantell said.
``Someone who has given up on life has nothing to lose.''
   Police said Purdy wore an olive-drab shirt bearing the Iranian
battle cry ``Death to the Great Satin'' (sic) and the words ``PLO''
and ``Libya.''
   Carved into the stock of the assault rifle was the word
``Hezbollah,'' the name of the radical Shiite Moslem faction
believed holding American hostages in Lebanon. Also carved into the
rifle were the words ``freedom'' and ``victory.''
   ``What the significance of that is I do not know,'' said Stockton
Police Capt. Dennis Perry. ``He obviously had a military hangup of
some kind.''
   Purdy, who killed himself after shooting the children, selected a
school he attended several years as a child. ``It's very likely that
he had some bad experience (there), maybe he was ridiculed as a
child,'' Fox said. ``As random as it seems, it's very specific:
namely getting back at this place.''
   A day after the Stockton murders, 227 of an expected 940
Cleveland Elementary School students returned to class Wednesday,
said schools spokesman John Klose. Individual and group grief
counseling sessions were available to the children, teachers and
parents, he said, adding that it appeared ``to be working very
well.''
   School officials decided to keep the school open after staff
psychologists agreed the ``preponderance of the evidence supported
going back immediately,'' Klose said. But he said an outside
psychologist told them they made a mistake: ``So there are two
schools of thought on this.''
   Either way, ``there is a wound here that will affect them to some
degree for the rest of their lives,'' said Tom Rusk, associate
professor of clinical psychiatry at the University of California,
San Diego. ``I don't care what kind of therapy is available. You
cannot erase this.''
   Sam Sava, executive director of the National Association of
Elementary School Principals in Alexandria, Va., said the
association pleaded last October for schools to implement security
plans.
   Sava said ``things have changed and we can't have our youngsters
walking around like blind mice, and we have to use the best
educational techniques to help children cope with these dangers.''
   Mantell also urged school authorities to develop security plans,
but he cautioned against turning elementary campuses into ``armed
camps.''
   ``There's very little we can do or should do,'' added Fox. ``We
start making our schools into fortresses, we'll make our kids
paranoid.''
   San Francisco School Superintendent Ramon Cortines said after
Tuesday's shooting that he would ask principals to take
``extraordinary precautions'' for safety.
   ``This shows how vulnerable our children and employees are,'' he
said. ``You can't take any chances with their safety.''
</TEXT>
