<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-UneasyStreets Bjt   01-19 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uneasy Streets, Bjt,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Scene Quieter But Tension Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man with the microphone was preaching Jesus
through a battered speaker near the Liberty City checkpoint. ``His
love is e-e-e-ternal,'' he intoned as police checked motorists in
the garish light of flares and squad car flashers.
   A few miles north, officers in helmets and flak vests closed in
on a house that might have been the source of gunfire, while fellow
officers laughed and lounged a hundred feet away.
   The streets of Miami's Overtown and Liberty City neighborhoods
were a little easier Wednesday night. But they were still far from
normal.
   The looting and gunfire that punctuated the past two nights was
muted. Police were still out in force. They wore body armor and
toted loaded shotguns, but this night they sipped sodas and snacked
on sandwiches and ice cream as their radios occasionally crackled
with reports of car fires, smashed store windows and rock throwing.
   The picnics spread out on squad car hoods spoke to the relative
calm of the evening. So did the numbers that were being compiled
back at police headquarters. Officials reported 50 arrests by 1
a.m., largely for rock-throwing incidents. Overnight Tuesday there
were 325 arrests, mostly for looting.
   ``We hope we can normalize the situation and get back to routine
patrolling,'' said Deputy Police Chief Walter Martinez.
   The biggest problem for Gary Wilcox, a police sergeant who manned
a Liberty City checkpoint, was fending off outsiders who wanted to
tour the riot scene.
   ``We'll ask people where they're from and they'll say `Kendall,'
'' a white suburb southwest of the city. ``When we ask them why
they're here, they'll say, `Just to see what it's like,''' according
to Wilcox.
   The violence sparked by the fatal police shooting of a black
motorcyclist Monday had not entirely abated. Police were fired upon
at least twice. One man was arrested for shooting at a squad car
from an apartment window. Caravans of police vehicles, known as
field force units, rushed through neighborhoods.
   One field force unit screeched to a halt in front of Lee and
Rita's Grocery after officers thought they heard shots. Three men
lounging in front of the store were forced to the ground while
special weapons and tactics teams checked an adjacent apartment
building.
   The men remained on the ground, watched by two officers. The rest
of the unit leaned on their cars, talking and joking while the SWAT
unit made its cautious rounds. When they failed to find evidence of
a sniper, the men on the ground were released.
   ``We're just trying to get the people off the streets without
disrupting their lives and making sure we're selective about who we
arrest,'' said Lt. Nelson Oramas.
   But mostly, the night seemed an aftermath of the previous two
evenings.
   At the edge of Little Haiti, Manuel Gorelick stood outside his
half-empty furniture store with some friends. On the street was a
huge iron grate that looters pulled off the storefront Tuesday night
after chaining it to a stolen car.
   The street was dotted with rocks, the ammunition used by rioters
on previous nights. Across the street, silent clusters of youths
stared at Gorelick and his partner, Gilberto Cusido, who had one
revolver tucked in his waistband and another in his hip pocket.
   ``I've been here for 10 years,'' Gorelick said. ``I've been
broken into for six times. A couple of times there were riots here,
but this is the worst.''
   Gorelick estimated looters carried off $40,000 of furniture. But
he had no plans of closing down.
   ``We're going to stay here still,'' he said, as the knots of
youths across the street continued to stare. ``We're still serving
the community.''
</TEXT>
