<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--ColdSpell     01-19 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Cold Spell,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>145 Die From Cold Waves in Bangladesh, India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week-long cold wave in parts of
Bangladesh and northern India has killed 145 people _ and
meteorologists predict a further drop in temperatures, officials
said today.
   India has recorded 75 deaths and Bangladesh 70 since temperatures
plummeted on the subcontinent Jan. 12.
   New Delhi and parts of northern India, where the normal
temperature at this time of year ranges from 46 to 50 degrees, has
recorded a low of 37.
   An official at the Dhaka Metereological Office said cold winds
would continue for another week and predicted more casulties. He
spoke on condition of anonymity. In New Delhi, the weather office
said there would be no break from the cold for another four or five
days.
   Temperatures in the region have been mild by international
standards, but exceptionally chilly in a region better known for
excruciating summer heat and where many have little or no shelter.
</TEXT>
