<FIRST>u a PM-Poll-Bush Bjt   01-19 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Bush, Bjt,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Doubts Bush on Tax Pledge but Views him Favorably</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans have read his lips but expect George
Bush to break his pledge of no new taxes, although a solid majority
likes him anyway, a national poll has found.
   Bush made opposition to taxes a cornerstone of his presidential
campaign, and six in 10 respondents to the Media General-Associated
Press poll agreed he should not seek a tax increase. But 71 percent
said they think he will.
   Even still, the survey found high approval ratings for Bush, who
takes office Friday as the 41st president. Respondents voiced high
expectations for his presidency and gave him strong marks for his
cabinet choices.
   A solid 59 percent said they viewed Bush favorably, precisely the
same approval rate President Reagan received in a Media General-AP
poll last spring. Only 25 percent rated Bush unfavorably; the rest
withheld judgment.
   Bush fared well in another comparison with his popular
predecessor: Expectations for his presidency came close to the
ratings of Reagan's performance in a Media General-AP poll conducted
this fall.
   Forty-eight percent in the new poll said Bush would be a good
president and 13 percent said he would be excellent; this fall, 47
percent said Reagan would be recorded in history as a good
president, 20 percent excellent.
   The new poll was conducted by telephone Jan. 4-12 among a random
sample of 1,162 adults nationwide. It has a 3-point margin of
sampling error.
   Although many respondents were unfamiliar with Bush's nominees
for his Cabinet, those who did have opinions were strongly positive.
Overall, 45 percent said their impression was that the Cabinet was a
good one and 8 percent called it excellent.
   The poll found a limited desire for more women or minority
nominees to the Cabinet, with 70 percent saying race and sex were
irrelevant. Bush has picked two women, one black and two Hispanics
for Cabinet-level jobs.
   Former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, nominated as
secretary of labor, was the best known and best liked of Bush's more
prominent nominees. Sixty-six percent viewed her favorably, a better
rating even than Bush's, while only 7 percent disapproved. The rest
had no opinion.
   James A. Baker III, nominated as secretary of state, received a
57-7 favorable-unfavorable rating, the rest having no opinion;
former Rep. Jack Kemp, picked for secretary of housing, scored
52-10; and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, who is keeping his
position, 51-7.
   Majorities had no opinion of former Sen. John Tower, named to
defense; Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, retaining his job; and
Louis Sullivan, health and human services nominee. Eighty-three
percent had no opinion of Bush's new chief of staff, former New
Hampshire Gov. John Sununu.
   Such unfamiliarity aside, 46 percent said Bush has done a good
job since the election in preparing to take over the presidency, and
11 percent said excellent; 28 percent gave him only a fair rating, 7
percent poor.
   Bush did better in approval ratings with wealthier and older
Americans and with men. His greatest support came from Republicans
and conservatives, but even in those groups, six in 10 doubted his
tax pledge, saying they think he will seek higher taxes during the
next four years.
   On ideology, six in 10 said they expected Bush's Cabinet to be
about as conservative as Reagan's, a view shared by the
conservatives polled. Forty percent said the Cabinet was about right
ideologically, with the rest split on their preference.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston,
S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
