<FIRST>r a PM-CommoditiesInvestigation     01-19 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Investigation,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Reportedly Investigating Chicago Commodity Exchanges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents posing as commodities traders have
obtained evidence of widespread fraud involving millions of dollars
at the nation's two largest futures exchanges, a newspaper reported
today.
   Investigators believe the traders cheated customers of millions
of dollars in the execution of buy and sell orders at the exchanges,
which deal in a variety of contracts for future delivery of grains,
livestock, Treasury bonds, foreign currencies and other commodities,
the Chicago Tribune reported.
   The investigation focused on 50 to 100 brokers, floor traders and
commodity executives at the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, the newspaper said, quoting anonymous sources.
   Hundreds of conversations were secretly tape recorded on the
exchanges' trading floors during a two-year period, the newspaper
said.
   ``We're talking about a ton of money on this thing,'' one source
told the newspaper.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas and FBI spokesmen in Washington and
Chicago refused to comment or acknowledge the investigation.
   Trades were rigged to prevent customers from getting fair-market
prices, and brokers allegedly sent false reports to customers to
hide that profits had been skimmed and that overcharges were made on
commissions.
   The Tribune said Valukas went to Washington on Friday to brief
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on the investigation.
   The newspaper said several subpoenas were served Wednesday, but
any arrests or indictments were at least a month away.
   ``We have received no official call or notification by a federal
agency or the U.S. attorney's office,'' a Board of Trade official
told the Tribune.
   Officials at the Mercantile Exchange said they did not know if
any subpoenas were delivered to traders there, and refused further
comment.
</TEXT>
