<DOCNO> AP890119-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0603EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Magazine     01-19 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Magazine,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Thriving Under Glasnost Comes Under Fire In Leading Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magazine that blossomed under glasnost and ran
stories this week on corruption, pollution and suicide has come
under attack in two leading newspapers, indicating some leading
Communist officials may be getting fed up.
   Seven prominent cultural figures, in a letter published Wednesday
in the Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda, bitterly attacked the
magazine Ogonyok, saying it went ``far outside the bounds of
literary arguments.''
   Those signing the letter, including conservative writers Valentin
Rasputin and Vasily Belov, said they supported ``with all their
souls'' President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms but had become
alarmed by ``scum bubbling up on the crest of the mighty stream of
renovation.''
   Izvestia, the government's afternoon newspaper, ran its own
correspondent's article Wednesday that cast doubt on Ogonyok's
credibility.
   He also wondered aloud why Ogonyok's editor-in-chief, Vitaly
Korotich, was trying to run in a Moscow neighborhood for a seat in a
new national assembly, the Council of People's Deputies, to be
elected in March.
   Izvestia correspondent A. Stepovoi said some Soviet social
organizations that are entitled to direct representation in the
assembly have already named Korotich as a candidate.
   The Ogonyok editor was seen by millions of U.S. television
viewers when CBS News anchorman Dan Rather visited with him in a
segment of the network's 1987 documentary on Soviet life, ``Seven
Days in May.''
   Under Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or greater openness, the
magazine has been transformed from a staid journal to a lively and
popular magazine.
   Ogonyok has drawn tough and insulting criticism from other Soviet
media before, but Pravda on Wednesday gave great prominence to its
critical letter, printing it above the fold on its back page. That
placement in the party's top daily could indicate high-level
irritation at Ogonyok.
   Many of the sensational revelations made by Soviet media under
glasnost have appeared in Ogonyok, whose title means small fire.
   In this week's issue, the slick magazine with more 3 million
subscribers nationwide revealed Soviet suicide statistics for recent
years, denounced pollution and ran the latest episode of an expose
on corruption and cronyism under the late Soviet leader Leonid I.
Brezhnev.
   Since the magazine has been one of the leaders in the drive for
franker discussion of social problems and a more honest
coming-to-grips with the country's past, any official attack on it
would be perceived by many Soviets as a signal of glasnost's limits.
   The seven cultural figures grouped Ogonyok along with Soviet
publications they said are engaged in an ``unprecedented distortion
of history, and that revise the social achievements of the people.''
   ``The magazine has taken upon itself the role of a kind of judge
on all questions of social life, politics, the economy, culture and
morals,'' they wrote.
   They accused it of printing unverified hearsay and of deprecating
Soviet cultural icons such as poet Vladimir Mayakovsky and Nobel
literature laureate Mikhail Sholokhov, author of ``And Quiet Flows
the Don.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
