<FIRST>r a PM-Brite-NursesCaps     01-19 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brite-Nurses Caps,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor's Challenge Brings Back Nurses' Caps _ For a Day, Lunch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Practicality may have made the classic
white nurses cap obsolete, but a doctor with a love of the past
brought them back for a day at Delta Medical Center's emergency room.
   ``I told the nurses one day that if they would wear their attire
that nurses used to wear 10, 15, 20 years ago, mainly the
traditional nurses cap, I'd dress up and buy them lunch,'' emergency
room physician David Merideth said.
   Five nurses did, so Meredith ordered a seafood lunch brought into
the emergency room last Friday.
   ``I didn't think they'd do that, but they held me to it,'' he
said.
   Merideth shucked the scrub greens that have become standard among
hospital medical staffs and put on whites _ complete with jacket and
tie.
   The nurses' white uniforms included caps representing their
nursing schools, except for one who had to borrow a cap for the
occasion.
   ``We don't think it's really practical to dress like this
everyday, although it looks better,'' Merideth said.
</TEXT>
