<DOCNO> AP890119-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolShooting-Terror Bjt   01-19 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Shooting-Terror, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Fled Violence, Now Face Terror</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ram Chun survived being born in a Thai
refugee camp eight years ago, and she survived the hostility
Cambodian immigrants faced in their ``wonderful'' new country. But
she didn't survive Patrick Purdy.
   Ram's mother, Im Chun, spoke of her daughter's difficult life and
death as she stood in the doorway of her apartment with reddened
eyes Wednesday, a day after Purdy inexplicably killed Ram and four
other Southeast Asian children and wounded 30 people at the
Cleveland Elementary School before taking his own life.
   ``She said that all her family, her brothers got killed in
Cambodia by communists,'' said interpreter Setha Thach, who
translated for Im Chun. ``She thought she came here to live
peacefully, but something like this happens. ... Even $1 million
can't buy her child (back) that she lost.''
   Wednesday evening, more than 200 mourners gathered at a church
next door to the school where they heard the Lord's Prayer intoned
in Cambodian as thankful parents, whose children survived the
attack, clung to their youngsters.
   ``Chance, random fate and a very disturbed gunman ... have
brought grief, mourning and chaos to our city,'' said the Rev.
Arnold Vorster of Central United Methodist Church.
   ``Especially do we weep for our Southeast Asian brothers and
sisters ... for all children belong to the American family ... They
are our wealth and our future, for the bell tolls for us all.''
   Earlier in the day, many children stayed home from school despite
the urging of psychologists and the efforts of workers who spent the
night repairing bullet holes and removing blood stains from the
school grounds.
   ``My father said we couldn't go to school,'' said fifth-grader
Sokchea Thlang, who added that her father had cried when he heard
about the shootings. Three of his older children had died in
Cambodia and he feared Sokchea, her third-grader sister or
kindergartener brother had been shot. They were all uninjured.
   ``I thought when we came to the states of America, I thought we
would have a wonderful life and everything was going to be
exciting,'' said Sokchea.
   At first, she said, she thought the gunfire was firecrackers.
   ``Then my teacher looked out the door and she saw a man and two
girls lying on the ground,'' she said. ``My teacher started to cry.
Everybody got under the tables and everybody started to cry.''
   For Cambodian refugees who have settled locally, the schoolyard
massacre was particularly incomprehensible.
   At an apartment complex about six blocks from the school, young
children peered through the windows and raced bicycles on tiny yards
of compacted mud. Many of the women and girls wear colorful batik
sarongs. Thongs are the most common footwear. The teeth of some
women are stained with beetlenut, a plant popular as chewing gum
among Southeast Asians.
   ``I wonder why he wanted to kill,'' fifth-grader Och Sao mused,
noting that all five victims were from Southeast Asian refugee
families. ``I think he hated Cambodians or something.''
   Och said many Cambodian immigrants have met hostility in their
new country.
   Down the street, friends huddled around a space heater on woven
mats under framed snapshots of another victim, 6-year-old Sokhim An,
and her family. The parents weren't home. The girl's mother,
Korn-Ing, was hospitalized for shock after her daughter, the eldest
of three children, was killed, Thach said.
   ``They wonder why? What's happening to the Cambodians?'' neighbor
Moeun Loeung said through the interpreter.
</TEXT>
