<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     01-19 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Says REgional Summit On for February 8-9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American presidents have
agreed to hold a summit next month to try to advance a stalled
regional peace plan, President Daniel Ortega said.
   The Nicaraguan leader said in a statement late Wednesday that the
summit would be held Feb. 8-9 in the Salvadoran capital, San
Salvador.
   The summit was riginally scheduled for Jan. 15-16, but was
postponed after President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica suggested a
delay to allow President-elect George Bush time to formulate a
Central American policy.
   Arias authored the regional peace plan, which was signed in
Guatemala in August 1987 by the five presidents. The plan calls for
an end to civil wars in Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua. It
also calls for movement toward democracy and political amnesties.
   Ortega's statement said foreign ministers from the region's
governments would meet in Managua to prepare an agenda for the
summit.
   The five presidents are Ortega, Arias, Jose Napoleon Duarte of El
Salvador, Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras and Vinicio Cerezo of
Guatemala.
   In another development, Costa Rican Public Security Minister
Hernan Garron charged late Wednesday that three Sandinista army
helicopters had violated Costa Rican airspace.
   Garron said the Nicaraguan helicopters flew over the Costa Rican
border posts of Las Delicias and El Cachito at about 5:00 p.m.
Wednesday. Las Delicias and El Cachito are about 55 miles north of
San Jose.
   A Nicaraguan Defense Ministry spokesman refused to comment on the
report Wednesday night. The spokesman, speaking on condition he not
be identified, said the Foreign Ministry possibly would comment
today.
</TEXT>
