<FIRST>r i PM-SteakThief     01-19 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steak Thief,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Serviceman Convicted Of Stealing T-Bones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court has sentenced a U.S.
Air Force sergeant to two years in jail after convicting him of
stealing $9,000 worth of frozen T-bone steaks from the commissary at
his base, the Air Force said today.
   Maj. Wayne Crist, a spokesman at the Clark air base, said Sgt.
Michael A. Lafayette also was given a forfeiture of $400 dollars a
month from his pay for two years and dishonorable discharge after
serving his prison term.
   The court martial ended on Jan. 10.
   Lafayette's age and hometown were not available. Crist said
Lafayette was assigned to the commissary at Clark, 50 miles north of
Manila.
   Two Filipino civilians were arrested along with Lafayette and are
being prosecuted before Philippine courts, Crist said in a telephone
interview from Clark. Several other Filipinos also were involved, he
added.
   Crist said Lafayette was apprehended on Aug. 1 when he was caught
stealing the steaks from cold storage. Crist said Lafayette had cut
off the seals of a freezer drawer and assisted his Filipino
companions in loading 60 cases of T-bone steaks in a jeep.
   Two of the Filipinos tried to get away with the jeep but were
caught by guards at one of the base's gates, Crist said.
   The stolen steaks apparently were intended for sale on the black
market. Although steaks are sold in most supermarkets in the
Philippines, many Filipinos, especially the wealthy, prefer American
products.
</TEXT>
