<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-EasternJet     01-19 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern Jet,0267</SECOND>
<UNK>Eastern Jet Makes Emergency Descent After Losing Pressure</UNK>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines DC-9 with 68 people aboard
lost cabin pressure and was forced to drop 26,000 feet, the
carrier's second pressurization problem in a month.
   Flight 753 was traveling from Cleveland to Atlanta on Wednesday
when it was forced to go to a lower altitude over northeast Georgia.
No injuries were reported, said Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   A sensor problem caused the plane to lose pressure, the airline
said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and National Transportation
Safety Board were investigating the incident, which followed the
Dec. 26 emergency landing of an Eastern Boeing 727 in Charleston,
W.Va. That plane lost pressure after a 10-by-20-inch hole opened in
the fuselage. There also were no major injuries in that incident.
   The FAA earlier this month directed airlines to step up
inspections of the DC-9 fleet, which has an average age of 18.18
years. The directive followed the agency's discovery of cracks in
more than 20 planes during a special inspection.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Wednesday's problem had
little to do with the plane's age. A sensor apparently
malfunctioned, erroneously setting the pressure for a lower
altitude, he said.
   ``The sensor in effect tells the plane what altitude it's at, and
that sensor device apparently malfunctioned,'' he said. ``This is
the type of thing that could happen on a plane one hour off the
production line. It's simply a mechanical malfunction.''
   During the descent from 35,000 to 9,000 feet, the oxygen masks
dropped for the passengers.
</TEXT>
