<FIRST>r a PM-Grocer-Robbery     01-19 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grocer-Robbery,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storeowner Says He Acted On Instinct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grocer who shot to death two armed robbers in
his store said he hoped he would never have to use his unregistered
handgun but he had no choice and would do so again.
   ``I don't feel good that I had to do it,'' Ramon Guzman said
Wednesday.
   ``This is a lesson to the robber on the street,'' said the
35-year-old Guzman, who bought the .38-caliber handgun three years
ago. ``They will think twice before doing something like this
again.''
   Three men armed with two handguns and a shotgun entered the
Rainbow Mini-Mart in the Bronx on Tuesday night and announced a
holdup, police said.
   One of the holdup men aimed a shotgun at the grocer and warned,
``Don't move or I'll blow your head off,'' Guzman recalled.
   As a second man with a pistol came around the counter, Guzman
reached for his own gun and fired twice, hitting the man in the face
and arm, the grocer recalled.
   Guzman said he turned and saw the man with the shotgun raise the
weapon. He said he fired his gun twice more, hitting the robber. The
third robber fled.
   ``I reacted on instinct,'' Guzman said.
   Guzman was charged with illegal possession of a weapon, a
misdemeanor, punishable by up to a year in jail. The district
attorney's office will convene a grand jury to determine whether
Guzman's use of the gun was justified.
</TEXT>
