<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Pays Call on PLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau, Jr.
visited the PLO's representative in Tunisia earlier this week, his
first such call on PLO offices, a U.S. Embassy spokesman said today.
   The visit on Tuesday to the offices of Hakam Balawi was a return
call for a visit Balawi paid on the ambassador at the start of the
new year, Embassy spokesman Richard Undeland told The Associated
Press.
   He was confirming PLO reports of such a visit.
   Undeland would not specify whether the visit was purely a
courtesy call or whether discussions took place.
   Pelletreau first met with a delegation of the Palestine
Liberation Organization on Dec. 16, the first such official talks
since PLO chief Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism and recognized
Israel's right to exist.
   Undeland said he was unaware of a date for those talks to resume.
   A member of the PLO executive committee, Yasser Abderabou, said
Wednesday that they would resume ``in the coming weeks.''
President-elect Bush is sworn in on Friday.
   Asked about the remark, Undeland added that he was ``not ruling
out anything.''
   Abderabou, speaking on a regional Tunisian radio, said a PLO
delegation would meet in Madrid with foreign ministers from Spain,
France and Greece on Jan. 26, when a European peace plan for the
Middle East would be unveiled.
