<DOCNO> AP890119-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Obit-Chatwin     01-19 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Chatwin,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Writer Bruce Chatwin Dead At 48</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Chatwin, a travel writer and novelist who
authored the acclaimed book ``In Patagonia,'' died in the French
resort of Nice from a rare bone marrow disease he contracted in
China, his family reported. He was 48.
   Despite suffering from the debilitating disease caused by a plant
fungus that eventually confined him to a wheelchair, Chatwin
recently completed his sixth book, a collection of writings called
``What Am I Doing Here?''
   It is to be published later this year.
   In a 1987 interview, Chatwin said he contracted the ailment
during a trip to western China, dismissing the disease that killed
him Wednesday with the comment, ``Hazards of travel _ rather an
alarming one.''
   His British agent, Gillon Aitken, said today, ``He had been
staying at a friend's house, became very ill and was taken to a
hospital in Nice, where he died. He'd been ill for about three
years, with a viral disease from China, and died from that.''
   The London newspaper The Daily Telegraph called him one of the
most remarkable writers of the last dozen years. In a relatively
brief career as a writer, he published five books, three of them
novels.
   After becoming an expert on Impressionist art, Chatwin gave up
his job with a major auction house at age 24 to study anthropology
and embark on the travels that inspired his books.
   He based ``In Patagonia'' on a trek through southern Argentina
and Chile, ``The Viceroy of Ouidah'' on West Africa, ``On the Black
Hill'' on the Welsh hills where he bought a house, ``The Songlines''
on travels in Australia and his most recent, ``Utz,'' on Prague's
art world.
   A private man and spare writer, he combined an obsession with
nomadic peoples with elements of fiction and realism and an original
method of composition compared by critics to film cross-cutting and
merging.
   Born in 1940 the son of a naval officer, Chatwin's first years
were restless as he and his mother followed his father's minesweeper
around Britain.
   He went to several boarding schools, skipped college and joined
Sotheby's auction house as a trainee. Within six years, he was head
of their Impressionist department _ the youngest person to hold the
post.
   At 24, Chatwin told an interviewer, he left the house ``out of
sheer boredom. Works of art are much tougher than those handling
them, who crumbled before your eyes.''
   He enrolled at Edinburgh University to study anthropology and
archaeology before embarking on his first travels. In 1965, he
married the American daughter of an admiral, Elizabeth Chanler.
   ``In Patagonia'' was published in 1977 and followed his solitary
journey through the southern tip of South America. It brought him
instant recognition as a writer.
   The book, based on his fascination with people there and their
stories, welded truth and imagination.
   Chatwin dubbed the technique ``searches'' _ an imaginative
mixture of anthropology, history, biography and fiction. The book
won both the Somerset Maugham and E.M. Forster literary awards.
   ``The Viceroy of Ouidah,'' published in 1980 and set in 19th
century West Africa, also showed his disregard for conventional
methods of writing. It won the Whitbread literary award.
   ``On the Black Hill,'' set in rural Wales, followed in 1982 and
was made into a movie of the same name in 1987. ``The Songlines,' an
expansive account of Australian Aboriginal creation myths, was
published in 1987.
   ``Utz,'' a novel about the psychopathology of the compulsive art
collector, was published last week.
   At that time, he was quoted by The New York Times Book Review as
saying that, for him, travel had become a form of tyranny. ``As you
go along, you literally collect places,'' he said. ``I'm fed up with
going places. I shan't go to anymore.''
   Fair-haired, with good looks and a penetrating gaze, Chatwin once
remarked in an interview: ``What interested me most were the people
who had escaped the archaeological record _ the nomads who trod
lightly on the earth and didn't build pyramids.''
   Insatiably curious about others, Chatwin refused to give personal
details about himself for reference books and was rarely
interviewed. Even a television program about him and his writing
showed him as singularly unforthcoming.
   He is survived by his wife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0079 </DOCNO>
