<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedBoy     01-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Boy,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Says Choice Was To Either Abandon Or Kill Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of abandoning his 7-year-old
retarded son at a freeway rest stop told a detective he probably
would have killed the boy if he hadn't deserted him, a prosecutor
says.
   Edward Tuinman, 29, and his 28-year-old wife, Deborah, were
arraigned in state court Wednesday on a felony child abandonment
charge in the case of their son, Eddy, who was found at an
Interstate 84 exit near here Jan. 4.
   Tuinman told Detective Ken Smith ``it was either leave him or
kill him,'' Ada County Deputy Prosecutor Daniel Miller told
Magistrate Lewis Woods on Wednesday. Tuinman said anything the boy
did bothered him, Miller said.
   Eddy, battered and wearing only a urine-soaked T-shirt, was found
by two truck drivers, authorities said.
   ``He reached out to whoever was around,'' said Miller. ``He had
bruises all over his body, cigarette burns all over his body ... He
had a broken nose.''
   The boy, who cannot speak, was transferred to an Idaho foster
home after treatment at St. Luke's Regional Medical Center in Boise.
   His parents, who were originally from the Salt Lake City area and
were believed to have been traveling in search of a job, were
arrested in Nephi, Utah, three days after the boy was found.
   Public defender Mark Stewart asked Woods via closed-circuit
television Wednesday to lower the $50,000 bond on Mrs. Tuinman,
saying she lives on welfare and has no prior criminal record.
   Miller requested a higher bond, saying there was risk the couple
would leave the county.
   Woods let the bond stand. Tuinman's bond is also $50,000.
   Mrs. Tuinman requested a public attorney, but her husband said he
did not need one. Asked if had read the complaint against him,
Tuinman said he could not read.
   Woods scheduled a preliminary hearing for Jan. 31 for the couple,
who were being held in the Ada County Jail.
   If convicted, they could be sentenced to up to 14 years in
prison, Miller said.
   Three other Tuinman children are in protective custody in Utah,
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
