<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Subpoena 1stLdWritethru a0480 01-19 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Subpoena, 1st Ld Writethru, a0480,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Mayor Called to Grand Jury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs on drug test after 7th graf, Federal officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry has been subpoenaed to
appear before a federal grand jury after failing to respond to an
``invitation'' to testify about his latest troubles, according to a
published report.
   Barry will be questioned about his visits last month with a drug
suspect and about a $260,000 personnel project involving the city
and the U.S. Virgin Islands that the man was supervising, according
to today's editions of The Washington Post.
   Barry has hired a criminal defense attorney, R. Kenneth Mundy,
who told the Post the mayor is not a target of the federal
investigation.
   ``We're not resisting the subpoena at all,'' Mundy said. ``We're
simply working out with the U.S. attorney's office a schedule for
his appearance.
   ``The mayor is merely a witness,'' he said.
   The Post, quoting unidentified sources, said U.S. Attorney Jay B.
Stephens of the District of Columbia sent a letter to Barry asking
him to testify but the mayor did not respond within two weeks.
   Federal officials are investigating the city's handling of a
probe of a drug suspect, former city employee Charles Lewis, whom
Barry visited several times last month at a downtown Washington
hotel. Barry was with Lewis Dec. 22 when, according to published
reports, two undercover police officers on the way to his hotel room
turned back after learning the mayor was inside.
   Barry's physician, Dr. Vincent Roux, also said Wednesday that the
mayor was drug-free, according to the mayor's press secretary, John
White.
   White told The Washington Times that tests were conducted for 10
drugs, including PCP, cocaine, heroin and marijuana. Roux told the
newspaper a drug test was ``not standard,'' but Barry requested it.
   The written results of the tests were given to two local radio
stations, WOL and WHUR. ``That is the way Mr. Barry wanted the
information released to the community,'' White said, refusing to
elaborate.
   Investigators are also examining possible improper spending of
public funds in a project Lewis was supervising for the Virgin
Islands government. Several city officials, including Barry, took
expensive trips to the islands as part of a consulting contract to
help revamp the personnel system there.
   According to the Post, the grand jury has subpoenaed police
records of telephone calls and radio transmissions for the week
covering the hotel incident. The grand jury began probing the hotel
incident and the personnel project on Jan. 6.
   It is not yet known when Barry was called to testify.
</TEXT>
