<FIRST>r w PM-US-Terrorism 1stLd-Writethru a0446 01-19 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Terrorism, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Corrects spelling of intefadah in grafs 2, 3</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   US Possesses Tape of Reported Arafat Threat
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says it has obtained a
tape recording of Yasser Arafat, the chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, threatening anyone who tries to stifle the
uprising on the Israeli-held West Bank.
   According to spokesman Charles E. Redman, the PLO leader said
last week: ``Whoever thinks of stopping the intefadah before it
achieve its goals, I will give him 10 bullets in the chest.''
   Intefadah is the Arabic word for the 13-month uprising by
Palestinians against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Redman said Wednesday that Arafat has since denied he intended
any threat against Elias Freij, the mayor of Bethlehem who is
considered a moderate Palestinian and was the purported target.
   The U.S. official gave no indication the United States was
reconsidering its decision to hold talks with the PLO. The decision
was taken last month after Arafat made a statement renouncing
terrorism in all forms and recognizing Israel's right to exist.
   At the time, Richard W. Murphy, the assistant secretary of state
for the Near East, said the ``substantive dialogue'' would be broken
off if Arafat reneged on his pledge.
   After Arafat's reported threat, Secretary of State George P.
Shultz, who had recommended the U.S. talks with the PLO, said ``we
will observe behavior as the process proceeds.''
   ``Threats against people who try to move in a calmer and more
peaceful direction are acts of intimidation and fall much more into
the terrorism category,'' Shultz said.
   At the same time, Redman criticized a reported decision by
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin to take tougher measures
against Palestinians who attacked soldiers on the West Bank and in
Gaza.
   He called the reports ``very disturbing, if true.''
   On other subjects, the State Department deplored the
proliferation of biological weapons capability and issued a new
report slamming Libya as a sponsor of terrorism.
   Citing intelligence sources, Redman said a number of nations were
bent on developing this ``particularly horrible form of warfare.''
   William H. Webster, the director of the Central Intelligence
Agency, said in a speech last October that at least 10 countries
were working to produce biological weapons.
   It was understood Iraq was one of the countries identified by
U.S. intelligence sources as having a biological weapons program.
However, a U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Wednesday ``it is not 100 percent certain yet.''
   Redman said he could not identify ``individual cases'' for
security reasons.
   Meanwhile, the department's office to counter terrorism reported
that Libya continued to support terrorism in 1988 despite a public
posture of moderation.
   The report, ``Libya Unchanged,'' said Libya also had participated
directly in at least one operation in Senegal and that Libyan
operatives were active worldwide, especially in Africa, Latin
America and the Caribbean.
   The Abu Nidal Organization, a Palestinian group with its
headquarters in Libya, has resumed terrorist operations with
``deadly consequences'' and several other groups supported by Libya
conducted terrorist operations against U.S. and Western targets, the
report said.
   The United States bombed Tripoli in April 1986 after linking
Libya to the bombing of a night club in West Germany frequented by
American servicemen. Subsequently, the Reagan administration said
the attack had the effect of dampening Col. Moammar Gadhafi's use of
terrorism.
   The new report said the Libyan leader ``has eventually resumed
his violent ways'' and that Libya was ``squarely in the ranks of
state sponsors of terrorism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
