<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     01-19 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Problems Solved; Way Cleared For Feb. 23 Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The engine and tile problems of the
last space shuttle mission have been resolved and the Discovery
probably will be launched into orbit on Feb. 23, said the director
of the Kennedy Space Center.
   ``We feel we have a good understanding of those problems and can
move ahead,'' Forrest S. McCartney told reporters Wednesday.
   Atlantis returned from orbit last month with severe damage to
about 200 of 28,000 tiles that protect it from re-entry heat. And
during post-flight inspection, two small cracks were found in a
bearing unit in a high-pressure engine turbopump.
   The tile damage resulted when insulation hit the shuttle during
liftoff after stripping away from both the external fuel tank and
the nose cone of one of the solid fuel booster rockets, McCartney
said.
   The fuel tank was the oldest one ever flown on a shuttle, it had
gone through some earlier test fueling cycles and some of its
insulation had been repaired before flight, he said.
   ``We feel we don't have those problems with the next tank because
we have better bonding which we have subjected to pull tests,''
McCartney said.
   The nose cone insulation has been strengthened, he said.
   Engineers believe the bearing cracks were caused by stress
corrosion, apparently resulting from moisture that somehow got into
the metal, McCartney said.
   He said the problem appears to be unique to Atlantis' turbopump
and that inspection of Discovery's turbopumps have cleared them for
flight.
   Discovery is set to make the third shuttle flight since the
explosion of Challenger three years ago. During five days in orbit,
the five-man astronaut crew is to deploy a communications satellite,
conduct experiments and photograph damage that man and nature have
caused to the Earth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
