<DOCNO> AP890119-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia-Premier 2ndLd-Writethru a0549 01-19 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-Premier, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0549,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ante Markovic, Croat, Nominated New Yugoslav Premier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more on reforms favored by Markovic
and price increases announced today. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ante Markovic, former head of Croatia
and an ardent supporter of radical market-oriented reforms, was
nominated today as Yugoslavia's new premier, the state Tanjug news
agency reported.
   The nomination by the nine-member federal presidency must be
formally approved by the country's parliament at an upcoming session.
   Markovic, 64, will succeed Branko Mikulic who, together with his
entire Cabinet, resigned Dec. 30. It was the first time since the
ruling communists took power after World War II that a federal
government had stepped down.
   Mikulic's government had failed to solve the country's myriad
social and economic ills, including a 250 percent annual inflation
rate and a $21 billion foreign debt. Even as Markovic was nominated
today, prices increases were announced on more than 300 goods and
services.
   Markovic, an electrical engineer successfully managed two of
Yugoslavia's largest engineering firms, has often advocated radical
market-oriented changes in the economy and demanded simultaneous
reforms in its political system, including a ``pluralism of ideas''
within the existing political structure.
   A record nearly 1,400 strikes were officially registered last
year amid public calls for the introduction of a multiparty system
as a solution to the protracted Yugoslav crisis.
   The Yugoslav presidency decided in favor of Markovic rather than
Borisav Jovic, a Serb, who was the only other official candidate for
the post.
   The decision is seen as an affront to Serbia's hardline Communist
Party president Slobodan Milosevic. Jovic, speaker of Serbia's
parliament, is a close political ally of Milosevic.
   Serbia has claimed the post should go to its candidate since the
largest of Yugoslavia's six republics has not had a premier in 22
years.
   The presidency's nomination of Markovic also means reformist
elements in the Communist Party have won a clear victory over more
conservative and dogmatic factions.
   The brief Tanjug dispatch did not indicate how the vote in the
nine-member presidency was conducted, or thge margin of Markovic's
victory. Before his nomination, Markovic enjoyed the support of
Yugoslavia's liberal and developed northern republics of Slovenia
and Croatia.
   Jovic was supported by the poorer and more conservative southern
regions that fear radical market-oriented reforms could result in
the closure of state-subsidized factories, massive layoffs and
further social unrest.
   In Yugoslavia, the federal government is generally responsible
for economic policy while the collective presidency, which appoints
the premier, dictates defense and foreign policy.
   But the bulk of political influence in the country is
concentrated in the Communist Pparty, with power dispersed in eight
often fractious central committees, reflecting the administrative
division of the country into six republics and two autonomous
provinces.
   The government essentially follows guidelines set by the party
bodies that must themselves hammer out a consensus before any
policies can be implemented.
   The government announced price increases today for 300 goods and
services, including a 30 percent boost in the price of gasoline and
diesel fuel.
   The national petroleum company attributed the increase to a 36.62
percent depreciation of the dinar against the U.S. dollar since the
last fuel price increase on Nov. 12, which makes foreign oil
purchases more expensive.
   Yugoslav workers earn the equivalent of about $80 a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
