<DOCNO> AP890119-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Cuba     01-19 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Cuba,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba, China Open Historic Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Isidoro Malmierca of Cuba arrived
in Beijing tonight for the first visit of a Cuban foreign minister
to China.
   Earlier today, the Xinhua News Agency reported that China's
foreign minister, Qian Qichen, has accepted an invitation to travel
to Cuba.
   Qian was quoted by Xinhua as saying Malmierca's visit to Beijing
would contribute significantly to Chinese-Cuban ties.
   Malmierca arrived a day later than scheduled. It was not clear
why the visit had been delayed.
   In an interview in Bucharest, Romania, Qian said Malmierca
invited him to Cuba and that he had accepted. It would be his first
visit to Latin America. No dates have been set.
   China and Cuba established diplomatic relations in 1960 but
relations with Cuba and the rest of the Soviet bloc remained chilly
for two decades due to China's split with the Soviet Union.
   When Beijing and Moscow began to improve ties in the early 1980s,
China and Cuba started cultural and other non-political exchanges. A
trade agreement was signed in 1985.
   Two-way trade jumped from $179 million in 1986 to $300 million in
1988, Xinhua reported. Prospects for further development are
limited, however, because the economies of China and Cuba are too
similar. Both export large quantities of raw materials and are
interested in importing high technology.
   Still, a ministerial level meeting on trade and commerce was held
recently in Beijing bectween Cuba and China. Qian said that meeting
marked a new beginning for economic cooperation.
</TEXT>
