<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Nutrition 1stLd-Writethru a0522 01-19 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Nutrition, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nutrition Care Urged For AIDS-Infected People and Those With AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs editor's note at end of story to clarify reference to brochure.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People infected with the AIDS virus should
correct bad dietary habits even before AIDS symptoms appear, a
nutrition task force says.
   Early corrective steps ``may slow weiht loss and avoid
nutritional complications'' seen in full-blown AIDS, the guidelines
say.
   Diet alone cannot cure AIDS, and scientists do not yet know
whether proper nutrition truly affects the course of the disease,
cautioned Myron Winick, chairman of the task force that produced the
guidelines.
   But experience with other conditions suggests it may help, said
Winick, professor of nutrition and pediatrics at the Columbia
University College of Physicians and Surgeons in New York.
   ``We hope that the course of this disease can be a little better
and that the quality of life can be improved if we pay attention to
nutrition, and we start paying attention right from the beginning,''
he said in a recent interview.
   The 11-member task force included representatives from the
National Institutes of Health, universities and hospitals. Its
guidelines on nutrition and AIDS were intended for health care
personnel.
   Infected but symptom-free people should be assessed for
nutritional deficiencies and counseled about the value of proper
diet in AIDS, the guidelines say. The person's nutritional reserves
can then be built up before they contend with the disease, Winick
said.
   People with AIDS may have mouth pain, difficulty swallowing,
diarrhea, nausea, loss of appetite and other symptoms that interfere
with proper nutrition, but they can take steps to ease the problems,
the task force said.
   For example, avoiding foods that are spicy, acidic or very hot or
cold may help in avoiding mouth pain, the task force said. Foods
with a single texture are easier to swallow than others, while
eating with a friend in a pleasant atmosphere may encourage a
flagging appetite.
   The task force was financed with a grant from Norwich Eaton
Pharmaceuticals Inc., which makes a nutrition formula that can be
used in AIDS patients with bowel troubles, Winick said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A task force brochure on nutrition for people
with AIDS will be available from Wang Associates Inc., 19 W. 21st
St., New York, N.Y., 10010.
</TEXT>
