<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HeartOperation 1stLd-Writethru a0511 01-19 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart Operation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Heart Operation May Cure Common Cause of Strokes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13 graf, `During the ...' to clarify that electrical signal
regulates heart beat.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new kind of surgery can correct a
common heart rhythm abnormality that is the underlying cause of
225,000 disabling strokes in the United States each year, its
developer said.
   The experimental procedure cures a disorder known as atrial
fibrillation, which affects an estimated 1.5 million to 2 million
Americans.
   Although the strokes that result from this problem can sometimes
be prevented with blood-thinning drugs, that treatment is often
ineffective and may itself cause unwanted bleeding.
   The new technique was developed by Dr. James L. Cox of Washington
University School of Medicine, who described it Wednesday at a
meeting of the American Heart Association. Slices are made in the
atria, the two upper pumping chambers of the heart.
   Cox has performed the operation so far on three people, and all
of them have been completely free of the disorder since their
surgery. However, more work will be necessary before doctors can
estimate how widely the operation will be used.
   ``I think we have a definitive treatment for people with atrial
fibrillation,'' said Cox.
   ``It's a remarkable step forward,'' commented Dr. Myron L.
Weisfeldt of Johns Hopkins University, who is president-elect of the
association.
   The surgery corrects chaotic beating _ fibrillation _ of the
atria. During fibrillation, the chambers stop orderly beating, and
this disrupts the flow of blood through the heart.
   As a result, blood tends to form clots inside the left atrium,
and these sometimes break off and flow into the brain. There, they
can plug arteries and shut off the flow of blood, causing strokes.
   To combat the problem, doctors often give anticoagulants, which
slow the body's natural tendency to form blood clots.
   However, Dr. Louis R. Caplan of New England Medical Center in
Boston said that doctors suspect this treatment may do more harm
than good.
   ``It's a huge problem,'' said Caplan, a stroke expert. ``The
question is which, if any, patient should have anticoagulants and
which, if any, should have this procedure.''
   During the 45-minute surgery, doctors make four slices in the
atria. This keeps the electrical signal that regulates the heart
beat flowing across the heart muscle in just one direction so it
doesn't become chaotic.
   ``This operation proves that you can deal with the problem of
chaotic traffic (inside the heart) by creating one-way streets,''
said Weisfeldt.
   Cox said it is still unclear how many of the 225,000 potential
annual victims of strokes resulting from atrial fibrillation might
be treated with the new operation. He said it is most likely to be
used in patients who are already undergoing heart surgery for other
problems.
   He said he has been cautious in expanding the operation, which
was first developed experimentally in dogs. But he said there is a
waiting list of 14 patients who want to receive it at his hospital.
   Cox said one goal will be to find ways to reduce the time it
takes to perform the operation, perhaps by using using lasers
instead of ordinary surgical knives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
