<DOCNO> AP890119-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LymeDisease     01-19 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lyme Disease,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Town with Nation's Highest Lyme Disease Concentration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of Lyme disease that struck one-third
of the people who lived near a Massachusetts wildlife preserve could
happen anyplace in the northern United States where deer are
plentiful, researchers say.
   In a study released today, doctors found that the disease spread
explosively near the preserve in Ipswich, Mass., after the deer herd
became infested with bacteria-carrying ticks.
   ``This appears to be a model for what might happen in other
locations in which the abundance of deer is undergoing a rapid
increase,'' said Dr. Andrew Spielman of the Harvard School of Public
Health.
   Lyme disease is a potentially serious illness that can cause a
variety of seemingly unrelated symptoms, including a rash,
headaches, facial paralysis, heart complications and arthritis.
However, it can be cured if treated early with penicillin.
   About 1,500 cases were reported last year to the U.S. Centers for
Disease Control, but officials estimate that the true total is
probably five times that. The disease is spread by ticks that feed
on the blood of white-tailed deer and field mice, but also will bite
humans.
   In the new study, doctors recorded the spread of the disease
among 190 people who lived along one road that connected the town of
Ipswich with the Crane Memorial Reservation and Wildlife Refuge. The
1,400-acre ocean-side nature preserve was already a haven for deer
before the outbreak began in about 1980.
   ``There were a lot of deer there, and once the ticks had arrived,
the transmission was really explosive,'' said Dr. Catherine C.
Lastavica. ``It was very intense in a short period of time.''
   The epidemic peaked in 1984 and 1985, athough people there
continue to catch Lyme disease. Experts believe that insecticides,
limited deer hunting in the reserve and increased awareness of ticks
have helped diminish the disease.
   Altogether, 35 percent of the area's residents got the disease
between 1980 and the end of 1987. Among those living closest to the
wildlife preserve, the attack rate was 66 percent, the researchers
found.
   The study, conducted principally by Lastavica of Tufts University
School of Medicine, was published in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
   The researchers said that until now, the most intense reported
outbreak was on Great Island off West Yarmouth on Cape Cod between
1979 and 1983. There, 16 percent of 162 summer residents got the
disease.
   Spielman said the disease has the potential to be widespread
anyplace north of the Mason-Dixon line that has deer. In the South,
he said, the disease probably will remain uncommon, perhaps because
ticks there feed on lizards, which are poor reservoirs for the bugs.
   Lyme disease has been seen in 34 states, but is most common in
New England, the mid-Atlantic states, Minnesota, Wisconsin, and
California.
   The disease was first recognized by Dr. Allen Steere, now of New
England Medical Center, in Old Lyme, Conn. Steere published a report
on Lyme disease in 1976 and gave the illness its name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0098 </DOCNO>
