<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Observe General Strike, One Youth Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Palestinian youth killed, 21 wounded.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier shot a Palestinian teen-ager
to death today as the youth urged on stone-throwers at a refugee
camp in the occupied Gaza Strip, the army and Arab reports said.
   Twenty-one Palestinians were reported wounded in scattered
clashes with Israeli troops in the Gaza Strip and occupied West
Bank, including 10 who were shot after attacking the home of an
alleged Palestinian collaborator.
   The violence came as West Bank residents staged a general strike
to protest an upsurge in Palestinian deaths. Fourteen Arab youths
have been killed in clashes with the army in the past week.
   The strike order came two days after the army instituted a
tougher policy that allows soldiers to fire plastic and rubber
bullets more freely and provides for harsher punishment for
stone-throwers.
   The military government also closed 84 of the West Bank's 1,200
schools today in an effort to block violent protests. The schools
were shut down for periods of three days to four weeks.
   In the Gaza Strip's Shati refugee camp, a soldier shot
18-year-old Mohammed Dahaise ``after he was identified as an
inciter'' of a stone-throwing attack on troops, said an army
spokeswoman.
   She said Dahaise, who was from nearby Gaza City, was killed
instantly. Arab hospital officials said he was shot in the head.
   His death brought to 363 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
began in December 1987. Fifteen Israelis also have died.
   In the West Bank village of Arraba, residents stoned the home of
a man suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities, Arab
witnesses said. The man emerged from his home with a pistol and shot
four of the stone-throwers, the witnesses said.
   Palestinians in the occupied lands are barred from bearing
firearms, but those cooperating with the authorities often are
issued weapons for self-protection.
   After the stoning attack, Israeli troops arrived and opened fire,
wounding six villagers, including a 10-year-old boy who was in
critical condition with a bullet in the head, hospital officials
said.
   The army spokeswoman confirmed the account, but said without
elaborating that ``several'' villagers were wounded.
   The strike in the West Bank, accompanying one already under way
in the Gaza Strip, was called Wednesday by the PLO-backed Unified
Leadership of the Uprising. But word of the strike spread slowly and
it was not fully observed until today.
   Israeli reports said leaflets calling for the shutdown were
circulated, but Palestinians in the West Bank said they saw none and
only heard of the strike on Arab-language radio from abroad or by
word of mouth.
   Some merchants in the West Bank town of Bethlehem opened their
shops today at 8 a.m., as usual, and only shuttered their doors
after neighbors told them about the strike.
   Hundreds of students walked to school but turned back after
hearing about the strike, Arab reporters said.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest and most militant city,
students headed for school were turned back by Palestinian youths
whose faces were covered by keffiyehs, the checked Arab scarves that
have become a symbol of the uprising.
</TEXT>
