Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport for a scheduled stop during
a flight from Los Angeles to West Palm Beach. Delta officials said
the actress was belligerent and used offensive language when flight
attendants asked her to put her two Shih Tzu dogs, Genghis Khan and
Macho Man, back into their carriers.
   In the lawsuit, Ms. Gabor said she ``was not treated in a
first-class manner'' by the ``servants and employees'' of the
airline. She said Delta was negligent in taking her money for four
tickets _ for herself, an assistant and the dogs _ and then failing
to deliver her to her destination.
   The lawsuit also said William D. Berry, Delta's vice president
for public relations, defamed Ms. Gabor when he told reporters that
she had ``insulted the Atlanta agents with vulgarities'' and used
words that were ``less than ladylike.''
   Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate called the lawsuit ``quite
interesting but totally unwarranted.''
