<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-East-WestTalks 1stLd-Writethru   01-19 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East-West Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0573,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says Soviets To Dismantle Some Short-Range Nuclear Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with U.S. reaction, details on weapons to be removed.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze said today the Soviet Union will withdraw some of its
short-range nuclear missiles from Eastern Europe.
   Shevardnadze said a security and human rights accord approved
Sunday by 35 nations attending a Vienna meeting made the move
possible. He said the missiles will be pulled out along with troops
being withdrawn from Eastern Europe.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced in December that
50,000 Red Army troops would be pulled out of Eastern Europe over
the next two years, but he made no mention of planned missile
withdrawals.
   Shevardnadze made the announcement to foreign ministers at the
conclusion today of the Conference on Security and Human Rights in
Europe.
   Stephen Ledogar, the U.S. ambassador to new arms talks scheduled
to open in Vienna in March, described Shevardnadze's speech as
``upbeat'' and in general an encouraging sign for relations between
NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Robin Stafford said, ``If this
signals that ... the Soviets are now beginning to realize that their
potential far exceeds legitimate requirements, we can only find such
steps encouraging.''
   But Stafford added, ``Certainly questions must be answered. Which
systems will be removed? How many? To where? And what happens to
them then? In any event, Soviet superiority seems certain to remain
for some time.''
   Saying that ``truth must be visible,'' Shevardnadze said the
Soviet Union should publish by the end of the month a detailed
schedule of its armed forces reductions.
   He said the Soviet Union has long offered to negotiate removal of
its short-range nuclear weapons and promised to withdraw them from
Europe as part of the Kremlin's ``fundamental objective of removing
any foreign military presence and bases from the territory of other
countries.''
   Short-range missiles, also known as tactical or battlefield
weapons, have a range up to 300 miles and are not covered in the
1987 arms accord signed by President Reagan and Gorbachev. That
agreement was to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear weapons, with
a range up to 1,500 miles.
   In a brief exchange with reporters after his speech, Shevardnadze
made clear that only those short-range weapons attached to military
units being withdrawn from Eastern Europe will be removed and
dismantled without conditions.
   Shevardnadze said he could not say what percentage of the
Kremlin's short-range stockpile would remain deployed. He called on
the West to negotiate removal of the remaining missiles as soon as
possible.
   Ledogar repeated the U.S. position that negotiations on the
remaining short-range missiles should be set only when some progress
has been made toward balancing the two sides' conventional forces,
such as tanks and artillery.
   ``We don't want to abandon the nuclear leg of the deterrent until
we have a much better situation on conventional forces,'' Ledogar
told The Associated Press.
   NATO believes the Warsaw Pact has a substantial edge in
conventional weapons.
   Referring to recent NATO statements that modernization of the
West's short-range nuclear missiles is possible, Shevardnadze said
the Kremlin regards those plans as ``a step backward'' in arms
control.
   Shevardnadze said the Kremlin foresees a summit meeting of the
leaders of all 35 countries participating in the Vienna meeting as
necessary.
   On Sunday, the nations approved an accord that includes agreement
on a new round of arms talks to reduce conventional weapons and
troops across Europe. Those talks are to begin in Vienna on March 9.
   The accord also put forth a sweeping definition of human rights
to be protected, including freer travel and religious practice,
environmental protection and economic cooperation.
   In his wide-ranging speech today, Shevardnadze paid tribute to
his departing American counterpart, Secretary of State George
Shultz, but he criticized comments made by Shultz and other Western
foreign ministers as ``fault-finding,'' full of accusations and
hazardous to the general spirit of trust and cooperation embodied in
the Vienna accord.
   Shevardnadze praised the accord as an achievement born of
cooperation and an indication of hope for the future.
   ``The Vienna meeting has shaken up the Iron Curtain, weakened its
rusty support, made new breaches in it and hastened its corrosion,''
Shevardnadze said.
   Also today, Italian Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti announced
that Gorbachev will make an official visit to Italy in November.
   No Soviet Communist Party chief has ever visited Italy and
analysts said the visit could set the stage for a historic meeting
with Pope John Paul II. The Vatican has always said the Pope would
be open to such a meeting.
</TEXT>
