<FIRST>r w PM-BRF-Salvador-Medals     01-19 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF-Salvador-Medals,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Command Denied Recommendation of Decoration for El Salvador Military
Advisers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Southern Command denied a
recommendation a year ago that two military advisers assigned to El
Salvador receive a decoration for their performance during a brief
firefight with guerrillas, the Pentagon said today.
   The incident, publicized Thursday by the Miami Herald, occurred
on Feb. 16, 1988, in the small town of Usulutan, where two U.S.
Marine trainers were residing next to a Salvadoran military base.
   That section of the town came under attack by leftist guerrillas
during the night and the two Marines ``simply protected themselves''
against small arms fire, said Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon
spokeswoman.
   After the action, the Marines' commander recommended the two for
the Combat Action Ribbon, saying he thought they had performed well
and kept their composure under fire. The U.S. Southern Command in
Panama, however, the parent command, ``denied the recommendation
with no reason given,'' Wood said.
   The Herald described the incident as previously unpublicized.
Wood said she did not think an account of the fighting had appeared
in the press, but said Congress had been notified of the incident on
Feb. 18, 1988, as mandated by federal law.
</TEXT>
