<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlaying     01-19 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slaying,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Programmer To Stand Trial In Wife's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been ordered to stand trial
on charges he masterminded the killing of his wife at the hands of
his teen-age daughter and then urged the girl to take blame for the
murder.
   David A. Brown, 36, was scheduled to be arraigned on murder
charges Feb. 2 in Superior Court in Santa Ana in the 1985 shooting
death of Linda Brown, 23, the defendant's fourth wife.
   Brown, a computer programmer, is accused of ordering his
then-14-year-old daughter, Cinnamon Brown, to kill his wife _
Cinnamon's stepmother _ so he could collect on his wife's life
insurance policy and be free to marry his wife's live-in sister.
   Cinnamon Brown, who had spent three years in a juvenile facility
after she was convicted of murder, told investigators recently that
her father was behind the murder, authorities said.
   After a three-week preliminary hearing, Municipal Court Judge
Floyd H. Schenk ruled Wednesday there was sufficient evidence to
bind Brown over for trial. Brown was held without bail in Orange
County Jail.
   Schenk also found there was enough evidence to support a special
allegation of murder for profit, which means that Brown could face
the death penalty if convicted.
   Brown admitted he told his daughter to take the blame for his
wife's killing and showed Cinnamon how to write a suicide note and
fake her own death after the slaying, a videotaped interview shows.
   But the tape also shows that Brown told investigators after his
arrest in September that he thought talk of a plot to kill his wife
was a ``joke'' and couldn't believe the girl and his sister-in-law
were serious about the killing.
</TEXT>
