<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev-Italy     01-19 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Italy,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Officials: Soviet Leader to Visit Italy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East-West Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will
visit Italy in November, but he probably won't meet with Pope John
Paul II, Italian officials said today.
   Gorbachev's plan to visit Italy was announced by Italian Foreign
Minister Giulio Andreotti after he met with his counterpart Eduard
Shevardnadze.
   The two were attending the 35-nation Helsinki review conference.
   The announcement immediately raised speculation Gorbachev might
see the Polish-born pontiff. But Vieri Traxler, the Italian envoy to
the international Helsinki review conference, told The Associated
Press he did not know of any plans for Gorbachev to see the Pope
during the visit to Italy. ``It would be surprising if Gorbachev did
(meet with the pope),'' said Traxler.
   Relations between the Vatican and the Soviet Union have been
warming in recent months. Soviet officials participated last year in
official ceremonies marking the 1,000th year of Russian Christendom.
   In previous meetings, the Vatican told Soviet officials the pope
would be open to a meeting with the Soviet leader. However, after
Gorbachev met with Vatican officials in Moscow in June, he said much
must still happen before the pope can visit the Soviet Union, which
is officially atheist.
   Soviet officials in Moscow reviewed Gorbachev's schedule and said
he could go to Italy in the second half of November, according to
Traxler.
</TEXT>
