<FIRST>r w PM-Reagan-Farewell 1stLd-Writethru a0430 01-19 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Farewell, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagans, White House Staff Bid Teary Farewell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, White House, to correct word to your sted our</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is a time of tears and farewells at the
White House as the eight years of the Reagan administration near
their end.
   On Wednesday, there were wet eyes galore in the East Room as
hundreds of White House staffers turned out to say farewell to the
president and first lady Nancy Reagan.
   On Friday, just before going to the Capitol for President-elect
Bush's inauguration, the Reagans will repeat the scene in a private
meeting with the household staff at the presidential residence.
   ``These are people that have served the president and first lady
for eight years, in most cases, in the residence,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. ``They will talk personally and
privately Friday morning.''
   If it's anything like Wednesday's event in the East Room, it will
be an emotional affair.
   The get-together began with cheers and applause from the
estimated 350 to 400 aides as the president and first lady entered.
   White House Chief of Staff Kenneth Duberstein, who was a White
House lobbyist in the beginning of the Reagan years, spoke for the
staff, telling the Reagans, ``You have allowed us to be part of your
lives and you are very much a part of ours.''
   Gifts were given: riding tack for the president, an avid
horseman; a gold and enamel box for the first lady's box collection;
and even a replica of the White House for the presidential dog, Rex.
   ``He's already taken over this White House,'' said the president.
``I'm glad he's got one of his own now. And you know something? He
doesn't get kicked out of it after two terms.''
   In a more serious vein, Reagan told his aides, ``We were all
revolutionaries, and the revolution has been a success.''
   Elaine Crispen, Mrs. Reagan's press secretary, said, ``We have
been proud to call you our first lady, or Nancy, or, as that taxi
driver in New York said, `a real classy broad,' but it's been
awfully nice to call you a friend.''
   When it came the first lady's turn to speak, the tears that had
been welling in her eyes were coursing down her cheeks.
   ``Elaine said I should say something, but I'll never get through
it,'' she said. ``See?''
   Then she just said, ``Thank you,'' and she and the president made
their way through the room to the Cross Hall of the White House,
shaking hands and exchanging hugs with well-wishers as they went.
   It was the second sentimental occasion for the president in one
afternoon.
   Earlier, he met with the championship Notre Dame football team,
renewing a tie with the school that began with his role as gridiron
star George Gipp in the movie, ``Knute Rockne, All-American.''
   ``My life has been full of rich and wonderful experiences,'' the
77-year-old president said. ``And standing near the top of the list
is my long and honored association with the University of Notre Dame
and its legendary hero Knute Rockne.''
   Then, paraphrasing the line from the movie that has become his
political watchword, he said:
   ``Right now, I can't help but think that somewhere, far away,
there's a fellow with a big grin and a whole lot of pride in his
school. And he might be thinking to himself that maybe you won
another one for the Gipper.''
</TEXT>
