<FIRST>r a PM-People-Weaver     01-19 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Weaver,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Oregon Congressman Declares Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Jim Weaver has filed for
bankruptcy in federal court, listing debts of $254,975 and assets of
$1,710.
   Another $4,100 of assets, including personal property and a
rental deposit in a San Francisco apartment, is listed as exempt
from bankruptcy proceedings.
   In his filing, Weaver gives a Eugene address as his home. He said
he lost another home to foreclosure by the state Department of
Veterans' Affairs.
   Weaver could not be reached for comment. His attorney, Thomas
Huntsberger of Springfield, said the legal filing was under Chapter
7 of federal bankruptcy provisions. He described it as a ``straight
liquidation bankruptcy.''
   Weaver, a Democrat, served as Oregon's 4th District
representative from 1975 to 1987.
   In 1986 he began a campaign for the U.S. Senate seat held by Sen.
Bob Packwood, R-Ore., but dropped out of the race amid an ethics
investigation into his handling of $82,000 he borrowed from his
campaign fund.
   Weaver said he lost the $82,000 in unsuccessful securities
investments in an effort to make money for his campaign fund. A
House committee found that Weaver violated House rules in handling
the funds but recommended no disciplinary action, saying Weaver
never intended to avoid public disclosure of the funds.
   In Tuesday's bankruptcy filing, Weaver said he owes $6,000 in
1987 federal income taxes and $3,200 in state income taxes for 1987.
   Weaver listed his 1987 income as $23,500 and said his current
monthly net pay is $1,612.
</TEXT>
