<FIRST>r a PM-DeliveryDiscovery     01-19 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delivery Discovery,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pizza Delivery Man Makes Surprising Discovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pizza deliveryman found more than a
hungry customer at one apartment _ his own stolen telephone and
stereo equipment.
   ``It was just blind luck, really,'' David Copeland, 21, said
after he got most of his property back this week.
   On one of his deliveries last week, the customers demanded a
discount because, they said, the pizza was late.
   Copeland said he had to check with his boss, and when the
customers showed him to a telephone in the bedroom he recognized the
phone as his own.
   ``I could see where my programmed numbers had been erased on
it,'' he said. ``Then I turned around and saw all my equipment
sitting there on the floor, in the same order as it was in my stereo
case.''
   The Florida State University junior decided to get out of the
apartment as fast as he could.
   ``It was tough to do, but I figured that if I let on to them that
would be really stupid. I gave them a $5 discount and left.''
   He called police, who arranged to go back with him the next night.
   ``It was really hard to keep from getting all my friends and
going back over there and getting my stuff back,'' Copeland said.
   The apartment's resident, Charles Barnes, 22, told police he
bought the equipment from a man who said he was a student who needed
money for Christmas, Copeland said.
   The theft remains under investigation.
   Copeland got a bonus: his stero receiver had been broken when it
was stolen, but when he got it back it had been fixed.
</TEXT>
