<FIRST>r a PM-Bundy-Tapes     01-19 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Tapes,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tapes Reveal Various Sides of Bundy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned killer Theodore Bundy once
complained that he felt like a ``caged animal'' in jail and said he
didn't want to hear about the widespread calls for his execution.
   Bundy reveals himself as variously impatient, sarcastic,
emotional and analytical in a series of tape recordings subpoenaed
by Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth in his attempts to prove
Bundy sane and ready for the electric chair.
   Bundy is scheduled for execution Tuesday in the 1978 death of
12-year-old Kimberly Leach. He also is under Florida death sentences
for the murders of two college students and has been suspected in as
many as 36 killings or disappearances of women, mostly in the
Northwest.
   In one excerpt from the self-recorded tapes, published today in
the St. Petersburg Times, Bundy reflected on public sentiment for
his death on the morning after his conviction in Miss Leach's
killing.
   ``The news is on,'' he said. ``They said the father of Kimberly
Leach wanted Bundy to have the electric chair. He didn't say whether
he wanted me to have a Lazy Boy or some other sort of vibrating
chair. ...
   ``I do take it personally when I hear it broadcast that people
want me killed. I know there are a lot of people with that opinion.
I'd just as soon not hear it, thank you.''
   In an earlier segment, Bundy expressed anxiety while awaiting a
verdict in the case.
   ``I am pacing this cell in the classic manner of a caged
animal,'' he said, his footsteps echoing across the floor. ``I hate
this waiting. ... It's like knowing that you are going to be struck
by lightning, but not knowing whether you are going to be struck in
five seconds or five hours.''
   After he was sentenced to death, Bundy recorded another segment.
``I wouldn't really say I am despondent,'' he said. ``But clearly I
am extraordinarily disappointed.''
   Bundy made the tapes for two authors writing a book about him.
</TEXT>
