<FIRST>r i PM-Bulgaria-France     01-19 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria-France,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Meets With Bulgarian Human Rights Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand of France
met today with a group of Bulgarian human rights activists who asked
for Western support in the face of persecution by communist
authorities.
   The group of 12 intellectuals were invited to have breakfast with
Mitterrand at the French ambassador's residence in the Bulgarian
capital.
   The 12 included prominent Bulgarian scientists, writers, artists
and journalists. Most were members of the Club for the Support of
Glasnost amd Perestroika, which was formed in November 1988 and now
has about 150 members.
   One member of the group, 65-year-old Alexei Cherlutko, an
academic, delivered a letter to Mitterrand that said police have
harassed the group.
   Mitterrand made a strong call for more human rights when he spoke
Wednesday evening at a state banquet presided over by President
Todor Zhivkov.
   ``National sovereignty, representative democracy, separation of
powers, freedom and respect for individuals: These values have lost
nothing of their actuality,'' Mitterrand said.
   Members of the group he met with today and French officials said
several human rights activists from Plovdiv, Bulgaria's
second-largest city, were prevented by communist authorities from
traveling to Sofia.
   Authorities detained about two dozen activists in Plovdiv last
week. They were released after French diplomatic intervention but
were placed under house arrest, French officials said.
   Zhivkov, in an interview published in the French daily Le Monde
on Wednesday, said 25 people were arrested. He described them as
common criminals.
   Describing today's session with Mitterrand, science professor
Nikolai Vassiliev told reporters, ``I am delighted with the meeting.
We discussed the problems in our social development.''
   ``We want our society to become more humanized and to find its
place in the European house, mentioned by (Soviet President Mikhail
S.) Gorbachev.''
</TEXT>
