<FIRST>r a PM-NitroLeak     01-19 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nitro Leak,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Confined Indoors After Chemical Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud of chemical vapor poured from a
shuttered plant this morning, forcing the residents of a 19-block
area to be confined to their homes for more than an hour,
authorities said.
   No injuries were reported, said state police Sgt. A.G. Angus.
About 2,500 of the 8,000 residents in the town were affected.
   Thionyl chloride, which leaked from a ruptured drum, is an
irritant, according to U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
spokesmen. The EPA has had control of the shut-down Artel plant
since June and evacuated downtown residents last fall to destroy a
chemical drum there.
   The federal Department of Transportation's emergency handbook
says thionyl chlordie can be poisonous if inhaled or swallowed.
   Used in the manufacture of pesticides, thionyl chloride can cause
``severe burns to skin or eyes,'' said state police spokesman Ric
Robinson.
   Reporters and photographers in Nitro said they became teary-eyed
after driving through the cloud.
   EPA officials earlier this summer called the plant ``a potential
emergency'' because of the thousands of drums of unidentified _ and
possibly hazardous _ chemicals stored there.
   Harold Yates, an EPA spokesman in Philadelphia, Pa., said the
leaking gas was in a 55-gallon drum.
   ``I could see the cloud earlier,'' said Don Mellert, who lives
about 800 yards from the Artel Chemical plant and was among
residents asked to stay inside. ``It looked like real thick smoke.''
</TEXT>
