<HEAD>Father Jailed For Allegedly Killing Wife, Beating Toddler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-month-old girl who authorities say
was bludgeoned by her father with an empty champagne bottle was in
critical condition today on life-support equipment, hospital
officials said.
   Doctors were waiting for results of tests to determine whether
Natalie Alexandra Lynch was brain-dead, said Dr. Donald Dicus, vice
president of medical affairs at Western Medical Center.
   Alexandra was found by officers early Tuesday in the arms of her
dead mother, who police say was also beaten by Joseph Peter Lynch, a
43-year-old electrical engineer and youth soccer coach.
   Lynch was being held at Orange County Jail after he admitted to
police that he killed his 35-year-old wife and critically wounded
his daughter, said police spokeswoman Maureen Thomas.
   Natalie's condition had not improved by early today, said nursing
supervisor Betty Chrisco.
   Two other daughters, Holly, 9, and Angela, 4, were found asleep
and unharmed in a bedroom of the house. The girls, who apparently
have no adult relatives in the United States, were taken to
Orangewood, the county's home for abused and neglected children.
   Lynch is a Scottish citizen and Mrs. Lynch is from Australia,
said Lt. Randi Ellridge. Police know of no previous trouble with
Lynch, who was involved in church, school and social activities.
   ``It was just one of those bolts from the blue,'' Ellridge said.
   Lynch was being held in lieu of $250,000 bail and was scheduled
for arraignment Friday on murder and attempted murder charges.
