<HEAD>Closing Arguments Set at Steinberg's Murder Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing statements; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for a man accused of killing his
illegally adopted daughter accused his former live-in lover today of
causing the injuries because she considered the 6-year-old girl a
rival.
   ``She didn't care about the kid a bit, not one bit,'' Adrian
DiLuzio, an attorney for Joel Steinberg said in a closing statement
to the jury. He also called Hedda Nussbaum ``a poor excuse for a
woman and a mother.''
   ``Lisa Steinberg was a rival,'' DiLuzio said in state court in
Manhattan. ``Lisa got all the attention she (Nussbaum) thought she
should have been getting.''
   Steinberg, 47, is accused of beating Lisa Steinberg to death.
Lisa, whom Steinberg illegally obtained at birth, was removed
unconscious from Steinberg's apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She died of
a brain injury three days later. Steinberg, a disbarred criminal
lawyer, is charged with second-degree murder.
   The prosecution has argued that Steinberg severely beat the girl,
then acted with reckless and depraved indifference to her life by
letting her lie unconscious on the bathroom floor for 12 hours
without seeking help.
   Defense attorney Ira London blames the girl's death on the
prosecution's chief witness, Ms. Nussbaum, 46, Steinberg's former
live-in companion of 12 years.
   London argues that Ms. Nussbaum, who testified Steinberg told her
he struck Lisa and ``she didn't want to get up,'' was jealous of the
relationship between Steinberg and Lisa, giving her a motive to
fatally injure the child.
   Ms. Nussbaum reached a deal with prosecutors in which similar
charges brought against her were dropped in exchange for her
testimony.
   During closing arguments, London planned to review and interpret
the bulk of the case for the defense while most of the medical
testimony was to be summarized and analyzed by DiLuzio.
   The prosecution presented a case that was almost entirely
circumstantial, with no eyewitnesses and no direct physical evidence
that Steinberg killed Lisa.
   Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro was to present the
prosecution's closing arguments.
