<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths Sub a0548 01-19 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, Sub, a0548,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to insert reference to cause of death, organized
crime allegations, murder plots and conviction that was later overturned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Irving Resnick</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving ``Ash'' Resnick, a longtime gaming figure
credited with bringing high rollers to the Las Vegas Strip, died
Wednesday. He was 72.
   Resnick died of heart failure at 1:45 a.m., said Humana Hospital
Sunrise spokeswoman Ann Lynch. He had been hospitalized after a long
bout with cancer.
   His forte was bringing high rollers to Las Vegas casinos for
high-stakes gambling, and he organized the first junkets that later
became a fixture to the casino trade.
   Resnick's Las Vegas career spanned four decades and included
stints at Caesars Palace, the Aladdin, the Dunes, the Tropicana, the
old El Rancho and Thunderbird hotels, and most recently the Maxim
Hotel.
   He was credited with starting the first baccarat game at the
Dunes. Baccarat is now featured at most Strip hotels.
   In 1974, Resnick was convicted of income tax evasion while
employed at Caesars Palace. The government alleged that Resnick
skimmed more than $300,000 from Caesars and failed to pay taxes on
it. The decision was later overturned.
   He also was troubled by allegations he had organized crime
associates and twice was the apparent victim of murder plots. In
1974, eight sticks of dynamite were found under his car and two
years later he was shot at while leaving Caesars Palace.
   Resnick, a former star basketball player at New York University,
also brought big-time boxing shows to Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
