<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   01-19 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0579,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WARSAW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Walesa Cautious On Party's Offer To Legalize Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with Walesa comments. Changes byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa today said the government's
offer to legalize Solidarity does not go far enough but that
officials had made progress toward recognizing the independent union.
   Walesa, the leader of Solidarity, said he was awaiting the
official text of the Communist Party statement, which outlines
conditions for legalization, before revealing his final position on
the offer.
   When pressed by reporters at St. Brygida's Church in the port
city of Gdansk, Walesa said: ``It is a lot for this party ... But it
is too little for social demands and expectations.''
   But he said: ``We can't destroy this possibility (of true union
freedom) but at the same time we shouldn't struggle for some
ambitious details.''
   Walesa spoke at his first news conference since the Communist
Party Central Committee cleared the way for the legalization of the
trade union federation, outlawed since 1982.
   As Walesa concluded his discussion, Poland's leader, Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski, was beginning a rare meeting with reporters in
Warsaw to discuss the developments from the party meeting.
   ``Our offer is honest and serious,'' Jaruzelski said in his
opening statement. ``I count on the fact that taking it up
constructively will allow ... a historical step in Poland's
development. That is what we all desire.''
   During an acrimonious debate, the Central Committee spent two
days devising conditions for restoring legal status to Solidarity _
Poland's most potent opposition force and the only independent labor
movement ever allowed in the Soviet bloc.
   Jaruzelski offered to resign as Communist Party leader and head
of state after encountering heated opposition to the plan, but he
then received a vote of confidence from the 230-member Central
Committee.
   The government, switching course after seven years spent trying
to eliminate Solidarity, now is seeking the organization's help in
battling Poland's severe economic problems and reforming its
political system.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski has offered to legalize
Solidarity for a two-year trial on condition it declare support for
socialism, observe a strike moratorium and give up Western financial
aid, which has exceeded $1 million a year. He recommended the offer
so long as the union agrees to act as a partner, not a ``political
opponent.''
   The resolution passed 143-42.
   Solidarity was formed in Gdansk in 1980, crushed in the
martial-law crackdown of 1981 and declared illegal the following
year.
   ``We cannot give up our independence and our sovereignty,''
Walesa said. ``If we blow it here, other people will have to deal
with the same problem again. I don't want my son and his generation
to live through such things again where it accumulates rocks and
then explodes.''
   He added, ``Conditions in Poland give enough justification to
everyone of us to strike.
   ``Everyone will be justified because the situation is so bad. But
reason shows that this leads nowhere.''
   Adam Michnik, a senior adviser to Walesa, called the plenum ``a
step forward'' and said the conditions put forth by the party are
viewed as ``a matter for discussion.''
   ``For the first time they announced at a plenum that the
legalization of Solidarity can be the subject of talks. That is new.
For the first time we have a declaration of intentions,'' Michnik
said.
   Opposition leaders have said Solidarity must be legalized before
they will sit down with the government for comprehensive talks that
were proposed during a wave of labor strife in August.
   ``Let us see,'' Michnik said when asked if Walesa now would join
in those oft-delayed talks. He called the party's new position ``a
very essential step'' but said the road ahead still is ``very
complicated.''
   Walesa said he saw as a sign of good faith from the government an
invitation to speak at two legal rallies in Warsaw next week, one at
the university. He said management at the Lenin Shipyard where he
works received an official request that he be excused for the events.
   Walesa said he will address workers at the shipyard during a
rally Friday and then speak again with reporters.
   The full text of the party's position paper on union and
political freedom is expected to be printed in Friday's newspapers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
