<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Press     01-19 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Press,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Press Corps Marks End of Reagan Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters said farewells Thursday at the last
White House press briefing of the Reagan administration.
   ``Working in the White House is about history,'' said spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater, who stays on as press secretary in the Bush
administration.''
   ``Long after the stories of the day are forgotten, we will
remember our history together on a personal basis,'' he said.
   All seats in the briefing room were occupied, unusual in the
waning days of the administration with reporters focusing the
president-elect.
   Fitzwater noted that some of the correspondents had covered the
White House for the full eight years of the Reagan administration or
longer and that many would be back again. But he added that one
thing was sure to change.
   ``We will never again be bound by the personality, character or
decisions of Ronald Reagan,'' said Fitzwater. ``We will never judge
ourselves and each other by those perspectives again.''
   Fitzwater paid tribute to the reporters, saying, ``You have been
tough, unrelenting, thoughtful and aggressive, yet we have all had a
hell of a lot of fun, and I still think the White House press corps
is the best.''
   He also praised assistant press secretary Mark Weinberg and
Connie Gerard, who has managed the office for 2 those dinners and she'll
probably be at more, so
maybe it's more fitting that we honor her here in the pits where she
has labored for so long.''
</TEXT>
