<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Family 1stLd-Writethru a0443 01-19 0958</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Family, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush: Look at Me Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Mrs. Bush's comments in top 11 grafs, picking up
in 4th graf pvs, Mrs. Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush won cheers and laughter today from
audiences that packed three theater halls to hear her joke about her
appearance and her husband's fishing.
   Mrs. Bush apeared at the ``Salute to the First Lady,'' an event
that more than 6,000 people paid $50 a ticket to attend.
   So many people came to the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts along the Potomac riverfront that Mrs. Bush made
three separate appearances _ in the Concert Hall, the Opera House
and the Eisenhower Theater.
   Known for her wit and for not putting on airs, Mrs. Bush stood on
one stage and told the audience, ``Please notice _ hairdo, makeup,
designer dress. ... Look at me good this week.''
   Dressed in a blue suit with a big patterned bow at her neck, Mrs.
Bush said she was ``a little nervous'' as she stumbled over the name
of National Symphony Orchestra music director Mstislav Rostropovich.
   Then she proceeded to joke abbut her husband's comments on how
tedious it has been for him to pack up in preparation for the move
to the White House.
   Noting he spent two days fishing last week in Florida, Mrs. Bush
said, ``So much to the packing story.''
   Mrs. Bush was introduced by Marilyn Quayle, the wife of the vice
president-elect, whose voice cracked as she described the new first
lady as a woman of ``gentleness and kindness and indomitable
spirit.''
   ``I'm going to get weepy,'' Mrs. Quayle said.
   In earlier comments, Mrs. Bush has said the feelings she has
about her husband's inauguration are like those she experienced
before her wedding day 43 years ago: She's excited but she's nervous.
   ``I'm still pinching myself,'' said Mrs. Bush, who becomes the
nation's first lady on Friday, the day George Bush is sworn in as
the 41st president.
   Mrs. Bush, a 63-year-old grandmother whose trademark is her white
hair and the three-strand choker of fake pearls, has said jokingly
that she's going to be a new kind of role model for American women.
   ``My mail tells me that a lot of fat, white-haired, wrinkled
ladies are tickled pink,'' she said in an interview with a group of
newspaper reporters last week.
   Mrs. Bush also talked about how she intends to be an activist,
promoting literacy and the needs of children, the homeless and AIDS
victims.
   But the soon-to-be first lady, known for her blunt-spoken manner
and self-deprecating sense of humor, said she doesn't plan to meddle
in her husband's business even though she's ``very candid'' about
speaking her mind.
   ``That's why we do so well,'' she said. ``I don't have to talk to
his staff. I talk to him.''
   After the election, she accompanied her husband on vacations to
Florida and Maine, but she declined to go to Texas for a
quail-hunting trip after Christmas so she could sort through her
things.
   ``Barbara's busy packing,'' Bush said. ``She's like a little girl
going off to college _ I tease her about that too.'' Bush often
refers affectionately to his wife as ``Bar.''
   Mrs. Bush said she became quite nostalgic packing up the vice
president's house, a gracious Victorian set on a hill at the Naval
Observatory a few miles from the White House. She called the move
``agony.''
   The Bushes spent Wednesday night at Blair House, the newly
renovated presidential guest quarters where they'll stay until they
go across the street to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue on Friday.
   To give their new house a lived-in feeling, Mrs. Bush has invited
her mother-in-law, Dorothy Bush, 87, her five grown children and
their spouses and her 10 grandchildren to spend the first night in
the presidential mansion.
   ``There are going to be people everywhere,'' said Sondra Haley,
Mrs. Bush's spokeswoman.
   All told, 230 Bush relatives will be in the nation's capital for
the inaugural festivities. When they leave town, the Bushes will be
alone at the White House except for Millie, the couple's
brown-and-white spaniel who is expecting puppies soon.
   Despite the hassles of moving, the Bushes have done so many times
before: They've lived in 28 houses and 17 cities since their
marriage near her hometown of Rye, N.Y.
   The couple, high school sweethearts, met at a Christmas dance
when she was 16 and he was 17. Mrs. Bush, the daughter of the
publisher of McCall Corp., dropped out of Smith College after two
years to marry the future president 43 years ago after he returned a
World War II hero from the Pacific theater.
   Unlike Nancy Reagan, Mrs. Bush has no plans to renovate the White
House's public areas. Mrs. Reagan spent about $1 million
refurbishing the public rooms in 1981. The Bushes, however, will
receive $50,000 to redo their living quarters.
   The Reagans, parents of four children, spent little time with
their family at the White House, but the Bushes are a tight-knit
family and will probably see their progeny more often.
   Only one son, though, Marvin, 32, lives in the Washington area.
He is an investment consultant.
   Bush's oldest son, George Jr., 42, an oilman in Midland, Texas,
worked on his father's presidential campaign as well as in the Bush
transition office as a volunteer. He is one of his father's close
advisers.
   Married with twin 6-year-old daughters, the younger Bush once ran
unsuccessfully for Congress in Texas.
   The other Bush children are Jeb, 35, a real estate developer in
Miami; Neil, 33, in the oil business in Denver; and Dorothy LeBlond,
29, of Cape Elizabeth, Maine, who has frequently worked in her
father's campaigns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
