<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   01-19 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0607,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Rally On 5th Day Of Public Dissent</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with rally broken up by police.
Pickup 4th pvs, `On Sunday...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of baton-wielding riot
police today violently broke up a crowd of more than 2,000 people
who rallied to demand freedom for jailed dissidents and more human
rights in Czechoslovakia.
   Chants of ``Gestapo! Gestapo!'' rang out as white-helmeted riot
police charged the crowd about 30 minutes after it gathered,
swinging their batons indiscriminantly. More than a dozen protesters
appeared badly beaten and at least 10 were taken away by police.
   Water cannons were brought onto Wenceslas Square but were not
used.
   Wenceslas Square has been the site of five straight days of
rallies, which began Sunday to commemorate the 20th anniversary of
Jan Palach's death. Palach committed suicide by setting himself
afire Jan. 16, 1969 to protest the Soviet-led invasion of
Czechoslovakia.
   Dissidents said today authorities had detained a human rights
activist and informed at least two others they will be prosecuted in
connection with demonstrations Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday.
   The public display of dissent is unprecedented since the weeks
after the 1968 invasion.
   About 15 minutes after today's rally began, a police van with a
megaphone asked the crowd to disperse, telling people they were
taking part in an illegal demonstration.
   Riot police poured into the half-mile-long square from
sidestreets when protesters refused to leave, charging the crowd and
pushing them along the boulevard.
   On Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, police used water cannons, dogs,
truncheons and tear gas to break up crowds.
   Vaclav Maly, a signatory of the Charter 77 human rights document,
said activist Martin Palous was detained by police at his home
today. Palous addressed Wednesday's rally, reading a Charter 77
protest of arrests made during the earlier rallies.
   On Monday, activists Vaclav Havel and Jana Sternova were arrested
when they tried to lay flowers in memory of Palach. A prosecutor
informed activists that those two will face hooliganism charges,
Maly said. He said the charge carries a maximum jail sentence of two
years.
   Another activist, Jiri Dienstbier, said dissident Jana Petrova of
the Independent Peace Association also will be prosecuted. There
were no details on the charges. Petrova spoke at an unofficial rally
in December.
   Families of three other people detained Monday said they were
informed the detainees face charges of obstructing the duty of an
officer, which carries a maximum penalty of six months.
   In an unusual move, the names and addresses of all 14 people
detained Monday were published by the state-run media. Communist
authorities accused the dissidents and the Western media of
fomenting unrest.
   The Communist Pary daily Rude Pravo said Wednesday night that ``a
cluster of about 1,000 people in the upper half of Wenceslas Square
made the usual everyday traffic impossible.''
   ``The purpose of this unauthorized gathering was also this time
evident from chanted slogans attacking the Socialist system and its
leading representative,'' Rude Pravo said.
   At one point Wednesday, several hundred people took up a chant of
``Jakes Out,'' referring to Communist Party leader Milos Jakes.
   ``Initiators of such actions want to destabilize our society,
create pressure on the Socialist state,'' Rude Pravo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
