<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiChronology 1stLd-Writethru a0561 01-19 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Chronology, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of Miami Troubles in Super Bowl Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 19th graf, ``12:30 a.m., arrest total ...' to CORRECT figure
to 325 arrests; SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT to 30 arrests.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Miami Riot, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology detailing the eruption of
racial violence in Miami:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MONDAY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _6:05 p.m, off-duty police Officer John Mervolion is sitting in a
marked patrol car when he spots two black men on a motorcycle
speeding into Overtown.
   Mervolian turns on blue lights and chases the motorcycle, but the
driver, Clement Anthony Lloyd, 23, doesn't stop, police say. Three
blocks away, Officer William Lozano hears call for assistance and
realizes the motorcycle is heading toward him.
   Lozano, 29, fires once, hitting Lloyd in the head, Lang said. The
bike veers across the center line and smashes into a car. Lloyd is
killed. His passenger, Allen Blanchard, 24, is hospitalized.
   _7:30 p.m., Mayor Xavier Suarez and City Manager Cesar Odio
arrive at scene with more police and try to calm the rapidly growing
crowd.
   _8 p.m., police, reporters and officials retreat under a hail of
rocks and bottles.
   _8:20 p.m., all off-duty officers and police supervisors are
called in as mobs roam the streets, smashing windshields, burning
vehicles, looting some stores and occasionally firing weapons.
   _Shortly before 10 p.m., police in riot gear fire tear gas, then
withdraw to a 17-by-9-block perimeter.
   _Midnight, police say area is mostly calm.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TUESDAY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Morning, police suspend Lozano with pay pending an investigation
into whether he used excessive force.
   _1:30 p.m., a white motorist fires into a crowd of blacks in
Overtown and drives away. Teen-ager is wounded, hospitalized.
   _4:10 p.m., Blanchard dies of head injuries from the collision,
hospital officials say.
   _5 p.m., police in Overtown shoot person alleged to be a sniper
in the leg.
   _7 p.m., a man is shot in the thigh in a gun battle between two
men in a store and a gang of looters, authorities said. Police are
fired upon as they try to rescue him but manage to get him out.
   _8 p.m. to 11:10 p.m., police tell residents of Overtown and
Liberty City to remain indoors and begin a block-by-block sweep.
Looting and fires reported at stores in Liberty City. Police wound
Liberty City man apparently firing at police. Police officer is shot
in bulletproof vest. Teen-ager is fatally shot in argument in
Liberty City, and a man is arrested on first-degree murder charges.
Two other people are shot and wounded.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WEDNESDAY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _12:30 a.m., arrest total reaches 325.
   _Toward dawn, calm enables police to ease presence in Overtown
and Liberty City.
   _8 a.m., traffic blockades remain in parts of Overtown; most
roads open in Liberty City.
   _ 11:45 a.m., Miami commissioners meet in emergency session, and
vote to appoint investigative panel of five police officers and five
Overtown residents, with Suarez as chairman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THURSDAY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _1 a.m., streets quiet except for a few instances of arson and
rock and bottle throwing.
   _6 a.m., police report about 30 arrests made in past 12 hours in
Overtown and Liberty City.
   _8 a.m., street cleaning crews and sweepers move into Overtown
and Liberty City.
</TEXT>
