<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--TajMahal     01-19 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Taj Mahal,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spots on Taj Mahal Blamed on Restoration Material, Not Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spots marring the Taj Mahal probably came
from material used to restore the 17th century monument, not from
pollution, news reports said Thursday.
   Scientists had thought the black and yellow spots were caused by
chemical pollutants discharged from a refinery near the Taj Mahal in
the northern city of Agra.
   However, O.P. Agrawal, director of the National Research
Laboratory for the Conservation of Cultural Property, said
accumulating dirt and material used to restore the monument were to
blame, according to the United News of India.
   The study pointed to polymer resin used to renovate the monument
a few decades ago as a likely source of the problem.
   Builders completed the Taj Mahal, ordered by Shah Jahan as a
mausoleum for a favorite wife, in 1653.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugHouse     01-19 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug House,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Couple To Lose Home Used As Drug Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly couple who claimed they were
unaware their grandson had turned their home into a base for drug
trafficking have agreed to sell the house and split the proceeds
with the government.
   A 1987 raid on the house turned up nearly $50,000 worth of
marijuana and cocaine and a cache of weapons, including a loaded
Israeli assault rifle and riot police shotguns.
   The couple had fought forfeiture, but their attorney said
Wednesday they were satisfied with the settlement that forces the
sale and gives them half the proceeds because the house had ``too
many bad memories.'' A 1984 federal law allows the seizure of
property used in drug trafficking.
   The couple, Paul Derbacher, 79, and Ruth Derbacher, 82, had
shared their house with their grandson, Julian Derbacher, 23. He is
serving a 15-year sentence on drug charges related to the raid and
on unrelated arson and robbery convictions.
   The grandson and the couple's son, Paul Derbacher Jr., were the
targets of an investigation that led to the raid. Paul Jr. used his
parents' home in Hamden as a ``stash house'' for drugs, but he was
not charged in the case, according to court records.
   Prosecutors said drugs were in plain view in almost every room
and that the Derbachers could not have failed to notice.
   The Derbachers were granted accelerated rehabilitation on state
charges of possession of marijuana and cocaine and possession with
intent to sell. If they complete probation, the criminal charges
will be erased.
   Under the settlement, the U.S. Marshal Service will hire
contractors to fix up the property, now valued at $175,000. Robert
Casale, attorney for the couple, said the house had been ``trashed''
by the grandson.
   It could then sell for about $250,000, Casale and prosecutors
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
