<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignGuests     01-19 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Guests,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Leaders Urged to Steer Clear of Inaugural Festivities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday it has
instructed American displomats to discourage foreign leaders from
attending the inaugural festivities swirling through Washington this
week.
   Their regular ambassadors will represent foreign countries at the
inauguration Friday on the Capitol steps. The envoys then will go by
bus the two miles to Blair House, the place where presidential
guests stay, across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House.
   There they will view the parade from reserved seats.
   Government officials fine tuning the arrangements were describing
the seats among themselves as ``the ambassadors' bleachers.''
   Blair House itself was the site of a reunion between Bush and the
World War II submariners who rescued him when the Japanese downed
his plane in 1944.
   Unlike many other countries, the United States does not
ordinarily invite foreign leaders to the installation of a new
administration, said Richard Gookin, associate chief of protocol at
the State Department.
   In contrast, Vice President-elect Dan Quayle has been named to
represent the United States at the inauguration Feb. 3 of Carlos
Andres Perez as president of Venezuela. Leaders from Latin America
and throughout the world are expected to attend.
   Gookin said a Dec. 15 memo to U.S. diplomatic missions told
American diplomats to ask that special delegations not be sent to
the inauguration. It cited the essentially American nature of the
occasion, lack of accommodations and a desire to keep events simple.
   As many as 300,000 people are expected in Washington for the
weekend. On Wednesday night the inaugural dinner _ price: $1,500 a
plate _ had to be held in three different sites, with Bush making an
appearance at each. Advocates of the poor and homeless set up a
``counter-banquet'' at one site.
   There will be dozens of balls and other events.
   Costs are being paid largely by private companies and
arrangements are made by a private committee, which counters
criticism that public money is being spent on social entertainment
rather than social needs.
   According to Gookin, the mmessage told from the State Department
told the American diplomats to assure other governments that
ambassadors in Washington and their wives would be accommodated.
</TEXT>
