<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FaxAttacks     01-19 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fax Attacks,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Wants Ban On Unsolicited Fax Messages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state legislator is going on the
offensive against ``fax attacks'' _ unsolicited advertising received
over facsimile machines.
   Rep. Richard Tulisano, chairman of the Judiciary Committee, said
Wednesday he has proposed a bill banning the use of fax machines to
send unsolicited ads.
   ``As fax machines become more prevalent, they become a vehicle
for unsolicited advertisements, thereby tying up not only your
machine but using your papers, all your fluids, and all that
stuff,'' said Tulisano, who added that he planned to buy a fax
machine soon.
   Fax machines permit users to send and receive copies of documents
over telephone lines.
   A legislative research report on Tulisano's bill found that
facsimile paper costs up to 10 cents a page.
   Donna Murdoch, executive director of the American Fascimile
Association in Philadelphia, which publishes a newsletter for
facsimile users, said the debate over ``junk fax'' is much ado about
nothing.
   ``We ask people, `How many pieces of junk fax are you really
getting?''' she said. ``And people say the most they can remember
getting is two pieces in a week.''
   Mr. Fax, a company based in Irvine, Calif., sells facsimile
supplies via unsolicited fax ads. ``We think this is a very
low-cost, convenient method of marketing,'' said Elliott Segal, vice
president for marketing.
   Segal said laws against unsolicited fax messages would ``punish
the entire fax population for something that has generated
relatively few complaints.''
