<FIRST>r a PM-SeattleMayor     01-19 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seattle Mayor,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Mayor Charles Royer Won't Seek Re-election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Charles Royer announced today that he will
not seek a fourth term and said he had no specific plans for the
future.
   Royer, 49, a former journalist who was elected mayor in 1977, won
re-election in 1981 and an unprecedented third term in 1985. His
office is up for election again in November.
   ``All I have ruled out is running for elective office in the
immediate future,'' he said. ``I do know this: I love public
service. It's fulfilling and I'm pretty good at it.''
   Royer said, ``I love this job,'' but that he needs new challenges
and new growth after serving 12 years as mayor of the Northwest's
largest city, which has about 500,000 residents.
   Royer, a Democrat, listed some of his accomplishments and looked
to the future.
   ``In 1989, we must reduce contention and division over growth and
build consensus on how we grow,'' he said. Royer also said the city
must continue the fight against drugs and ``invest more in our kids'
future.''
   The mayor, accompanied by his wife, Rosanne, said he leaves a
city government that is fiscally strong.
   Royer's lone venture into statewide politics was in 1983, when he
ran for the U.S. Senate seat left vacant by the sudden death of Sen.
Henry Jackson that September. Royer finished second among Democrats
in that special election to Congressman Mike Lowry, who eventually
lost to Republican Dan Evans.
   Before entering politics, Royer was a newspaper and television
journalist in Oregon and Seattle. He is a University of Oregon
graduate.
</TEXT>
