<FIRST>r w AM-BakerConfirmation     01-19 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker Confirmation,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Darman Confirmation, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baker Wins Panel's Endorsement; Floor Vote Due Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee, in a
strong show of bipartisan support, voted 19-0 Thursday to recommend
the Senate confirm James A. Baker III as secretary of state.
   The Senate is expected to approve the Baker nomination, possibly
unanimously, in a roll call vote next Wednesday.
   Baker, 58, who served President Reagan as White House chief of
staff and secretrary of the Treasury, is one of President-elect
George Bush's closest friends and managed his 1980 and 1988
presidential campaigns.
   In two days of testimony this week, he displayed a comprehensive
grasp of foreign policy issues, issuing a strong call for a new era
of bipartisanship as the keystone to success.
   He said this was especially true in Central America, where
wrangling between the Reagan White House and Congress led, Baker
said, to stalemate and a distinct lack of success in dealing with
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   On a note of caution, Baker said the United States should
exercise restraint in its relations with the Soviet Union, viewing
the domestic, foreign policy and defense changes being made by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev with prudence and realism.
   He endorsed the general outlines of Reagan administration foreign
policy while sidestepping questions about any specific changes Bush
may make or specific initiatives he may undertake.
   After the panel's unanimous vote, committee members hailed Baker
in high terms.
   The chairman, Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said the vote
represents ``approval for Baker as a man, a belief in him as an
experienced and able public servant.''
   Pell said the vote did not indicate that the committee's
Democratic majority will agree with Baker on every foreign policy
issue over the next four years.
   ``But we are certainly starting out on a more even keel'' Pell
said.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said he believes the unanimous
nature of the vote represents ``a bipartisan approach to the new
administration.''
   Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., said of Baker, ``He's one of the all
time Washinagton greats.''
   ``I am very optimistic he is going to be an outstanding secretary
of state,'' said Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md. ``He has diplomacy,
restraint and carefulness. I think he's the kind of person that
would work very well with Congress.''
</TEXT>
