<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MSGene     01-19 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MS Gene,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Evidence Finds Heredity Plays Role in Multiple Sclerosis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least two genes play a role in the
development of multiple sclerosis, a finding that supports earlier
studies that susceptibility to the crippling disease is powerfully
influenced by heredity, a researcher said Thursday.
   Dr. Dale E. McFarlin, a researcher at the National Institute of
Neurological Disorders and Stroke, said he and colleagues at the
California Institute of Technology and the University of California
in Los Angeles have found that certain combinations of T-cell
receptor genes occur more often in MS patients than in healthy
people.
   ``What this suggests is that there is a genetic component in MS,
but there is more than one gene,'' McFarlin said in a telephone
interview.
   McFarlin said that though the study shows heredity may increase a
person's susceptibility to MS, the disease ``is not purely
genetic.'' Other components, as yet unknown, also must be present
for multiple sclerosis to develop, he said.
   Multiple sclerosis is a disease of unknown origin that attacks
the tissue covering nerves in the brain and spinal column. This can
result in vision disturbances, weakness and eventually crippling
disability. No successful treatment for the disease has been found.
   McFarlin said earlier studies showed a gene that reacts to an
antigen called DR2 may play a role in multiple sclerosis. Now, the
new study shows that a combination of genes that help build the
T-cell receptor also is involved in the disease.
   The T-cell is a disease-fighting cell produced by the immune
system. Molecules on the surface of the T-cell, called receptors,
lock onto antigens, which are molecules recognized by the immune
system as foreign bodies, such as germs.
   McFarlin said that the new study has shown that patients who have
an abnormal combination of T-cell genes plus an elevated level of
DR2 antigen are three times as likely to develop MS as healthy
people without these genetic characteristics.
   The study focused on a group that includes the T-cell genes, said
McFarlin, but the specific gene in that group that plays a role in
MS has not been identified.
   ``More work needs to be done on that,'' he said.
   The study was published in the Journal of Neuroimmunology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
