<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WetlandsProtection     01-19 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wetlands Protection,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Pledges to Protect Wetlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Thursday it will try to keep the nation from losing any more swamps,
marshes and other wetlands, a conservation goal President-elect Bush
endorsed during the campaign.
   Any unavoidable losses should be ``fully offset by wetlands
restoration or creation,'' the agency said.
   Such a goal was recommended last November by a study group led by
New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean under the sponsorship of the
Conservation Foundation. Bush had earlier said the nation should aim
for a ``no net loss'' wetlands policy.
   Since then, Bush has chosen William Reilly, the foundation's
president, to head the EPA.
   The agency said it would step up enforcement of existing water
pollution laws dealing with wetlands, cooperate more closely with
other federal agencies and encourage the states to develop
protection programs.
   Much wetlands decision-making is in the hands of the states and
local governments. The principal federal power is the authority of
the Army Corps of Engineers to grant permits for putting fill in
waterways and wetlands, a process over which the EPA has certain
veto powers.
   The agency can delegate those powers to the states; so far only
Michigan has been granted that authority.
   Gail Bingham, vice president of the foundation, said, ``We are
delighted'' with EPA's new policy.
   Thought for generations to be nothing more than the breeding
grounds of disease, wetlands today are recognized by
conservationists as an important cog in nature's machine, playing
important roles in water purification and storage; as a habitat for
wildlife, including many endangered species, and in the productivity
of marine life, including commercially important species.
   The study group noted, however, that wetlands often are sought by
developers as the only close-in land to large urban areas.
   Of the 200 million acres of fens, bogs, marshes, estuaries,
swamps and other wetlands in the United States at the time of
settlement by Europeans in the 17th Century, about half remain.
   There are no good estimates of how much is lost each year. One
widely cited estimate of 450,000 acres annually was made in the
1970s, when farmers were believed to be bringing more wetlands under
the plow than they are now. The Conservation Foundation uses a range
of 200,000 acres to 450,000 acres.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Inaugural-BoysChoir     01-19 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural-Boys Choir,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inaugural Choir Recalls Harlan County Labor Strife of 1930s</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They yawned, they squinted, they fidgeted and
they sang _ 76 boys with voices like angels, rehearsing Thursday for
the three-minute performance that will put their county on the map.
Again.
   More than 50 years after coal mining union battles left the
legacy of Bloody Harlan, the Harlan (Ky.) Boys Choir stood on the
West Front of the Capitol singing ``This Is My Country'' in
four-part harmony.
   ``Bass and tenor, you need to tone down a bit. Sing away from
that mike,'' director David Davies barked at his boys, a bunch of
10-to-19-year-olds in jeans, sneakers and bright green boys choir
jackets.
   ``You were shifting your feet. You were moving your eyes. And
you're scratching your noses!'' he shouted incredulously. ``Don't
scratch your noses''
   It was a jarring note of reality in the fairy tale of how the
24-year-old choir won a place in the brief inaugural ceremony, a
slot normally reserved for star entertainers or hometown favorites
of the president-elect.
   While the final decision was up to George Bush, it didn't hurt
that the chairman of the inaugural proceedings is Sen. Wendell Ford,
D-Ky.
   ``I've been kin to you for a long time,'' Ford told the boys
before their run-through in the midday sun. In 1972, as governor, he
gave them $5,000 from a contingency fund for a trip to compete in
Graz, Austria. This year, he's playing proud host and Dutch uncle.
   Told that the choir raised $51,000 for its trip to Washington,
more than twice its $25,000 goal, Ford commented: ``See what
charisma you have? What drawing power? Now fellas, don't think it's
going to be that easy in the real world.''
   They've been all over the country, as well as to Europe, but the
boys and parents agree: this trip tops all.
   ``This is the zenith. It's just awesome. The boys just can't
believe it,'' said Dawn Nunez, the finance chairman, whose
17-year-old son Matt has been in the choir for eight years.
   ``Everything's larger than life. It doesn't seem real because
there's so much history,'' said choir president Richard Atkins, 17.
``I'm a little more relaxed than I thought I would be,'' said Seth
Spoelman, 14.
   All the boys are from Harlan County's 1,200-student school
system. They come from all racial and economic backgrounds, the sons
of insurance agents and coal miners as well as doctors and lawyers.
   ``We've got football players, basketball players. This is the in
thing to do at our school,'' said Mrs. Nunez. ``It's not considered
a sissy thing,'' agreed Roy Allison, the choir's business manager.
   Mrs. Nunez, who was in charge of raising money for the choir's
trip, said her job was easy. ``We didn't even have to ask. Many
donations weren't even solicited,'' she said. ``People know that we
have met our goal and they're still sending in money.''
   The biggest contribution was $5,000 from The New York Times, she
said. The Kentucky governor gave $3,000 and a few anonymous donors
gave $1,000 apiece, she said, but most of the money came in small
chunks from local businesses and residents.
   ``Music is a big thing in the hills of Kentucky,'' she said.
``Whenever the choir does something, the community gets behind it.''
   ``It's supposed to be a mean place. Bloody Harlan, it's been
called. We've never been able to live that down,'' said Allison.
``But I couldn't tell you when there was a mugging in Harlan, when a
woman was raped, when there was an armed robbery in Harlan. You'd be
perfectly safe walking down our streets. You might not see much, but
you'd be safe.''
   Harlan remains coal country, and boys graduating from the choir
each receive a coal miner's hard hat. But the choir's inaugural
appearance has already drawn a different kind of attention to Harlan.
   Networks and filmmakers are doing reports and documentaries not
about union violence but about a group of disciplined boys who will
sing beneath five U.S. flags for the new president of the United
States.
   Said Allison: ``This is the most significant thing ever to happen
to Harlan, Ky.''
</TEXT>
