<DOCNO> AP890119-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OathofOffice     01-19 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oath of Office,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twice as Many Words for the No. 2 Guy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAUL PETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As every school kid must know by now, George
Bush will repeat a 35-word oath to become president of the United
States at noon Friday.
   As probably few school kids know, Dan Quayle will recite a
70-word oath to become vice president. Both oaths say substantially
the same thing, but the vice president is required by law to take
twice as long saying it.
   The difference would suggest that the framers of the second oath
might have been more suspicious or, at least, more nervous about new
vice presidents than new presidents. Thus, they spelled out
conditions in greater detail for the second man and insisted he
invoke God's help.
   In none of this could they have had Dan Quayle in mind. The
presidential oath was written 202 years ago in the Constitution. The
vice presidential oath comes in a law that evolved through several
congressional statues over more than 100 years.
   The president must say: ``I do solemnly swear (or affirm) that I
will faithfully execute the office of president of the United
States, and will to the best of my ability, preserve, protect and
defend the Constitution of the United States.''
   The vice president, according to the inaugural committee, must
say: ``I do solemnly swear that I will support and defend the
Constitution of the United States against all enemies, foreign and
domestic; that I will bear true faith and allegiance to the same;
that I take this obligation freely, without any mental reservation
or purpose of evasion; that I will well and faithfully discharge the
duties of the office on which I am about to enter. So help me God.''
   Quayle should have no trouble with the wording. He has taken a
similar oath twice as senator.
   The careful reader will note that the vice president is more
circumscribed than the president. The president may affirm if he
doesn't choose to swear solemnly. (So far, only Franklin Pierce in
1853 chose to affirm.)
   The vice president has no choice. He has to swear solemnly or not
get the job, not legally.
   Nothing in the Constitution or subsequent law says the president
of the United States can't be an agnostic or atheist. He does not
have to say, ``So help me God.'' Most presidents since George
Washington have said that as a matter of custom or choice.
   The vice president is given no choice. He must say ``so help me
God'' or he risks unemployment. His oath doesn't even specify the
job he is promising to faithfully execute.
   But Congress took no chance and left him as little room as
possible. He must swear and forswear for the job that Harry Truman
thought was ``as useful as a cow's fifth teat'' and Alben Barkley
called ``a spare tire on the automobile of government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
