<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From one first lady to another, Rosalynn
Carter has a bit of advice for Barbara Bush.
   ``I would tell her to do whatever she wants,'' Mrs. Carter said
Wednesday. ``She's going to be criticized no matter what she does,
so she should do things that she thinks are important.''
   Mrs. Carter spoke at Lander College as inaugural week activities
for President-elect Bush got into full swing in Washington.
   In a speech to about 200 participants in a workshop on ``Women in
Leadership,'' Mrs. Carter also said women have ``wonderful
opportunities, but we still have to work out how they fit in with
traditional women's responsibilities.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Papandreou has agreed to grant a
divorce to her husband, Premier Andreas Papandreou, newspapers
reported Thursday.
   ``My personal affair with the prime minister has ended,'' said
the American-born Mrs. Papandreou. ``There remains only the
legalization of the separation, which I'm trying to get over and
done with as quickly as possible.''
   The 60-year-old premier, who is living with girlfriend Dimitra
Liani, 34, announced his intention to dissolve his 37-year marriage
shortly before undergoing heart surgery three months ago.
   Mrs. Papandreou, 66, revealed her intentions in remarks to the
Women's Union of Greece, the nation's biggest feminist organization.
She is a founding member.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She was fired from her first radio job, but
Jessica Hahn isn't giving up on her broadcasting career just yet.
   Ms. Hahn, the former church secretary whose sexual liaison with
Jim Bakker led to the PTL evangelist's downfall, is scheduled for an
on-air audition Friday on WANS-FM.
   ``There's a chance she'll come to work here. We're putting her on
the air to see what our listeners say,'' said Bill McCown, WANS
operations manager.
   As part of the promotion, Ms. Hahn has agreed to a chaperoned
dinner with the listener who calls in the most clever request before
her visit.
   Ms. Hahn spent five months as a morning personality on KOY-FM in
Phoenix, but the station refused to renew her contract when it
expired last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian director Lina Wertmuller has assembled an
international cast for a new English-language film on AIDS and the
news media.
   Wertmuller said Thursday that Faye Dunaway, Rutger Hauer and
Nastassja Kinski will star in the film, whose working title is ``Of
Crystal or of Ash, of Fire or of Wind, Because it's Love.''
   ``But the definitive title we will see at the cinema,'' said a
smiling Wertmuller, known for her long titles.
   Wertmuller was reluctant to go into details about the film's
content, but Hauer said his character is ``a journalist with two
women in his life who then changes his career.''
   ``For me its a story about friendship, death and love, but it's
not as heavy as it sounds,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Daniels, the sole surviving member of
the original Ink Spots, says he was surprised but not disappointed
he wasn't invited to induction ceremonies for the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame.
   ``It's no big thing,'' said the 73-year-old Daniels. ``I don't
feel left out.''
   Daniels, the group's lead tenor, left a year before the Ink Spots
recorded their best-known song, ``If I Didn't Care'' in 1939.
   A spokeswoman for the Hall of Fame said Daniels wasn't invited
Wednesday ceremonies because he left the group before it became
famous.
   The inducted Ink Spots, all of whom are dead, were Deek Watson,
Charlie Fuqua, Orville ``Hoppy'' Jones and Bill Kenny, who replaced
Daniels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As far as Zsa Zsa Gabor is concerned, first class
just isn't what it used to be.
   Ms. Gabor, who was kicked off a Delta Air Lines flight earlier
this month when she let her dogs loose on the plane, has sued the
airline for $10 million, charging that she was not treated ``in a
first-class manner.''
   The suit was filed Wednesday in Palm Beach County, Fla., where
Ms. Gabor lives.
   Ms. Gabor, 69, was escorted off a Delta on Jan. 6 when it landed
in Atlanta on a scheduled stop during a flight from Los Angeles to
West Palm Beach.
   The lawsuit said Delta spokesman William D. Berry defamed Ms.
Gabor when he told reporters that she had ``insulted the Atlanta
agents with vulgarities'' and used words that were ``less than
ladylike.''
   Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate called the lawsuit ``quite
interesting but totally unwarranted.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisville's battling Bingham family is up
in arms again, this time over a book by Sallie Bingham that contends
her relatives exploited blacks and women.
   Ms. Bingham's mother and other family members sent a letter to
book reviewers this week saying ``Passion and Prejudice'' is
``maliciously skewed.''
   The Bingham family owned the Courier-Journal and Louisville Times
Co. for 50 years and operated other local news media companies
before dismantling its empire amid family squabbling.
   In the book, due out next month, Sallie Bingham contends that the
family's reputation for public service and support of liberal causes
was a myth.
   Relatives charged that the book's arguments ``rest on unsupported
assertions, erroneous suppositions, leaps of logic, and in some
cases, outright fabrications.''
   The letter went out on the letterhead of Sallie Bingham's mother,
Mary Bingham, and was signed by Sallie's brother, Barry Bingham Jr.;
her sister, Eleanor Bingham Miller; two sisters-in-law and a niece.
</TEXT>
