<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   01-19 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY36</HEAD>
<HEAD>Last Year's Price Rise Matches Previous Year's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of increase in consumer prices held
steady in 1988 at 4.4 percent, the government said Thursday, but
many economists are warning that inflation could accelarate
moderately this year.
   Although the rise in the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index
last year was identical to the 1987 gain, the reasons were very
different.
   The summer drought pushed food prices up by 5.2 percent in 1988,
compared with 3.5 percent a year earlier. Last year's gain was the
steepest since 1980. Consumers got a break on energy costs, which
rose a scant 0.5 percent, compared with 8.2 percent in 1987.
   The inflation rate excluding the volatile food and energy
catagories _ a compilation many economists say is a better gauge of
underlying inflationary pressure than the larger index _ did
accelarate, from 4.2 percent in 1987 to 4.7 percent last year.
   ``The core inflation is ticking up,'' said Samuel D. Kahan, an
economist with Kleinwort Benson Government Securities Inc. in
Chicago. ``I would not treat last year's number as something very
calming.''
   Nevertheless, 1988 ended on a moderate note, with 0.3 percent
increases in both November and December.
   Last month's advance left the price index at 120.5 percent of its
1982-84 base, meaning that a hypothetical selection of goods costing
$100 during the base period would have cost $120.50 in December, 20
cents more than in November.
   President Reagan, who will leave office Friday, has listed the
taming of inflation as one of his proudest accomplishments. During
his term, inflation hit a 25-year low of 1.1 percent in 1986.
   Under his predecessor, Jimmy Carter, the nation saw price
increases of 13.3 percent in 1979 and 12.5 percent in 1980.
   Many economists worry that the country may be in for a taste of
the bad old days this year. They say tight labor markets and rising
factory operating rates will inevitably lead to higher costs for
consumers. Many predict an inflation rate of 5 percent to 5.5
percent.
   ``What you see is no evidence of runaway inflation, the kinds of
problems we had in the late '70s and early '80s, but you see
pressure on prices building on a fundamental level,'' said William
Dunkelberg, dean of business at Temple University in Philadelphia.
   Unemployment in December matched a 14-year low while use of
factory capacity hit a nine-year high.
   Meanwhile, in other economic news, the Commerce Department said
housing construction fell 2.2 percent in December, the first decline
in four months. For the year, rising mortgage interest rates helped
to dampen construction activity, which fell 8.2 percent to 1.49
million units, the lowest rate since the recession year of 1982.
   The Labor Department also reported that Americans' average weekly
earnings, after adjusting for inflation, decreased 0.4 percent in
December after falling 0.5 percent a month earlier.
   Average weekly earnings last month were $329.81, 3.8 percent
higher than a year ago but still not high enough to keep up with
inflation.
   The department offered these details of inflation in 1988:
   _Hot weather pushed poultry and egg prices up 17.9 percent and
16.5 percent, respectively. On the other hand, beef and pork prices
fell or rose only slightly during the second half of the year as
farmers sent more animals to slaughter to reduce the need for feed
made more expensive by the drought. For the year, beef was up 5.6
percent; pork was down 3.1 percent. Fruit and vegatable prices rose
6.2 percent; cereals and baked goods, 8.4 percent, and dairy
products, 4.4 percent.
   _Fuel oil prices jumped 2.8 percent in December after falling for
six consecutive months. Despite the December advance, the price was
6.3 percent below that of a year earlier. Electricity charges rose
1.1 percent for the year, while natural gas was unchanged. Gasoline
prices were 1.1 percent lower than a year ago.
   _In other areas, housing costs rose 4.0 percent. Price increases
for new and used cars were a moderate 2.1 percent and 3.4 percent,
respectively. However, the costs of auto insurance and automoile
financing took steep jumps of 8.4 percent and 8.3 percent,
respectively.
   The cost of medical care, up 6.9 percent, also rose faster than
the general inflation rate last year. Tobacco prices posted one of
the steepest rises of any subcatagory, up 9.4 percent.
   Clothing prices rose 4.8 percent overall, with men's and boys'
apparel up 6.0 percent and women's and girls' clothing up 3.4
percent.
   The Federal Reserve Board, whose prime job as the nation's
central bank is to keep inflation under control, has been pushing
interest rates slowly but steadily higher since March in an effort
to slow the economy and ease inflationary pressures.
   ``In the end, I don't think inflation is going to move up all
that much (in 1989) because I think the Fed is going to remain very
vigilant,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co.
</TEXT>
