<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouse-Shuffle     01-19 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Shuffle,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moving Day at the White House: Staff Facing Tight Time Squeeze</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As soon as Ronald and Nancy Reagan exit the
White House Friday to escort George and Barbara Bush to the
inaugural ceremonies on Capitol Hill, the mansion's staff begins a
three-hour, behind-the-scenes race to transform the mansion into the
Bush's new home.
   President Reagan, at his last official function on Thursday,
joked about his impending move, telling an East Room luncheon group
to ``stick around. We're having a tag sale upstairs and everything
has to go.''
   And Bush poked fun at his wife this week for ordering him to
shoulder some of their packing crates and commanding him to ``move
this one over here.''
   But in reality, the outgoing and incoming first couples have
little to do with the shift. The mansion's domestic staff sees to it
that the personal belongings are switched during the swearing-in
ceremonies and inaugural address.
   ``When the president leaves the White House to go to Capitol Hill
(for the ceremony), this is still his home,'' James Allen, head
usher of the executive mansion, said in an interview. ``And when the
new president returns, it is then his home, with his things in
place.''
   Allen, who oversees the mansion and its 93-member staff,
described the frenetic shuffle as ``a very cut-and-dried job, that
has to be done in about three hours.''
   As their final social duty on Friday, the Reagans will treat the
Bushes, as well as Vice President-elect Dan Quayle and his wife
Marilyn, to a 10:30 a.m. coffee in the Blue Room of the executive
residence.
   The Reagans then depart the White House for the last time as the
nation's first couple. After Bush's swearing-in, they are slated to
travel by helicopter from Capitol Hill to Andrews Air Force Base
outside Washington, from whence they will fly to Los Angeles.
   Until Friday, the Bushes stay at Blair House, the newly renovated
presidential guest quarters across the street from 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue.
   Allen said his job has been made easier this year because Mrs.
Reagan had most of the departing couple's furniture packed up and
sent in October to their California residence.
   The head usher said that since the Reagans have primarily only
clothing and some small personal items remaining in the house, the
mansion is nearly completely furnished and ready for the Bushes.
   ``They really only need to put their clothes in the drawers.'' he
said.
   When Mrs. Reagan removed her red upholstered furniture from the
second floor living room, other pieces were taken from the White
House supply held in a warehouse in Virginia and put in place, said
Elaine Crispen, Mrs. Reagan's press secretary.
   ``Believe me, the Bushes won't be sitting on orange crates _ Mrs.
Reagan has made every effort to find things in the White House
collection that they could be happy with from the moment they walk
in the door on Inauguration Day,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   Last week, a visitor to the private quarters could see that the
elegant rooms were in perfect order, with some pale upholstered
furniture in place and the walls and tables adorned with artworks
and antique china pieces from the White House collections.
   Mrs. Bush, following a tour of the residence with Mrs. Reagan
last week, called herself ``very lucky. Nancy Reagan has set up such
a beautiful house that all I have to do is move in and say `ditto.'
... It was perfect.''
   Mrs. Bush said that besides their dog, Millie, their king-sized
bed and a few curtains, she intends to move in some of their living
room furniture. The staff will move the larger pieces of furniture
next week, said Mrs. Crispen.
   Allen said a supply of oil paintings and ``a collection of small
things'' like Boehm birds, vases and statues are available to help
decorate.
   ``It's adequate, but by no means complete,'' Allen said. ``Each
family brings their own touches with them to make it their home.''
   The Bush's sprawling seaside home in Kennebunkport, Maine, and
their vice presidential residence are full of family pictures as
well as Mrs. Bush's needlepoint treasures and furniture from their
stay in China, all expected to find their way to the White House.
</TEXT>
