<FIRST>u a AM-SmokingGun Bjt   01-19 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking Gun, Bjt,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Claim First Link of Smoking to Measurable Heart Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EST, time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart disease patients who smoke are three times
more likely to have chest pains and restricted blood flow to their
hearts than those who don't light up, researchers say in a study
touted as the long-sought ``smoking gun.''
   The finding is the first direct evidence linking cigarettes and
heart disease, said an editorial accompanying the study in Friday's
Journal of the American Medical Association.
   The data indicated smokers were more likely than non-smokers to
have angina, or chest pains, and painless periods of inadequate
blood flow to the heart, both called ischemic episodes, the
researchers said.
   These episodes lasted longer among smokers, whose median episode
was 24 minutes compared to 2 minutes for non-smokers, the study
said. Both frequency and duration increased as the number of
cigarettes increased, the study said.
   Ischemic episodes damage the heart temporarily and can lead to
heart attacks, said Dr. Andrew Selwyn, a co-author of the report and
a cardiologist and associate professor at the Harvard Medical School.
   ``The more they smoke in general, the more ischemia they have and
the greater their risk of heart attack and death,'' Selwyn said.
   But the short-term effects are ``reversible and very treatable,
and that's what makes it (the study) useful to show to patients and
say `Look, you haven't damaged your heart yet, so stop smoking
now,''' Selwyn said in a telephone interview.
   ``This is a solid piece of evidence you can show patients before
they actually have a heart attack,'' he said.
   However, Gary Miller, a spokesman for the tobacco industry's
Washington-based Tobacco Institute, disputed that view.
   ``This is not really enough evidence to make such a claim,'' he
said in a telephone interview Thursday, noting the study involved
only two dozen smokers. Forty-one non-smokers also participated.
   ``Anything can cause these ischemic episodes. Caffeine,
excitement can cause them,'' Miller said.
   The JAMA editorial said research on smoking and heart disease
until now has been based on indirect evidence.
   What had been lacking was a ``smoking gun'' linking the two,
wrote Dr. Peter F. Cohn of the Health Sciences Center of the State
University of New York at Stony Brook.
   The study, based at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, was
conducted in 1984-87 by attaching a monitor to the hearts of 24
smokers and 41 non-smokers, all of whom had been diagnosed as having
heart disease.
   They wore the monitors for 24 hours while they went about their
daily routines.
   The monitors showed a total of 975 ischemic episodes, 8 percent
of which were accompanied by chest pains, the study said. The median
number of episodes over 24 hours was three for smokers and one for
non-smokers.
   ``What this did was show during the normal daily life the actual
activity of your heart,'' said Joan Barry, a researcher at Harvard
and another author of the study. ``Patients walk around and have
this abnormality and they're not even aware of it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
