<FIRST>u a AM-MiamiRiot-Damage Bjt   01-19 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Riot-Damage, Bjt,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Businesses Spared, Others Targeted in Miami Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benny O'Berry's side-by-side businesses in Miami's
Liberty City section survived the 1980 and 1982 riots unscathed. But
Tuesday night, one of them, a grocery operated by an Arab family for
a year, was looted and burned to the brick.
   ``There's no doubt about it. If they had known I still own the
building, they would have never torched it,'' said O'Berry, a black
businessman whose driving school next door was untouched. ``They
didn't realize it hurts me more than it hurts the Arabs.''
   As the dust settled in Liberty City and Overtown, shopkeepers in
the predominantly black neighborhoods shoveled up debris and counted
up their losses Thursday.
   Business owners and a black community activist said it was clear
black-owned businesses were spared and others specifically targeted
during three nights of rioting.
   While the fatal shooting of an unarmed black motorcyclist by an
Hispanic police officer Monday set off the violence, deep-rooted
racial tension in these impoverished areas fueled the riots, those
in the community said Thursday.
   The rioters picked their targets carefully, they said, sometimes
even ransacking a store and destroying its cash registers and scales
but leaving behind large stocks of beer, wine and food.
   Sam Bahhur, whose Palestinian family operated seven small food
markets in Overtown and Liberty City, watched with anger as
customers streamed into the black-owned Dobson Grocery across the
street from his ransacked store.
   ``They were not hungry. They just wanted to destroy,'' he said
while his son used a shovel to clean up a heap of canned goods,
cookies and panty hose packages.
   ``We ran away from the uprising back home in Palestine, now we
find this. We ran away from persecution over there, and we end up
destroyed here. Where can a man run to?'' Bahhur asked.
   Six of the seven Bahhur stores were damaged, including the market
in O'Berry's building. That store was the only one on a block of
other businesses _ all black-owned _ to be hit by the rioting youths.
   Bahhur estimated the family's losses in inventory and store
fixtures, along with structural damage, at $3 million. The family
will rebuild if it can find the money, he said.
   City officials said overall structural damage from the rioting
was less than $1 million.
   Across the street, Thomas Dobson said his grocery was untouched
by rioters, not necessarily because he is black but because he
stayed to protect it every night.
   ``Did they avoid black businesses? That might have had some input
into it. Another thing may be the way they treat people when they go
in to stores,'' he said.
   Black community activist Georgia Ayers agreed with business
owners that the riots were more than just youths running wild.
   ``Everything was planned and targeted: Protect black businesses
and get the white man, the Hispanic and the Arab out of our
community,'' she said.
   For O'Berry, seeing destruction in his neighborhood of nearly 30
years is painful.
   ``I don't particularily think that solves the problem,'' he said.
``They thought they'd hurt the white and Arab businesses, but that
thinking process is wrong. It doesn't solve anything.''
</TEXT>
