<FIRST>r w AM-ComputerSecurity     01-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Security,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Security Plans Being Reviewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer specialists have begun reviewing
security plans covering thousands of computer systems handling
sensitive data throughout the federal government, a government
official said Thursday.
   Douglas Hunt, of the National Institute of Standards and
Technology, said that ``I think the review activity is moving very
well. We're very optimistic.''
   Hunt said scrutiny of the plans, being carried out by a joint
team of specialists from the institute and the Pentagon's National
Security Agency, had started Tuesday.
   ``We're still receiving some plans. Most of them have come in _
most of the agencies have sent their submissions. And we are
proceeding with the review,'' he said.
   Hunt said he did not yet have a count of the specific number of
computer security plans submitted so far, but said it was ``in the
thousands.''
   Drafting, review and implementation of new security plans for
computers handling sensitive but unclassified data were among steps
_ including improved training programs for computer users _ mandated
under the Computer Security Act signed into law last year by
President Reagan.
   The legislation came in the wake of increased concern over
vulnerability of government computer systems to so-called computer
viruses and other threats.
   In a report released last September, the General Accounting
Office, an arm of Congress, said federal agencies at that time had
identified 53,443 computer systems _ an estimated 52,000 of them
within the Defense Department _ containing sensitive data.
   However, Hunt said he did not expect the number of security plans
submitted for review to reach that high because agencies are being
permitted to group together similar computer systems under a single
plan.
   He said the team reviewing the plans now includes 16 specialists
and was expected to peak this spring at about 30 people. The
institute is spending about $1.5 million on the effort, he said.
   ``We are planning on completing the review at the latest by the
end of May. Then we will be wrapping up with a final report,
summaries and stuff in June,'' Hunt said.
</TEXT>
