<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     01-19 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opponents of U.S. Bases Face Off With U.S. Supporters, Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGELES, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 people protesting the
U.S. military presence in the Philippines marched toward the gates
of Clark Air Base on Thursday, but riot police and thousands of
residents blocked their way.
   About 2,000 residents massed at the main gate of the U.S. base
hours before the protesters, who oppose nuclear weapons they say are
kept by U.S. forces, arrived from Manila.
   Scantily clad bar girls danced and chanted or waved signs with
slogans directed at opponents of the bases. Some of the signs read:
``Leave us alone,'' ``U.S. bases yes, pullout no,'' and ``We love
our job. Retain the bases.''
   Most of the 200,000 residents of Angeles depend for their
livelihood on income from the base, primarily on spending by its
26,000 U.S. personnel and dependents.
   The anti-U.S. demonstrators were blocked by dozens of jeeps left
by police and local residents about 300 yards from the base. About
1,000 riot police manned a bigger barricade of trucks about 100
yards from the main entrance.
   Police said they set up the barricades to keep apart the two
rival groups after receiving reports that local residents and
right-wing extremists planned to disrupt the anti-U.S. rally.
   After two hours of negotiations, police allowed base opponents to
march to a park about 100 yards from the base for an overnight
rally. The group was to travel to the U.S. navy base at Subic Bay 30
miles to the southwest for a similar rally Friday.
   While base opponents were en route from Manila on Thursday, armed
soldiers searched each of the more than 150 vehicles at three
checkpoints. One officer said the troops were ordered to search for
weapons and right-wing elements who might have joined the group to
create trouble.
   ``This is plain and simple harassment,'' said Philippine Rep.
Gregorio Andolana, who was taking part in the anti-U.S. protest.
Opposition to the bases runs strong both in the population and in
Congress.
   The Senate must approve any extension of the lease agreement for
the six U.S. installations. The pact expires in 1991.
   Also Thursday, communist rebels warned they were ready to launch
new attacks on U.S. military bases in the Philippines.
   A regional branch of the National Democratic Front, a Marxist
umbrella group, said in a statement that rebel forces ``are in a
position to launch action _ armed and unarmed, legal and illegal _
directly aimed at the U.S. bases.''
   In October 1987, rebels mounted simultaneous ambushes outside
Clark, killing three U.S. servicemen and a Filipino.
</TEXT>
