<HEAD>Bermuda to Vote in February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in this British colony will go to
the polls in Feburary for the first time in more than three years,
Premier John Swan announced Thursday in a call for early general
elections.
   He set the Feb. 9 election date after weeks of speculation that
he wanted to extend the term he first won in 1983.
   In the last general election in 1985, Swan's governing United
Bermuda Party took 31 of 40 seats in the Assembly, the party's
largest majority ever.
   The government's support has eroded as a result of several recent
problems, including overspending on work at Bermuda's airport and a
controversial plan to build a trash-burning plant.
   Swan could wait until 1990 to schedule elections, but the premier
apparently believes he would have a better chance of winning if they
are called quickly.
