<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Rescue     01-19 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rescue,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icebreaker Fails to Rescue Soviets From Drifting Ice Floe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet icebreaker dispatched to rescue North Pole
researchers from a drifting ice floe north of Greenland failed to
cut its way through to them, leaving the scientists stranded, Tass
reported Thursday.
   The icebreaker Rossiya will try again, bypassing the
``impregnable wall of ice'' and circling around to attempt a
breakthrough from the north, Tass said, quoting a report from the
ship radioed to the northern Soviet port of Murmansk.
   The rescue operation was mounted after the ice floe under Soviet
research station North Pole-28 was caught in a warm current and
began drifting southward and thawing, according to the official news
agency.
   Tass said the floe could no longer accommodate a rescue plane, so
the Rossiya was sent Sunday to try to pick up the researchers. Tass
did not say how many scientists were at the station or when the
Rossiya would make its next attempt to reach them.
   Tass indicated that authorities had decided to abandon the
drifting station, which it said had been conducting research in a
poorly explored area north of Greenland.
   ``It was decided that the Otto Shmidt research ship will later
subsitute for the North Pole-28 station,'' Tass said. ``With the
help of an icebreaker, the vessel will be frozen into the ice and
will then drift with it for several months.''
