<FIRST>u w AM-Inaugural-HighRollers 1stLd-Writethru a0712 01-19 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural-High Rollers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Keeping GOP High Rollers Happy During Inaugural Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: `Cosmetics queen,' to CORRECT Kravitz
to Kravis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some inauguration celebrants have had their
ball gowns delivered by Federal Express. Others simply must have the
perfect table at the perfect time. And there's always the worry
about what to do between events.
   Welcome to inaugural week in Washington, where high-roller
Republicans _ and parties for them _ are aplenty.
   ``I guess we'll be going to some parties here,'' San Francisco
banking executive Don Stephens said calmy upon arriving in the
capital, an understatement in a week overflowing with festivities.
   By Thursday, those with energy as well as money were well into
party mode.
   ``After the opening ceremony we're going to eat and then to a New
Jersey reception, but we'll see you tonight at Union Station or back
at the hotel afterward,'' one mink-draped woman told another
Wednesday in a conversation overheard in a hotel lobby, where the
well-heeled are easy to find these days.
   They also can be found in the choice seats at inaugural events,
or the choice restaurants, or the choice clothing stores _ which
report high demand for formal gowns from those who didn't bring
enough and can't be seen in the same one twice.
   ``I called home and had my daughter send me this because I looked
at the schedule and realized I needed another one,'' said a woman
who got Federal Express involved in the overnight gown-delivery
business. ``Oh, God, no, I'd be too embarrassed,'' she said when
asked her name, confessing only that home was California and her
next stop was the hotel's valet desk to inquire about having the
gown pressed.
   Keeping high rollers happy is a top priority of the Republican
National Committee, which is trying to take care f those who
bankrolled the 1988 campaign.
   The RNC held a dinner-dance Tuesday night for its leaders and top
contributors, welcoming them to Washington a night before the formal
inaugural events began.
   Since then, the celebration has been virtually non-stop for, in
the words of one GOP fund-raiser, ``those of us who paid so
generously in advance.''
   There was the kickoff ceremony at the Lincoln Memorial and the
first round of dinners Wednesday, and another full day of events
Thursday, including a salute to the new first lady, Barbara Bush,
and vice president, Dan Quayle, and a star-studded gala to be
attended by President-elect Bsuh, as well as his wealthy supporters.
   The RNC also has arranged a number of private receptions to keep
its favorite guests entertained between official inaugural events,
and many are organizing smaller dinner parties and private
receptions.
   The Ritz-Carlton ordered 5,000 ounces of choice caviar to please
the palates of its guests this week.
   And when the affluent eat out, they expect royal treatment.
   ``You have to use your intuition, your imagination,'' said maitre
d' Martin Garbisu of the Ritz's exclusive Jockey Club. ``You don't
want to create bad feelings.''
   Cosmetics queen Estee Lauder and Wall Street takeover king Henry
Kravis were among this week's visitors to the Jockey Club, where the
most frequent request has been for a table in the front section _
the most visible. ``People will do anything,'' said Garbisu, smiling
as his voice trailed off.
   There have been a few glitches amid the glamor.
   Limousines are scarcer than scarce, guests had to scramble for
unassigned seats despite paying $1,500 a plate for dinner Wednesday
night, and tickets to some of the high-profile events are
nonexistent, even for high rollers with invitations.
   Indeed, a special ``trouble room'' at the Washington Convention
Center for those with ticket problems was packed with grumbling
Republicans on Thursday.
   ``They don't like lines and they especially don't like standing
in line only to be told `Sorry,''' one inaugural organizer said.
``These are people who are treated like kings in their home states.
But we've got a lot of people to look out for here and not all of
them are too happy right now.''
</TEXT>
