<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg     01-19 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Blames Nussbaum At Steinberg's Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, former live-in lover of murder
defendant Joel Steinberg, killed their adopted daughter herself
because she saw the girl as a rival for his attention, defense
attorneys charged Thursday.
   Ms. Nussbaum ``didn't care about the kid a bit, not one bit,''
Adrian DiLuzio said in closing arguments, calling her ``a poor
excuse for a woman and a mother.''
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, was the key witness against Steinberg. The
47-year-old disbarred lawyer is charged with murder in the beating
death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg, whom he illegally obtained at
birth from an unwed teen-ager.
   The child was removed unconscious from Steinberg's Greenwich
Village apartment in 1987 and died of a brain injury three days
later.
   The defense charged that it was Ms. Nussbaum who inflicted the
fatal injuries during a fight with the girl while Steinberg was out
to dinner.
   ``Lisa Steinberg was a rival. Lisa got all the attention she
(Nussbaum) thought she should have been getting,'' DiLuzio said. He
recalled testimony that Ms. Nussbaum thought Steinberg was a ``god.''
   ``If someone's stealing your god, you kill them, and you kill
them without remorse, vindictively,'' he said. ``Nor would you ever
have a sense of guilt about what you did.''
   Charges against Ms. Nussbaum were dropped and she was granted
immunity from prosecution for her testimony against Steinberg. She
said she was battered by Steinberg and she has spent nearly the past
year in a psychiatric facility.
   Another defense attorney, Ira London, said Ms. Nussbaum's
hospitalization was an attempt to win jury sympathy and avoid
prosecution.
   ``She was also granted an opportunity to get revenge against Joel
by being appointed his accuser,'' he said.
   The prosecution says Steinberg hit the girl then let her lie
unconscious for 12 hours without seeking help for her. Steinberg
denies ever hitting the child.
   Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro was expected to give
his closing arguments on Friday.
</TEXT>
