<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseProbe     01-19 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Suspends 2 Consultants in Continuing Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Thursday suspended two private
consultants and their companies from receiving or working on new
federal contracts in connection with an on-going probe of Pentagon
corruption.
   The suspensions were ordered against William L. Parkin and his
consulting firm, Crest Inc., and Fred H. Lackner and his company,
Acris Associates.
   The suspensions will prevent the men and their companies ``from
contracting with any agency within the executive branch of the
federal government pending the outcome of legal proceedings
initiated against them,'' the Pentagon said in a statement.
   The suspension orders also will prevent the two men and their
firms from dealing with the federal government on behalf of other
defense contractors, the Navy said.
   Thursday's action had been expected since Jan. 10, when the
Pentagon first announced that Lackner, Parkin and several other
companies and individuals were being considered for suspension as a
result of a federal indictment and guilty pleas in the probe.
   During the subsequent week, the Pentagon announced it had
suspended the Hazeltine Corp., a subsidiary of Emerson Electric Co.
Inc., and the Teledyne Electronics Division of Teledyne Industries
Inc. The Pentagon also suspended without pay a Navy contracting
official indicted in the case.
   All of the actions flow from the Jan. 6 return of the first
indictment in connection with the two-year fraud investigation.
   The probe, which has been conducted over the last two years under
the code name ``Operation Ill Wind,'' focuses on allegations that
private consultants bribed government employees for information that
gave client companies an edge in winning contracts.
   The first indictment alleges that Teledyne Electronics and its
employees paid Parkin, of Alexandria, Va., to obtain details about a
Navy radar contract worth more than $100 million. Parkin then paid
Lackner, a consultant based in Woodland Hills, Calif., who in turn
gave bribes to Stuart Berlin, a Navy contracting officer, the
indictment asserts.
   Berlin, Parkin and Lackner face maximum penalties of 185 years in
prison and fines of $5.5 million each if convicted on all counts.
Teledyne Electronics faces a fine of $6.5 million if convicted.
   All three men and the company have pleaded innocent to the
charges. A federal judge has set a trial date of March 27.
   On the same day the indictment was returned, the Hazeltine Corp.
agreed to plead guilty to conspiracy to defraud the United States,
conversion of government property and making false statements to the
government.
   Affidavits released three weeks ago suggested that Hazeltine also
hired Parkin to obtain inside information from Pentagon employees
that would allow the company to compete for a $15.9 million contract
for electronic testing gear for an aircraft identification system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-NATO     01-19 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Welcomes Soviet Plan to Reduce Short-Range Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East-West, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO would welcome a unilateral
reduction in the Soviet Union's short-range nuclear missiles in
Eastern Europe, an official of the Western military alliance said
Thursday.
   Robin Stafford, a spokesman for the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, said, however, the allies had to wait until the cuts
were implemented to determine their significance.
   ``In any event,'' he said, ``Soviet superiority seems certain for
some time.''
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze told the final
session of a 35-nation conference in Vienna that Moscow will
withdraw some of its nuclear missiles from Eastern Europe. The
missiles, he said, will be pulled out along with troops who control
them.
   ``If this signals that in this field ... the Soviets are now
beginning to realize that their potential far exceeds legitimate
requirements, we can only find such steps encouraging,'' Stafford
said.
   U.S. Gen. John R. Galvin, NATO's top military commander in
Europe, said, ``If the Soviets are serious about reducing tactical
nuclear weapons, they need to make significant cuts.''
   Shevardnadze's speech came a day after Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev said in Moscow his program to slash his country's armed
forces by a half-million men would mean a reduction of 240,000
Soviet soldiers in Europe and 200,000 in Asia in the next two years.
   Gorbachev said the Kremlin's military budget will be trimmed by
14.2 percent and the production of arms and military supplies by
19.5 percent.
   Stafford, responding to Gorbachev's remarks, said, ``Any
indication that the Soviet Union is prepared to reduce its military
spending and the overwhelming imbalance in existing weaponry is to
be welcomed and encouraged.''
   He said, however, that the Soviet Union has never published
figures on total military spending. ``To speak, therefore, of
percentages of an unknown figure gives a blurred picture, which
makes it difficult to calculate what the result would be if the cuts
are, in fact, enacted,'' Stafford said.
   ``We have made public our data for years,'' Galvin said. ``It is
about time the Warsaw Pact responded.''
   Stafford also urged the Soviet Union to release it defense
figures and provide additional details on its planned reductions.
   Still, he said, ``the statement of intent nevertheless augurs
well for the atmosphere in which the coming round of arms
negotiations will be held.''
   The accord signed in Vienna by 35 nations, including the United
States, Canada and all European nations except Albania, mandates new
East-West negotiations on reducing conventional arms in Europe.
Those talks, between the 16 NATO nations and seven Warsaw Pact
countries, are to begin March 9 in Vienna.
   Shevardnadze said in his speech that Moscow has long offered to
negotiate removal of its tactical nuclear weapons and promised to
withdraw them from Europe.
   Later, at a news conference, he said only short-range weapons
that are part of military units targeted for withdrawal will be
removed and dismantled without conditions. Other tactical or
battlefield weapons, he said, were subject to negotiations.
   ``We would welcome the announced unilateral reduction by the
Soviet Union of its large tactical nuclear force,'' Stafford said.
``One of course has to wait to see how and if the announced steps
are implemented to assess their actual importance.''
   He said the allies wanted to know: ``Which systems will be
removed? How many? To where? And what happens to them then?''
   Galvin said that for talks on short-range nuclear weapons to be
held, ``we need to achieve a parity in conventional forces first.''
   NATO foreign ministers last month announced their position for
the March negotiations, known as Conventional Stability Talks.
   The Western alliance says the Soviets and their allies maintain
imbalances that give them a large superiority in conventional forces
in Europe. They want the East bloc to make much sharper reductions
in their forces to bring the two sides to equality.
   The allies also are expected to decide this spring whether to
give a go-ahead to upgrading short-range nuclear weapons in the
Western arsenal.
   The issue has gained prominence since President Reagan and
Gorbachev signed in December 1987 the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces Treaty, which provides for eliminating all U.S. and Soviet
land-based missiles with ranges of 300 to 3,400 miles.
</TEXT>
