<FIRST>r w AM-Wilson-Davis     01-19 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wilson-Davis,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen with Rare Disease Gets Capitol Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old California teenager suffering
from a rare form of leukemia saw his dreams come true Thursday as he
toured the White House, met two members of the Senate and even asked
the first question at an impromptu news conference.
   Jason Davis drew laughs from reporters when he ended a brief
meeting with Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., by asking the senator if he
would run for governor now that George Deukmejian has announced he
will not seek re-election.
   ``I don't know,'' a surprised Wilson said. ``A lot of people are
asking me to think about it; a lot are asking me to do it. ... Both
are great jobs; I wish I had two lives.''
   Davis got a taste of politics as he sat in the senator's chair,
posed for photographs and placed a call to Senate Minority Leader
Bob Dole's office. The Kansas Republican was not in and Davis left a
message for him to call Wilson.
   Earlier in the day, Davis toured the White House and the Capitol,
and met Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska. Davis was scheduled to attend
the inauguration and a black-tie ball Friday. Wilson also arranged
for Davis to meet Vice President-elect Dan Quayle.
   The Sacramento teenager was in Washington under the auspices of
the Make-A-Wish Foundation, which helps make dreams come true for
children with life-threatening diseases. At the age of five, Davis
was diagnosed as having Fanconi anemia, which severely affects his
blood count.
   Davis had worked for the campaign of President-elect Bush and
wanted to attend the inauguration. His doctor, Mary Retzer,
contacted the Make-A-Wish Foundation, which picked up the expenses
for Davis' trip.
   ``I like science and politics. I'll get into both,'' said Davis.
</TEXT>
