<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Youths     01-19 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Youths,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges High Schoolers to Build for the Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush challenged America's youth
Thursday to start thinking now about how to serve their country and
help build ``a better America.''
   Bush, on the eve of his inauguration, used wisecracks and wit to
emphasize the importance of education as he addressed a crowd of
5,000 high school students at the D.C. Armory.
   ``I certainly learned the importance of education during the
campaign. I learned how vital it is to memorize dates _ Pearl Harbor
day, for example,'' he said jokingly in reference to a campaign
remark in which he misstated the date of the 1941 Japanese attack on
U.S. forces in Hawaii.
   He prevented Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., from falling down a flight
of steps leading to the stage, but made a minor slip of his own as
he joked about the Harrison who delivered a notoriously long
inaugural speech.
   Bush mixed up President Benjamin Harrison with his grandfather,
William Henry, the actual perpetrator of the prolix address.
   ``I've been reading some history this week in preparation for the
swearing-in tomorrow. And one thing I've learned is that George
Washington's second inaugural address was exactly 134 words long. So
I want to take a lesson from that first George and try to keep these
remarks pretty short,'' the vice president said.
   ``And then I'd want to do better than Benjamin Harrison did,''
Bush said. ``I think he spoke for an hour and a half and then got
pneumonia and died a few weeks later. So I'll try to do better than
that tomorrow.''
   Actually, it was William Henry Harrison, the ninth president, who
refused to wear a coat in the rain at his March 4, 1841, inaugural
and droned on through 8,445 words. A month later, he became the
first president to die in office. Benjamin Harrison, his grandson,
was the 23rd president, from 1889-1893.
   Quoting Franklin Delano Roosevelt, he said, ``We can't always
build a future for our youth, but we can build our youth for the
future.''
   ``I can't predict all the twists and the turns that you'll see in
your lives, nor can I as president prepare you for them, but this I
do pledge: that I will do all in my power to help you help
yourselves prepare for a brighter future,'' Bush said.
   ``I ask that you begin now to think about how you can help your
country, think about how you can serve your country,'' he said.
   ``You see, my mission truly is to help, to reach out, to help
build a better America,'' he said. ``No president can do it without
you.''
   Bush spent much of the day at the White House, working on the
address he will deliver at noon Friday and sitting for a round of
media interviews. He was heading out to a private dinner with
relatives before an evening gala.
   ``I really feel this: our best days are yet to come. And if we
are to retain our place as a source of inspiration and hope for
people everywhere ... we must be a nation that respects ideas and
nourishes the ability of the people to develop and understand
them,'' Bush told his young audience.
   ``I do see a better-educated America, an America that respects
teachers and the noble role they fill in our society, an America
that makes it easier for families to save for college, an America
that rewards excellence,'' he said.
   The teens cheered when Bush said, ``Our American optimism about
the future is legendary and perhaps no one better personifies that
than a president named Ronald Reagan, whose shoes are going to be
pretty darn hard to fill.''
   Asked afterwards by a reporter how he planned to answer Bush's
call to service, Doug Metz, 17, a senior from Poolesville High
School in Maryland, said, ``Join the Army, I guess.''
   Yvette Gissing, 18, a senior from Chantilly High School in
Virginia, wondered if ``making people look good'' would help the
country. She wants to be a hairdresser.
   Stacey Clark, 16, a junior from La Plata High School in Maryland,
confessed that ``I didn't like Bush at first. I liked Dukakis
better.''
   ``I always thought that Bush wanted things to be the same too
much. He didn't want change. I wanted somebody who would change
things,'' said the teen-ager. But now ``he's doing better.''
</TEXT>
