<FIRST>r w AM-FinanceMinisters 1stLd-Writethru a0703 01-19 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Finance Ministers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Allies to Review World Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 7 grafs on Verity proposal involving Third World debt,
bgng ``Meanwhile, outgoing''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance ministers from Japan, West Germany,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada have been invited by the United
States to meet Feb. 3 in Washington to review the economic situation
in the world, a Treasury Department official said Thursday.
   Third World debt has reached $1.3 trillion and President-elect
Bush, who takes office Friday, has said he wants to have a review of
the problem.
   The invitation for the meeting of the so-called Group of Seven,
or G-7, was announced by a treasury official who spoke only on
condition of anonymity. The official said it also would be a chance
for Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and his counterparts to get
acquainted with a new member.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama, who took office Dec.
27, is the new member since the group met in Berlin last September.
   Third World countries have complained about having to pay tens of
billions every year in principal and interest to wealthier
countries, money they would like to use for investments that would
check the decline in their living standards.
   On the same day as the Washington meeting, heads of the leading
Latin American debtor governments are to meet in Caracas, Venezuela.
They owe more than $440 billion of the debt.
   James A. Baker III, Bush's nominee for secretary of state, told
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Wednesday that a way must
be found to get new capital to debtor countries. At the same time,
he opposed shifting the burden of their old debts from private banks
to taxpayers in the United States and other creditor countries.
   He also asked for more ``transparency'' on new credits recently
offered to the Soviet Union by banks in allied countries. Former
Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger has estimated those credits at
$7 billion. The money could all be going to improve fertilizer
production but the same chemicals could be used for warfare, he
added.
   Meanwhile, outgoing Commerce Secretary C. William Verity on
Thursday called for an ``academic peace corps'' in lesser-developed
countries to be financed by exchanging Third World debt for the
foreign education of American students.
   Verity said that while the program would have only a marginal
impact on the huge amounts owed by debtor nations, it could
dramatically increase the slim numbers of Americans studying in
Third World countries.
   He said America's inadequate understanding of other cultures
handicaps its dealings in international affairs and world trade.
   Less than 2,500 Americans received credit for study in Latin
American in 1986, Verity said.
   Under Verity's proposal, loans that foreign countries have
received from U.S. banks would be given or sold at a discount to
American universities, which would exchange the debt for local
currency in the foreign countries and use it to finance education
programs there.
   Banks could benefit by clearing debt from their books, debtor
nations would have their dollar debt reduced, and the universities
would obtain foreign currency at favorable prices, Verity said.
   He said several universities have expressed interest in using the
debt-for-education program, including Texas A&amp;M, Michigan State
University and Ohio State. The Commerce Department will help promote
the idea and keep banks and schools advised of swap opportunities,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
