<HEAD>Makers Plan to Buy More Tobacco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. cigarette manufacturers plan to buy 427
million pounds of 1989-crop burley tobacco, up from 364.5 million
pounds in 1988, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Milton Hertz, administrator of the Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service, said federal law requires major domestic
cigarette manufacturers to report annually to USDA how much burley
tobacco they intend to buy from auction markets and producers.
   The information is used to determine, in part, the department's
annual burley tobacco marketing quota.
