<FIRST>u i AM-Poland Bjt   01-19 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, Bjt,0969</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Leader: Offer to Solidarity a `Momentous Event'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski on
Thursday disclosed the government plan for legalizing Solidarity,
saying conditions to reinstate the banned union can be negotiated if
it agrees to respect the law.
   The Communist Party's position paper on trade unions and
political freedoms was a ``momentous event'' for Poland, Jaruzelski
said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa reacted cautiously in his first
comment on the offer, but said his union was at a critical juncture
in its quest for legalization.
   ``If we blow it here, other people will have to deal with the
same problem again,'' he said in Gdansk. ``I don't want my son and
his generation to live through such things again where it
accumlates, rots and then explodes.''
   Walesa said he would await a copy of the official text of the
party document before making a more complete statement on the
conditions for reinstating the Soviet bloc's first independent trade
union.
   ``Our offer is honest and serious,'' Jaruzelski said at a rare
news conference. ``I count on the fact that taking it up
constructively will allow ... A historical step in Poland's
development. That is what we all desire.''
   The offer marks a dramatic reversal in policy for Jaruzelski and
other party leaders whose decision to impose martial law on Dec. 13,
1981, crushed the union, and reflects the failure of efforts to
eradicate the opposition in the past seven years.
   The party appears to be seeking a partnership with ``constructive
elements'' of the opposition to battle rapidly rising inflation, a
multibillion-dollar foreign debt and chronically ill-stocked stores.
   The position paper released to the media Thursday night and to be
published in newspapers nationwide Friday contains broadly written
conditions for allowing more than one legal trade union.
   Jaruzelski said Solidarity's willingness to respect Poland's
Constitution was the most important condition to legalize the union
and that details could be worked out at government-proposed
discussions.
   ``For me, an obvious and unquestionable condition, and this is a
condition, is whether Solidarity agrees to accept and will respect
the order of the socialist state, legal and constitutional,'' he
said.
   Jaruzelski declined to say when the talks, first proposed by the
authorities in August during Poland's worst wave of labor unrest in
seven years, could begin.
   Other conditions outlined in the position paper say the new
unions must be non-violent; must rely on lawful sources of funding,
an apparent reference to Solidarity's financial support from the
West; and must contribute positively to economic development, which
appeared to be an effort to discourage strikes.
   Jaruzelski said that just as the party is not the same as it was
in 1981, ``We expect that Solidarity, if it is created in its legal
form will not be the same either.''
   The party leader defended the martial law decision, saying ``I
think without martial law ... there would have been no
round-table,'' referring to the talks with the opposition.
   The paper does not contain a timetable for legalization or call
on the new unions to refrain from striking, although party leaders
have suggested a two-year trial period with no strikes.
   There is one direct reference to Soldiarity, saying it could be
one of the new trade unions created. It says the various unions at a
work place should negotiate together.
   Jaruzelski said he was optimistic the government could reach
agreement with the opposition and would not rule out a meeting with
Walesa, saying politicians ``never say never.''
   ``I think you will share the view that it was a momentous event
in the life of our party and at the same time it has a big chance to
become a turning point in the life of our country,'' Jaruzelski said
of th plenum's decisions.
   Although the television evening news opened with the Jaruzelski
news conference, a short fragment of Walesa's comments in Gdansk was
also shown on TV and the state-run news agency PAP carried a summary
of Walesa's remarks.
   The Solidarity leader sounded cautious but optimistic, saying the
decision at the party meeting showed the first signs of
understanding on the part of the authorities.
   At the news conference in the Solidarity stronghold at St.
Brygida's Church in the port city of Gdansk, Walesa said the party
offier has some positive and negative elements to consider.
   ``We can't destroy this possibility'' of true union freedom, but
``at the same time we shouldn't struggle for some ambitious
details,'' he said.
   ``It is a lot for this party ... but it is too little for social
demands and expectations,'' he said.
   The party leadership approved the document on political and union
freedom early Wednesday after a two-day meeting. Jaruzelski offered
to resign as party leader and head of state after encountering
heated opposition to the plan but then received a vote of confidence
from the 230-member Central Committee.
   Walesa said he will address shipyard workers in Gdansk on Friday,
when workers will have been able to read the party position paper.
   Adam Michnik, a senior adviser to Walesa, called the plenum ``a
step forward,'' saying that ``for the first time they announced at a
plenum that the legalization of Solidarity can be the subject of
talks.''
   Walesa has said the authorities must agree to legalize Solidarity
in order for talks with the opposition to take place.
   He said he saw invitations to speak at two legal rallies in
Warsaw next week as a sign of government good faith, and said
officials asked management at the Lenin shipyard where he works as
an electrician to excuse him for the events.
</TEXT>
