<FIRST>r w AM-ForestRules     01-19 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forest Rules,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Proposes New Rules Involving Leasing to Oil and Gas Developers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department on Thursday proposed
new rules that will give the agency a say in the leasing of national
forest land to oil and gas developers.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the department's Forest Service, said
oil and gas companies hold leases for 17 million acres of the
agency's 191 million acres of national forest land.
   In the past, leasing authority was held exclusively by the
Interior Department's Bureau of Land Management. But
leasing-revision legislation in 1987 expanded the authority of the
secretary of agriculture.
   Under the proposed rules, leases for oil and gas on forest lands
cannot be issued by BLM without approval of the Forest Service,
Robertson said.
   Final regulations will be issued after a 60-day comment period
and time for agency officials to study those comments, he said.
   Written comments can be sent to F. Dale Robertson, Chief, Forest
Service, USDA, P.O. Box 96090, Washington, D.C. 20090-6090.
   In a separate action, the Forest Service said it has begun ``new
streamlined procedures'' for handling public appeals of land and
resource management decisions by agency officials.
   The new rules separate procedures for appealing Forest Service
decisions on use and occupancy permits for national forest land from
procedures appealing decisions on land and resource managment plans.
   ``Using the two appeals channels will expedite the resolution of
disagreements between citizens and decision-makers without
unnecessarily delaying national forest management,'' Robertson said.
</TEXT>
