<FIRST>r w AM-Housing-TaxCredit     01-19 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing-Tax Credit,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Urge Tax Credit Be Made Permanent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A task force representing both the housing
industry and tenants recommended Thursday that Congress make
permanent a tax credit to investors as an incentive for building
low-income rental housing.
   ``The low-income housing tax credit is the prime producer now of
low-income housing,'' said Elizabeth Mitchell, chairman of the group.
   ``First and foremost we believe that it should be made
permanent,'' said Ms. Mitchell, who is executive director of the
Maine State Housing Authority. ``It is vital to the successful means
employed to solving the nation's housing problems.''
   The panel also recommended that Congress extend the duration of
the low-income use compliance period, remove constraints to using
other federal subsidies with the tax credit and expand the pool of
investors who can use the credits and types of projects the credit
covers.
   The recommendations were delivered to Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine and Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., who formed
the panel to study the tax credit last May.
   Mitchell and Danforth, members of the Senate Finance Committee,
said they would use the panel's report as a basis for proposed
changes in the tax law to amend and extend the current credit.
   ``In my view it would be unthinkable not to extend the only
remaining incentive in the tax code for the health of low-income
housing,'' said Mitchell.
   The low-income tax credit was amended in 1986 to encourage
developers to invest in building and rehabilitation of housing for
low- and moderate-income people after changes took away most of the
deductions for passive losses and property depreciation.
   To get the credit, property owners must set aside either 20
percent of the units in a property for families with incomes less
than 50 percent of the median income in an area, or 40 percent for
families with incomes less than 60 percent of the area median.
   If Congress fails to act the tax credit will expire at the end of
this year.
   The panel's recommendations came on the same day the government
reported Thursday that housing construction fell to its lowest level
in six years in 1988. Earlier in the week, Jack Kemp,
President-elect Bush's choice as secretary of the Department of
Housing and Urban Development, told city officials the tax revision
may have gone ``too far'' and stunted low- and moderate-income
housing construction.
</TEXT>
