<FIRST>r a AM-BankHeist-VMI     01-19 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Heist-VMI,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Military Institute Shocked At Cadets' Role In Armored Car
Heist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Military Institute, where
gray-uniformed cadets live by an honor code so strict they are
thrown out for lying, was in shock Thursday over two cadets' role in
a $4.5 million armored car heist.
   ``Most people are in disbelief,'' said senior Greg Skinner of New
York City. ``They can't believe it happened. It shouldn't have
happened.''
   William T. Jasinski, 22, of Boonton, N.J., and Bryan Smals, 21,
of Columbus, Ohio, were in custody awaiting a hearing Friday in
federal court in Roanoke.
   They are accused along with Jasinski's father, Robert T.
Jasinski, 51, also of Boonton, in a Dec. 22 robbery.
   The cadets told a U.S. magistrate Wednesday they put on rented
police uniforms and carried out the robbery. That acknowledgement
ensures they will be ``drummed out'' of VMI if they try to return, a
spokesman and a number of cadets said.
   ``They're dead ducks,'' VMI spokesman Tom Joynes said in an
interview. ``We hope these kids will have sense enough to resign.
   ``If they come back, they'll be dismissed by the Honor Court,
because they admitted stealing. The honor code prohibits lying,
cheating or stealing or tolerating those who do.''
   Cadets interviewed Thursday outside the school's Stonewall
Jackson barracks said the incident will harm VMI's reputation.
   ``VMI cadets are supposed to uphold the image of an honorable
person, but one bad person can give VMI a bad image,'' said Robin
Pitaniello, a junior from Lynchburg.
   But he said he was not calling the two cadets ``bad'' because he
did not know if they were guilty.
   Publicity of the heist could not have come at a worse time, with
some 400 cadets ready to march in Washington at George Bush's
inauguration Friday, Joynes noted. But he doubted the arrests would
tarnish VMI's image for long.
   ``This is the only scandal we've had in anybody's memory,''
Joynes said. ``Other schools go through this sort of thing all the
time.''
   About four or five cadets are expelled by the Honor Court each
year, generally because of lying, he said.
   ``Stealing is rare,'' Joynes said. ``I doubt we've had one of
those in 10 years.''
   Respect for the honor code is obvious to visitors of the
150-year-old VMI, which has some 1,300 cadets, all of them male.
   A reporter who stopped at a snack bar on campus noticed a dollar
bill tacked to a bulletin board. Snack bar workers said that when a
cadet finds money in the dining area, he tacks it on the board for
the person who lost it.
   But Joynes said the cadets' respect for authority may have been
what led Jasinski into going along with his father's alleged plot to
rob the armored car of Coin Depot Armored Car Co., where the elder
Jasinski worked as a part-time driver.
   ``I'm sure his father could have influenced him, but how did he
influence the other kid?'' Joynes said.
   The elder Jasinski was released Thursday on $400,000 bail backed
by the deed to his house, which Assistant U.S. Attorney John Lacey
said was valued at about $900,000. But he was represented by a
federal public defender, for which he was ruled eligible for
financial reasons by U.S. Magistrate Ronald Hedges in Newark, N.J.
   Joynes described Smals, a sophomore, as an extremely bright
English major on a Navy scholarship, while Jasinski was a C-student
and a fifth-year senior studying mechanical engineering.
   Cadets who knew the pair said they were quiet but friendly young
men who worked out a lot with weights and did not get involved in
extracurricular activities.
</TEXT>
