<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Mayors     01-19 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayors,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Urge Bush to Boost Reagan's Urban Aid Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mayors, declaring their readiness
to cooperate with the Bush administration, urged the incoming
president Thursday to add $10.7 billion to President Reagan's budget
for urban aid.
   ``The last Reagan budget recommended additional cuts in urban
programs which, over the past 10 years, have shouldered an
overwhelming burden in the battle to reduce the deficit,'' the
mayors said in a statement issued at the close of their annual
winter meeting.
   The mayors said that during Reagan's eight years in office the
cumulative budget for key urban programs was cut by nearly 82
percent.
   Mayor Arthur J. Holland of Trenton, N.J., president of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, said a delegation of mayors met with Bush a
few weeks ago and left with the impression that ``the
president-elect was sensitive to our needs and would do eveything he
could to help meet those needs.''
   Holland and a bipartisan group of mayors who participated in a
news conference closing the winter meeting had high praise for Jack
Kemp, Bush's choice as secretary of the Department of Housing and
Urban Development.
   Kemp met with the mayors Wednesday, telling them:
   ``I'm going to be an activist. I'm going to be an advocate. The
door is open. My mind is open.''
   Holland said that he didn't know ``of any secretary who's
approached his responsibilities with more enthusiasm than Jack
Kemp.''
   The mayors said the budget Reagan sent to Congress last week cut
$2.7 billion over current appropriations for urban programs such as
mass transit, clean water construction grants and Urban Development
Action Grants. The mayors called for freezing those programs at
current levels.
   The mayors also called for $2 billion in additional money for
assistance to children through such programs as Head Start, Job
Corps, Medicaid and Compensatory Education.
   Finally, said the mayor, the federal government should invest an
additional $3 billion in housing, $2 billion in child care and $1
billion in Trageted Fiscal Assistance to help cities facing
financial crises.
   When Holland was asked if he had any hope that the new
administration would respond favorably to the request from the
mayors, he replied, ``To be a mayor is to live in hope.''
</TEXT>
