<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Warns Its Nationals to Leave Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th `The guerrillas' with reports of
fighting; picks up 14th `Most of'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain issued an advisory Thursday
urging its nationals and citizens of six other countries for whom it
has diplomatic responsibility to leave Afghanistan immediately.
   Officials at the U.S. Embassy said they probably would give the
same advice to the dozen or so American missionaries still in the
country. Western embassies also confer regularly about whether to
close.
   Britain's warning coincided with reports that all Soviet troops
in Kabul would withdraw by early February along the Salang highway,
the main route north to the Soviet border, to guard the final
departure from Afghanistan by a Feb. 15 deadline.
   When Soviet forces are gone, after more than nine years, the
Afghan civil war will be back in the hands of the government's
poorly trained conscript army and Moslem guerrillas who began
fighting after a communist coup in April 1978.
   As the Soviet soldiers have withdrawn under a U.N.-mediated
agreement, guerrillas have increased attacks on the Salang highway
to stop supply convoys from reaching Kabul. The result has been
acute food and fuel shortages that are growing worse.
   The insurgents predict a quick victory over the forces of
President Najib, and some Western diplomats agree. One said Najib's
regime should ``fall fairly fast after the Soviet withdrawal is
complete.''
   Clovis Meath Baker, the British charge d'affaires, summoned the
few British journalists in the capital and delivered what he called
``a final warning'' to leave ``while normal flights are still
available.''
   In a letter to the 71 Britons, Australians, Canadians, New
Zealanders, Irish, Danes and Finns still in the country, Meath Baker
said: ``There is no question of any subsequent evacuation being
arranged by the British government.''
   At the Foreign Office in London, a spokesman said in announcing
the warning: ``The situation in Kabul is deteriorating. There are
food shortages, fuel shortages and the probability is that these
will get worse nearer to the Russian withdrawal.
   ``Near the time of the withdrawal, you can't guarantee commercial
flights will come in and out.''
   An informed Soviet source said privately all Red Army troops were
expected to be out of Kabul early in February, along with the Soviet
high command.
   Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and
an estimated 115,000 were in the country when the withdrawal began
May 15 under an agreement signed in Geneva a month earlier. Half
were gone by Aug. 15 and the remainder are to be out by Feb. 15.
   The guerrillas, most of whom are based in border camps and cities
just inside Pakistan, were not parties to the Geneva agreement and
have rejected offers of a coalition government from Najib.
   Kabul radio said Thursday that government troops shot down two
Pakistani helicopters ferrying ``foreign advisers'' and guerrilla
leaders to the eastern Nangarhar province. It said everyone aboard
was killed but did not give casualty figures. Pakistan routinely
denies such reports by official Afghan media.
   Another radio report said a rocket attack wounded five people at
a 315-bed hospital in Kandahar, Afghanistan's second-largest city.
It blamed the insurgents, who are supported by the United States and
Pakistan.
   Most of the Britons and others warned by the embassy are with
U.N. agencies or the International Committee of the Red Cross, which
has a hospital for war wounded in Kabul.
   Also among the Britons are 19 resident missionaries, with their
families, who work for the charitable International Aid Mission.
Families of most foreigners left last summer after the first half of
the Soviet withdrawal was complete.
</TEXT>
