<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Press     01-19 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Press,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Footloose Bush Won't Be `Anchored Down' by Media Entourage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, saying he doesn't want to be
``anchored down,'' indicated Thursday he will keep on making
spur-of-the-moment jaunts around town as president _ with or without
reporters in tow.
   Bush voiced clear skepticism over the practice in which a small
``protective pool'' of reporters follows a president whenever he
leaves the White House _ whether on official business or personal
business.
   ``What's being protected?'' Bush asked in an inauguration-eve
interview with a group of news service reporters.
   ``You mean, if something happened like I fell over and choked at
a restaurant? What if I fall over and choke in the White House?
You're not there.''
   ``I can't pledge to be anchored down. I'd like to work out some
understanding that the world is not going to come to a screeching
halt if you don't know that I'm eating Peking duck over in
Virginia,'' Bush said.
   ``You may not agree with that,'' he said. ``But I think it's
silly to have to feel that, when the president goes out of that
thing (the White House) that serious journalists, or their editors,
feel the nation's business will come to a halt if that is not
reported.''
   Bush as vice president has been known for venturing into public
places frequently _ often going to restaurants with family and
friends, dropping in a neighborhood delicatessen, shopping in super
markets and visiting hardware stores.
   This style contrasts sharply with that of President Reagan, who
seldom left the White House except with advance notice or without a
travel pool of reporters in his motorcade.
   ``I'm not going to give up my ability to make a decision in a
hurry,'' Bush said.
   He suggested that, for one thing, going around town with a large
entourage that includes reporters can make it harder to find a
parking place in front of a restaurant.
   Bush said if he decides at the last minute to have dinner with
friends ``at Joe's Bar or Joe's Restaurant, we've got to be able to
be flexible.''
   ``And you shouldn't have to be rudely treated by standing out in
the cold wondering what the hell I've ordered in a Chinese
restaurant,'' Bush said.
   ``I'm not going to shake you,'' Bush added. ``But I'm not going
to feel obligated to say we can't do this for an hour because we've
got to notify (the news media).''
</TEXT>
