<FIRST>u w AM-Inaugural-FirstLady     01-19 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural-First Lady,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Charms Audiences With Wit, Self-Deprecating Humor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, displaying the ``wicked wit''
that has become her trademark, was cheered by thousands of
supporters Thursday as she poked fun at her appearance, joked about
her husband's fishing and bragged about her family.
   Mrs. Bush, a 63-year-old grandmother with snow white hair and an
imposing figure, appeared at the ``Salute to the First Lady,'' an
event that more than 6,000 people paid $50 a ticket to attend.
   The gathering, held at the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts, drew so many people that Mrs. Bush and Marilyn
Quayle, the wife of Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, appeared before
audiences in the concert hall, the opera hall and the theater.
   ``Speaking of glamor, I want you to look at me very carefully,''
said Mrs. Bush, who often indulges in self-deprecating remarks.
   As the crowd roared, Mrs. Bush stood on the stage and pointed to
herself: ``Please notice the hair, the makeup, designer clothes. ...
I want you to watch me all week and remember _ You may never see it
again.''
   Mrs. Bush, wearing a blue suit _ her favorite color _ with a
large patterned bow at her neck, called the tribute ``unbelievable''
and ``undeserved.''
   The blunt-spoken Mrs. Bush, known for her candor and lack of
pretense, also poked fun at her husband's complaints this week that
packing for the move to the White House was a laborious and tedious
process.
   Noting that Bush spent last weekend fishing in Florida, his wife
of 43 years said: ``So much to the packing story.''
   Mrs. Bush, who is fiercely loyal to her husband and five children
and their families, later said she considered herself the ``world's
luckiest woman'' because she had married ``a man I love more than
life.''
   Actors Bruce Boxleitner and Charlton Heston and actress Cheryl
Ladd read virtually identical scripts as they introduced Mrs. Bush
to successive audiences. They described her as ``kind, generous,
warm and dedicated,'' with values that are similar to those held by
most Americans.
   Mrs. Quayle, in presenting Mrs. Bush to the audiences, had a
difficult time controlling her emotions. ``I'm going to get weepy
because Barbara is so special,'' said the wife of the vice
president-elect, a lawyer with three children.
   ``Barbara Bush brings joy, a wicked wit ... and an indomitable
spirit that she will take to the White House,'' Mrs. Quayle said.
   ``She's the one who is going to cry in the family,'' Mrs. Bush
joked.
   At each hall, Mrs. Bush was entertained by performers ranging
from the National Symphony Orchestra to the Preservation Hall Jazz
Band to the Gatlin Brothers.
   But the obvious hit of the day was the Mora Ariaga Mariachis
band, a group that played Mexican music and featured Noelle Bush,
Mrs. Bush's 11-year-old, Spanish-speaking granddaughter. The girl
sang, danced and played the accordion.
   ``Unless there is an enormous change in our family ... all the
talent was put in one child,'' Mrs. Bush said after Noelle had
presented her grandmother with a huge sombrero.
   Noelle is the daughter of Jeb Bush, a Miami real estate
developer, and his Mexican-born wife, Columba. Mrs. Bush took pride
in introducing Columba, as well as her three other daughters-in-law
and her own daughter, Dorothy LeBlond, to the audiencs.
   Although the speakers talked of Mrs. Bush's keen interest in
promoting literacy and her desire to spotlight other social
problems, the incoming first lady kept her remarks brief and on the
light side.
   The tribute was one of the few inaugural events that Mrs. Bush
was to attend without her husband. The couple stayed in the
presidential guest quarters at Blair House on Wednesday night in
preparation for the move across Pennsylvania Avenue to the White
House after Friday's swearing-in ceremony.
   About 250 Bush relatives are in town for the festivities. A
private dinner with family members was planned Thursday night. On
Friday night, Mrs. Bush's mother-in-law, Dorothy Walker, 87, the
Bush's five children, their spouses and 10 grandchildren will sleep
in the White House.
</TEXT>
