<FIRST>r a AM-Overtown-Profile     01-19 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overtown-Profile,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Past Bright But Future Bleak In Riot-Torn Overtown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Miami Riot, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The message was written in block leters on the side
of a boarded-up market:
   It read: ``HELP.''
   In Miami's impoverished and predominantly black Overtown
district, the plea could easily symbolize the area's turbulent
present and uncertain future.
   The graffiti-covered building stands two blocks from where a
Hispanic police officer fatally shot a 23-year-old black
motorcyclist Monday night, triggering violence fueled by frustration
over unemployment and an influx of Central American refugees.
   Many of the 10,000 Overtown residents look beyond the arson,
gunfire and looting toward the specter of downtown development that
threatens to wipe out the once-vibrant neighborhood.
   ``We may be seeing the beginning of the end of Overtown,'' said
Rev. Richard Barry of St. Agnes Episcopal Church, in the heart of
the neighborhood. ``You see them building expensive condos over by
Miami Arena. The city fathers want to change downtown. That means
getting rid of Overtown.
   ``Among all the burned-out buildings and neglect, there's hardly
anyone who remembers that Overtown has a rich history.''
   The first residents of the area were black workers extending the
Florida East Coast railroad south from West Palm Beach in the 1890s.
They built the area into a flourishing business and residential
community by the 1950s.
   But highway construction for the growing Miami metropolis in the
1960s forced many black middle-class residents and business owners
out of what was then known as the Central Negro District.
   The name Overtown derives from the conversations of people
planning to visit the neighborhood.
   ``They'd say I'm going `over-town,''' said Leome Culmer, chairman
of the speakers' bureau of the Black Archives of Miami. ``It was
quite a place back then.''
   But the legacy of Overtown's heyday has long since disappeared.
``What's left was low-income blacks in a congested area and without
jobs,'' said Barry.
   Since the riots of 1980 claimed 18 lives and dozens of businesses
citywide, the decline of Overtown has been steady, residents say.
   City officials, Overtown residents claim, have focused on the
surge of Cuban and Central American refugees at the expense of job
and housing programs in black neighborhoods, including Overtown and
Liberty City, which is about 30 blocks to the north.
   Liberty City was started as a residential development for blacks
in the 1920s to relieve overcrowding in Overtown.
   Overtown now is a collection of struggling stores and
deteriorating two-story apartment buildings. Palm trees are
surrounded by junk and litter in vacant lots. A 1983 city study
placed the unemployment rate at more than 36 percent.
   ``There's probably crack on every corner,'' said police spokesman
Raymond Lange, referring to the addictive and low-cost form of
cocaine.
   Stephen Wayne traveled from rural Alabama to Miami in search of
construction work. He ended up on a second-floor apartment, in sight
of a supermarket burned during Tuesday night's violence.
   ``I have a gun. Everyone I know has a gun. I don't like going out
on any night,'' he said. ``If I could leave I would.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
