<DOCNO> AP890119-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-LastSpeech     01-19 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Last Speech,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan's Last Speech as President: `Nothing So Precious as Freedom'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan made the final public speech
of his presidency a fittingly patriotic one Thursday as he presented
the Medal of Freedom to Secretary of State George P. Shultz and
Ambassador Mike Mansfield and saluted them as ``two remarkable
Americans.''
   ``Since this is the last speech that I will give as president, I
think it is fitting to give one final thought: an observation about
a country that I love,'' Reagan said.
   ``There is nothing so precious and irreplaceable as America's
freedom,'' added Reagan in the patriotic manner that has marked his
speeches for decades.
   ``America's freedom does not belong to just one nation,'' he
said. ``We are custodians of freedom for the world.''
   ``We lead the world because, unique among nations, we draw our
people and our strength from every country and every corner of the
world.''
   The president described the United States as ``always on the
cutting edge, always leading the world to the next frontier.''
   Reagan said the Medal of Freedom, awarded for contributions to
the national interest, world peace and cultural achievement among
other endeavors, ``represents the reverence Americans have for
liberty.''
   He said Mansfield, former Senate majority leader who recently
resigned after more than a decade as ambassador to Japan, had
``distinguished himself as a dedicated public servant.''
   Mansfield, accepting the medal, said Reagan had ``laid out a
sound policy for our future in the Pacific and East Asia'' and ``for
the first time in memory, we have both a president of the United
States and a secretary of state who are actively interested in the
Pacific, in Japan and in East Asia.''
   ``I anticipate that the policy these men have laid down will be
continued,'' he added.
   Reagan said Shultz had ``inaugurated a new era of hope in foreign
policy'' and presided over the State Department ``during one of the
most critical periods in the history of this nation's foreign
policy.''
   Shultz, in his response, said, ``There is a phrase that's
catching on. `The Reagan years.' And, Mr. President, it has a ring
to it. It's the ring of freedom. You have adocated it, fought for
it.''
   ``You have known that the price of freedom is enternal vigilance
... that there are times when it requires action, sometimes at least
at first not necessarily popular action, but you have to do it,'' he
said.
   Mansfield paid tribute to his wife, Maureen, in his remarks and
Shultz walked over to his wife's table, gave her a kiss and handed
the medal to her after receiving it at the ceremony in the East Room.
   Among those in the audience was Vernon Walter, U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations, who earlier in the day received the Citizens
Medal from Reagan. The Citizens Medal is given to ctizens who have
performed deeds of service to their country or their fellow citizens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
