<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SillyBills     01-19 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Silly Bills,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>No More Turkey Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Congress passed a bill designating
National Asparagus Month during a crush of important legislation
last year, for Rep. Dave McCurdy it was the last stalk.
   The Oklahoma Democrat on Thursday introduced legislation to ban
Congress' growing practice of passing commemmorative bills, and
instead create an 11-member advisory panel to judge the merits of
various requests for commemorative days, weeks, months and years.
   McCurdy pointed out in a statement that more than one-third of
the laws passed in the last Congress were in the commemorative
category. Among bills introduced were Snow White Week, National
Dairy Goat Awareness Week and National Elvis Presley Day. In all,
646 such bills were introduced in the 100th Congress.
   ``The annual costs of commemorative legislation cannot be
precisely determined, but we know from examining the process that
they are enormous,'' McCurdy said. ``The annual printing costs of
the resolutions alone run into the hundreds of thousands of
dollars.''
   McCurdy said most of the commemmorative bills are worthy, but his
bill was a more ``common-sense approach'' to deciding which to
recognize than spending time on the floor of a billion-dollar
Congress.
</TEXT>
