<FIRST>u w AM-Barry-Probe 1stLd-Writethru a0749 01-19 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf new material after 2nd graf pvs</HEAD>
<HEAD>D.C. Mayor Testifies Under Subpoena</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. appeared under subpoena
Thursday before a federal grand jury investigating his ties to a
suspected drug dealer. Barry told reporters he had done nothing
wrong and was not the target of the probe.
   ``I'm not in trouble,'' Barry said at an impromptu news
conference as he headed into the grand jury's meeting room in the
federal courthouse. ``The public sometimes has the impression that
going before a grand jury means that someone is guilty ... but it
only means they are investigating. That's the American way.''
   Barry met with the grand jury for about three hours. He said
little to reporters afterward.
   Kenneth Mundy, Barry's attorney, said he has received assurances
that Barry is not a target of the probe. Federal officials were not
available to comment on Mundy's comment.
   Officials also refused to comment on Barry's appearance before
the grand jury, but had earlier said that investigators are
gathering information on whether Barry thwarted a police drug probe
and are also looking into the possible misuse of government funds.
   The mayor was subpoenaed after failing to answer an informal
request that he appear. Barry is expected to testify before the
grand jury again next week, Mundy said.
   On Dec. 22, police were inexplicably called off an attempt to
make an undercover drug purchase from a former city employee,
Charles Lewis, after Barry showed up at his hotel room. Barry has
also acknowledged contacting police officials looking into the
affair, but said he was only trying to speed up the probe.
   District of Columbia Police Chief Maurice Turner has denied that
police were tipped off that Barry was in Lewis' room, but did say
that detectives were called off their attempted drug purchase by the
hotel's manager.
   The grand jury is also hearing testimony on a joint personnel
project involving the district and the U.S. Virgin Islands
government. Lewis, a former city employee, spearheaded that project
for the Virgin Islands. He was fired last April after Virgin Islands
officials expressed concern about cost overruns on the project.
Barry and other top city officials ran up hotel and restaurant bills
of more than $37,000 in connection with the project.
   So far, Lewis, city personnel director Theodore E. Thornton and a
personal bodyguard who accompanied Barry to Lewis' hotel room have
testified at least once before the panel.
   Barry's telephone records, police phone logs, and thousands of
documents connected with the Virgin Islands personnel project have
also been subpoenaed. Those include contracts officials have said
were prepared and back-dated well after the project began.
   Because of his connections with Lewis, Barry, 52, is mired in his
worst political crisis in the decade he has served as mayor of the
nation's capital.
   Barry's latest troubles have revived persistant rumors that he
uses drugs and associates with drug users, while he and his
associates have also come under fire for the city's involvement in
the Virgin Islands project.
   The Interior Department, which oversees affairs of the Virgin
Islands government, has not been able to find a written contract for
the $260,000 project, and Virgin Islands Gov. Alexander Farrelly has
said that the spending overruns means the district may not be paid
the $80,000 in costs it has claimed.
   Barry attempted to quell questions about his alleged drug use by
taking a drug test Tuesday.
   Dr. Vincent J. Roux, the mayor's personal physician, pronounced
Barry drug-free after testing his urine for up to 10 illegal drugs,
including marijuana, cocaine and barbituates.
   However, John White, the mayor's press secretary, said he did not
know whether the mayor's blood was tested for drugs. Medical experts
have said that blood testing is more exhaustive and can show traces
of drugs that a urine test won't turn up.
</TEXT>
