<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels Attack Relief Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels ambushed a railroad relief convoy
and its escort of troops and 75 people died in the battle, official
reports said.
   Al-Guwat Al-Musalaha, the military's biweekly magazine, said the
soldiers killed 70 rebels and lost four of their own men. The
government said a civilian train worker was also killed.
   The military report also said Wednesday that 16 people were
injured in the ambush by rebels of the Sudan People's Liberation
Army.
   The government said the convoy of four trains reached its
destination, Aweil, 11 days after leaving the capital, Khartoum,
about 600 miles away. It said the attack took place last week but
did not give an exact date.
   The convoy left Khartoum on Jan. 5 with food, medicine and relief
supplies for refugees from the civil war in the south.
   The rebels have fought the government since 1983, demanding
reforms in the south.
