<FIRST>r w AM-Oakar-Hostages     01-19 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oakar-Hostages,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oakar Says Assad Makes Firm Commitment to Work for Release of Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, said Thursday
that Syrian President Hafez Assad has made a firm commitment to her
to work for the release of the nine American hostages held in
Lebanon.
   Oakar, who met with Assad for more than four hours in Damascus,
Syria, on Jan. 9, said in an interview that Assad was ``very
positive in saying that he would help'' in the hostage situation.
   Oakar's comments came as President Reagan told reporters a day
before leaving office that he was frustrated by his inability to
free the Americans in war-torn Lebanon.
   ``We don't know where they are,'' Reagan said, adding officials
are working ``quietly and privately'' to win freedom for the
hostages.
   Oakar said she raised the case of Terry Anderson, a hostage since
March 1985. Anderson, an Associated Press correspondent in Lebanon
when he was kidnapped and the longest-held hostage, is a native of
Lorain, Ohio, which is near Oakar's Cleveland district.
   During a trip to the Middle East, Oakar arranged the wide-ranging
session with Assad. Also attending the meeting were Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., and Edward Djerejian, the U.S. ambassador to Syria.
Specter's office said he was attending inaugural events and could
not be reached for comment immediately.
   But Oakar, who has an Arab-American heritage, said she was
pleased with the reaction from Assad when the discussion turned to
the plight of Anderson.
   ``I felt that he was extremely firm in his commitment to help
Terry,'' she said. Reading from her notes on the meeting, Oakar
quoted Assad as saying, ``I want to say to the family that I will
help.''
   The hostages are thought to be held by pro-Iranian militants in
the southern suburbs of Beirut. Syria considers itself the main
power broker in Lebanon, though fighting between rival militias has
put pressure on Syria's ability to influence events over the last
few months.
   The prospect of a Syrian-sponsored settlement in Lebanon, a
country where Moslems and Christians have fought for 13 years, is
not considered bright in the near future.
   Oakar said Assad did not provide any details about how he might
work for the hostages' freedom. However, he said he viewed the
hostages as a humanitarian issue rather than a political issue.
   The Syrian leader said the ``whole hostage question is a human
question,'' Oakar said.
   But Assad is obviously a player in the region, Oakar said. ``He
could use his influence. ... He obviously has occasions for
dialogue,'' she said.
   She said Assad stressed the hostages were a sensitive issue and
he would avoid doing anything that might harm them.
</TEXT>
