<FIRST>r w AM-Darman-IronTriangle     01-19 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Darman-Iron Triangle,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Darman Confirmation, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Darman Contests Shape of Reagan's Iron Triangle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to the federal deficit, George
Bush's chosen budget director, Richard Darman, sees the problem
differently than President Reagan does.
   At his confirmation hearing before the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee on Thursday, Darman was asked whether he agreed
with Reagan's characterization of an ``iron triangle'' consisting of
Congress, the news media and special interest groups as the culprits
for the government's huge budget imbalances.
   ``It doesn't sound like a complete explanation,'' he said after a
long pause. ``I think we probably need something larger than a
triangle.''
   ``Like a pentagon?'' asked Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, the
committee's chairman.
   ``It would have to be at least a hexagon,'' he said. ``But
certainly these three would make any short list.''
   Glenn asked Darman if he believed the White House might also be
included in any compilation of those responsible for the red ink.
   ``That would probably make the list too,'' he said.
   Reagan made his remarks in a speech Dec. 13.
   Darman spent most of the 1980s working in the Reagan
administration. He is expected to receive Senate confirmation to be
director of the Office of Management and Budget, perhaps as early as
Wednesday.
