<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InaugurationsPast     01-19 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugurations Past,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>How Outgoing Presidents Treated Their Successors And Other Notable
Tidbits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the presidential torch is passed Friday
to George Bush, the transition will be quite unlike the inaugural
experience of the nation's second president, one historian says.
   ``When John Adams was inaugurated, he was furious,'' said Thomas
O. Kelly, chairman of American Studies at Siena College. ``Nobody
was talking to him; they were all going up to George Washington to
say good-bye.''
   There was even a ``good-bye'' party for Washington from which
Adams ``was frozen out.''
   ``It wasn't Washington's fault. I think they just forgot to
invite him (Adams),'' said Kelly.
   That snafu would repeat itself four years later, in 1801, when
Thomas Jefferson was inaugurated. ``Adams wasn't invited to that
ball either.''
   A bitter campaign between Herbert Hoover and Franklin D.
Roosevelt left an icy barrier between the two at Roosevelt's
inauguration in 1933.
   ``FDR had been elected on a pledge to maintain a balanced
budget,'' Kelly said, adding that Roosevelt's campaign charges of
mismanagement created the iceberg.
   The worst inaugural ball? That dubious honor goes to Ulysses S.
Grant after his election to a second term in 1873.
   That ball, with about $40,000 worth of food (and in those days,
the average day laborer earned between $400 and $500 a year), was
held in a temporary building. But the weather contributed high wind
and freezing temperatures.
   ``There was no heat (in the building) so everyone went home
early,'' said Kelly.
   While the electronic news media has been kind to President
Reagan, they would have been ``destructive'' for the country's 16th
president. ``Abraham Lincoln had a bad speaking voice,'' Kelly
explained.
   He added that the sight of FDR's wheelchair also may have
tarnished Roosevelt's popularity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Koop     01-19 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koop Has No Great Fear of Back-Alley Abortionists if Court Overturns
Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop said Thursday
he has no great fear of back-alley abortionists if the Supreme Court
overturns its 1973 decision legalizing abortions.
   The National Abortion Federation criticized Koop for diminishing
the risks involved in illegal abortions.
   Koop, interviewed on ``CBS This Morning,'' said the number of
illegal abortion deaths was exaggerated by pro-choice advocates when
the high court issued its Roe vs. Wade decision.
   ``The greatest number of deaths ever in one year was 373,'' said
Koop, an opponent of abortion. ``That's a terrible number, but it
wasn't 10,000.''
   Koop said, ``That doesn't mean that there's not going to be a
black market, and we don't have problems on our hands.'' But he
added that ``with the techniques that are being used by abortionists
now, those same techniques will be used in the future, and they are
safer.''
   He also said that if the Supreme Court returns control of
abortions to the states, ``it will open Pandora's box, because we'll
have 50 problems instead of one.''
   The National Abortion Federation said forcing women to seek
illegal abortions would create a serious public health problem.
   ``Whenever medicine goes underground, complications and deaths
rise. Not only would we have a Pandora's box of legal issues but
we'd have a Pandora's box of health issues we haven't seen in the
past 16 years,'' said Alice Kirkman, a spokeswoman for the
federation.
   The group agreed with Koop's assessment that giving control of
abortions to states would create problems.
   Koop said if the decision is overturned, ``it will go back to
pre-1973 where certain states will opt to be very liberal about
abortions and others will clamp down. ... And what it meant was that
abortions were available on demand to people who could get to those
states but they were essentially inaccessible to those'' who could
not.
   Koop angered many anti-abortion activists recently when he
decided not to issue a report requested by President Reagan on the
health impact of abortion.
   In a letter to the president earlier this month he said that
among Reagan's advisers, ``it was a foregone conclusion that the
negative health effects of abortion on women were so overwhelming
that the evidence would force the reversal of Roe vs. Wade.''
   But Koop said in the letter that no such scientific evidence
exists. He said that while anecdotal reports are plentiful to
support both sides, ``individual cases cannot be used to reach
scientifically sound conclusions.''
   The Supreme Court last week agreed to hear an appeal that the
Justice Department wants the court to use as a vehicle for
overturning its landmark 1973 decision.
   Nancy Broff of the National Abortion Rights Action League said
``there are not good figures'' for pre-1973 abortion deaths, but she
said Koop's estimate is ``extremely low.''
   She cited research that estimated as many as one death for every
100 illegal abortions. Other research said that in 1955 between
200,000 and 1.2 million illegal abortions were performed in the
United States.
   ``And that doesn't take into account women who are mutilated and
who suffered long-term health consequences'' from illegal abortions,
Broff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
