<FIRST>r w AM-US-Arafat 1stLd-Writethru a0700 01-19 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arafat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs new material</HEAD>
<HEAD>Another `Contact' with PLO Disclosed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department disclosed Thursday another
U.S. meeting had been held with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, but no details of the ``contact'' in Tunis were
released.
   ``I am not going to go into any specific agenda items,''
department spokesman Charles E. Redman said of the meeting. He also
refused to release the text of a statement in which PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat threatened to pump 10 bullets into the chest of anyone
who tried to stem the Palestinian unrest on the Israeli-held West
Bank.
   The Reagan administration broke a 13-year ban on U.S. talks with
the PLO last month. Secretary of State George P. Shultz said the
decision was based on a public statement by Arafat renouncing
terrorism in all forms and accepting Israel's right to exist.
   Robert Pelletreau, the U.S. ambassador to Tunis, was designated
the only official U.S. channel to the PLO, although it was revealed
later that restrictions had been lifted on other American officials
meeting socially with PLO representatives.
   Redman said the latest ``contact'' was a meeting Tuesday in Tunis
between Pelletreau and a PLO representative. He said it was not like
the initial meeting in mid-December, but was ``more in the nature of
an informal contact.''
   The spokesman declined to say whether the bombing of a Pan Am
jumbo jet Dec. 21 was discussed. A total of 270 passengers, crew
members and people on the ground died in the crash in Scotland.
   The PLO has offered to assist in the bombing investigation. PLO
representatives have been quoted as suggesting Israel was behind the
attack.
   Redman refused to say whether the PLO had made the allegation
directly to U.S. officials or which side initiated the latest Tunis
meeting.
   ``I'm just not going to go into the agenda,'' he said. ``As this
develops, I don't think you'll find it unusual that there may be
contacts of one kind or another, initiated by one side or the other,
as this process develops. The kind of things you will know about
will be the real meetings, the real dialogue.''
   He added: ``I don't want to set the precedent of going into the
agenda.''
   Redman's disclosure of another U.S.-PLO meeting came in response
to a reporter's question.
   On Wednesday, again in response to a question, he said the State
Department had obtained a tape recording in which Arafat had said:
``Whoever thinks of stopping the intefadah before it achieve its
goals, I will give him 10 bullets in the chest.''
   Intefadah is the Arabic word for the violent, 13-month uprising
by Palestinian inhabitants of the West Bank and Gaza.
   Redman said Wednesday that Arafat has since denied he intended
any threat against Elias Freij, the mayor of Bethlehem who is
considered a moderate Palestinian and was the purported target.
   Redman gave no indication the United States was reconsidering its
decision to hold talks with the PLO. Assistant Secretary of State
Richard W. Murphy said last month the talks would be suspended if
Arafat reneged on his renunciation of terrorism.
   Redman refused to provide the text of Arafat's entire statement.
   ``I read the particularly relevant part yesterday,'' he said.
   Asked about the uprising itself, the spokesman said, ``We do not
consider the intefadah terrorism.'' Redman also reiterated the U.S.
call for ``everybody to refrain from violence and to work for
peace.''
   Elaboratoring, the U.S. official said ``individual acts would
have to be evaluated.''
</TEXT>
