<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-France     01-19 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-France,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Presidents Meets with Bulgarian Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand of France
met on Thursday with 12 Bulgarian human rights activists who asked
for Western help in relaxing their country's rigid communist system.
   The group invited to have breakfast with Mitterrand at the French
ambassador's residence included scientists, writers, artists and
journalists, some of whom belong to the Communist Party.
   Most are among the approximately 150 members of the Club for the
Support of Glasnost amd Perestroika, formed in November to promote
the economic and social reform being pursued in the Soviet Union by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Alexei Chelutko, a 65-year-old academician, delivered a letter to
Mitterrand that described official harassment of club members.
   At a news conference with Tolor Zhivkov, the Bulgarian president
and party chief, at the end of his 36-hour visit to Bulgaria, the
French president said:
   ``I would like to thank Mr. Zhivkov and the Bulgarian leadership
because I was also able to meet those with different opinions, those
who approve and those who don't approve.''
   Asked by a Bulgarian television reporter what he thought of some
French newspaper reports on Bulgaria and its recent crackdown on
dissidents, he said: ``The press is free and this sometimes creates
inconveniences, but less than the absence of freedom.''
   Rabotnichesko Delo, the party newspaper, carried an article
Thursday attacking some French reports on harassment of dissidents.
   Authorities detained about two dozen activists last week in
Plovdiv. They were released after French diplomatic intervention but
put under house arrest, French officials said.
   Zhivkov said in an interview with the French daily Le Monde
published Wednesday that 25 people had been arrested. He described
them as criminals.
   A French reporter asked him Thursday when his government would
allow Bulgarians free travel to the West. Zhivkov replied: ``No
problem. We signed the document in Vienna and they will be able to
come and go as they please.''
   In his speech at a state banquet Wednesday evening, Mitterrand
made a strong call for greater human rights with the declaration:
``National sovereignty, representative democracy, separation of
powers, freedom and respect for individuals; these values have lost
nothing of their reality.''
   Nikolai Vassiliev, a science professor who attended the meeting
with Mitterrand, told reporters: ``We discussed the problems in our
social development. We want our society to become more humanized and
to find its place in the European house mentioned by Gorbachev.''
   He quoted Mitterrand as telling his visitors ``France cannot help
solve our problem directly but would do its best indirectly.''
Vassiliev said French media could help by publicizing his group's
activities.
   French sources said the intellectuals told Mitterrand they felt
Gorbachev-style reform was the road Bulgaria should take.
   Chelutko, who presented the letter, told reporters the club was
not illegal and membership in it and Communist Party were
compatible, but said police persecution had begun.
   In the letter to Mitterrand, he quoted Zhivkov as saying the club
would be left alone if it did not violate the law, but added:
``After our founding declaration and our meeting, the club's
activity was completely paralyzed by police prosecutors and party
organs.''
   After talking with the club members, Mitterrand went to Sofia
University and answered questions for 80 minutes from about 1,000
students packed into an auditorium.
   The first question was: ``What do you think about democracy and
human rights in Bulgaria?''
   Mitterrand said he could not judge because he had arrived only
Wednesday, but added to loud applause: ``What is interesting is not
my response, but your question.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
