<HEAD>Reagan Legacy In Safe Hands With Bush, Falwell Declares</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell on Thursday praised
President-elect Bush as an experienced manager whose administration
is likely to continue the Reagan legacy and will not bring any ``bad
surprises'' for the country's conservative movement.
   ``I am convinced in my heart that George Bush by osmosis, just as
Ronald Reagan 30 years ago, has moved from _ he would say the
center, I would say a little left of center _ to where he is
today,'' Falwell told a convention of Students for America, a
conservative youth group.
   ``And I think where he is today is clearly where Ronald Reagan is
today,'' the Moral Majority founder added.
   Falwell said he considers Bush a better manager than Reagan.
   ``Ronald Reagan, the visionary we needed eight years ago, laid
the foundation for it, he gave us the dream,'' Falwell said. ``But I
see George Bush as a hands-on, very experienced manager.''
   He said everything he had heard from Bush both in public and
private ``tells me that we don't have any surprises upcoming. I
don't think any of us are going to be disappointed.''
   Falwell expressed satisfaction with the health of the
conservative movement, saying that today more young people
``understand the bankruptcy of the liberal, socialistic point of
view that almost dominated this country 20 years ago.''
   ``All over Washington today, conservative young people and older
people are here celebrating the Reagan revolution and praying that
the agenda will continue,'' Falwell said.
