<FIRST>r w AM-Shultz-Farewell     01-19 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz-Farewell,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Gets Emotional Sendoff At State Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of applauding State Department
officials gave a teary-eyed Secretary of State George P. Shultz an
emotional sendoff Thursday as he ended 6{ years as America's top
diplomat.
   Standing before the throng in the State Department lobby, Shultz
placed his arm around his wife, Obie, and said, ``We came as a
package deal. We leave as a package.''
   In a wavering voice, Shultz praised his State Department
colleagues and said it was a ``tremendous privilege to be a part of
this family.''
   ``We just appreciate so much the partnership we've had with all
of you,'' he said.
   As Shultz headed out the door, a five-piece Marine band played
``California, Here I Come.'' Shultz has a home in the San Francisco
area and will fly there on Friday. He plans to resume teaching at
Stanford.
   Shultz flew 880,000 miles during overseas travels since July
1982. He served longer than his five immediate predecessors. The
last secretary of state with a longer tenure than Shultz was Dean
Rusk, 1961-69.
