<FIRST>r a AM-Murder-a-Day     01-19 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder-a-Day,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Formed As New Orleans Sees 18th Homicide Of '89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jewelry store employee was murdered Thursday
just as the mayor was announcing the appointment of a task force to
look into the wave of killings that have averaged one a day since
the year began.
   Police said the female employee was shot in the back of the head,
apparently just after she opened the jewelry store at 9 a.m.,
becoming the 18th homicide victim in 19 days.
   Display cases were ransacked and police suspected armed robbery.
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, Police Chief Warren Woodfork and Coroner
Frank Minyard blame drugs for most of the homicides.
   Cocaine was found in the blood of eight of the first 17 victims,
said Minyard. Eight of the victims had police records and nine died
of wounds from machine-gun type weapons that more and more drug
dealers in New Orleans are carrying, the coroner said.
   Barthelemy said his task force, made up of business and civic
leaders, was part of an effort to draw the community together in the
fight against drugs and drug-related violence.
   ``Law-abiding citizens must come to the forefront,'' he said.
``We must take a stand that we're not going to accept drugs in this
community.''
