<DOCNO> AP890119-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Walesa     01-19 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Walesa Cautious In Face Of Government Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told
reporters on Thursday that any agreement to legalize his banned
union movement must preserve its independence.
   Walesa said he was being cautious before responding to the
Communist Party's new position on trade unions and would have no
answer to the party document until Friday, after he examined it.
   He appeared upbeat and hopeful, however, as he addressed a packed
room of reporters and supporters in St. Brygida's Church in his home
city of Gdansk.
   Walesa spoke a few hours before a news conference in Warsaw by
Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski at which Jaruzelski unveiled
the party's plan to legalize Solidarity under conditions to be
negotiated.
   ``Tomorrow I will try to say something, when I see what it's
like,'' said Walesa, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize and a
founder of Solidarity, the first free trade union movement in the
East bloc.
   Solidarity was suspended when martial law was imposed in Poland
in December 1981 and was outlawed in 1982.
   Walesa said that under no condition would he accept an offer that
deprives Solidarity of its freedom of action.
   ``After all the experiences, losses and struggles, we cannot give
up our independence or sovereignty,'' he said.
   ``If we blow it here, other people will have to deal with the
same problem again. I don't want my son or his generation to live
through such things again, where it all accumulates, rots and then
explodes.
   ``We cannot destroy this chance (by conceding too much), but at
the same time we should not struggle for some ambitious details.''
   Legalization, he said, has become increasingly important because
of poor economic conditions and deteriorating public moods.
   The labor leader noted that a scattering of strikes took place in
recent weeks and said he heard more strikes might be declared as
early as Monday.
   He said that ``despair (may bring) ... desperate acts.''
   ``I treat Soldarity's revival as very important, very urgent and
very timely _ an independent Solidarity without any confinements in
freedoms,'' Walesa went on.
   ``I believe that Solidarity will be wise and reasonable, that it
will understand what's necessary. But I won't allow anybody to
deprive it of its independence.''
   Walesa said he saw some positive developments among authorities.
   ``Now everybody is convinced that Poland really needs agreement
based on principles of freedom and pluralism, with as few
limitations and confinements as possible and as much faith in
people's wisdom as possible,'' he said.
   He minimized the risk to the government of permitting legal
operation of his union movement.
   ``This is not the time when workers destroy machines or burn
them. Today workers are much more sophisticated and they can
understand other's reasons. But they must themselves be understood
first,'' he said.
   ``Working people in Poland are able to take responsibility for
development in a civilized and not destructive way. I deeply believe
it.''
   When pressed about his assessments of a Communist Party plenum
this week, Walesa would make only general comments.
   ``It seems to me that it provides too much to die on and too
little to live on,'' he said. ``It is a lot for this party. ... But
it is too little for social demands.''
   He said it is easier for authorities to talk to an organization
than to a shouting mob.
   Walesa continued: ``Conditions in Poland give justification to
every one of us to strike ... because the situation is so bad. But
reason shows that this leads nowhere.
   ``I think that the opinion in Poland is similar on all sides. .
.. We have to create condition for good work for everyone in the
country. At the same time we have to respect their independence.
   ``This is the only way we can develop and this seems to be
understood.''
</TEXT>
