<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Students     01-19 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Students,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Rally in Support of Banned Organization</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of supporters of the banned
Independent Students Organization rallied in several cities on
Thursday to demand legalization of the group, state-run media and an
opposition spokesman said.
   Students marched through the cities of Cracow, Lublin and
Wroclaw, the official news agency PAP said.
   In Cracow, a delegation of students was received by Jozef
Gajewicz, a Communist Party first secretary. Gajewicz talked to the
group about the results of this week's party meeting, which called
for greater political and union freedoms.
   The student group was founded during the period of Solidarity
trade union's legal existence in 1980-81 and was banned after the
martial law crackdown in Dec. 1981. The organization went
underground, but last fall began an open campaign to obtain legal
registration.
   Zygmunt Lenyk, an opposition spokesman in Cracow, said the group
dispersed peacefully and there were no arrests. There were no
reports of arrests in the two other cities.
</TEXT>
