<FIRST>r a AM-WhizKid     01-19 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whiz Kid,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Custody Settlement in Case of Youngest College Graduate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A battle over 12-year-old mathematics
whiz Adragon De Mello _ the world's youngest college graduate _ has
been settled, with his parents agreeing to joint custody.
   Cathy Gunn and Agustin De Mello came to terms Wednesday as Santa
Cruz County sought to have Adragon named a ward of the court, said
the father's lawyer, Paul B. Meltzer. The county dropped its action,
the lawyer said.
   Adragon last year graduated at age 11 from the University of
California at Santa Cruz, earning a spot in the Guinness Book of
World Records.
   The boy was placed in a foster home in September after his mother
alleged that the boy and his father had a suicide pact. Since
November, Adragon has been living with his mother, while De Mello
had supervised visits.
   The boy's father was arrested for investigation of felony child
endangerment, but no charges were filed, and he denied forming a
suicide pact.
   Meltzer said the settlement allows each parent to spend
``significant time'' with the boy and calls for no contact between
the parents.
   Gordon Salisbury, Adragon's lawyer, said the boy is ``very happy
the way the custody is structured.''
   ``I hope my son is happy,'' said his father. ``I'm happy with the
result.''
   Neither the mother nor her attorney would comment.
</TEXT>
