<HEAD>Quayle Quotes Churchill as Thousands Jam History Museum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Subs graf 3 to make clear costumed guard behind him; edits to
tighten, eliminates last graf redundant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle on Thursday
borrowed a line from Winston Churchill about surviving an attack in
what seemed to be a reference to the controversy over his nomination
last year.
   ``Winston Churchill once said that there's nothing more
exhilarating than to be shot at without result,'' Quayle told a
group gathered in the lobby of the National Museum of American
History.
   ``Here we are, ready to go, to do the work that you and the
people of America said they wanted us to do,'' he said as costumed
members of the U.S. Army Old Guard Fife and Drum Corps stood behind
him.
   The remarks seemed to refer to the GOP's November victory despite
the campaign uproar over Quayle's experience, military record and
other matters.
   He spent the afternoon shaking hands with thousands of ``our best
friends'' at the museum. An estimated 13,000 supporters paid $20
each to see Quayle, his wife, Marilyn, and his parents, and each of
the visitors received a commemorative medallion etched with his
picture.
   Quayle elaborated on the Churchill remark before a later
audience, saying it was ``rather appropriate to my particular case.''
   He arose at 5:30 a.m. and appeared on morning television talk
shows on CBS and NBC, then stopped at a downtown fast-food
restaurant for breakfast.
   After an afternoon of receptions, Quayle planned to attend the
Indiana Society ball, then the inaugural gala and other festivities
lasting until around midnight.
   Earlier, Quayle spoke to 8,000 high school students and expressed
regret about his own missed opportunities as student.
   ``As one looks back at life, I'll be the first to admit I wish I
had taken education more seriously,'' Quayle said.
   ``Seriousness about education is something, to be honest with
you, I wish I had done differently,'' he added.
   The former Indiana senator has acknowledged before that he was
not the most serious student in his class but declined in the fall
campaign to release his college grade transcripts.
   His selection by Bush to the Republican ticket in August sparked
controversy over his service in the National Guard, which allowed
him to avoid military service in Vietnam.
   Quayle received polite applause from the youthful crowd of high
school juniors and seniors that filled the Washington, D.C., Armory.
The students, who earlier in the day were addressed by
President-elect Bush, came from more than 700 schools nationwide.
   Quayle spoke of the importance of family, traditional values and
hard work.
   ``Hard work has dignity, and let me tell you, hard work has
rewards,'' said Quayle, who is among the heirs to a family newspaper
fortune. ``... Those rewards are opportunities.''
   He said the new administration will ``march forward and crusade
for greater opportunity.''
   ``I've known George Bush now for over 10 years,'' Quayle said.
``We're together on a day-to-day basis, and I can tell you that his
commitment to helping people, and particularly to helping people
that have not had the opportunities that he had or I had or you had
is not only genuine but he has a deep compassion to helping these
people out.''
   Quayle was introduced by his niece, 17-year-old Jennifer Tucker
of Paoli, Ind.
</TEXT>
