<HEAD>Nicaragua To Celebrate Reagan's Departure With Parades, Parties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government workers plan to celebrate
the end of the Reagan administration on Friday with parties, parades
and political meetings, the state radio Voice of Nicaragua said.
   ``The workers will show their ingenuity to mock imperialism and
the reactionaries in this country,'' the radio said Thursday
   It said a parade will be held from the northeastern, industrial
part of the capital to the Plaza of the Revolution, in what was
downtown Managua before it was destroyed an earthquake 16 years ago.
   A public party will follow, the broadcast said.
   The newspaper Barricada of the governing Sandinista National
Liberation Front began publishing articles by American writers this
week on ``Eight Years of Yankee Failure in Nicaragua.''
   The leftist government says it hopes normal relations with the
United States can be restored after President-elect George Bush
takes office.
   The Reagan administration financed Contra rebels who have fought
to overthrow the Sandinistas since 1981. It also has maintained
economic sanctions on Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
