<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-InauguralBriefs     01-19 1032</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural Briefs,1090</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inaugural Activities in Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sign on the street stand read ``Sweatshirts
$11,'' but the Bush inaugural sweatshirts were going for $18 with
the vendor's apologies Thursday.
   ``They cost me almost double,'' explained Said Mahfus, 47, as he
tended his stand on the corner of 17th Street and Pennsylvania
Avenue, a block from the White House.
   ``I pay $80 a dozen for these,'' he said, pointing to his
customary stock of ``Welcome to Washington'' and ``Georgetown
Hoyas'' sweatshits, ``and $148 for these,'' patting the shelf full
of ``George to George'' sweatshirts with pictures of both Washington
and Bush.
   Even at $18, he had sold about three dozen from this prime
location, and his stock of buttons was disappearing fast.
   ``This `George to George' is very hot,'' said Mahfus, an Afghan
refugee who has sold souvenirs on the same corner for nearly three
years.
   Mahfus hopes to return to his homeland one day. ``I was not
working on the street in my country. I had my own business,'' he
said. ``But I have to feed my family.''
   And the new president?
   ``It's great for us, especially for Afghanistan's problems. Bush
and Reagan were the best,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gordon Littig, a retired military man, had a
plan: take the subway downtown Thursday, check out the reviewing
stands outside the White House, then watch the festivities Friday
from the comfort of his living room.
   Littig, 69, and his wife, Betty, were strolling in the
unseasonably warm sunshine when they heard that Bush might be
driving out of the White House soon.
   A full hour later, the Alexandria, Va., couple was front and
center in the crowd that stood in the middle of Pennsylvania Avenue
and cheered as the vice president's limousine pulled out the
driveway and Bush, his nose practically pressed against the glass,
gave a big wave.
   ``We just stumbled onto this,'' said Littig. ``We thought it
would be nice to see it here today and watch it on TV tomorrow.''
   The Littigs have been particularly pleased with the post-election
Bush.
   ``I'm more impressed now after the election at some of his
speeches than I was before. It seems like he's sort of a
practical-type person that will give us the leadership,'' he said.
   ``He's a good Republican. That's a big plus in the first place,''
said Mrs. Littig. ``He just impresses me. We thought Reagan was
wonderful and I thought he'd be a hard man to follow _ and he is
going to be a hard man to follow. But I think Bush is going to be
equally as good.''
   And as for those living rooms plans Friday?
   ``That's what he thinks,'' Mrs. Littig said firmly. ``I'm going
to try to drag him back down here to watch the parade.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inside St. John's Church, facing the White
House from across Lafayette Square, organist Samuel Carabetta
practiced ``Amazing Grace.''
   The organ music filled the empty pews of the small, pillared
church that on Friday morning will be occupied by President-elect
Bush and Vice President-elect Dan Quayle and their wives in a
private service a few hours before the swearing-in.
   Their presence will help the 172-year-old Episcopal church uphold
the title that appears on its bulletin boards: ``The Church of the
Presidents.''
   ``Every president of the United States since James Madison has
attended services here,'' the signs read.
   The Bushes and Quayles will be facing an altar draped in green
with fresh flowers arrayed beneath a cross. Above the altar, a
stained-glass window made at Chartres Cathedral in France depicts
the Last Supper.
   The parish bulletin for Sunday starts with a note from the
pastor, the Rev. John C. Harper: ``We have prayed for our leaders
this past week, and we will do so again.
   ``Our prayer is for wise actions in order that the land we love
will provide room for individuals and that truly great men and women
will love the truth so much that they will be thus enabled to
accomplish great things,'' said Harper, who will preside at the
service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $25 million, four-day party celebrating
George Bush's inauguration is neither excessive nor inappropriate,
Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson said Thursday.
   ``We've passed Andy Jackson's time, when the president of the
United States could say, `Y'all come on over,' and just throw open
the doors of the White House,'' the governor said at an
inaugural-week breakfast.
   ``We're a different nation now,'' Thompson told his Illinois
audience. ``And I don't think the nation minds if George Bush begins
his inaugural with a flyby over the Lincoln Memorial and fireworks.''
   Thompson branded as ``sour grapes'' a complaint by former Sen.
William Proxmire, D-Wis., that private donors should have used the
$1,500 they spent on the inaugural dinner to feed the poor instead.
   ``The price for the dinner was not to buy $1,500 worth of food,
obviously,'' he said. ``It goes to pay the expenses of the
inaugural, which includes many events which are free and open to the
public _ whether you're a Republican or a Democrat.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marylanders created a giant cowboy boot and
10-gallon hat for a float, cooked thousands of meals and groomed
tiny horses in preparation for Friday's inauguration.
   ``It's been a heckuva week,'' said Jim Caulfield, president of
Ridgewell's Caterers, a Bethesda-based company that was among the
five caterers serving five $1,500-a-plate inaugural dinners
Wednesday night.
   ``We'll serve 25,000 people at 70 different locations this
week,'' Caulfield added. ``This is a logistical nightmare.''
   Six horses owned by Fernando Ruiz, 42, of Clarksburg, Md., will
march in the inaugural parade, as will 15 carefully clipped
miniature horses from Denton.
   Float makers are busy too. Earl C. Hargrove's company, which is
working on its 10th inauguration, has 66 floats on its agenda this
year. One float features a pair of maroon, gold glitter-studded
cowboy boots. One boot, probably dozens of sizes too big for even
Paul Bunyan, anchors each end of the float, a tribute to Texas,
President-elect Bush's adopted state.
   A 10-gallon plastic foam hat that stands more than 10 feet tall
will pull the entire contraption.
</TEXT>
