<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TurtleTumors     01-19 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtle Tumors,0288</SECOND>
<UNK>Researchers Seek Cause of Tumors Affecting Endangered Sea Turtles</UNK>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research veterinarians are trying to pin
down the cause of mysterious tumors threatening the survival of
endangered green sea turtles off Florida and around the Hawaiian
islands.
   ``The incidence of the tumors has greatly increased during the
past seven years,'' said Dr. Elliott Jacobson, wildlife specialist
at the University of Florida's College of Veterinary Medicine, in a
statement Thursday.
   ``The best information we have so far suggests they're caused by
a virus, and at the moment, we're seeking to isolate a virus from
the tissues of affected turtles,'' he said.
   The efforts of Jacobson and co-investigator Dr. Jack Gaskin, are
supported by grants from the private ``Save a Turtle'' group in the
Florida Keys and ``Save the Turtle'' of Chicago.
   Jacobson said the tumor epidemic is a particular threat to the
already endangered green sea turtle.
   ``The tumors have been spotted on about half the green sea
turtles found along the Indian River lagoon system,'' said Jacobson,
referring to the 100-mile-long stretch of waterways protected by
barrier islands along Florida's Central Atlantic Coast.
   He said the same percentage of affected sea turtles has been
reported in Hawaii by biologist George Balazs of the National Marine
Fisheries Service.
   The tumors develop over both the soft body tissue and shell of
the turtle, often appearing on and around their eyes.
   Dr. Peter Pritchard, vice president of the Florida Audubon
Society and an expert on green sea turtles, said the disease now
threatens only certain sea turtle populations, but others are not
immune.
   ``The potential for the disease to spread through migration is
definitely there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
