<FIRST>r a AM-Chopsticks     01-19 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chopsticks,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chopsticks Plant Closed For Repairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>By TONY KENNEDY</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP Business Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIBBING, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chopsticks plant that was hailed at its
1986 opening for boldness in taking on the Japanese in the foreign
trade war is $7 million in debt and closed for repairs after losing
$3.5 million in 1988.
   The heavily subsidized plant in this mining town in severe
decline was shut down Dec. 15 and its 65 employees were laid off
because of faulty equipment, said Ian Ward, the company president.
   Machinery intended to speed production was vibrating and spoiling
the chopsticks' veneer, said Ward, president of Lakewood Forest
Products, the Vancouver, British Columbia, owner of the plant.
   Ward said a new machine is being built and is expected to be
installed by the end of January. Production will resume in early
February, he said.
   Japanese buyers of the chopsticks haven't gotten discouraged and
will buy as many sets as the plant can produce, said Don Myers, a
Lakewood spokesman in Canada.
   Lakewood originally said it would employ up to 120 workers and
produce up to 7 million pairs of disposable chopsticks a day, but it
was making about 700,000 pairs a day when it closed, Myers said.
   The Iron Range Resources and Rehabilitation Board loaned $3.4
million to the company in December 1985 to help get the plant
started. The company also got about $1 million in loans, grants and
free land from the city and state.
   Jim Benson, a planner with the IRRRB development agency which
issued industrial revenue bonds to make the loan, said he will visit
the plant Friday. ``It's been a concern. That's why we make site
visits,'' Benson said Thursday. ``We've been over there monthly for
the past six months.''
   The chopsticks plant, which has a contract to supply a consortium
of Japanese buyers, lost $3.5 million in 1988 on sales of $420,000,
said Myers. The plant is worth about $13 million, he said. The
company is a total of $7 million in debt, Ward said.
   Production problems have plagued the operation since its June
1986 opening.
   New problems surfaced in July 1988 when the plant installed a new
lathe, Ward said in a telephone interview from Vancouver. An
adjoining machine, called a reeler, made vibrations that disturbed
the lathe's finishing work, he said.
   The manufacturer of the reeler, which was supposed to be an
improvement over the plant's original model, is buiding a new one at
no cost to Lakewood, Ward said.
   The city, faced with a severe decline in the mining of iron ore,
gave Lakewood a $225,000 grant, 10 free acres of land, a $250,000
loan and $275,000 in tax-increment financing to get it started,
Hibbing City Administrator Harry Gherarei said. The state loaned the
company an additional $250,000, he said.
   Lakewood recently raised about $603,000 in stock offerings to be
used to restart production, Myers said.
   ``Once this one is up and running we may build a second or third
plant,'' Myers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
