<DOCNO> AP890119-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-BushExcerpts     01-19 1544</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Excerpts,1500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Bush Interview</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from President-elect Bush's
interview Thursday with a group of news organizations.
   Q. How long are you going to let the (START) talks hang and do
you think you risk losing the momentum that President Reagan
achieved?
   A. I don't think we risk losing momentum that President Reagan
achieved because I think the Soviets understand that my intention is
not to drag my feet but to simply do a prudent reassessment. And in
terms of how long _ I don't think we know yet.
   I don't feel inclined to adopt a timetable at this point. We may
be able to do that in a week or two, just have a better feel for
when these things will be finished.
   But you've got to realize we don't have a lot of the people in
place whose views will be required on a reassessment. So we'll go
forward with whatever the assets are in defense and in state and in
the NSC but all of these bureaucracies are in a state of change.
   So my main point is: I think the Soviets understand this. I made
it very clear to General Secretary Gorbachev that there was _ that
this reassessment in no way was a footdragging operation exercise.
   Q. Does that mean that the talks themselves cannot be resumed
until that review is completed?
   A. There may be things that could be accomplished. To really move
forward on talks that have already made progress, we have to finish
our review.
   Q. Do you think it's going to be six months, a year?
   A. Have no way, can't help you, don't know. ... One of the first
things I'll do as president is order this review.
   Q. What are odds of talks with Mr. Gorbachev this year?
   A. I don't think we can make the odds. And more important than
that, that we have good sound positions that we will be advocating.
And whether that results in a summit or not, I think, is less
important than the fact that the process will go forward. ... I
don't think that progress should be measured solely on whether
there's a summit meeting.
   Q. President Reagan said yesterday that we should consider
renegotiating the Panama Canal treaties if Noriega remains in power.
How do you feel about that?
   A. I think we need to go slow on all that. The treaty has certain
obligations that ought to be met. I'm a great believer that once a
treaty is entered into and ratified, it ought to be kept.
   But I'd have to look at the treaty before I have any commment on
something like that.
   Q. Did you think process (of filling senior jobs) might be more
complete by now?
   A. In terms of undersecretaries and department heads? I know
we're about where we thought we'd be on the Cabinet. On the rest of
it, I don't know what a historical precedent was. I'd like to be
further ahead, put it that way. But I think we're doing all right on
it.
   Q. What would you like to accomplish in the first 100 days?
   A. ... I keep saying ours is different. Only Martin Van Buren and
I really know how different it is. And he ain't talking. ... I'm not
shooting for any 100 days. And I think it's kind of a concept that
doesn't really apply. Some may want it to apply.
   Q. What do hope to accomplish then as you first take control?
   A. I hope to see progress made on the budget. This is the No. 1
domestic economic problem facing the country. So we're going to have
to move forward on that, in terms of negotiations with the Congress.
I'm not quite naive enough to believe they'll accept everything I'll
propose in February.
   ... And then we'll have some things we will accomplish in the
first few months. Ethics legislation will be part of it. I'd like to
see some action on not only formulating the policy, but taking
certain steps toward more accomplishment and understanding in the
environmental field.
   We'll see the drug, anti-narcotics operation get geared up in
that first few months there. And I think we've got to have a good
plan there that shows a seriousness that surely I feel. ...
   Educational initiatives are important, but they won't be simply
adding to the federal spending account.
   Monies are not going to be there to do all the things I want to
do, and that I feel are priority. So we'll have to sort through and
set priorities. Some of what I want to do will have to wait on a
solution to the budget question.
   Q. How do you see that being solved?
   A. I see it being solved through negotiation. I think you're
going to have serious negotiation. And even then, you're not going
to do this in a year obviously.
   If we can get a good agreement on the budget, I think the
psychology of that will have an ameliorating effect on these
interest rates.
   And I think the problem will be easier once world markets see
agreement has been reached and it is clear the U.S. government is
determined to get the deficit down. ...
   Q. Will your campaign proposal to reduce the capital gains tax be
in your budget plan?
   A. Yes. There are some technical things that have to be done, but
yes it will have to be there.
   Q. The State Department tape of Arafat threatening people with
``ten bullets'' _ what's your reaction?
   A. I'd like to see the context of the tape before commenting, but
clearly that does not facilitate improving relations with Arafat. So
I want to see it. I don't know what the context of that. But just
from what I've read, I'd say it's a setback to peace rather than an
enhancement of peace.
   Q. Will you authorize resumption of U.S.-PLO contacts?
   A. I'm not going to change the policy. I supported the policy. It
was part of what I wanted ... that policy will not change. In terms
of when you need more talks, I think each talk should be on a
case-by-case basis. And we'll just see what will facilitate the
peace dialogue.
   ... I can't tell you about the tape because I haven't read it or
listened to it or know what the context of it is. But if it's a
reversion to supporting international terror, that could foul up the
dialogue.
   Q. Will you maintain the present policy of benign neglect toward
hostages?
   A. I will maintain the policy of leaving no stone unturned for
the release of the hostages. But that policy has another side of it,
and that is we will not buckle under to the demands that are being
thrown out there by those that are holding the hostages. ...
   Q. Can you give us some idea of the message, the tone, you will
strike tomorrow?
   A. I've got it pretty well in my mind now. The text is locked in,
all but locked in.
   It will be just a broad appeal to the American people to pitch in
and help. It'll be an expression of satisfaction about how far we've
come as a nation, and a recognition that we've got a long way to go.
   It will be a re-emphasis of my conviction that many of these
problems that remain unsolved can best be solved by engagement of
the private thousand points of light concept. The private entities
that do things so much better than government, and that have done so
much to solve pressing problems. ...
   It will be along those thematic lines. ... I'm now an expert on
inaugural addresses in terms of numbers of words as well as themes.
Most of them, at least the modern ones, are pretty much the same in
that context: broad and thematic as opposed to point specific.
   Q. Are there any concrete actions you will take tomorrow
afternoon?
   A. There may be, but they won't be of major import. I'll go to
work, though, just as I always have.
   Q. Will you continue the Saturday radio addresses?
   A. I think we're not going to do those. We may later on.
   Q. Will you be wandering out (of the White House for
spur-of-the-moment trips in the evening and weekends)?
   A. I can't pledge to be anchored down. But I'd like to work out
some understanding that the world's not going to come to a
screeching halt if you don't know that I'm eating Peking duck over
in Virginia some place.
   And you may not agree with that, but I think it's silly to have
to feel that when the president goes out of that thing for a private
supper, or to eat in a restaurant, that serious journalists, or
their editors, feel that the nation's business will come to a halt
if that is not reported.
   I'm not going to give up my ability to make up a decision in a
hurry. ...
   What's being protected? You mean, if I fall over and choke in the
restaurant? Suppose I fall over and choke in the White House _
you're not there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
