<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     01-19 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist North Ready To Start Joint Ventures With South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea says it stands
ready to start trade and joint venture projects with its capitalist
rival, South Korea, the Ministry of Trade and Industry announced
Thursday.
   It said the North made this known when one of its senior trade
officials met for business talks with a South Korean businessman in
Tokyo on Dec. 30.
   The announcement said that Lee Kang-sae, a vice president of
Sunkyong Ltd., a leading Seoul trading firm, had government approval
for the talks.
   Ministry officials refused to identify the North Korean official.
   The North Korean told Lee the Pyongyang government intends to
give ``active support'' for joint venture projects between business
companies of the two sides, the announcement said.
   ``The two sides discussed wide-ranging measures to promote trade,
especially in the areas of textiles and mining products, and the
North Korean side was ... enthusiastic about starting joint
projects,'' it said.
   South Korean business magnate Chung Ju-yung will leave for the
North on Monday for a 16-day visit to discuss investment and joint
venture projects. The government formally authorized the visit on
Thursday.
   Accompanying Chung, 74, honorary chairman of the giant Hyundai
group, will be two executives specializing in civil engineering and
plant construction.
   Chung is orginally from North Korea. He is the first leading
South Korean businessman to be invited by Pyongyang to visit the
North since the Korean peninsula was divided into communist North
and capitalist South in 1945, when Soviet and U.S. troops ended
Japan's colonial rule over Korea.
   Observers in Seoul believe the North is under pressure to revive
its sagging economy even with investment from South Korea. The North
reportedly owes about $5 billion to communist-bloc as well as
Western nations.
   North Korea adopted a joint venture law in 1984, but failed to
lure major foreign investment. Last year it created a new government
ministry to handle joint venture business with foreign concerns.
   Also Thursday, the South Korean news agency Yonhap reported that
South Korean radical students will be allowed to attend the World
Youth Festival in Pyongyang this year but will be warned to avoid
political discussion.
   Yonhap said the government will send members of the radical
National Council of Student Representatives as well as other
students.
   South Korean officials previously took the position that the
North's invitation was aimed at stirring up anti-U.S. and
anti-government activism.
   Yonhap, quoting an unidentified government source, said Seoul now
felt ``it is desirable to make full use of all opportunities . .. to
promote exchanges between South and North Korea.''
   The festival, held every four years, is a major political, arts
and sports event involving mostly communist and Third World nations.
   Yonghap also reported that Washington may consider closing the
U.S. cultural center in Kwangju, which has been attacked by radical
students seven times since last year.
   It quoted U.S. Charge d'Affaires Thomas S. Brooks as telling
Kwangju Mayor Choi In-ki on Thursday: ``After yesterday's attack on
the Kwangju cultural center, we think it may be time to reconsider
whether to keep it any longer.''
   The mayor disagreed, telling Brooks ``it is not proper to
consider the attack as the intention of the entire citizenry,''
Yonhap added.
   Kwangju, 180 miles southwest of Seoul, is the capital of South
Cholla province.
   About 50 students attacked the center with firebombs and rocks on
Wednesday. No one was hurt, but damage was done.
   The students accuse the United States of complicity in the harsh
military suppression of a bloody civil uprising in Kwangju in 1980.
America denies it.
   Also Thursday:
   _The government has decided to jam ``slanderous'' North Korean FM
radio broacasts aimed at young audiences in South Korea, officials
said.
   _Three shipyard workers took poison but survived during a violent
labor protest at Samsung Shipbuilding's head office in Seoul, police
said. The workers said they were protesting the company's alleged
suppression of the labor movement.
</TEXT>
