<FIRST>u i AM-FishingFeud     01-19 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fishing Feud,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trawler Flees Disputed Waters After Irate Islanders Threaten Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PIERRE, St. Pierre and Miquelon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French fishing
company ordered one of its ships to leave disputed waters off
Canada's Atlantic Coast on Thursday after citizens of this French
island territory threatened to ram it.
   Fernand Leborgne, president of the French fishing company
Comapeche, broke a five-day deadlock in the dispute by ordering the
factory ship Grande Hermine to go to a U.S. port.
   Comapeche officials in Paris said the decision was aimed at
ending the ``violent tension'' that developed this week when
islanders threatened to ram the trawler with a smaller boat if it
did not leave the area.
   ``It's a partial victory,'' said a weary Victor Reux, economic
adviser to St. Pierre and Miquelon, a group of eight French-owned
islands. ``For the time being we are happy, but nothing is over.''
   The 6,000 people living on the rocky archipelago 10 miles south
of Newfoundland rely almost entirely on fishing for their
livelihood. Last fall, a compromise in a long-running dispute
allowed one factory ship from France to fish in the zone.
   But the dispute flared again Sunday when the French government
allowed the Grande Hermine to fish in the zone. Another trawler, the
Victor Plevin, also owned by Comapeche, has been fishing in the area
since early January.
   The fishermen charge the factory ships take in too many fish and
don't provide any employment at the territory's fish processing
plants.
   The Grand Hermine will stay away from the area during a new round
of negotiations between the territory and Paris, Comapeche officials
said.
</TEXT>
