<HEAD>Britain's Prime Minister Says Goodbye To Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Thursday called
President Reagan a ``true and perfect gentleman'' in a letter of
thanks and farewell to one of her staunchest allies.
   The letter, made public by Mrs. Thatcher's 10 Downing St. office
the day before President-elect George Bush takes over from Reagan,
read: ``Dear Ron, As you leave office, I wanted simply to say thank
you.
   ``You have been a great president, one of the greatest, because
you stood for all that is best in America.
   ``Your beliefs, your convictions, your faith shone through
everything you did. And your unassuming courtesy was the hallmark of
the true and perfect gentleman. You have been an example and an
inspiration to us all.''
   Mrs. Thatcher also thanked Nancy Reagan ``for all the warmth and
support which she has given you, as well as for her own very special
contribution in the war against drugs.''
   The prime minister said she and her husband, Denis, ``wish you
both every happiness as you lay down your great burden.''
   Mrs. Thatcher added in her own handwriting: ``We shall miss you
both very much. Warm personal regards. Yours ever, Margaret.''
   The ``special relationship'' between Britain and the United
States was strengthened greatly during the long terms in office of
Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher.
