<FIRST>u a AM-MiamiRiot-Heat     01-19 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Riot-Heat,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Basketball Returns To The Riot Zone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crowds returned to the streets of Miami on Thursday
night _ not for civil disobedience, but rather for slam dunk and
Michael Jordan.
   People streamed in to the area surrounding Miami Arena for the
National Basketball Association game between the Miami Heat and the
Chicago Bulls.
   The game was a test of whether this city had calmed after three
nights of looting, burning and rock throwing that followed the
police shooting of a black motorcyclist just 12 blocks from the
arena.
   The sold-out game came two nights after officials canceled a Heat
contest with the Phoenix Suns.
   ``We had no concern about coming down here at all,'' said Glen
Haft, who brought his wife and son. ``We thought things had calmed
down. We were sure the police would make sure there were no
problems.''
   Haft's son, David, 11, had been looking forward to the game
featuring slam-dunk artist Michael Jordan's only Miami appearance
this year, but confessed he feared he might miss the game.
   ``I was afraid I was going to get bottles and rocks and sticks
thrown at us but it hasn't happened so far,'' David said.
   There was no indication of trouble in the area surrounding the
new, pastel pink stadium. About 100 police officers _ 60 more than
usual _ maintained a highly visible presence, and there were no
incidents.
   The $52 million, 15,000-seat stadium opened last summer and it
and its NBA tenant were an instant success.
   Fifteen of the Heat's 18 games home games have been sell-outs. A
19th game was canceled because of the riots Monday. Thursday night's
game had sold out in October 18 minutes after tickets went on sale.
   But empty seats in the arena were still visible at halftime,
indicating some no-shows.
   The arena is an important part of plans to revitalize the
neighborhood and bring people back to the city's downtown.
Construction has already begun on an apartment building complex for
people who work in the city; the arena is designed as the anchor of
that project.
   But not all the fans thought the location of the arena on the
edge of Overtown was that wise.
   ``It's a good place, I just think they should have put it some
place else,'' said Dwayne Burgard. ``They should have known
something like this would happen.''
   City boosters were anxious for the night to go smoothly.
   ``It's absolutely critical that the game takes place tonight,''
said Bill Collom, president of the Greater Miami Chamber of
Commerce. ``It's just got to take place.''
   The street vendors and ticket scalpers had similar sentiments.
One T-shirt seller said he lost hundreds of dollars when Tuesday
night's game was canceled.
   Raymond Scales, a city school counselor, had a good night by
selling out of T-shirts that read, ``I survived the Miami riot.''
   ``I don't think people had much to worry about here tonight,''
said Scales. ``I think it's good they put the arena here. This area
needs to be revitalized.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Crime     01-19 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crime,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crime Rate Up 17 Percent In Gorbachev's Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms
contributed to a 17 percent increase in the Soviet crime rate last
year, the interior minister was quoted Thursday as saying.
   ``Robberies, assaults and theft of personal property increased in
frequency by more than a third,'' Interior Minister Vadium Bakatin
said in an interview in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda.
   Attacks on police increased and street crime rose by more than 40
percent, said Bakatin, who supervises the Soviet Union's uniformed
police.
   In his first major interview since taking over in October, he
said police themselves were often corrupt and ill-prepared to fight
crime.
   Under Gorbachev, officials and the state media have been more
open about reporting drug abuse, prostitution and other crimes,
including details of criminal investigations.
   But Bakatin's half-page interview in Pravda was an important
admission that reform has brought problems as well.
   He said the reforms have created ``complicated, at times painful
processes of self-cleansing, an increase in civil and ethnic
self-awareness.''
   Two republics where ethnic awareness is growing most rapidly,
Latvia and Estonia, headed the areas where Bakatin said crime is
growing most rapidly.
   He also cited several times the violence between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis, where Interior Ministry troops were called in to
restore order.
   Many criminals released from labor colonies under legal reforms
have been unable to find work because state industries are cutting
back their workforces to meet efficiency demands of Gorbachev's
economic reforms, he said. Some return to crime.
   Bakatin also said police are ill-prepared to cope with organized
crime seeping into the cooperative movement of private enterprise,
which Gorbachev has encouraged to provide goods and services not
available under the state economy.
   Bakatin gave no figures for the number of crimes committed, but
said, ``It can be stated boldly that the level of crime in the
country is significantly higher than statistics indicate today.''
   He also said the police system should be reformed.
   ``We have everything in the system of the Ministry of Internal
Affairs: bribery, treachery, bureaucratism, callousness, rudeness,
departmental separatism and illegality,'' he said.
   Some local police have tried to keep the number of crimes they
report as low as possible, fearing that reporting an increase will
damage their careers, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Egypt 1stLd-Writethru a0710 01-19 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede Jerusalem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Border Talks With Egypt Start With Squabble Over Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with progress reported, other detail.
Changes dateline. No pickup</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   TABA, Israel-Egypt Border (AP) _ Negotiators reported progress on
the Taba border dispute after opening talks were delayed for 90
minutes Thursday by a squabble over whether Egyptian delegates would
arrive in a car with Israeli or Egyptian license plates.
   The Egyptians finally drove up in a U.N. bus, accompanied by
jeeps from both countries.
   The two sides finally sat down to discuss the border strip of
Taba, with its Israeli-built luxury hotel and holiday village, and
later reported progress on the issue of access by Israeli tourists
to the 250-acre resort strip.
   Abraham Sofaer, the U.S. mediator, said he expects a compromise
can be reached.
   The focus on access for Israelis suggested the strip could wind
up in Egypt's hands after straining Israeli-Egyptian relations for
six years.
   Reuven Merhav, the chief Israeli negotiator, reported ``progress
in the mutual issues we discussed, and arrangements regarding access
by Israelis.''
   He said the agreed points would be summarized in Friday's round
of negotiations as an ``initial agreement.''
   Nabil El Arabi, head of the Egyptian delegation, told reporters:
``I don't see any problem to finishing the negotiations in two
days.'' He said only ``very small items'' were left to discuss.
   ``We would like Israeli tourists to come here, not only by the
tens of thousands but by the tens and hundreds of thousands,'' said
Arabi.
   Taba came under Israeli rule when Israel captured the Sinai
Peninsula during the 1967 Middle East war. In 1982, Israel withdrew
from all of Sinai except Taba following the 1979 Israeli-Egyptian
peace treaty.
   The dispute was submitted to international arbitration. In
September, the arbitrators awarded Egypt key border points, but said
they were not authorized to determine a final marker that includes
the beach resort.
   The two countries are negotiating over where to place the last
marker.
   The talks are also supposed to develop a framework for Egyptian
purchase of the Sonesta Hotel, with the final deal to be worked out
by negotiations involving the hotel owners.
   As talks were going on, a group of Israeli yacht owners sailed
along the Taba coastline to demand free water access. An Israeli
gunboat chased them away.
   About 50 Israelis from nearby Elat symbolically marked the border
by stretching a rope that put Taba within Israel. One protester was
detained, Israel radio said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
