<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra     01-19 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Fights Subpoenas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fired National Security Council aide Oliver
North is challenging efforts by prosecutors in the Iran-Contra case
to subpoena the notebooks he compiled of his daily activities at the
NSC, the judge in the case disclosed Thursday.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell issued an order specifying
that North's filing outlining his opposition would be sealed to
protect references to a grand jury transcript. The filing was made
Wednesday, the judge's order said.
   Gesell had earlier scheduled a hearing for next Wednesday in the
event that North opposed the subpoena for the notebooks, which
detail his involvement in the Contra resupply operation as well as
the Reagan administration's arms sales to Iran.
   North used the spiral-bound stenographer's notebooks from Feb. 1,
1983 until the day he was fired, Nov. 25, 1986, when the
administration disclosed that a portion of the proceeds from the
Iran arms sales had been diverted to the Contras fighting the
leftist government in Nicaragua.
   Portions of the notebooks were turned over to the congressional
Iran-Contra investigating committees and disclosed during hearings.
   But North, through his attorney Brendan Sullivan, invoked his
Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination last year when a
Senate committee tried to get the notebooks.
