<FIRST>u i AM-Reagan-Horse 1stLd-Writethru   01-19 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Horse, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0850,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Putting Cart Before The Horse, Reagan To Get Gift From Mounties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with government saying Reagan will
get horse; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will get to look a gift horse in
the mouth after all.
   After professing ignorance of the impending gift most of the day,
the government finally confirmed Thursday evening that it plans to
send the outgoing president a horse from the Royal Canadian Mounted
Police.
   The first hint the gift was planned came Wednesday, when the
White House staff presented Reagan with new harnesses for the horses
at his ranch near Santa Barbara, Calif.
   Reagan held aloft the leather gear and said: ``When I get home, I
understand the Canadian Mounted Police are delivering a horse. This
will take care of that horse.''
   But the Mounties, the prime minister's office and the Department
of External Affairs said all day Thursday they knew nothing of the
gift _ possibly because of a U.S. law preventing presidents from
accepting gifts while in office.
   After Friday's inauguration of President-elect George Bush, the
restrictions are gone.
   Late Thursday, a spokesman for Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's
office said: ``I can now tell you that the president is getting a
horse, when he ceases to be president. That's all I can tell you.''
