<FIRST>u w AM-Inauguration-Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inauguration-Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,1070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Counter Glitter with Shouts, Signs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with protest outside Convention
Center gala, comments from guests; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs bgng, `We want
to;' Junior Bridge is cq in 20th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black-tie guests at Thursday night's gala in
honor of George Bush's inauguration sniffed that it wasn't
``appropriate'' as their festive evening got off to a dissonant
start with protesters screaming, ``Bush, Quayle, you can't hide; we
charge you with genocide.''
   Some three dozen demonstrators from gay and lesbian rights
groups, armed with a megaphone, taunted the fur-bedecked partygoers
as they waited in long lines to get through security screenings at
the Convention Center.
   ``Fifty thousand dead from AIDS; where was George?'' they
screamed, along with ``Money for AIDS, not for inaugurals,'' and
``Someone you love will die for AIDS; where will you be?''
   Police asked organizers to keep the circle moving, to clear an
area of sidewalk for passersby and to turn the megaphone down a bit.
They complied only with the first two requests, but police said
nothing further about the decibel level.
   ``The reason we're here is that $32 million is being spent on the
inauguration,'' said Robert Bray of Washington, a spokesman for the
demonstrators. ``We want to call attention to the fact that there's
a huge problem George Bush must face. ... He has been handed this
legacy by former President Reagan and he has to handle it.''
   Signs lofted by the protesters were direct: ``The government has
blood on it's hands. One AIDS death every half hour.''
   ``I don't think it's appropriate at all,'' said Tom Aubrey of the
American Bankers Association, one of 12,000 guests at the nationally
televised gala featuring Frank Sinatra, Chuck Yeager, Loretta Lynn
and Randy Travis, among others. ``I don't think a celebratory
evening is the time or place for this kind of demonstration.''
   ``I think they like trying to rain on somebody else's parade,''
commented Doug Richardson, who works with the transition for
Transportation Secretary-designate Samuel Skinner.
   Jeff Vogt of Arlington, Va., who has been tapped for a job in the
White House public liaison office, asked for ``Silence, please. ...
There's a time and place for it.''
   Protesters angry with GOP policies of all kinds are staging
alternative events throughout the week.
   So far, the protests have been peaceful.
   A gathering of hundreds Wednesday night outside Union Station,
where some 2,500 Republicans attended a $1,500-a-plate gala,
featured free food and chants such as ``What about the homeless?,''
but no violence.
   That was the plan, said an organizer of the Counter-Inaugural
Coalition for a People's Agenda, which has some 80 member groups
ranging from the Gray Panthers to the Committee in Solidarity with
the People of El Salvador.
   The coalition's members, including the gay and lesbian rights
groups demonstrating Thursday night, had agreed in advance not to
conduct any civil disobedience.
   ``We want to ensure that we maintain a positive attitude,''
coalition spokeswoman Lisa Fithian said.
   Thursday night, a ``No Honeymoon'' concert benefiting the
Christic Institute, which has sued the U.S. government over its
Central America policies and activities, charged $25 per ticket.
Entertainers David Crosby and Graham Nash were featured.
   Demonstrators planned to be out in force Inauguration Day, along
with the National Organization for Women, which has scheduled a
silent protest along the parade route.
   The NOW demonstrators were to wear buttons numbered 1 to 1,000
that light up in rebuke to Bush's oft-stated reliance on ``a
thousand points of light.'' The buttons will carry the message
``Keep Abortion Legal.''
   ``We want Mr. Bush to know this is a re-mobilization, that we're
not going to stand by and see what little rights we have whittled
away,'' said NOW spokeswoman Junior Bridge.
   Bridge said a survey of the parade route revealed little access
to those without tickets. ``The public is obviously not a welcome
part of this inauguration,'' she said.
   The northwest corner of Lafayette Square, across the street from
the White House, has been set aside for demonstrations, but there is
no hour-by-hour schedule of who will be able to use the space.
   ``The extravagance of George Bush's inauguration _ by far the
most expensive in U.S. history _ demonstrates how far removed the
Bush-Quayle administration is from the concerns and worries of most
American people,'' Fithian said.
   Courtney Miller, an organizer with Justice for Janitors, part of
the coalition, noted that his people have a role in the inauguration
festivities, but not one that gets much attention.
   ``These are the people who will be at the inaugural parties after
the glitz and glitter is shut down,'' Miller said.
   The coalition, whose slogan is ``1,000 Sparks of Dissent,
Inaugurate a People's Agenda,'' plans a Counter-Inaugural Ball at
the Crispus Attucks Museum on Friday night, with a $6 to $10
admission. On Saturday, the coalition will hold a Counter-Inaugural
Forum at All Soul's Church, followed on Sunday by an interfaith
gathering outside the National Cathedral featuring traditional
Native American prayers from representatives of the Piscataway
nation.
   The coalition's groups include: American Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee; Anti-Fur Coalition; DC Statehood Party; Student Coalition
Against Apartheid and Racism; Environmental Action; Jobs With Peace;
National Coalition for the Homeless; National Gay and Lesbian Task
Force; National Pledge of Resistance; Peace Park Anti-Nuclear Vigil;
Socialist Party, USA; United Farm Workers; Vietnam Veterans Against
the War; Women Strike for Peace and Women's International League for
Peace and Freedom.
   Many of those groups, as well as Mitch Snyder of the Community
for Creative Non-Violence, have called on Bush to ask those who
donated money for the inauguration to donate an equal amount to
solve some of the problems facing the country.
   And some just want the nation's policies changed.
   Ken Butigan of the National Pledge of Resistance said, ``George
Bush, read our lips. The U.S. war in Central America must end. ...
What Ronald Reagan learned during eight years was that there is no
mandate for war.''
   Daniel Becker, legislative counsel of Environmental Action,
called on Bush to change the policies of the administration he has
served for eight years ``that showed marked hostility to
environmental protection.''
</TEXT>
