<HEAD>Marcos Health Hearing Interrupted With Word of Collapsed Lung</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `In Honolulu, ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
Marcos' condition upgraded to stable; picks up 3rd graf: `The hearing ...;
SUBS 9th graf, `Later, hospital ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing on whether Ferdinand Marcos is too sick
to stand trial on racketeering charges was interrupted Thursday with
word that the deposed Philippine president had suffered a collapsed
left lung.
   In Honolulu, Marcos' doctors said his condition had improved and
he was listed as stable, said hospital spokewoman Norma Kop at 4:15
p.m. Earlier, Marcos' doctors said he was in guarded condition.
   Ms. Kop said Marcos would remain in the hospital's intensive care
unit through Friday, she said.
   The hearing was to resume Friday. But U.S. District Judge John F.
Keenan said at the end of the day that, if reports from Hawaii were
correct: ``There is no way in the world he is going to be arraigned
in a courtroom in the next couple of weeks _ or maybe months.''
   Prosecutors in New York were cross-examining a doctor who had
testified that Marcos was a ``dying man,'' too ill to be brought to
trial, when a FBI agent entered with a note on the 71-year-old
former president.
   After conferring with lawyers in his chambers, Keenan announced
that Marcos' left lung collapsed that morning and that he was
returned to the intensive care unit at St. Francis Medical Center in
Honolulu, where he has been since Sunday with pneumonia and
bronchial asthma.
   Keenan said doctors had been able to reinflate Marcos' lung and
added, ``I also understand there was an additional cardiological
problem.''
   ``He's doing much better now,'' Wong said. Asked if Marcos was
out of danger, the doctor said, ``I think so. If he weren't, I'd
still be in there.''
   Later, Ms. Kop said Marcos was resting and sleeping in the
intensive care unit. She said that during the lung collapse episode,
there were indications Marcos suffered a heart irregularity or
arrythmia.
   Wong said he couldn't say how long Marcos would remain in
intensive care. Marcos' wife, Imelda, was at his bedside, hospital
officials said.
   Mrs. Marcos, dressed in black, left the hospital at 12:50 p.m.
HST and refused to answer questions while she walked to her black
limousine.
   Keenan is to determine if Marcos is fit to stand trial on charges
he stole $103 million from his country. Marcos and his wife have
been living in Hawaii since their ouster in a popular uprising in
1986.
   Since his indictment in October, Marcos had asked that the
arraignment be moved to Hawaii for health reasons. He has had two
kidney transplants and has been hospitalized three times in the past
two months, twice for congestive heart failure.
   On Wednesday, Marcos' attorneys argued that the leader was now
too ill to be arraigned anywhere.
   Before the hearing was interrupted Thursday, Dr. Robert Eliott, a
cardiologist, testified for the defense that he was shocked by
Marcos' physical condition when he examined him earlier in the week
at the Honolulu hospital.
   ``He was unable to complete a sentence without stopping and
gasping,'' Eliot said. The doctor, who went to Hawaii to give Marcos
a stress test, said Marcos was suffering from heart failure and
kidney problems.
   ``To make a long story short, I felt this was a dying man,'' he
said.
   The Marcoses are accused of plundering their homeland, funneling
the money into foreign bank accounts and using it to buy prime New
York real estate and art. Mrs. Marcos was arraigned in New York in
October and released on $5 million bond.
</TEXT>
