<SECOND>AM-Corrections Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Police Exploring Revenge as Motive in Prison Chief's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE autopsy shows Francke died of stab
wound to heart; friend saying he described such a death several weeks earlier;
picks up 6th graf: `Francke apparently ...; drops outdated first reference
to Sides in 7th graf pvs: `Former state...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities investigating the stabbing death
of Oregon's corrections chief said Thursday they are focusing on the
possibility he was slain by a former inmate bent on revenge.
   Michael Francke, 42, who was found dead outside his office early
Wednesday, had received death threats ``on a regular basis,'' a
friend said.
   District Attorney Dale Penn said Thursday many leads were being
pursued and one motive could be revenge connected with Francke's
work in Oregon or New Mexico.
   Francke was head of New Mexico's prisons before coming to Oregon
about 19 months ago.
   Investigators had no suspects and no weapon was found at the
scene. Penn said police where looking into whether any recently
released inmates had a motive.
   An autopsy showed Francke died of a stab wound to the heart.
   Former state Rep. Chuck Sides, a friend of Francke's, said the
corrections chief made comments about death by stabbing several
weeks ago.
   ``I can't remember what brought it up, but he told me exactly how
a person would die with a stab through the heart,'' Sides said.
``Basically, he showed me with his own hand how you would do that.''
   Francke apparently stayed after a staff meeting ended Tuesday
evening and was killed sometime before midnight in the parking lot,
Penn said.
   Sides said the corrections chief had shown him a letter
threatening his life last fall.
   Sides said he could remember no details of that letter but that
Francke shrugged it off with a joke about which legislator might
have sent it.
   ``Michael was getting death threats on a regular basis,'' Sides
said. ``It was part of the job, almost.''
   Sides said Francke had told him he was glad to have left the New
Mexico Correction Department because of death threats there.
   Gov. Neil Goldschmidt on Wednesday named Francke's top aide,
corrections manager Dick Peterson, to serve as interim director.
</TEXT>
