<SECOND>AM-Commodities Investigation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0853,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating Fraud Allegations at Chicago Commodity Exchanges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with trading records subpoenaed;
picks up 5th graf: `We are ...; a longer version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading records of the Chicago Board of Trade and
Chicago Mercantile Exchange were subpoenaed Thursday in an FBI probe
of alleged widespread fraud at the nation's two biggest futures
exchanges.
   The U.S. attorney's office subpoenaed all trading records dating
to Jan. 1, 1983, Mercantile spokesman Andrew Yemma said.
   Similar records were subpoenaed at the Board of Trade and the
Board of Trade Clearing Corporation, said spokesman Raymond
Carmichael, adding that executives ``must and will'' comply with the
request.
   FBI agents posed as traders in the probe focusing on 50 to 100
brokers, traders and executives at the Merc and Board of Trade, the
Chicago Tribune reported Thursday, citing unidentified sources.
   In Chicago, FBI spokeswoman Diane Rivers and Assistant U.S.
Attorney Daniel Gillogly in Chicago would neither confirm nor deny
such an investigation was under way.
   In Washington, however, law enforcement officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity, confirmed the Justice Department was
investigating allegations of fraud at the two exchanges.
   ``We are now aware of an investigation and we intend to cooperate
with it,'' Yemma said.
   Chicago Merc attorney Jerrold Salzman said he was contacted late
Wednesday by several traders who had been subpoenaed by the FBI.
   However, the Board of Trade ``has no knowledge of surveillance
activities of any nature being conducted on the trading floors or
any other Board of Trade location,'' Chairman Karsten Mahlmann said
in a statement Thursday.
   Over a two-year period, investigators secretly tape-recorded
hundreds of conversations on the exchanges' trading floors, the
Tribune said.
   Investigators believe traders cheated customers out of millions
of dollars in the execution of buy-and-sell orders at the exchanges,
which deal in a variety of contracts for delivery of grains,
livestock, Treasury bonds, foreign currencies and other commodities,
the newspaper said.
   Several subpoenas were served Wednesday, but arrests or
indictments were at least a month away, the Tribune reported.
   Investigators believe some trades were rigged to keep customers
from getting fair-market prices and some brokers sent false reports
to customers to hide the skimming of profits of overcharges on
commissions, the Tribune said.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, the federal agency that
regulates futures trading, had no comment, said spokesman David Gary
in Washington.
</TEXT>
