<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     01-19 1023</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,1062</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man with the microphone was preaching Jesus
through a battered speaker near the Liberty City checkpoint. ``His
love is e-e-e-ternal,'' he intoned as police checked motorists in
the garish light of flares and squad car flashers.
   A few miles north, officers in helmets and flak vests closed in
on a house that might have been the source of gunfire, while fellow
officers laughed and lounged a hundred feet away.
   The streets of Miami's Overtown and Liberty City neighborhoods
were a little easier Wednesday night. But they were still far from
normal.
   The looting and gunfire that punctuated the past two nights was
muted. Police were still out in force. They wore body armor and
toted loaded shotguns, but this night they sipped sodas and snacked
on sandwiches and ice cream as their radios occasionally crackled
with reports of car fires, smashed store windows and rock throwing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans have read his lips but expect George
Bush to break his pledge of no new taxes, although a solid majority
likes him anyway, a national poll has found.
   Bush made opposition to taxes a cornerstone of his presidential
campaign, and six in 10 respondents to the Media General-Associated
Press poll agreed he should not seek a tax increase. But 71 percent
said they think he will.
   Even still, the survey found high approval ratings for Bush, who
takes office Friday as the 41st president. Respondents voiced high
expectations for his presidency and gave him strong marks for his
cabinet choices.
   A solid 59 percent said they viewed Bush favorably, precisely the
same approval rate President Reagan received in a Media General-AP
poll last spring. Only 25 percent rated Bush unfavorably; the rest
withheld judgment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman describing herself as the best
friend of a schoolyard killer whose clothes and guns bore radical
Islamic slogans says his struggle to cope plunged him into dark
moods ``where he didn't want to live.''
   ``He had a bizarre attitude, kind of paranoid,'' said Kelley
Riley, whom residents of the area described as Patrick E. Purdy's
frequent companion in late 1987 and early 1988. ``He wanted to make
it on his own (as a welder) but he couldn't. He'd get upset at
things. He'd get mad at himself.''
   However, she said, Purdy was ``nice'' most of the time, would
``just walk away when he was mad,'' was never violent toward anyone
and never demonstrated an unusual interest in guns.
   Authorities concede they may never know why Purdy, described as a
drifting loner with a long criminal record, returned to the school
of his youth in army clothes and sprayed rifle fire at a playground
full of pupils Tuesday, killing five, wounding 29 children and one
teacher and then killing himself.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychologists say mass murderers like the
drifter who sprayed rifle fire at his boyhood school are part of a
recent unprecedented wave of ``grandstand suicides'' expressing a
hair-trigger anger at the world.
   But some experts warn that such acts of violence, whether they
represent a copycat trend or are only isolated incidents, should not
turn the nation's schools into ``armed camps.''
   The issue took on new significance as police investigated the
motivations of Patrick Purdy, a drifter who returned to his former
elementary school on Tuesday and opened fire on a crowd of children,
killing five students and wounding 30 people before killing himself.
   ``For these people, it is typically their last chance to show
society how angry they are,'' Michael Mantell, chief psychologist
for the San Diego Police Department,'' said Wednesday. ``Striking
out at children is their way of building up their flagging egos by
taking out their frustration on young victims.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new kind of surgery can correct a
common heart rhythm abnormality that is the underlying cause of
225,000 disabling strokes in the United States each year, its
developer said.
   The experimental procedure cures a disorder known as atrial
fibrillation, which affects an estimated 1.5 million to 2 million
Americans.
   Although the strokes that result from this problem can sometimes
be prevented with blood-thinning drugs, that treatment is often
ineffective and may itself cause unwanted bleeding.
   The new technique was developed by Dr. James L. Cox of Washington
University School of Medicine, who described it Wednesday at a
meeting of the American Heart Association. Slices are made in the
atria, the two upper pumping chambers of the heart.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers today reported the first ``very
promising'' evidence outside a test tube that an experimental new
treatment will slow the lethal spread of the AIDS virus inside the
body.
   The medicine, CD4, apparently works as a decoy, mimicking the
blood cells that the virus usually infects and kills.
   In a report in today's journal Nature, researchers reported that
the treatment dramatically reduced the level of virus in monkeys
infected with the simian version of the AIDS virus.
   ``This is the first evidence in vivo (in a living animal) that it
has anti-viral effects with chronic administration in a relevant
animal model,'' said Dr. Robert Schooley of Massachusetts General
Hospital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garlic and onions can put a crimp in your
social life, but they also could provide unexpected protection
against cancer, according to a study published by the National
Cancer Institute.
   The study compared foods eaten by stomach cancer victims with the
diet of healthy people in Linqu, China. Researchers found that the
strong-smelling vegetables ``can significantly reduce the risk of
stomach cancer.''
   Published this week in the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute, the study says researchers used questionnaires to compare
the dietary habits of 685 patients with stomach cancer with those of
1,131 other people, matched by age, gender, occupation and
education, who had no diagnosed cancer.
   People in the cancer-free group each year consumed at least 25
and sometimes more than 50 pounds of allium vegetables, a genus
which includes onions, garlic, leeks, chives, ramps and scallions.
   The cancer patients generally ate less than 25 pounds of the
vegetables.
</TEXT>
