<DOCNO> AP890119-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Lennon-Giuliano ADV20   01-19 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Lennon-Giuliano, ADV 20,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Jan 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AP Arts: Lennon Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>Actor-Turned-Author Writes Valentines To Beatles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKPORT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Geoffrey Giuliano is on the track to
Hollywood stardom with a stopover in a mansion on the Erie Canal
where he's writing portraits of the artists who influenced him.
   At the moment, the actor-turned-author is writing his fourth book
on the Beatles, ``Dark Horse: The Secret Life of George Harrison.''
   Five years ago, Giuliano was living in Toronto, out of work and
out of money. The 35-year-old had played roles from Shakespeare to
Ronald McDonald on stages from England to Florida. He had cut two
offbeat rock albums, developed a pilot for a British comedy TV show
and exhibited his collage art across Canada. He also had met George
Harrison and Paul and Linda McCartney, and interviewed Yoko Ono and
Sean Lennon for Playgirl magazine.
   Still he was broke. On a whim, he called a publisher in Toronto,
saying he had one of the world's largest collections of Beatles
artifacts, inside contacts with the musicians and were they
interested in a book?
   They were, and the result was ``The Beatles: A Celebration,'' a
slick, oversized Valentine of a book published in 1986 by Methuen
Publishing in Canada and St. Martin's Press in the United States.
   His next book, ``My Brother, John Lennon,'' written with the
slain Beatle's step-sister Julia Baird, came out last fall.
Giuliano's ``Tomorrow Never Knows: The Beatles' Recorded Rarities,''
is in production, and a Canadian publisher, Stoddard General, has
bought the Harrison biography.
   The book will be the authoritative biography, ``the one-stop
shopping place'' for those seeking information on Harrison, Giuliano
boasts.
   Giuliano, his wife, and their three children moved to Lockport
two years ago, living in an 1850s canalside mansion he bought and
restored with his book profits. The mansion has become something of
a monastery, he says. After ``Dark Horse,'' he plans to scale back
his writing to a book every three or four years so he can focus on
acting.
   He plans to move to Los Angeles next year, hoping to break into
movies and ``bring some intelligence to Hollywood.''
   Giuliano admits he has a bloated ego and turns it on anyone or
anything he lumps in with the modern age of mediocrity: The media
trivializes American life and are largely at fault for making
``people today far more superficial and covetous than their
parents.''
   ``My wife's parents had clear plastic over their furniture. We've
got it over our minds,'' Giuliano said.
   Giuliano's Beatles books have been something of a ``thank you''
to the group that helped him keep the plastic off his own mind. But
``Dark Horse'' will be his last book on the group, he says.
   ``I acknowledge the gift the Beatles gave me,'' Giuliano said.
``I've spent a few years trying to get others to understand them.
But now I want to move on. Already I'm a little embarrassed, I feel
like I've stayed at the fair too long. I've been on the Magical
Mystery Tour long enough.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Jan. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
