<FIRST>a w AM-NewstoUse Adv25   01-19 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News to Use, Adv 25,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Jan 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Salad Bars: Where the Savings Are _ and Aren't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convenience-conscious Americans have made salad
bars one of the most popular new supermarket innovations in recent
years, and with some care these shoppers can also realize value for
their money.
   Salad bar ingredients have proven popular not just for salads,
but also as ingredients in stir-fry dishes, side dishes, sandwich
fillings and the raw materials for a hearty soup, say researchers
Eileen Patz Newman and Dianne D. Odland.
   Nutritionists at the Department of Agriculture decided to look
into the growth of supermarket salad bars, and studied those at
markets in the Washington, D.C. area.
   They found that some items, not surprisingly, cost a lot more on
the salad bar than they do if purchased in larger units in other
sections of the market.
   But other items cost about the same, and shoppers could even find
savings on some items at the salad bar, the researchers reported in
the magazine Family Economics Review.
   The difference exists, of course, because salad bars generally
charge one per pound price for whatever ingredients the customer
selects, while prices for the same items bought individually would
vary widely.
   Cucumbers, carrots, green cabbage, yellow onions and watermelon,
for example, were as much as four times more expensive at the salad
bar.
   And salad-bar buyers paid triple the regular price for lettuce,
celery, bean sprouts, red cabbage, zuccini, canned kidney beans and
peas, cole slaw, macaroni salad, potato salad and hard-cooked eggs,
the researchers said.
   Tomatoes, spinach, radishes, green pepper, cantaloupe, sliced
beets, chickpeas, raisins, pineapple, tofu, egg salad and cottage
cheese cost about double if bought at the salad bar.
   On the other hand, mushrooms, cauliflower, broccoli, spring
onions, strawberries, honeydew, grapefruit, peaches, pears,
three-bean salad, pickled beets, salsa and rice pudding cost about
the same at the salad bar as in other supermarket areas.
   And the nutritionists found that shoppers could actually save
money at the salad bar by buying alfalfa sprouts, pineapple,
mandarin orange slices, tuna fish, American cheese, domestic ham,
sunflowwr seeds, croutons, chow mein noodles, jalapeno peppers,
pitted olives and bread pudding.
   While their research concentrated on supermarkets in the
Washington area, shoppers in any part of the country might also find
savings by comparing per-pound costs of salad bar foods to the same
item in other sections.
   A straight price comparison isn't always valid, of course,
because at the salad bar shoppers can buy any quantity of an item
then need, eliminating potential waste.
   This can be especially important for one- and two-person
households or those who prepare meals at home infrequently. Buyers
from those homes need to consider whether they can use an entire
head of cauliflower or carton of cottage cheese, or if much of it
will end up thrown away eventually, negating the saving.
   Another consideration is time, since salad-bar ingredients are
already cut up and prepared. This may be an advantage for the cook
who needs items for a stir-fry dinner and doesn't want to spend the
time slicing and chopping.
   Sale prices and local price differences also make a difference,
the researchers pointed out.
   But the final conclusion is that basic salad ingredients are most
costly at the salad bar while salad toppings and products of animal
origin can offer a saving there.
   Thus, consumers anxious to make the best use of their shopping
dollar, and who have time and storage space, might want to consider
buying items like lettuce, carrots and cabbage at the regular
produce counter, and turning to the salad bar for the extras such as
tuna, ham, sprouts, cheese and croutons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Jan 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:NevadaFilms ADV23   01-19 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Nevada Films, ADV 23,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan 23 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' Leads List of Films Shot in Nevada in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You'll forgive Nevada film chief Robert Hirsch
if he shows a special interest in the Academy Award nominations this
year.
   Some of the years leading movies, films likely to capture a
nomination or two, including the hit ``Rain Man,'' used Nevada
locales during 1988 _ a record year for Hirsch's state Motion
Picture Division.
   ``I picked up a copy of Variety the other day and here's this
double page spread promoting `Rain Man' for Oscar nominations,''
Hirsch said proudly, thumbing through the entertainment publication.
``Then I came to this ad for `Midnight Run,' then another for the
film `Things Change.'''
   Significant shooting on the three movies was carried out in
Nevada last year. The three films helped boost Nevada film industry
revenues to $50 million in 1988 _ 10 times the annual revenue
generated before former Gov. Richard Bryan appointed Hirsch to head
the new Motion Picture Division in July 1983.
   ``That's real income, dollars spent in the state by the industry,
with no multipliers applied,'' Hirsch said.
   Hirsch recently issued a glowing report, reflecting Nevada's
growing role in the film industry. A number of top box-office stars
are headed for the state, promising an even bigger year in 1989.
   Twenty-two feature films, 25 television and-or movie projects and
five documentaries used Nevada locations for filming during 1988.
Commercial production increased 400 percent over 1987. Nearly half
of the 52 projects used Southern Nevada locales.
   The year's film highlights included ``Rain Man'' with Dustin
Hoffman; ``Midnight Run,'' which starred Robert DeNiro and Charles
Grodin; Clint Eastwood's ``Pink Cadillac''; ``Far From Home'';
``Bonanza: The Next Generation''; ``Homer and Eddie''; and ``Once
Upon a Texas Train.''
   Other TV films shot in Nevada included ``High Mountain Rangers,''
``Elvis and Me'' and the former hit NBC series, ``Crime Story.''
Other theatrical features included ``Rambo III'' and ``China Lake.''
   Several factors are making Nevada an increasingly attractive
location for filming.
   ``One of the keys is the level of cooperation you get from our
resorts,'' Hirsch said. ``The contribution of the resort industry is
significant. Even if the hotel isn't used in the film, and the
studio is just looking for a place to stay, the hotel costs in
Nevada are half what they would cost in Texas or Colorado.
   ``The motion picture industry is first and foremost a business.
If we can save a company money on such things as hotel rooms, it
gives us an edge.''
   Another factor, according to Hirsch, is the lack of bureaucracy
in Nevada because it is a small state. ``We can get an answer for a
film company in a matter of hours,'' he said. An example was
``Midnight Run.'' Hirsch negotiated with authorities to close a
section of busy Interstate 15 southwest of Las Vegas to film a
roadblock segment for the movie.
   One-third of ``Midnight Run'' was filmed in Nevada. A significant
portion of ``Rain Man'' was also filmed in the state, much of it
during a month-long stint at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas last summer.
   The movie features the glitz and pizzazz of the Las Vegas Strip
and the world-famous resort, but it also captured on film some less
famous Southern Nevada locales. The tiny town of Blue Diamond,
southwest of the city, got a new laundromat front for one scene. A
diner in tiny Pahrump, 50 miles west of Las Vegas, was refurbished
for another scene.
   The diverse locales offered in Nevada is a major selling point
Hirsch hammers home to movie production companies _ from the glamour
and excitement of Las Vegas to nearby desert landscapes, and the
scenic Sierra Nevada in the northern part of the state.
   ``This is an exciting place to be and it has a vast appeal to the
Hollywood mentality,'' Hirsch said of the Las Vegas area. ``Desert
is desert, whether it's outside of Las Vegas, in Arizona or the high
desert of Colorado. But most people would rather spend their
off-time in Las Vegas if they had their choice.''
   Several major films are scheduled for shooting in Nevada in the
upcoming months.
   _ Tom Selleck will be shooting ``Hard Rain,'' a movie for the
Disney Co. that also features Ben Kingsley.
   _ Steven Spielberg will be shooting his new movie, ``Paradox,''
with Michael J. Fox, a film that Hirsch described as ``Back to the
Future: Part II.''
   _ A new Mike Hammer TV movie will be filming in Las Vegas in
February.
   _ A television pilot, ``Winner Take All,'' featuring Abe Bigoda
as a hotel security guard, is in production.
   _ A motion picture, ``Kill Me Again,'' is scheduled to begin
production in the Las Vegas and Reno areas in March.
   _ Two films, ``Destiny Turns on the Radio'' and ``Beneath
Perfection,'' are scheduled to spend 18 weeks filming in Nevada.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
