<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-SkinheadBrotherhood Adv22-2Takes   01-19 1149</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Skinhead Brotherhood, Adv 22 - 2 Takes,1177</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Racist or Anti-Racist, Skinheads Are Complex, Intense Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in grafs 14, 31, 35 and 40, may be offensive to
some</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Skinheads have grabbed headlines recently for
their white-power and Nazi leanings. But in fact not all skinheads
share those views and they often battle among themselves. The
skinhead culture is intense, complex and tribal, often built more on
friendship and unity than on ideology. Here is a look at the
phemonenon, particularly what happened among a group of skinheads in
Milwaukee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By FRED BAYLES</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP National Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the early days the whole crew was cool. Hippy
Pat and Big Brian lived at the house. Little Bryan, John and his
brother Tiny were around. So were Jeff the black skinhead, Mike the
Jew and a whole lot of other guys.
   Nobody gave you bad slack; there wasn't much politics and there
was plenty of beer. Sure, you might go out on manhunts or
fag-bashing, but you weren't after anyone in particular. Mostly it
was a place to hang out, a place to be with your skinhead brothers,
a place you felt you belonged.
   They called the house at 700 Wright the 700 Club. As a joke, they
called themselves SHAM, Skinheads Around Milwaukee.
   Then, things got weird, and then it got scary.
   Today SHAM is the Skinhead Army of Milwaukee. Depleted by
defections and arrests, its numbers are down to a hardcore few who
praise Hitler, preach white power and recruit for the cause.
   They are opposed by the Brew City Skins, anti-racist skinheads
who include old SHAM members. There have been fights between the two
groups of former friends and the violence is likely to continue.
   ``It's real sad what happened,'' said John Lyman, a thoughtful
21-year-old skinhead who has tried to maintain a neutrality between
the warring factions. ``We were all brothers, that was important to
us. Then it went every which way and now everybody totally hates
each other.''
   The story of SHAM is a mirror to what is happening around the
country. Disaffected teen-agers, attracted to the skinhead culture
by its music, its sense of belonging and its urban warrior image,
are waging tribal wars on the hard streets of the nation's cities.
   Some become avowed racists and fascists who sport swastika
tattoos. Sometimes they set upon the targets of their rage.
   Others choose a militantly anti-racist stance, battling not only
the racists but also those who try to remain apolitical.
   ``There is definitely a war going on within a subculture of
society and 99 percent of us aren't aware that it's happening except
for those moments when it spills out and a Jew or a black is
assaulted,'' said Chip Berlet of Political Research Associates, a
Cambridge, Mass., think-tank that studies right wing movements.
   Most public attention has focused on the talk show and crime news
sensationalism of racist skinheads, whose numbers are thought to be
around 3,500.
   Assaults on minorities and synagogue vandalism by these skinheads
have made headlines in big cities like Chicago and Dallas and
smaller communities like Grand Rapids, Reno and Paramus, N.J. Three
skinheads have been charged with beating an Ethiopian immigrant to
death with baseball bats in Portland, Ore. Skinheads have thrown
racial slurs and chairs during national talk show appearances.
   ``I want a white world,'' said Scott, a 21-year-old skinhead in
Chicago. ``I don't want my kids to go to school with niggers and
Jews. I'll die for my race. I'll die for my skinhead brothers.''
   There has been less news media coverage of anti-racist skinheads
who have been in bloody brawls with their rivals in places like
Chicago and Minneapolis. No one has counted their numbers, but in
many cities they are equal if not stronger in number than the racist
skinheads.
   Last weekend skinheads from eight Midwestern cities held a summit
in Minneapolis to form a ``syndicate'' to organize and fight the
racist skins.
   ``This is a war,'' said Dave, a member of the Minneapolis
Baldies. ``We're not going to stop till we've wiped out the scum.''
   Both factions pay homage to the British sociological stew of the
1960s and early '70s that produced the skinhead phenomenon from the
ranks of working class youths. They shaved their heads and adopted a
style of dress from the factories that included high-laced,
steel-tipped Doc Marten work boots, suspenders, called braces on
both sides of the Atlantic, and Fred Perry knit shirts.
   At some point the movement shifted. Many skinheads, victims of
Britain's high unemployment, began to blame and attack Pakistanis
and other immigrants. Skinheads were recruited by the National
Front, Britain's ultra right wing political movement. Ska, a
racially mixed music once favored by skinheads was replaced by the
hardcore rock of Skrewdriver, a band whose music is a call to arms
for white supremacists.
   One song complains:
   ``They come here to this country from the jungles and the trees,
   ``Traitors in the Parliament gave them a better deal ...
   ``Before the night falls, heed the white call.''
   Basic skinhead philosophy rejects drugs and encourages a pride in
yourself and your country. Skinheads also stress a family unity
among themselves, an enticement to many alienated youths whose real
families have been fractured.
   ``A lot of them are damaged goods,'' said Larry Harding, a
Portland probation officer. ``They come from broken homes, they
don't fit in in school and they are sometimes attacked by ethnic
gangs. Being a skinhead offers them a chance to be part of
something.''
   While some American skinheads like Scott were first attracted by
the white power message, many others, like those at Milwaukee's 700
club, join the scene for its style and unity.
   ``It was more out of a strong sense of friendship, a sense of
security,'' said Tom Dusick, another ``neutral'' skin who was at the
700 Club when it began in late 1987. ``When you went down there, you
were important and no one was going to mess with you skinheads.''
   The scene in the early days of SHAM was open and relaxed. Jeff
Merchant, a black skinhead from Chicago was an accepted member of
the crew.
   But the crew members weren't angels. They would get beery and go
out on ``manhunts,'' roaming nearby Downer Avenue in search of
trouble.
   ``It's not like we really were looking for it, but 10 bald guys
walking down the street, somebody's got to say something,'' said
Merchant, now a leader of the Brew City Skins.
   But even in the early days there was a latent racism. The crew at
the 700 Club would joke about Jews and blacks. Even today some of
Lyman's friends talk about ``the niggers who do all the crime,'' and
the Jews ``who own all the corporations.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-SkinheadBrotherhood Adv22-1stAdd   01-19 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Skinhead Brotherhood, Adv 22 - 1st Add,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>MILWAUKEE: the corporations.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``A lot of us are from places where there are no black people or
Jewish people, so a lot of the guys just had these stereotype ideas
and it just took something to bring them out,'' said Lyman.
   Most agree things began to change with the appearance of Pat
O'Malley, an intense, gravel-voiced 18-year-old from Madison with a
spiderweb tattoo on his shaved skull and a swastika ``tatt'' on his
finger.
   O'Malley got a post office box and began corresponding with
racist skinhead groups in Chicago and Detroit and with White Aryan
Resistance, a Fallbrook, Calif., group run by Tom Metzger, host of
the white power ``Race and Reason'' cable television show.
   The material sent to SHAM was filled with jarring words and
images. ``Nigger'' and ``kike'' appeared often along with talk about
revolution and race warfare. Much of it was in the form of
``fanzines,'' newsletters published by racist skinhead groups in
America and Europe.
   ``The skinhead phenomena has its own motor and own leadership and
then you have Metzger who is trying to inject ideology, discipline
and a level of expertise,'' said Leonard Zeskind, research director
for the anti-racist Center for Democratic Renewal.
   Metzger says he is doing nothing more than responding to the
anger and frustration of young whites.
   ``They see they are slipping through the cracks economically and
they don't feel they have much of a future,'' he said. ``I give them
guidence on the law to stay out of trouble and I give them our
ideology. But I don't try to organize them. They have their own
subculture and tampering with it would destroy it.''
   Whatever the reason, the scene at the 700 Club slowly changed.
   Someone drew a cross-hairs on the television set and labeled it
the ``niggerscope.'' When a black appeared on the screen there would
be cheers of ``we got another one.''
   Merchant retaliated by changing the label to ``Naziscope,'' and
altering the ``white power'' scrawls on the wall to ``white coward.''
   Nobody threatend Merchant _ after all, he was a brother skinhead
_ but after awhile he stopped coming around.
   ``They started handing out hate literature and stuff and people
told me, `Hey, just don't go over there,' so I didn't,'' he said.
   The black college student wasn't alone. Bryan Lauer, Little
Bryan, dropped out too, turning his back on a childhood friend who
had become more and more racist.
   ``I can't talk to him anymore,'' said Lauer.
   But SHAM continued to grow. Word went out on the post office box
grapevine that Milwaukee had a cool scene. Racist skins from
Detroit, Chicago and Texas showed up and moved in.
   Now the scene got scary.
   ``I remember this one guy who had been in Virginia and Detroit
and Cleveland saying how he was going to die to see this country all
white,'' said Dusick. ``They were talking about how they were going
to exterminate everybody.''
   He concluded, ``These guys are wacky,'' and he didn't go back.
   SHAM moved from the wrecked house on Wright Street to another
address. Members attended Klan and Nazi rallies in other cities and
attracted local media coverage by goose-stepping and then brawling
at a neighborhood fair.
   A newspaper printed a map of the skinhead house and carloads of
teen-agers began to drive by, tossing bottles and shouting threats.
   Last July 14, Hollin Lange, a member of the Dallas Hammerskins,
was hit by birdshot while standing outside the house. Six days later
he and O'Malley fired into a car of teens, claiming they had seen a
gun.
   The shooting ended SHAM. As in other cities, like Chicago and Los
Angeles, the violence and subsequent arrests broke up the group,
sending some members fleeing to Oregon, Texas and Oklahoma.
   These days the five or so remaining members of SHAM keep a low
profile at their new house. The street buzz is they are recruiting
younger kids in nearby towns like Racine and Kenosha. They refuse to
talk to the press as does O'Malley, who is scheduled to go on trial
this week.
   Lauer and the Brew City Skins are also recruiting, passing out
literature to explain the differences between them and SHAM.
   ``We want people to know we're different,'' said Lauer.
   ``Neutrals'' like Lyman and Dusick are facing growing pressure to
choose between the two sides.
   ``It's getting real hard to stay out of it,'' said Lyman.
   If forced to choose, Lyman says he will have to back his friends
in SHAM. He doesn't believe in their hatred, but he goes back with
them to the days when it was just a bunch of people with shaved
heads and a kinship.
   ``It's a real deep friendship thing. It made me feel like I was
somebody for once,'' he said. ``Even if they are the worst to
everybody, they were still our brothers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 22</NOTE>
