<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-ConsumerDebt-Counseling Adv22   01-19 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Consumer Debt-Counseling, Adv 22,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Jan. 22 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Help Available For Those Drowning In Red Ink</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Consumer Debt, b0677</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget &amp; Credit Counseling Services Inc., just
north of the Wall Street financial district, seems almost cheery
with smiling receptionists, bright lights and pretty pastel-colored
cubicles.
   But once inside, debt-plagued clients are asked to spill their
financial guts, detailing everything from mortgage payments to the
monthly cost of cleaning their underwear.
   A recent visit showed it's seldom pleasant.
   Mary, a 58-year-old Brooklyn woman, sat tearful as counselor Ann
Quigley tried to concoct a repayment plan for the $12,056 in credit
card debts she racked up over two years. Mary said she made the
charges, mostly for cash advances, to help pay her 19-year-old
grandson's college costs.
   ``I really don't know how I spend it because I don't make it,''
said the woman, who earned $17,352 last year in her social services
job, 10 percent of which was donated to her church.
   ``Have they (creditors) been calling you a lot?'' asked Ms.
Quigley.
   ``No, just sending letters mostly,'' Mary replied. ``I knew after
the start of the year that they would start bugging me, though.''
   ``Tell me, how much is your monthly rent? Transportation costs?
Laundry or dry-cleaning bill? ...,'' Ms. Quigley asked.
   She discovered that all of Mary's $926 monthly pay is spent on
necessities. That left nothing for savings _ not to mention the $455
a month Ms. Quigley had proposed as a payback to creditors under a
three-year plan.
   ``Would you consider getting a part-time job?'' she asked.
   Meanwhile, several feet away, Mark, a 30-year-old word processor
operator, sat with a phone in his ear. He had discarded his $10,000
worth of credit-card bills two years ago, and was trying to
re-establish contact with creditors.
   ``Who invented these credit cards anyway?'' he huffed.
   The New York budget counseling office, which sees about 10,000
families and individuals a year, is one of about 400 offices
nationwide affiliated with the non-profit Maryland-based National
Foundation for Consumer Credit. It's also one of the busiest.
   Foundation President Donald L. Badders says the number of people
seeking credit help has risen steadily for reasons ranging from
family economic problems to wider credit card use.
   In the fiscal year ended Oct. 1, the foundation offices counseled
211,000 clients, 78 percent higher than five years ago. Last year,
the foundation said it recovered $242 million to businesses through
the repayment plans it arranged with clients.
   For a $20 fee, sometimes waived for extreme cases, these offices
act as an intermediary between debtors and creditors, arranging for
small monthly repayments.
   There are also for-profit budget counseling offices, but the
foundation says some are fly-by-night operations that charge big
fees and make false promises.
   ``Watch out for credit clinics that purport to be able to repair
your credit rating because it cannot be done,'' said Luther Gatling,
founder and president of the New York budget counseling office.
   Debtors have several options to reform.
   Besides following the foundation's standard three-year plan, they
can take out a debt-consolidation loan. But some experts warn these
loans are disguised home-equity loans, saddling a debtor with the
risk of losing his home if he fails to repay.
   Another alternative is personal bankruptcy. Debtors can either
repay loans after liquidating assets under Chapter 7 of federal
bankruptcy laws or reorganize and stave off creditors under Chapter
13. Either way, their credit rating will remain tarnished for at
least seven years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
