<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit ballooned to $12.5
billion in November, the biggest imbalance in five months, the
government said in a report many private economists and even the
Reagan administration viewed as a disappointing indication of how
deep the country's trade problems are.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the trade gap was 22
percent larger than October's $10.3 billion deficit, reflecting a
surge in imports, particularly for business capital goods, and a
slight drop in exports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan said its surplus of exports over imports
surged in December to a monthly record, despite official assurances
that the Asian economic giant is moving forcefully to open markets
to foreign goods.
   Although the Finance Ministry said Wednesday the surplus shrank
for all of 1988, figures showed it was widening in the last four
months of the year, capped by the $9.65 billion imbalance recorded
last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans used more energy in 1988 than in any
year in history, and oil imports hit a 9-year high, an industry
trade group said.
   The American Petroleum Institute said Wednesday a more
encouraging development last year was an indication the nation is
making new gains in the efficient use of energy.
   The trade organization, representing the bigger U.S. oil
producers and refiners, said U.S. consumption of all types of energy
rose 4 percent last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industry operated at its highest rate in
nine years last month, the government reported, but analysts said
the modest pace of growth should allay fears of increasing inflation.
   Use of industrial capacity at factories, mines and utilities rose
0.1 percentage point to 84.2 percent last month, the Federal Reserve
said Wednesday.
   In an accompanying report, the agency said industrial production
climbed a moderate 0.3 percent in December following a revised
increase of 0.4 percent in November.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey found that despite expectations of
better business activity for this year, financial executives at many
U.S. corporations foresee the possibility of an economic downturn in
1990.
   For three consecutive quarters, a majority of executives
responding to the National Association of Accountants survey have
predicted a recession will occur next year.
   Asked to project where the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial
stocks will be at the end of 1989's first quarter, most of the
executives answering said it would be at or below recent levels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board authorized five of
the nation's largest banks to underwrite corporate debt and said it
would decide in a year whether to allow banks to underwrite stock.
   The unanimous decision Wednesday by the seven-member board
greatly expands the type of underwriting permitted, but still
severely limits the quantity of underwriting.
   The Fed said bank holding companies may only conduct securities
underwriting through a separate subsidiary regulated by the
Securities and Exchange Commission. And, the subsidiary may earn no
more than 5 percent of its revenue from underwriting activities.
</TEXT>
