<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-19 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Up; Crude Hits 14-Month High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market gathered more steam,
with the price of crude oil reaching a 14-month high and refined
petroleum products rising more than a penny a gallon.
   Analysts attributed Wednesday's rally largely to a bullish trade
report on oil production and to continued optimism that the
13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will abide
by its production-cutting pact that went into effect Jan. 1.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
at $19.26 a barrel Wednesday, up 31 cents from Tuesday, when it
gained 7 cents.
   Wednesday's close was the highest since Nov. 3, 1987, when the
near-term contract settled on the exchange at $19.49 a barrel. At
that time, there were concerns that the Iran-Iraq war could
seriously disrupt shipments of crude from the Persian Gulf.
   Among refined contracts traded on the exchange Wednesday, the
February contract for home heating oil settled 1.56 cents higher at
54.61 cents a gallon. The contract had fallen 0.11 cent on Tuesday.
   February unleaded gasoline jumped 1.16 cents to settle at 52.26
cents a gallon, after rising 0.19 cent Tuesday.
   ``Traders are more confident in OPEC and they feel that OPEC will
continue to get it together through the summer,'' said Bob Baker, an
energy analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The oil cartel had agreed last fall to slash daily output to 18.5
million barrels in an effort to prop up sagging worldwide oil
prices. OPEC members have shown signs of sticking to that agreement,
and prices have steadily risen since the first of the year.
   Baker said a weekly report from the American Petroleum Institute
showing a sharp decline in U.S. oil supplies also added a positive
tone to the energy market Wednesday.
   API, which represents the major U.S. oil producers and refiners,
said oil imports last year jumped to the highest level since 1979.
It said production fell to 8.1 million barrels a day, a nearly 3
percent drop from 1987.
</TEXT>
