<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Whittle-Television Bjt   01-19 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whittle-Television, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Plans to Test TV News Show For Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications LP plans to launch a daily
televised news show that will include commercials and give schools
thousands of dollars in equipment to show it in the classroom during
the school day.
   In its first venture into television, the Knoxville, Tenn.-based
media company plans to begin testing its daily 12-minute news show _
which includes up to two minutes of ads _ in early March in four to
six schools.
   If the seven-week test proves successful, the program could
launched nationally in the fall of 1990 in up to 10,000 schools with
as many as 7 million students at a cost of more than $100 million in
hardware alone.
   Christopher Whittle, chairman and founder of the company, said
the project represents ``what we hope will be our major contribution
to the media business'' in the 1990s, and possibly Whittle's most
lucrative venture.
   Whittle believes the program has advantages for students,
educators and advertisers. But the plan also has raised questions
about allowing marketers to make sales pitches in the classroom.
   Peggy Charren, president of Action for Children's Television, a
self-styled children's advocate, said it is ``outrageous to let
sales people into the schools connected to education.''
   The schools will get dozens of television monitors, a satellite
dish and a system hooking it all together so that the news show,
dubbed Channel One, can be shown to students daily. The schools can
use the system for their own non-commercial purposes, provided they
run the show or explain why not.
   Whittle said the hardware alone will cost about $50,000 per
school, a price many schools could not afford.
   The show, initially being produced in Los Angeles, will be sent
by satellite to the schools every weekday. It is being produced by
Susan Winston, a former producer of ABC's ``Good Morning America''
show.
   A typical show _ which could have possibly four 30-second
commercials _ would have several hard news stories relevant to
students in the 12-to-17 age group and narrated by young anchor
people, a profile of someone in the news, a segment in a multi-part
series on an issue like the environment and other features,
interlaced with trivia or a quiz.
   Whittle said 60 percent of the ad time has been sold for the test
but refused to identify the buyers. He said if the program goes
national, sponsors will be asked for long-term commitments, possibly
up to five years.
   He said many advertisers are interested in reaching the elusive
teenage audience, which has attracted even wider attention as teens
have started shopping for the family because both parents work
outside the home.
   But the paid pitches have raised some concerns.
   Whittle has identifed only three of the schools selected for the
test. They are Mumford High School in Detroit, Eisenhower Middle
School in Kansas City, Kan., and Central High School in Knoxville,
Tenn.
   Robin Oden, principal at Mumford, conceded he has reservations
about airing commercials in school.
   But he said the advantages of getting the video hardware and a
timely program with educational value outweighed the negatives of
the commercials.
   The school could ``absolutely not'' afford to buy the 103
television monitors and satellite dish it will get for the test
project, Oden said.
   He likes the idea of being able to use the system to address the
entire school by television, show videos of classroom lessons or run
tapes recorded from television, such as a special on Martin Luther
King Jr.
   Nonetheless, Oden said he told Whittle Communications he would
not permit a show, for example, which had advertising that
encouraged students to wear the type of clothing or jewelry to
school that Mumford's dress policy forbids.
   Whittle said his agreement with the schools allows administrators
to review shows before they are aired and to withhold them if they
find something objectionable, provided they report their reasons for
doing so.
   He said he has banned ads for beer or other alcoholic beverages,
cigarettes and contraceptives.
   Whittle Communications has found rewards in creating media aimed
at reaching narrowly-defined audiences. Its revenue amounted to $150
million last year, and Time Inc. paid $185 million for a 50 percent
interest in the concern last October.
   Whittle currently reaches about 10,000 students with sponsored
posters and its GO! (Girls Only!) magazine.
   Last summer, it launched Special Reports magazine, a series of
six magazines available only in doctor's waiting rooms. That project
generated $40 million a year in ad revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
