<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports     01-19 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Steel Nears Quota Limits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports rose in November, pushing the
total for 11 months of 1988 to a level 6.8 percent above 1987,
although foreign steel continued near the limits set by a U.S. quota
plan.
   November imports totaled 1.85 million tons, up from 1.55 million
tons in October and 1.78 million tons in November 1987. For the
first 11 months of the year, imports were 19.47 million tons in
1988, compared with 18.23 million tons in 1987.
   The figures were compiled by the American Iron and Steel
Institute in Washington, D.C., using Commerce Department data, and
were released Wednesday.
   Market penetration by imports was 22.2 percent in November, up
from 18.9 percent in October and 21.5 percent in November 1987. For
the 11 months, foreign steel captured 20.6 percent of the market in
1988 and 21 percent in 1987.
   Import quotas due to expire in September after five years in
force were intended to restrict imported steel to 20.2 percent of
the U.S. market.
   A rival to the U.S. producers' organization, the New York-based
American Institute for Imported Steel in New York, said that after
subtracting semifinished steel ordered by U.S. mills from foreign
producers, market penetration was only 17.7 percent, below the 18.5
percent goal for that category.
   U.S. steelmakers bought an estimated 2.84 million tons of foreign
steel in the first 11 months of 1988, the AIIS said.
</TEXT>
