<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     01-19 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady against most major currencies
in European trading this morning, buoyed by speculation the market
was preparing to test central bank resolve at keeping the U.S.
currency from climbing.
   Gold prices were mixed but also steady.
   The dollar withstood several rounds of central bank intervention
Wednesday following the report of a bigger-than-expected U.S. trade
deficit in November, dealers said.
   The market had expected a deficit of about $11 billion, but
instead it widened sharply to $12.5 billion from a revised $10.3
billion in October.
   Traders said today they interpreted the dollar's resilience as a
sign the market was gearing up to test central bank willingness to
intervene to slow the dollar's advance.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7555 to buy one pound, dearer than $1.7550 late Tuesday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates included: 1.8665 West German marks, down from
1.8705; 1.5885 Swiss francs, down from 1.5890; 6.3735 French francs,
down from 6.3800; 2.1062 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0925; 1,368.75
Italian lire, up from 1,356.75; 1.1920 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1937.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.30 Japanese yen to a closing 129.20
yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 129.15 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $402 a troy ounce, down
from $402.25 late Wednesday. At mid-morning, major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $402.30.
   In Zurich, gold was slightly lower, trading at a bid $402.25,
compared with $402.40 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 81 cents to close at a bid
$403.83.
   Silver bullion fell on the London market to a bid price of $5.92
a troy ounce from $5.94 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
