<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen
today despite an increase in the U.S. trade deficit, while share
prices eased on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 129.20 yen, up 1.30 yen from Wednesday's
finish of 127.90 yen. It opened at 128.55 yen and ranged between
128.37 yen and 129.35 yen.
   The dollar, which now has gained 3.08 yen in four days, finished
above 129 yen for the first time since its 129.65 yen closing last
Oct. 12.
   The U.S. trade report released Wednesday showed a $12.5 billion
deficit for November, up 22 percent from October.
   But Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank in Tokyo said investors
still were buying dollars. He said they looked for continued high
U.S. interest rates because the figure showed that with steady
economic growth, the United States still was able to increase
imports.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make dollar-denominated
investments more attractive to foreigners.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 127.03-point gainer
Wednesday, shed 43.15 points, or 0.14 percent, closing at 31,311.40.
   The index gained in early trading, but then started to fall as
institutional investors moved to the sidelines, while some others
were selling to collect profits, said a dealer with a major
securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``The Nikkei's decline, triggered by the selling of steel issues,
was mainly because of the falling yen,'' said the dealer, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Other dealers said the recent uptrend in oil prices also
discouraged investors.
   In active trading, volume on the first section was estimated at
1.2 billion shares.
</TEXT>
