<FIRST>u f BC-Germany-Rates     01-19 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Germany-Rates,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Central Bank Raises Key Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank said
Thursday that it was raising two key interest rates a half
percentage point each to battle inflation and counter the Deutsche
mark's recent slide against other major currencies.
   The Bundesbank said that effective Friday it was boosting its
discount rate to 4 percent and the Lombard rate to 6 percent.
   The discount rate is the interest the central bank charges on
loans to member banks, while the Lombard rate is the rate charged
for short-term loans when securities are used as collateral.
   In a statement, the Bundesbank said its policy-setting council
decided on the increases to dampen money supply growth, a sign of
growing inflation, and to counter the depreciation of the mark
against other major currencies, particularly the U.S. dollar.
   The world financial markets had expected West Germany to raise
its interest following the sharp rise in the dollar in recent days.
   Still, shortly after the rate increases were announced the dollar
continued to rise in nervous European trading, hitting a nearly
four-month high in Frankfurt, dealers said.
</TEXT>
