<FIRST>r f PM-Church's-Popeyes     01-19 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church's-Popeyes,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church's Fried Chicken Announces Company's Auction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church's Fried Chicken, fighting a $290
million hostile takeover by its chief rival, says it is for sale,
but still calls inadequate the buyout offer made by Popeyes Famous
Fried Chicken and Biscuits.
   Church's, which over the past three months has sold off
restaurants and taken Popeyes to court in an attempt to halt the
hostile takeover bid, announced Wednesday that it would be in the
company's best interest to be auctioned off.
   In a prepared statement, the company's board of directors said it
could end the bidding for the company's sale within 30 days.
   The statement also said that Church's financial advisers still
believed Popeyes offer of $8 per share was inadequate, but that it
was willing to provide Popeyes the information that had been
provided to other interested third parties.
   ``We believe the offer by Copeland is inadequate and to have them
(shareholders) move on that is not in their best interest,'' said
Church's attorney Diane Kerr. ``We think this decision is a move
made out of responsibility by the directors for the shareholders.''
   Popeyes is owned by Al Copeland, who earlier this month was given
permission to continue his attempted takeover of Church's, after
federal court proceedings stalled his efforts.
   San Antonio-based Church's, the country's No. 2 chicken
restaurant chain with 1,478 units, has been fighting since last
November a hostile takeover bid by New Orleans-based Popeyes, the
country's No. 3 chicken chain with 703 restaurants.
   Church's claims that two of its former executives now working for
Popeyes used illegally obtained information in the buyout offer and
that the buyout would violate U.S. antitrust laws.
   On Nov. 4, Church's adopted anti-takeover bylaws to make a
takeover less attractive, and later challenged Popeyes in court.
   Church's announcement Wednesday came a day before a San Antonio
federal judge was to preside over a hearing to determine the
legality of anti-takeover bylaws.
   Church's spokeswoman Faye Kilgore said that Ernie Renaud,
Church's president and chief executive officer, would not be
available for comment Wednesday.
   Popeyes officials did not return telephone calls to The
Associated Press.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Schwartz of New Orleans in late
November prohibited Popeyes from buying Church's stock until it
revealed more information about its buyout offer.
   Church's, meanwhile, sued by shareholders worried that their
earnings would be jeopardized if the company was not sold, announced
in mid-December that it would immediately close 120 of its
restaurants around the country.
   In January, a 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel said that
Popeyes could continue with its takeover bid.
   Under the tentative plan given to Schwartz in December, Popeyes
planned to close 250 of Church's restaurants, rename 303 others as
Popeyes, sell 440 others for $160 million and would keep 83
restaurants with the Church's name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
