<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     01-19 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher at Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher in active trading at
midday Thursday, with players encouraged by the market's ability to
easily surpass its previous post-crash highs.
   Shares were also boosted by bullishly interpreted British
unemployment and industrial production figures.
   But shares fell back from their morning peaks when a stock
shortage appeared to ease.
   By about 12:30 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index was up 17.3 points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,909.4 points, off
from its early morning best level of 1,913.5 points up. The index
slumped to its minimum of 1,904.5 at midmorning.
   Volume was a healthy 494.1 million shares by midday, compared
with 301.6 million shares at the same time Wednesday.
   ``There's lots of business for everybody,'' said one market
maker, who described trading as ``electric.''
   Britain's underlying average earnings dipped in November, easing
worries over inflationary pressures on the economy, dealers said.
Unemployment and manufacturing both dropped.
   ``The market's reaction was one of pleasure to the figures,'' a
trader said.
