<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0003 01-19 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0003,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report of Big Trade Deficit Doesn't Faze Financial Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with reports on consumer price index and housing starts.
Tightens thruout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation on the consumer side reached 4.4 percent during 1988,
the same as a year earlier, as hefty, drought-induced increases for
groceries offset stable energy prices, the government reported today.
   The gain, as measured in the Labor Department's Consumer Price
Index, matched the 1987 increase, which was the highest since 1981
but was four times the 1.1 percent rate in 1986, a 25-year low.
   A 0.3 percent rise in the index in December, which followed a 0.3
percent November increase, helped inflation finish the year at a
moderate pace.
   The summer drought, which shriveled crops and seared pastures,
pushed food prices for the year up 5.2 percent, the steepest rise
since 1980. However, energy for the year rose only a slight 0.5
percent following an 8.2 percent jump in 1987.
   In another economic report today, the Commerce Department said
housing construction fell 2.2 percent in December from the previous
month. That helped drag down construction for the entire year to
1.49 million units, the poorest showing for the housing industry
since the recession year of 1982 when 1.06 million units were built.
   December's seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.52 million units
was down from 1.56 million units a month earlier. It was the
steepest monthly drop since a 12.1 percent decline last May.
   On Wednesday, the Commerce Department reported that November's
trade imbalance reached $12.5 billion, the biggest in five months
and 22 percent larger than October's $10.3 billion deficit.
   But even with the November deterioration, the trade deficit for
the first 11 months of 1988 was running at an annual rate of $137.3
billion, almost 20 percent below the all-time imbalance of $170.3
billion set in 1987.
   Many private economists viewed the latest report as an indication
of the severity of the country's trade problems.
   Undaunted by the disappointing trade figures, though, financial
markets posted strong performances Wednesday. Some analysts said
market operators took comfort from renewed hopes that inflationary
pressures may be abating.
   The stock market rose in heavy trading, with the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials up 24.11 points at 2,238.75, surpassing
its post-crash peak of 2,226.07 it reached last Friday.
   Some of the power driving equities higher came from the
surprising resilience of the dollar. Frequently in the past, a poor
trade report induced currency dealers to dump dollars but on
Wednesday heavy buying pushed the dollar higher against most leading
currencies.
   Taking a cue from the currency markets, bond prices rose with the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond gaining nearly $7 for each $1,000 in
face value.
   In commodity markets, crude oil futures continued their recent
rally and pierced the important psychological level of $19 a barrel.
   In other economic reports Wednesday:
   _The Federal Reserve Board said production at the nation's
factories, mines and utilities climbed 0.3 percent in December
following a revised increase of 0.4 percent in November.
   _The Fed said the operating rate at factories, mines and
utilities rose in December to the highest rate since November 1979.
Industrial capacity rose 0.1 percentage points to 84.2 percent last
month, the highest rate since 84.3 percent in November 1979. The
operating rate for November 1988 was a revised 84.1 percent.
   But even with the November deterioration, the trade deficit for
the first 11 months of 1988 was running at an annual rate of $137.3
billion, almost 20 percent below the all-time imbalance of $170.3
billion set in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
