<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Norway-Smoking     01-19 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Norway-Smoking,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Action Plan For Smoke-Free Norway By Year 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-smoking activists have presented the
government with an action plan for a smoke-free Norway by the year
2000.
   The plan, handed to Social Minister Tove Strand Gerhardsen this
week, was a follow-up to a law adopted last year forbidding smoking
in areas like theater lobbies, bus or train terminals, and in
offices occupied by more than one person.
   The government itself has endorsed the goal of making Norway
smokeless by the end of the century, though tobacco consumption in
recent years has increased by 500 tons per year. Norway has
prohibited tobacco advertising since 1973.
   Seven organizations, including the Norwegian Association of
Sports Federations, the National Public Health Assn. and the
Norwegian Cancer Society, formulated a tough program urging the
government to adopt it in stages over the next six years.
   Among the measures were a smoke-free environment in schools and
kindergartens, an increase in taxes on tobacco products and
outlawing their sale to youths under 18.
   The action plan demanded a smoking ban in prisons and other
public institutions. It called for setting aside for non-smokers at
least one-third of all hotel rooms and tables at hotel restaurants
by 1992, and further reducing that by at least half by 1995.
   All discoteques, clubs, theater, restaurant and concert halls
should be off-limits to smokers, the plan said.
   Chewing tobacco and snuff, which some Scandinavians stick to
their upper gum, would be declared health hazards.
   The plan called for a special working group including government
representatives to monitor implementation of the action plan.
</TEXT>
