<FIRST>r f PM-Borman'sSuit     01-19 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Borman's Suit,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grocery Chain Will Contest Stockholders Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borman's Inc. says it will contest a lawsuit by
shareholders who say they sold their stock at artificially low
prices at a time company officials were holding secret acquisition
talks with A&amp;P.
   Mortimer Flohr and Pauline Flohr, who own about 100 shares of
Borman's stock, seek punitive damages of $20 million in a suit filed
Jan. 11 in U.S. District Court in New York.
   The Flohrs also ask class-action status on behalf of all others
who sold Borman's stock between Nov. 28 and Dec. 12.
   Officials at Borman's, operator of 79 Farmer Jack supermarkets in
the Detroit area, said in a news release that the company was served
with the complaint Wednesday and would defend itself.
   The lawsuit claims that Borman's stock began trading in heavy
volumes in late November, and that on Nov. 28 a spokesman said the
company had no explanation.
   On Dec. 12, Borman's announced that it was negotiating with A&amp;P.
Its stock rose the next day to nearly $25 a share from $13. On Dec.
23, Borman's announced an agreement to sell the Farmer Jack stores
to A&amp;P for $76 million.
   Borman's officials did not return phone calls Wednesday and early
today about the suit. Lester Levy, the Flohrs attorney in New York,
declined to elaborate on the suit.
</TEXT>
