<FIRST>r f PM-Arco-Lyondell     01-19 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arco-Lyondell,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Sale in Lyondell Subsidiary is 3rd Biggest Initial Offering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantic Richfield Co. put half its Lyondell
Petrochemical Co. subsidiary up for sale to the public in an initial
stock offering that, at $1.2 billion, is the third biggest by an
American company.
   The sale of 40 million shares of Lyondell stock at a price of $30
per share is being underwritten by Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. and Salomon
Brothers Inc.
   Proceeds from sale of stock in the Houston chemical manufacturer
will go to Arco, with potential uses including purchase of
oil-producing property and repurchase of Arco stock, said
spokeswoman Jacqueline Wilson.
   Lyondell, which produces fuel and lubricants as well as oil-based
chemicals, has been approved for listing on the New York Stock
Exchange, Arco said. Its symbol on stock lists will be LYO.
   The stock sale ranks as the third largest initial public offering
by a U.S. company, though two other companies have gone public at
the same $1.2 billion price, according to IDD Information Services
Inc., which compiles such data.
   Consolidated Rail Corp. went public with a $1.65 billion stock
sale in 1987 and Henley Group Inc. had an initial public offering of
$1.3 billion in 1986. Duff &amp; Phelps Selected Utilities and Coca-Cola
Enterprises Inc. both went public at $1.2 billion.
   Arco owned all of Lyondell's 80 million shares previous to the
sale. It has given the underwriters the option of buying 6 million
shares to cover over-allotments. That could dilute Arco's ownership
to 42.5 percent, and if that happened, the Los Angeles-based oil
company said it would repurchase shares on the open market to keep
its holdings just under 50 percent.
   Here, according to IDD, are the biggest initial public offerings
by U.S. companies:
   Consolidated Rail Corp., $1.65 billion, March 26, 1987
   Henley Group Inc., $1.3 billion, May 20, 1986
   Lyondell Petrochemical Co., $1.2 billion, Jan. 18, 1989
   Duff &amp; Phelps Selected Utilities, $1.2 billion, Jan. 21, 1987
   Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc., $1.2 billion, Nov. 21, 1986
   MFS Multimarket Income Trust, $1.1 billion, March 5, 1987
   Fireman's Fund Corp., $824 million, Oct. 23, 1986
   Commercial Credit Co., $779 million, Oct. 29, 1986
   First Australian Prime Fund, $750 million, April 17, 1986
   Rockefeller Center Properties Inc., $750 million, Sept. 12, 1985
   Ford Motor Co., $658 million, Jan. 18, 1956
   Global Yield Fund, $570 million, June 30, 1986
   UNUM Corp., $562 million, Nov. 6, 1986
</TEXT>
