<FIRST>u f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock     01-19 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Boosts Its Offer For Polaroid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. said today it has raised its
tender offer for Polaroid Corp. to $45 per share, including
approximately 10 million shares issued to Polaroid's employee stock
ownership plan, valuing the new deal at $3.2 billion.
   Stanley P. Gold, Shamrock's president and chief executive
officer, also said that Shamrock would wage a proxy battle for
control of Polaroid's board at the annual meeting May 9.
   Shamrock, a Burbank, Calif.-based television and radio concern
wholly owned by the Roy E. Disney family, previously had offered $42
a share, not including the ESOP shares, or $2.6 billion.
   There was no immediate comment from Polaroid, the instant camera
company based in Cambridge.
   Polaroid management has rejected previous Shamrock offers, and
more than 5,000 of the company's 8,300 employees signed a petition
last month saying they had ``no comfort or confidence'' that a
takeover would benefit the company.
   He added that Shamrock's slate of nominees would be committed to
the sale of Polaroid to Shamrock, ``unless a bonafide third party
offer is made for all the then outstanding shares at a higher
price.''
   Shamrock said its tender offer expires March 15 and is contingent
on obtaining at least 90 percent of Polaroid's 71.6 million
outstanding stock, including the shares in the employee stock
ownership plan.
   The takeover may hinge on a court battle over the legality of the
ESOP, which Shamrock claims was enacted to forestall a takeover. The
Delaware Supreme Court has scheduled oral arguments in March on
Shamrock's appeal of a Chancery Court ruling that upheld the ESOP.
   Shamrock said that if it wins the appeal, it will raise its offer
to $47 dollars a share.
</TEXT>
