<SECOND>PM-Fairchild-Carlyle,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fairchild Rejects Offer By Carlyle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense electronics contractor Fairchild
Industries Inc. has rejected an unsolicited $264 million takeover
offer by a Washington, D.C.-based investment partnership.
   Fairchild notified the Carlyle Group Wednesday it would become a
private company as a means of heading off the hostile takeover
attempt.
   A statement issued by the company read in part: ``The proposed
conditional cash purchase of $15.50 per share of common stock was
financially inadequate and not in the best interests of Fairchild
and all its stockholders.''
   The company's stock closed up 12{ cents per share Wednesday to
$16.25 following news of the rejection.
   The Carlyle Group said it would review its options, according to
Stephen Norris, one of the company's managing directors.
   ``I suspect shareholders, if given the option, would tend to
support a purchase ... over a vague plan to improve performance over
some extended period of time. Our interest in owning the company
hasn't diminshed,'' Norris said.
   The investment partnership purchased about 10 percent of
Fairchild stock last fall and offered to take the company private.
But Fairchild said it will go private in a $264 million transaction.
   Carlyle has made takover offers for an increasing number of
companies in recent years and purchased Oakite Products Inc., a New
Jersey chemical company last year.
