<FIRST>r f PM-ChrisCraft     01-19 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chris Craft,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chris-Craft to Close Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Murray Chris-Craft Inc. boatworks will
close Jan. 27, ending a 50-year presence here and Michigan's legacy
as home to the world's oldest manufacturer of pleasure boats,
company officials confirmed today.
   Chris-Craft's debt-ridden parent company, Murray Industries Inc.
of Bradenton, Fla., made the announcement Wednesday to the 70
workers still employed at the Holland Township plant, which employed
about 600 workers as recently as 1983.
   The workers will lose their jobs because a potential buyer of the
Chris-Craft line doesn't want the 50-year-old local classic cruiser
plant and one in Bellingham, Wash., company and union official said.
   The company filed for reorganization under the federal bankruptcy
code Dec. 9. A week ago, Murray tentatively accepted a $15 million
offer from Genmar Industries of Minneapolis, one of the nation's
largest recreational boat manufacturers. Genmar does not want the
Holland plant.
   Chris-Craft has its roots in Algonac, Mich., where it was founded
in 1874. The recreational boats have been built in at least one
Michigan plant since. When Chris-Craft opened its Holland plant in
1939 in Allegan County, it was touted as the largest boat-buiding
oepration in the world.
   Holland Township Superintendent Willis Driesenga said the closing
``will be a shock to the whole community. I think everybody at one
time worked there or knew someone who worked there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0308 </DOCNO>
