<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-19 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Gain; Corn, Soybeans Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices opened sharply higher today
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for continued dry
weather in the Great Plains and indications of renewed foreign
buying interest.
   Corn and soybean futures were nearly unchanged in early trading.
   A 6-to-10-day forecast issued Wednesday by the National Weather
Service predicted at least another week of below-normal
precipitation from Texas to Nebraska, the heart of the nation's
winter wheat area.
   The forecast fanned bullish interest in the wheat market, where
memories of last year's drought are still fresh, analysts said.
   ``We're getting buying now on a weather basis,'' said Walter
Spilka, a grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
in New York. ``The market looks like it's just going to work higher
now until it rains.''
   The winter wheat crop is planted in the fall and harvested in the
spring.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 4 cents higher with March
at $4.43 a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to } cent higher with March
at $2.70\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1} cents higher with March
at $2.39{ a bushel; soybeans were } cent lower to 2} cents higher
with January at $7.61 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .38 cent higher with February at
73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .33 cent
higher with January at 84.70 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged
to .30 cent higher with February at 43.80 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to .38 cent higher with February at 40.75
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Wednesday.
