<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     01-19 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0370</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market continued to push forward today,
surpassing the level where it stood just before the October 1987
crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.04 to 2,246.79 by
noon on Wall Street.
   On Oct. 16, 1987 the last session before the crash, the
closely-watched index closed at 2,246.74.
   Gainers outnumbered losers today in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 770 up, 522 down and 555
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 96.69 million shares at midday.
   The Labor Department reported that the consumer price index rose
0.3 percent in December, bringing the increase in the index for all
of 1988 to 4.4 percent.
   The latest monthly figure was a bit lower than most advance
estimates by financial economists, and thus helped contribute to a
generally upbeat mood in the market.
   However, brokers say the market's recent strength has not seemed
to derive from current economic news, but rather from a gradual
easing of the fears that have persisted ever since the crash.
   As stock prices have risen lately, they have attracted fresh
buying from investing institutions and other market participants who
began to worry that their caution might cause them to miss a
significant rally.
   ``There's a better feeling from the market itself,'' said Michael
Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Metz said the continued strength in the dollar also boosted stock
prices. When the dollar is higher, traders believe the Federal
Reserve is less likely to tighten credit.
   A stronger dollar also makes U.S. investments more attractive to
foreigners.
   Leading the NYSE's most active list was Lyondell Petrolem, which
was unchanged at 30].
   Digital Equipment surged 5[ to 104} after the company reported
quarterly earnings that exceeded analysts' estimates.
   Polaroid climbed 3[ to 39~. Shamrock Acquisition III Inc. raised
its offer for the company from $42 a share to $45 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.57 to 161.58. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .68 at 318.90.
