<FIRST>u f PM-Newton-NBC 1stLd-Writethru f0121 01-19 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newton-NBC, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0121,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wayne Newton Accepts Libel Award of $6 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with background, further quotes, details;
ADDS byline. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Wayne Newton said today he will
accept a $6 million libel award in his long-running lawsuit against
NBC, saying he feels vindicated from a nearly 9-year-old report that
linked him to the Mafia.
   ``This was not a matter of money,'' Newton told reporters at a
morning news conference. ``This was a matter of vindication of my
name.''
   Newton's attorney, Morton Galane, said the interest accrued on
the reduced $5.3 million award now equals $6 million.
   ``Such an award would be higher than any (libel) award ever
affirmed by an appellate court in the United States,'' he said.
   The case does not yet appear to be over, however. NBC attorneys
had indicated earlier they would appeal the award to higher federal
courts.
   Newton said that as far as he was concerned the case was over for
him personally. He said that if NBC appeals he will leave the matter
to his attorneys.
   Galane told reporters that one factor in Newton's decision to
accept the award was a survey of public attitudes toward Newton's
acceptance of such a high award.
   ``Three weeks ago that survey confirmed that the public believes
that the reporting of a high libel award in favor of Mr. Newton
would be perceived by others as restoration of a positive public
image,'' Galane said.
   In late December U.S. District Judge Myron Crocker gave Newton
until Feb. 1 to accept the award, which had been reduced from $22.8
million, or face the prospect of proving his case against NBC in a
new trial.
   Newton won the original amount against the network when a jury
ruled the singer was defamed in a series of broadcasts that linked
him to organized crime figures.
   Crocker later threw out all but $5.3 million of the award and
gave Newton the option of accepting the money or seeking a new trial
strictly on damages.
   The Newton-NBC case stems from an Oct. 6, 1980, broadcast titled
``Wayne Newton and the Law.''
   NBC correspondent Brian Ross reported that Newton had gone to
organized crime figure Guido Penosi for help after his
then-3-year-old daughter's life had been threatened.
   Newton argued the report left the impression that his October
1980 purchase of the Aladdin Hotel in Las Vegas was linked to
organized crime. The hotel has since been sold and is currently
owned by a Japanese businessman.
   Asked today if he would again ask for Penosi's help, Newton said,
``I would go to the devil himself to save my daughter's life.''
   Newton emphasized that his lawsuit was not meant to suppress
reporting of the news.
   ``All I hope is that responsible journalists will think before
they do to someone what they did to me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
