<HEAD>Chrysler, Chevy Expand Incentive War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. and General Motors Corp. expanded
low-interest incentives Thursday by offering financing as low as 4.9
percent on some of their small cars and light trucks.
   Ford Motor Co. started the latest wave of low-interest incentives
last week by offering 4.9 percent interest on some of its small cars.
   Each of the Big Three plans provide for options of cash rebates
or interest rates ranging from 4.9 percent for a two-year loan to
9.9 percent for a five-year loan.
   On Thursday, GM and Chrysler announced financing plans for some
small Chevrolet, Dodge, Eagle and Plymouth cars, Jeeps and pickup
trucks.
   The two companies also announced expanded cash-back programs for
a variety of cars and trucks.
   The Chrysler incentives run indefinitely and the GM plan runs
until March 6.
