<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     01-19 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0411</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was narrowly mixed today after
temporarily surpassing the level where it stood just before the
October 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was unchanged at 2,238.75
at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Earlier in the session, the widely followed index was up more
than 10 points and moved past 2,246.74, where it closed on Oct. 16,
1987, the last trading day before the crash.
   Profit-taking in blue chip issues eroded today's gains in the
average. But advancing issues outnumbered losers by a margin of
about 4-to-3 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
issues, with 790 up, 631 down and 512 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 142.90 million shares at
mid-afternoon.
   The Labor Department reported that the consumer price index rose
0.3 percent in December, bringing the increase in the index for all
of 1988 to 4.4 percent.
   The latest monthly figure was a bit lower than most advance
estimates by financial economists, and thus helped contribute to a
generally upbeat mood in the market.
   However, brokers say the market's recent strength has not seemed
to derive from current economic news, but rather from a gradual
easing of the fears that have persisted ever since the crash.
   As stock prices have risen lately, they have attracted fresh
buying from investing institutions and other market participants who
began to worry that their caution might cause them to miss a
significant rally.
   ``There's a better feeling from the market itself,'' said Michael
Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co. He noted that on Wednesday,
despite a disappointing trade deficit report, the Dow Jones average
gained more than 24 points.
   Leading the NYSE's most active list was Lyondell Petroleum, a
spin-off of Atlantic Richfield Corp. that was quoted at 30\ in its
first day on the Big Board.
   Digital Equipment surged 4} to 104] after the company reported
quarterly earnings that exceeded analysts' estimates.
   Polaroid climbed 3 to 39}. Shamrock Acquisition III Inc. raised
its offer for the company from $42 a share to $45 a share.
   Caterpillar fell 4} to 63 after reporting a fourth-quarter
earnings decline.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.21 to 161.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .48 at 318.70.
</TEXT>
