<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell     01-19 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farley Again Extends Pepperell Offer, Challenges Another Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. extended its $1.4 billion hostile
tender offer for West Point-Pepperell Inc. on Thursday and asked a
federal judge to invalidate another of the textile company's
takeover defenses.
   It was the eighth extension in Farley's tender offer, which is
$48 per share. The deadline, which has been bumped back a week to
two weeks at a time since it was first set for Nov. 21, now is set
for midnight Jan. 25.
   In a motion filed in U.S. District Court, the Chicago-based
conglomerate, which controls Fruit of the Loom Inc. and Acme Boot
Co., asked Judge G. Ernest Tidwell to invalidate Pepperell's
so-called ``flip-over'' provisions that would allow its shareholders
to buy shares at a discount in an uninvited suitor.
   Most analysts, however, view the legal wrangling as delaying
tactics, giving Pepperell management time to put together their own
response.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pepperell was up 37{
cents a share at $45.62{ at midafternoon.
   In extending the tender offer, Farley said it currently has
received tender offers for about 14 million shares, which together
with the 2.9 million shares Farley already owns account for about 57
percent of Pepperell's outstanding shares.
   The amount of shares tendered has varied little since late
December, but Farley officials said that is to be expected.
   Farley's offer for the West Point, Ga.-based company is
contingent on being tendered, or owning outright, two-thirds of
Pepperell's outstanding shares, as well as overturning the textile
company's takeover defenses and voiding Georgia's anti-takeover law.
   The motion filed with Tidwell on Thursday was placed under seal,
as has much of the evidence in previous court challenges of the
takeover.
   But Farley said in a statement that the ``flip-over'' provision
``has no legitimate business purpose and harms West Point's
shareholders.''
   Even though Farley is not publicly traded, the ``flip-over''
would allow Pepperell shareholders to purchase Farley shares at a
discount, effectively reducing William Farley's control of his own
company.
   Tidwell previously has voided Pepperell's ``flip-in'' provisions,
which give shareholders the right to purchase more Pepperell stock
at a deep discount.
   That ruling has been appealed to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, where a decision is pending.
   Tidwell also is considering Farley's claim that the state's 1988
anti-takeover law is unconstitutional. A court-appointed expert told
Tidwell last week that he believed the conditions set on mergers
were too restrictive and therefore improperly restrained trade.
   A ruling had been expected last week, but there currently is no
indication of when one will come.
   Farley also has succeeded in calling a special shareholders
meeting for Feb. 25, where his company will seek to oust current
Pepperell directors, replacing them with its own slate which then
would toss out the takeover defenses.
   Pepperell is the nation's largest publicly traded textile
company, with products including Martex towels and sheets and Arrow
shirts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
