<FIRST>u f BC-DollarGold     01-19 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar Gold,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Varies In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
in busy European trading on Thursday. Gold prices were higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said nine central banks, including the
U.S. Federal Reserve, intervened to halt the dollar's rise in the
morning with mixed results.
   Dealers said that as the dollar surge continued, the Fed and
government banking authorities from three other countries entered
the market a second time with more success. But by the end of the
day the dollar had resumed rising.
   The dealers said central bankers clearly did not want to see the
dollar as high as it was Wednesday, when it surged despite the
announced higher-than-expected U.S. trade deficit.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7615 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's $1.7550.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates were: 1.8672 West German marks, down from
1.8705; 1.5805 Swiss francs, down from 1.5890; 6.3315 French francs,
down from 6.3800; -2.1060 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0925; 1,368.50
Italian lire, up from 1,356.75; and, 1.1890 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1937.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.20 Japanese yen, up
from 127.90 yen. Late Thursday, in London, the dollar traded lower
at 128.75 yen.
   Gold bullion prices were modestly higher in light dealings as the
dollar's fluctuations commanded the attention.
   In London, gold closed at $402.50 bid a troy ounce, up from
$402.25. The Zurich closing bid was $403.40, up from $402.40.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at a bid $403.83, down from
$404.64.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.97 bid a troy ounce,
up from $5.94.
</TEXT>
