<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TexasEastern     01-19 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Texas Eastern,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Posts $40.3 Million Fourt Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp., the subject of a hostile
takeover bid launched this week by Coastal Corp., said Thursday its
fourth-quarter profit rose 28.3 percent while its earnings for all
of 1988 increased by 58 percent from 1987.
   The gas pipeline company attributed the yearly gains to the net
positive impact of $90 million from nonrecuring transactions and
other items.
   For the three-month period ended Dec. 31, Texas Eastern said its
after-tax profit totaled $40.3 million, or 75 cents a share, up from
$31.4 million, or 59 cents a share, in the same 1987 period.
   The Houston-based company said its fourth-quarter earnings
reflected non-recurring gains and charges with a net positive impact
of about $8 million, or 15 cents per share, compared with about $7
million, or 13 cents per share, in the 1987 period.
   Operating revenue for the fourth quarter totaled $985.6 million
in 1988 and $924.1 million in 1987.
   For all of 1988, Texas Eastern posted earnings of $151.9 million,
or $2.85 per share, compared with $96.1 million, or $1.80 per share,
in 1987.
   Texas Eastern's operating income for 1988 was nearly $3.5
billion, compared with $3.6 billion the previous year.
   Executives from Texas Eastern and Houston-based Coastal plan to
meet this weekend for the first time since Coastal announced a $2.6
billion offer for all outstanding shares of Texas Eastern stock.
   Coastal said its tender offer for Texas Eastern had commenced
Tuesday at $42 per share and that the offer would expire Feb. 13,
unless it is extended. If the buyout is successful, the
Coastal-Texas Eastern pipelines would be the nation's largest in the
volume of gas transported.
</TEXT>
