<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     01-19 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Interest Payments Continue To Boost Some Bank Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp. and three other big banking companies on
Thursday reported profits for the last quarter of 1988 and the full
year, with some reaping the benefits of Brazil's payment of back
interest.
   The banking concerns, which also included Bankers Trust New York
Corp., Bank of Boston Corp. and Bank of New York Co., said they
benefited from the overall improvement in the Third World debt
crisis, which had peaked in 1987.
   Meanwhile, two large savings and loan holding companies, Great
Western Bank of Beverly Hills, Calif., and Glenfed Inc. of Glendale,
Calif., also reported mostly higher earnings in their latest reports.
   BankAmerica, based in San Francisco, said net income for the
three months ended Dec. 31 totaled $265 million, or $1.36 per share,
more than four times as high as earnings of $60 million, or 27 cents
a share, a year earlier.
   The company said the latest results included $351 million in cash
interest payments from Brazil, which just a year ago had declared a
temporary moratorium on commercial bank interest payments.
   For the year, BankAmerica netted $726 million, or $3.79 per
share, in contrast with a a loss of $955 million for 1987. The
previous year's results reflected a second-quarter $1.1 billion
addition to its loan-loss reserves to cover shaky Third World loans.
   New-York based Bankers Trust said its fourth-quarter income
totaled $185.5 million, or $2.29 a share, compared with a record
$284.5 million, or $3.70 a share, in the previous year. The company
blamed the decline partly on lower trading volume.
   But Bankers Trust said its 1988 income reached a record $647.7
million, or $8.09 a share. That compared with earnings of $1.2
million, or 2 cents a share, in 1987, when the company added $636
million to its loan-loss reserves.
   It said it received about $95 million in Brazilian interest
payments in the fourth quarter.
   Bank of Boston said it earned $83 million, or $1.18 a share, in
the fourth quarter, in contrast with a $41 million loss in the
previous year, when it added $200 million to its loan-loss provision.
   For the year, the Boston-based company netted a record $322
million, or $4.66 a share, compared with 1987 earnings of $20
million, or 10 cents a share.
   Bank of New York said it earned $54.7 million in the fourth
quarter, a 19 percent increase over the $45.9 million earned in
1987. But earnings per share declined 11 percent on a fully diluted
basis last year, to $1.10 from $1.24.
   The New York company said the securities issued in the acquisiton
of Irving Bank Corp. at the end of last year had diluted per-share
earnings.
   For the year, net income was a record $213.0 million, or $5.21 a
share, compared with $103.4 million, or $2.81, in 1987.
   Great Western said its fourth-quarter profit was $59.7 million,
or 47 cents a share, up from $13.7 million, or 11 cents a share a
year earlier. Annual income totaled $248 million, or $1.95 a share,
up 17 percent from $212 million, or $1.66 a share, in 1987.
   Glenfed said that in the second fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31 it
earnings before extraordinary items totaled $35.16 million, or $1.19
a share, vs. $32.56 million, or $1.11 per share, the year before.
But for the six months, it's net income dropped to $66.60 million,
or $2.27 a share, from $67.20 million, or $2.29, a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
