<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-StockExchange-Snowball Bjt   01-19 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stock Exchange-Snowball, Bjt,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snowball Throwing (A</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign currency traders who want to make a
mark on the market can make one first with a snowball Friday when
the Philadelphia Stock Exchange opens expanded early morning trading
hours.
   The exchange is introducing a 4:30 a.m. starting time _ 3{ hours
earlier than its current opening time _ to let currency trading
coincide with morning hours in Europe. A half-hour before the
opening, the exchange is hosting a snowball throwing contest
officials expect could become a snowball fight.
   ``Maybe if we throw a snowball in somebody's face they'll
listen,'' exchange president Nicholas Giordano said Thursday.
   ``Sometimes you've got to do something corny to get people's
attention to listen to the substance.''
   The new hours will be 4:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. and 6 p.m. to 10
p.m., the latter period begun in September 1987 to cover the
Japanese morning hours.
   Giordano said he couldn't estimate what kind of volume to expect
with the new hours, but said there is demand for the change.
   ``In our visits to our members and customers in Europe, they have
been requesting these hours for some time now,'' Giordano said,
adding they have had ``to to sit around to 1 p.m.'' local time
waiting for the 8 a.m. opening of the Philadelphia exchange.
   ``Whether some of that business will move from the afternoon to
the morning and how much will be new business remains to be seen,''
he said.
   David Cohen, vice president of Tague Securities, the exchange's
designated specialist firm in the German mark and the Japanese yen,
said the new trading hours will mean less sleep for him but more
convenience for the Europeans.
   As for the snowball throwing, Cohen expects to be at the exchange
by 4 a.m., getting ready for the trading day.
   ``Hopefully I won't get hit in the head,'' he said.
   Lacking snow in a mild winter, officials are trucking it in, and
lacking sunlight at 4 a.m., they're setting up flood lights. Jack
Frost Mountain Ski Area of Lake Harmony, Pa., is bringing in 42
cubic yards of snow, officials said.
   Snowball throwers will have five official targets _ symbols of
some of the eight foreign currencies traded at the exchange _ but
others may develop.
   ``The temptation of having a snowball in your hand and throwing
it at someone is almost too great to resist,'' Giordano said.
   So, does the stock exchange president have a target or two in
mind?
   ``I do, but I'm not going to disclose them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
