<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Paper     01-19 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Paper,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Champion, Bowater Report Increased Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A healthy market for paper and paper products in 1988 helped
boost Champion International Corp.'s annual profit 19 percent, while
Bowater Inc.'s net income more than doubled last year, the companies
reported Thursday.
   Champion, based in Stamford, Conn., reported its 1988 after-tax
profit rose to $456.4 million, or $4.65 a share, from $382 million,
or $3.92 a share, in 1987. The company's revenue totaled $5.1
billion, up 11 percent from $4.6 billion in 1987.
   For the fourth quarter ended Dec. 31, the wood and paper products
company had reported net income of $119.89 million, or $1.22 a
share, up 46 percent from $82 million, or 85 cents a share, in the
same 1987 quarter.
   ``It's been very, very good,'' said Andrew C. Sigler, Champion
chairman. ``Markets for the grades of paper we produce were as
strong as we've ever seen.''
   Bowater, the largest U.S. newsprint manufacturer based in Darien,
Conn., said its fourth-quarter profit rose 54 percent to $45.5
million, or $1.22 a share, from 29.6 million, or 77 cents a share,
in the same 1987 period.
   The company's revenue rose to $367.3 million to $349.2 million,
an increase of 5 percent.
   For all of 1988, Bowater's profit soared a record 102 percent to
$164.3 million, or $4.37 a share, from $81.1 million, or $2.12 a
share, in 1987, the company reported. Sales for the year totaled
$1.4 billion, up 14.6 percent from $1.2 billion in 1987.
   ``With stable operating costs, strong pricing for our pulp and
paper grades, and a favorable dollar exchange rate to support our
export trade, all our plans made since we became public in 1984 bore
fruit,'' said Anthony P. Gammie, Bowater's chairman and chief
operating officer.
</TEXT>
