<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-19 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Closes Higher On Weather; Corns, Beans Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed moderately higher Thursday on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid mounting concern about dry weather
in winter wheat growing areas, while corn and soybean prices
finished mostly lower.
   Analysts said the rally in the wheat market was fanned by
Wednesday's 6-to-10-day weather outlook from the National Weather
Service, which predicted continued drier-than-normal conditions from
Texas to Nebraska.
   ``I think we'll continue to extend upward until some
precipitation is perceived there,'' said Richard Feltes, director of
commodity research with Refco Inc., a large Chicago-based futures
brokerage firm.
   Last week's Agriculture Department crop report, which indicated
winter wheat growers had planted fewer acres than analysts had
expected, has given the market a firm layer of support, he said.
   Liquidation of soybean and corn futures resumed Thursday
following a one-day pause in the sell-off sparked by the USDA's
report of larger-than-expected supplies of those commodities.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.42} a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 3{ cents lower with March at $2.68 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
3} cents lower with March at $2.34 a bushel; soybeans were 10 cents
lower to 4\ cents higher with January at $7.53 a bushel.
</TEXT>
