<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CorporateFinancing     01-19 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corporate Financing,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Advises Caution in Dealing with Corporate Takeovers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee said Thursday that lawmakers will have to consider how the
economy would be affected if they try to crack down on corporate
takeovers.
   ``I think there's an appetite here on the (Capitol) Hill to do
something,'' the chairman, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., told
reporters. The big question, he added, ``is whether we can write a
law without causing a downturn in the economy.''
   As he has in the past, Rostenkowski indicated he thinks Congress
will act to reverse a recent trend that has seen a sharp increase in
borrowing to finance corporate takeovers and other acquisitions,
including the use of leveraged buyouts. However, he declined to
predict whether any law will be changed.
   ``Something really should be done, particularly when we are
seeing the junk-bond abuse,'' he said, referring to high-risk,
high-yield bonds that are often used to finance takoevers.
   Rostenkowski added he is ``concerned with the fact we shouldn't
have a meat axe when we are engaged in writing law, if we are going
to write law.''
   At Rostenkowski's insistence, the House in 1987 approved some
limitations on tax benefits associated with corporate borrowing. But
some analysts cited that action as one reason for the October stock
market crash, and the proposals were dropped.
   ``Some of the people who criticized us when we wrote that
amendment are now suggesting there's a need for it,'' Rostenkowski
said.
   The Senate Finance Committee and the Ways and Means Committee
have scheduled public hearings this month and next on takeovers and
the broad subject of corporate financing in general.
   Rostenkowski noted several other House committees are planning
their own investigations. But he emphasized that his panel and the
Senate Finance Committee, which control the tax law, should have the
major role.
   ``You get their attention when you tickle the tax code,'' he
said. The key question involved in the issue is how the law treats
the deductibility of interest used to finance takoevers,
Rostenkowski said.
   Economists say a major reason for the growing shift toward
corporate debt and away from stocks is the fact a corporation can
deduct interest on debt but not dividends on stock.
</TEXT>
