<DOCNO> AP890119-0336 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TropicalOils     01-19 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Oils,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Crusader Says His Campaign Against Tropical Oils Will Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A health advocate whose campaign helped prompt
nine major food processors to start removing highly saturated
vegetable oils from their products vowed Thursday to continue his
crusade until all such fats are eliminated.
   ``The battle is far from won. There are hundreds of products out
there with highly saturated coconut and palm oil,'' said Phil
Sokolof.
   Sokolof, a multimillionaire Omaha businessman, announced Monday
that five major food processors joined four others that earlier said
they would work toward eliminating the ``tropical'' oils from their
products.
   ``Our victory was getting nine food giants to switch to the good
vegetable oils, and hopefully the entire industry will follow,'' he
said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   But some food processors say switching to other fats is not as
simple as just changing ingredients. They say tropical oils impart a
certain taste and texture to some foods, such as cookies.
   Among products containing coconut and palm oils are crackers,
cookies, candies, cereals, cooking ingredients, desserts, frozen
foods, canned goods and TV dinners.
   Ron Wirtz, the librarian of the American Institute of Baking in
Manhattan, Kan., said tropical oils have other desirable properties,
such as a resistence to spoilage and lower cost than certain other
vegetable oils. In addition, he said, they are superior for use in
frostings and coatings because they are stable at room temperature.
   Wirtz said the use of tropical oils in food products wasn't
common until the late 1960s. Many made the switch because the oils
were cheaper than alternative fats.
   Sokolof said he has spent $2 million of his own money on his
cholesterol-awareness campaign. In November he placed full-page ads
in five newspapers warning of the dangers of tropical oils and
listing brand names of products that contain them.
   ``Most people know that meat, dairy products, McDonald's
hamburgers are high in saturated fat. They did not know that coconut
and palm oil are,'' he said.
   Saturated fats can increase blood cholesterol levels; high
cholesterol is a risk factor for heart attacks. Sokolof, 66, blames
high cholesterol for the near-fatal heart attack he suffered 22
years ago.
   Sokolof said he will place additional newspaper ads, but they may
be broadened to include warnings about the health risks of eating
certain dairy products and meats. He also said he will point out the
use of lard and beef tallow in certain processed foods.
   ``The most important statistic the public should know is that for
every 1 percent the cholesterol level is lowered, the chance of
having a heart attack is reduced 2 percent,'' he said.
   Most of the companies that said they would phase out the use of
tropical oils said they were responding to consumer and health
concerns, not pressure from Sokolof.
   Sokolof said he believes his campaign was part of the companies'
decision-making process, but agreed the public will be the ultimate
reason food processors switch oils.
   ``If the public reads ingredient labels and does not buy the
highly saturated fat foods, companies will get the message and
respond,'' he said.
   Sokolof established his non-profit advocacy group, the National
Heart Savers Association, in 1975.
   The nine companies that said they would eliminate tropical oils
are: General Mills Inc., Ralston Purina Co., Borden Inc., Pillsbury
Co., Quaker Oats Co., Kellogg Co., Sunshine Biscuits Inc., Campbell
Soup Co.'s Pepperidge Farm division and Keebler Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
