<DOCNO> AP890119-0338 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Health     01-19 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Health,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pfizer, Bristol-Myers Post Higher Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pfizer Inc. said Thursday that strong sales in consumer and
health care products helped boost its profit to an all-time high of
$791.3 million last year, while Bristol-Myers said its profit
margins rose for the 16th consecutive year.
   For all of 1988, Pfizer's per-share profit totaled $4.70 a share,
up 15 percent from $690.2 million, or $4.08 a sare in 1987. Its
revenue rose 9 percent to $5.4 billion, from $4.92 billion in 1987.
   Pfizer's fourth-quarter net income was up 4 percent to $141.6
million, or 84 cents a share, from $136.6 million, or 82 cents a
share, in the year-earlier quarter. The company's sales during the
quarter rose 7 percent to $1.4 billion, from $1.3 billion in 1987.
   Pfizer, whose largest-selling drug is the arthritis medicine
Feldene, said sales in its consumer segment rose 54 percent and in
its health care segment, 8 percent.
   Pfizer Chairman Edmund T. Pratt Jr. said the company continued to
invest heavily in research and development and began increasing its
U.S. sales force in preparation for the introduction of a range of
new drugs.
   ``The roll-out of these new products worldwide is starting to be
reflected in Pfizer's sales,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Bristol-Myers reported that for the fourth quarter
ended Dec. 31, its profit rose 12.4 percent to $195.6 million, or 68
cents a share, on sales of $1.5 billion. In the same 1987 period,
its net income was $174.1 million, or 61 cents a share, on sales of
$1.4 billion.
   For the year, Bristol-Myers' profit rose 16.8 percent to $829
million, or $2.88 a share, compared with $709.6 million, or $2.47 a
share. Its revenue for the year totaled $5.97 billion, up 10.6
percent from $5.4 billion in 1987, the company said.
   Richard L. Gelb, chairman of Bristol-Myers, said the company's
profit margins improved for the 16th straight year, due in part to
strong international sales, which rose 21 percent. Gelb said
exchange rate fluctuations contributed to the company's gains.
</TEXT>
