<FIRST>r f AM-CoorsLabel     01-19 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coors Label,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citing Customer Confusion, Coors Drops `Original Draft' From Label</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co. on Thursday dropped the
7-month-old ``Original Draft'' label from its flagship beer, saying
too many customers thought the label change also signaled a taste
change.
   Last July, Coors replaced its longtime ``Banquet Beer'' tag with
the words ``Original Draft'' as part of an effort to update its
packaging, but the move backfired.
   ``People believed we changed the beer,'' said Mike Marranzino,
brand director for the brewery based in Golden, west of Denver. ``It
looked like a new brand name to them. But we didn't change the
beer.''
   New labels on cans and bottles that will reach store shelves in
three weeks simply will say ``Coors,'' Marranzino said.
   He said design changes made to the cans and packaging when the
Original Draft name was added will be retained because beer drinkers
like the ``contemporary look.''
   The Coors experience in some ways recalls Coca-Cola Co.'s
experiment in April 1985, when it replaced its original cola flavor
with a new one. The ensuing customer protest forced Coca-Cola to
bring back the old formula three months later, renaming it Coca-Cola
Classic.
   Marranzino said the Original Draft label was prompted by Miller
Brewing Co.'s successful advertising campaign promoting its bottled
draft beer. Coors wanted to tell customers it had been making
bottled draft beer for 30 years, he said.
   The other changes included toning down the can color from yellow
to buff, adding stripes to the can bottom and replacing the old
red-and-white packaging with an updated red-white-and-blue diagonal
design.
   Coors spokesman Doyle Albee said the label change had no
discernible effect on earnings, which reached record levels in 1988.
``We are simply responding to requests from customers,'' Albee said.
   Added Marrazino, ``The use of Original Draft has not performed
well for us, and it has created enough confusion that we will simply
remove the phrase, keeping the new graphics look.''
   Early signs of customer dissatisfaction surfaced last fall among
Coors loyalists in El Paso, Texas, and Southern California. Sales
fell in some liquor stores and taverns as cans and bottles bearing
the new label replaced the old Banquet Beer labels.
   Last month, Coors announced it would reintroduce the Banquet Beer
label in those two markets in an attempt to appease disgruntled
customers.
   Marranzino said beer with the Banquet Beer label will continue to
be shipped to El Paso and Southern California ``as long as they want
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
