<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Computers     01-19 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computers,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Digital Earnings Fall 15.1 Percent; Microsoft Rises 34.4 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp., the world's second-biggest computer
maker, said Thursday its earnings fell 15.1 percent in the latest
fiscal quarter, but the results were better than analysts expected.
   Meanwhile, Microsoft Corp., the biggest personal computer
software company, said earnings jumped 34.4 percent in the latest
quarter.
   Digital stock rose $5.25 a share to $104.87{ in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading. Microsoft rose $2 a share to $53.50 in
over-the-counter trading.
   Digital, of Maynard, Mass., said earnings fell 15.1 percent to
$279.6 million, or $2.20 a share, in its second fiscal quarter from
$329.5 million, or $2.48 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 14
percent to $3.18 billion from $2.78 billion.
   Despite the earnings decline, Digital reported stronger demand,
lower expenses and wider profit margins than analysts had expected,
said Marc Schulman of UBS Securities, the investment banking arm of
Union Bank of Switzerland.
   Tighter controls on costs will help earnings if the computer
business turns sluggish in 1989, Schulman said.
   ``Digital is beginning to see improvements in its cost trends.
One example of this cost containment is the fact that Digital's
hiring pace has slowed,'' the company said in a statement.
   Employment rose 1,250 in the quarter to 124,400, the company said.
   Digital's announcement came one day after International Business
Machines Corp., its bigger rival, reported a 12.4 percent quarterly
earnings gain.
   For the first half of its fiscal year, Digital said its earnings
fell 16.1 percent to $503 million, or $3.90 a share, from $599.5
million, or $4.50 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 15 percent
to $6.12 billion from $5.31 billion.
   Microsoft, of Redmond, Wash., said its earnings rose to $47.5
million, or 85 cents a share, in its second fiscal quarter, from
$35.3 million, or 63 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 35
percent to $209.9 million from $155.9 million a year earlier.
   For the first half of its fiscal year, Microsoft said its
earnings rose 49 percent to $84.1 million, or $1.50 a share, from
$56.6 million, or $1.02 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 49
percent to $386.3 million from $258.5 million.
   Microsoft said international revenue, accounting for 57 percent
of its business, was particularly strong. It was the company's 13th
consecutive quarter of record revenue.
</TEXT>
