<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-19 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central banks slammed the dollar lower Thursday,
cooling a rally that had brought the U.S. currency to its highest
levels since early October.
   Gold bullion prices were modestly higher in light dealings.
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $403.60 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $401.75 late Wednesday.
   Foreign exchange dealers said one round of dollar-selling by nine
central banks was unsuccessful, but a second round drove the dollar
lower against most currencies.
   Dollar sales were accompanied by West Germany's central bank
raising two key interest rates, a step intended to make yields on
German securities more attractive and keep investors from switching
from marks to dollars.
   The dollar had gotten as high as 129.8 Japanese yen and 1.88
marks before the successful attack by the central banks at
midmorning in New York.
   On Wednesday, the dollar had risen strongly despite two negative
reports: a bigger-than-expected U.S. trade deficit and a record
Japanese trade surplus.
   The dollar was due for a pullback, at least a temporary one, said
Frank Conte, vice president for foreign exchange at Barclays Bank in
New York.
   ``It just can't continue at this momentum. Since January we've
had a one-way direction, up,'' he said.
   William N. Griggs, managing director of Griggs &amp; Santow Inc.,
said he believed the dollar had gotten too cheap and the current
rise ``looks more like a return to reality or a correction.''
   But Griggs said, ``There's no way to prove what the appropriate
level ought to be.''
   The markets showed little reaction to government reports that
consumer prices rose 0.3 percent and housing construction fell 2.2
percent in December.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.20 Japanese yen, up from
127.90 yen. Late Thursday, in London, the dollar traded lower at
128.75 yen. In New York, the dollar edged up to 128.66 yen from
128.65 yen.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7615 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's $1.7550. Later in New York,
the pound rose to $1.7650 from $1.7535.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, were: 1.8548, down from 1.8721; 1.5775 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5916; 1.1873 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1907; 6.3225
French francs, down from 6.3825; and 1,359.4 Italian lire, down from
1,370.4.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates were: 1.8672 West German marks, down from
1.8705; 1.5805 Swiss francs, down from 1.5890; 6.3315 French francs,
down from 6.3800; 2.1060 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0925; 1,368.50
Italian lire, up from 1,356.75; and 1.1890 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1937.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose rose to $403.60 a troy ounce from $402.30 Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $403.83, down from $404.64. In
London, gold closed at $402.50 bid a troy ounce, up from $402.25.
The Zurich closing bid was $403.40 an ounce, up from $402.40.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.97 bid a troy ounce,
up from $5.94. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $5.976 an ounce from $5.905 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
