<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Kidder-GE Bjt   01-19 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidder-GE, Bjt,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Unveils Changes At The Top At Kidder, Peabody</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. on Thursday announced a
management shuffle at its Kidder, Peabody Group, the venerable Wall
Street investment house that has provided its share of problems
since GE took control in 1986.
   Installation of new leadership at Kidder reflects the corporate
parent's desire to exert greater control over Kidder's day-to-day
operations, as well as GE's latest attempt to deal with difficulties
posed by the firm, analysts said.
   GE Capital, the company's financial services division stated that
Michael A. Carpenter, an executive vice president of GE Capital, has
been named president and chief executive officer of Kidder, Peabody
Group.
   Silas S. Cathcart, a former GE director brought in as an interim
chief executive in 1987, will stay on as chairman of Kidder.
   Max C. Chapman Jr., a longtime Kidder employee who had been
running the group from his position as president of Kidder, Peabody
&amp; Co., the broker-dealer unit, resigned to pursue other interests,
the statement said.
   While at GE Capital, Carpenter built a reputation as a savvy
manager able to work well within GE's corporate structure.
   Commenting on his appointment, Gary C. Wendt, president of GE
Financial Services, said: ``Mike Carpenter, a creative and talented
thinker himself, has substantial experience in leading the type of
creative and talented people who make up the Kidder organization.''
   Carpenter also will retain responsibility for the corporate
finance group of GE Capital, which specializes in developing
financing packages for leveraged buy-outs. He will continue
reporting to Wendt.
   Once the oldest privately-held firm on Wall Street, Kidder sold
an 80 percent stake in itself to GE in April 1986, boosting Kidder's
capital base and enabling it to compete more effectively with larger
rivals.
   The 124-year-old firm suffered a major blow to its reputation
when it became embroiled in the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal.
Kidder agreed in 1987 to pay a then-record $25.3 million settle
civil charges with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The episode also prompted GE to make aggressive management
changes at the firm in response to what it perceived as management
weaknesses to led to Kidder's involvement in the scandal.
   The management shakeups at Kidder are seen by many as
highlighting the problems that can occur when smokestack companies
try to bring new types of business into their corporate fold, as has
happened frequently this decade.
   GE management generally has gotten excellent marks for the
handling of its expansion into financial services. But analysts say
some clashes are inevitable even in the most carefully handled
situations.
   While Wall Streeters pride themselves on an entreprenuerial
spirit, they often are criticized for following a strategy that
focuses on short-term rewards at the expense of long-term planning.
   ``It's tough for industrial companies to own Wall Street
financial firms. They drive the creative people out. Creative people
feel limited, suffocated,'' said one analyst, who asked not to be
named. ``It's not like running an insurance company or a bank.''
   Earlier this week, two senior members of Kidder's merchant
banking group announced they were leaving the firm.
   But in response to recent reports indicating GE may be sorry it
bought Kidder, Lawrence A. Bossidy, vice chairman of GE Financial
Services, stated GE was not disappointed with Kidder's 1988 results.
He said Kidder's operating net income came to nearly $50 million in
1988, up about 20 percent over 1987.
   On Thursday, GE reported its net income rose to $1.01 billion in
the fourth quarter, the first time quarterly earnings have exceeded
$1 billion. For all of 1988, GE earned $3.39 billion after taxes, up
16 percent from $2.92 bllion in 1987. The earnings benefited from a
strong showing by GE Financial Services, the largest single GE
business.
   Bossidy also emphatically denied reports that disenchantment with
the profitability of the securities business could induce GE to sell
off Kidder's retail business, which could lead to the dismissal of
2,000 employees.
   Kidder underwent a major restructuring beginning in the wake of
the October 1987 stock market crash _ as did most major Wall Streete
firms _ to consolidate and reduce costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
