<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     01-19 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Fall In Latest Week</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ The two broadest measures of the nation's money supply
declined in the week ended Jan. 9, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 fell $7.1 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,063.2 billion from a revised $3,070.3 billion
the previous week. The prior week's figure was originally reported
as $3,068.7 billion.
   An even broader measure, M3, decreased $3.9 billion to an
adjusted $3,903.6 billion from $3,907.5, revised from $3,905.0
billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, also declined,
falling $7.7 billion in the latest week to an adjusted $785.4
billion from $793.1 billion. M1 includes cash in circulation,
deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is
M1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money- market mutual
funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of
deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   In other reports:
   -The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $387 million in
the week ended Jan. 11, compared with a gain of $663 million a week
earlier.
   -The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $544 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, up $235
million from $309 million a week before.
   -The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $288.5 billion in the two-week period ended Jan. 11, up from
$285.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
