<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-19 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0839</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures Surge On Technical Factors, Botha Stroke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices surged Thursday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in a technically inspired rally fanned by
concerns about the health of South African President P.W. Botha.
   On other markets, gold and silver futures also gained; orange
juice futures fell sharply; grains and soybeans were broadly mixed;
energy futures were mostly lower; livestock and meat were mixed and
stock-index futures advanced.
   Platinum settled $8.40 a troy ounce to $9.10 an ounce higher with
the contract for delivery in April at $535.70. Platinum for spot
delivery finished at $534.20, a high for the new year.
   Analysts said the buying was triggered mainly by the April
contract's rise above $532.30 an ounce, the highest closing price of
the previous three weeks.
   Platinum prices had been on a gradual upswing for the past week,
but that action was seen primarily as a reaction to recent strong
gains in the palladium market. Palladium is a ``platinum group''
metal _ it shares some characteristics with platinum and is often
found near platinum deposits in nature.
   Platinum managed to ride on palladium's coattails through $532.30
an ounce, at which point it became much more attractive to
speculators, analysts said.
   ``The strength in palladium has spilled over to platinum and now
platinum could become a favorite based on the technicals,'' said
Craig Sloane, a metals-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   Peter Cardillo, commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co.,
a New York-based brokerage house, said the April contract could rise
as high as $550 an ounce before finding strong resistance.
   ``Technically, the market looks quite strong here,'' he said.
   Cardillo said the platinum rally also reflected fears of
potential supply disruptions from South Africa, the world's largest
platinum producer. Those concerns were sparked by reports that
Botha, leader of the racially divided nation for the last 10 years,
had suffered a mild stroke on Wednesday.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $1.20 to $1.30
higher with February at $404.50 a troy ounce; silver was 6.3 cents
to 6.8 cents higher with March at $6.038 a troy ounce.
   Futures prices for frozen concentrated orange juice dipped
sharply on the New York Cotton Exchange on expectations for a large
Florida orange crop.
   ``At this point, we're past the critical freeze period,'' said
Judith Ganes of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``There's an expectation
that prices will have to come down to stimulate demand.''
   Orange juice settled 2.45 cents to 4.65 cents lower with March at
$1.455 a pound.
   Wheat futures moved moderately higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid mounting concerns about dry weather in winter-wheat
growing areas, while corn and soybean prices finished mostly lower.
   Analysts said the rally in the wheat market was fanned by
Wednesday's 6-to-10-day outlook from the National Weather Service,
which predicted continued drier-than-normal conditions from Texas to
Nebraska.
   ``I think we'll continue to extend upward until some
precipitation is perceived there,'' said Richard Feltes, director of
commodity research with Refco Inc., a large, Chicago-based futures
brokerage firm.
   Liquidation of corn and soybean futures resumed in a continuing
reaction to the USDA's report of larger-than-expected supplies of
those commodities. Contracts for delivery of soybeans from the 1989
crop advanced as traders sold contracts for near-term delivery and
bought the new-crop contracts.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 3} cents higher with March at $4.42} a
bushel; corn was 1} cents to 3\ cents lower with March at $2.67} a
bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3} cents lower with March at $2.34 a
bushel; soybeans were 9} cents lower to 4{ cents higher with January
at $7.53 a bushel.
   Oil futures were mostly lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange
following the previous session's robust advance.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 56 cents lower to 2
cents higher with February at $19.28 a barrel; heating oil was .65
cent to 1.04 cents lower with February at 53.75 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .64 cent lower to .04 cent higher with
February at 52.10 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed in a partial recovery
from the previous day's steep losses.
   Live cattle were .32 cent lower to .18 cent higher with February
at 73 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .30 cent lower
with January at 84.37 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower
to .32 cent higher with February at 43.92 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent to .40 cent lower with February at 40.20 cents
a pound.
   Stock-index futures gained modestly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled .55 point
higher at 289.25. The contract is worth $500 a point.
</TEXT>
