<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-RJR-Divestiture     01-19 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR-Divestiture,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apartheid Foes Applaud Treasurer's Decision to Renege on Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state treasury has canceled a $110
million commitment to the company acquiring RJR Nabisco Inc. because
of Michigan's new law banning investments in business with ties to
South Africa.
   Foes of South Africa's race-segregation system said Thursday they
welcomed the decision a day earlier by State Treasurer Robert Bowman
to scrap the investment in a fund run by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co., the firm buying RJR in a takeover valued at a record $24.53
billion.
   ``I think it's a courageous decision in line with the spirit of
the legislation,'' said state Rep. Perry Bullard, one of the
sponsors of the measure banning South African-related investments.
   RJR, a food-and-tobacco giant with products ranging from Oreo
cookies to Salem cigarettes, agreed to sell itself to Kohlberg late
last year.
   Based in Atlanta, RJR is one of 95 U.S. companies with South
African involvement, according to a list Bowman compiled in
compliance with the law which took effect Jan. 1.
   The measure bans new investments of state pension funds in
companies involved in South Africa until that white-ruled nation
drops its policy of racial segregation known as apartheid or until
the companies sever their ties with the country.
   It also requires the $16 billion pension fund to sell off over
the next five years the $5 billion in investments it holds in South
African-involved companies.
   Bullard and state Sen. Virgil Smith, D-Detroit, another sponsor
of the divestiture measure, said they had talked privately to Bowman
and argued against the Kohlberg investment.
   ``My reaction is a positive one,'' Smith said. ``He did what I
wanted him to do.''
   Bowman's decision makes Michigan the second state to back out of
participating in Kohlberg's fund for the acquisition of RJR.
Massachusetts withdrew earlier.
   Kohlberg officials referred inquiries to its public relations
company, Kekst and Co., in New York, but officials there didn't
return three telephone calls seeking reaction to the Michigan
decision.
   The apartheid foes' praise of Bowman was in contrast to the
criticism they heaped on the treasurer when he decided to invest
$335 million in South African-involved companies shortly before the
divestiture law took effect Jan. 1.
   Treasury spokesman Robert Kolt said the two situations were
different because the state had completed those purchases before the
investment ban took effect.
   ``We haven't actually released the money yet (to Kohlberg), which
would take place after the law took effect so that's the problem,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890119-0350 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;LActivity     01-19 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Activity,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Withdrawals Hit Monthly Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-month record of $7.01 billion in deposits
flowed out of the nation's savings institutions in November as
increases in interest paid on deposits lagged behind the market, the
government said Thursday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates about 3,000
federally insured S&amp;Ls, said it was the seventh consecutive month of
net withdrawals, which from May through November totaled $16.4
billion.
   In the seven months from October 1987 through last April, $28.1
billion in new deposits had flowed into S&amp;Ls as investors fleeing
stock market turmoil sought the safety of federally-insured accounts.
   James Barth, chief economist at the bank board, attributed
November's deposit drain to the fact that S&amp;Ls, on average,
increased the rates offered on one-year certificates of deposit by
only 0.13 percentage points.
   That compares with gains of about 0.20 percentage points on
commercial bank deposits and mutual funds and 0.53 percentage points
on U.S. Treasury bills, he said.
   Barth said the lag in rates paid on S&amp;L deposits indicated
thrifts, at least in November, have been able to resist market
pressures driving up their cost of doing business.
   Many analysts have been worried about how well the industry would
be able to cope with rising interest rates.
   However, James Christian, chief economist of the U.S. League of
Saving Institutions, said the big deposit drain was worrisome. He
said mortgage rates have also lagged other kinds of interest rates
and speculated that S&amp;Ls are taking in fewer deposits because
they're having a harder time making a profit on mortgage lending.
   ``There's been a significant cost squeeze ... so some managers
may be saying, `Why take it in if I can't make a profit on it,'''
Christian said.
   ``I do not read this at all as a situation where the industry is
having trouble attracting deposits,'' said economist Martin Regalia
of the National Council of Savings Institutions. ``... I read this
as a situation where wise institutions are backing away.'
   He added, ``Some of the money that came out of the stock market
is going to go back into the market now that it is doing better.''
   One of regulators' goals in the recent spate of S&amp;L closings,
particularly in Texas, has been to reduce the number of unhealthy
institutions paying high interest rates on deposits because that in
turn had driven up the cost of funds for all S&amp;Ls.
   Barth said in November a California S&amp;L allowed a deposit runoff
of $1 billion at a New Jersey institution it acquired in a
government-assisted deal. He was apparently referring to First
Nationwide of San Francisco's purchase of Lincoln Federal Savings
and Loan Association of Westfield, N.J.
   Also, in line with regulators' plans, 10 thrifts in the Southwest
had $1.7 billion in deposits flow out, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
