<FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Caterpillar     01-19 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Caterpillar,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caterpillar's Profit Down 4.1 Percent in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earth-moving giant Caterpillar Inc. on
Thursday reported that its profit slipped 4.1 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1988, while soaring to record levels for the year as a
whole.
   Caterpillar's fourth-quarter earnings declined to $163 million,
or $1.61 a share, from $170 million, or $1.67 a share, in the
year-earlier quarter.
   The decline occurred despite an increase in revenue for the
quarter to $2.66 billion from $2.24 billion.
   For the 1988 fiscal year, the company said it posted the highest
sales and profit in its history, boosted by surging demand for farm
equipment.
   Annual earnings jumped 76 percent, to $616 million from $350
million the year before.
   Revenue for the year increased to $10.43 billion from $8.18
billion.
   ``The only appropriate word to describe 1988 financial results is
excellent,'' said Len Kuchan, company treasurer. ``We're very
pleased to have a record year but ... we're not popping any
champagne. We're too busy working on 1989.''
   If there's no celebration, it's due to the memory of the
company's disastrous performance after its 1981 triumph.
Caterpillar's market collapsed due to overcapacity in the industry
and fierce competition at home and abroad, and a strong dollar
further weakened its ability to compete overseas.
   A strict cost-cutting program _ including plant closings and
18,000 layoffs in the Peoria area _ helped Caterpillar survive $950
million in losses and serious labor turmoil over the next three
years.
   ``Vigilance is the word of the day. Our competition is still very
strong,'' Kuchan said.
   He attributed Caterpillar's strong 1988 performance to a huge
surge in demand for its equipment.
   ``We were running sales volumes last year that were not
anticipated until 1991,'' Kuchan said. ``We were not expecting the
kind of sales strength we experienced that evolved in every major
sales category and in every region of the world. The demand was
universal, especially on the replacement market.''
   Kuchan said Caterpillar officials were aware that much of the
company's equipment in the field was aging and in need of
replacement but never expected the demand that developed.
   Kuchan said the company remains guarded about its profits outlook
despite forecasting that 1989 would bring another record in sales.
He said earnings likely will only match the 1988 record performance
and not grow significantly, due to increasing costs in numerous
areas.
   ``Our costs are still too high. We're still not happy with the
return on shareholders' investments,'' he said. ``But 1989 still
will be a good year.''
   Caterpillar sales in the United States were $5.07 billion in
1988, an increase of 18 percent from 1987.
   Foreign sales accounted for $5.18 billion of Caterpillar's
business last year, or about 33 percent over the 1987 level.
   Caterpillar's worldwide workforce stood at 60,558 at the end of
the fourth quarter, an increase of 6,095 over employment levels for
the year-earlier period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
