<HEAD>Time Extends Stock Buyback Program, Amends Rights Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc., the subject of recent takeover
speculation, said Thursday it had extended its stock repurchase
program and amended its shareholder rights plan.
   Time said its board approved the buyback of a total 20 million
shares, up from the 10 million approved in 1986. So far, the
publishing and entertainment company said, it has bought back 8.1
million shares under the program.
   There are currently 56.7 million shares outstanding.
   Time stock rose sharply after Thursday's announcement, closing at
$110.37{ a share, up $2.37{, in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading.
   The board also approved amendments to the shareholder rights plan
that would make it more difficult to mount a hostile takeover of the
firm. Among the changes approved was a lower percentage required to
trigger some of the plan's provisions.
   Time and other publishing concerns have been named from time to
time as possible takeover targets. Time said Thursday it was not
aware of any attempt to take over the firm.
