<FIRST>u f AM-Princeton-Newport     01-19 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Princeton-Newport,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Promised Superseding Indictment Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury returned a long-promised
superseding indictment of Princeton-Newport Partners officials
Thursday, adding 33 more counts _ but no new defendants _ to the
previous racketeering and fraud charges.
   Five partners in the securities firm and a former official of the
investment banking giant Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. were charged in
August with racketeering, conspiracy, mail and wire fraud for an
alleged tax scam.
   The case marked the first time federal racketeering laws were
used against officials of a securities firm. No charges were leveled
against the firm itself, which was headquartered in Princeton, N.J.,
and Newport Beach, Calif.
   Drexel has since reached an agreement with prosecutors to plead
guilty to six felony counts and pay a record $650 million in fines
and penalties.
   Princeton-Newport announced it was liquidating last month,
blaming the indictment as well as the publicly-promised _ but
long-delayed _ superseding indictment for spooking many of the
firm's investors into withdrawing their capital.
   A week after the original August indictment, which accused the
six defendants of engaging in a racketeering conspiracy to create
illegal tax losses through phony stock deals, it was disclosed that
prosecutors planned an updated indictment, which could include new
charges of defendants.
   But the government pushed the date back to November and then
January without disclosing details. In October the partners posted a
$14 million bond because alleged illegal profits are subject to
seizure upon conviction under the federal racketeering laws.
   No new defendants were added by the superseding indictment.
   Specifically, the new indictment charged that the six engaged in
additional acts of racketeering, mail and wire fraud; committed
securities fraud in connection with public offerings by Drexel and
previously uncharged tax law violations.
   The defendants were identified as: James Sutton Reagan, 46, of
Pennington, N.J., one of Princeton-Newport's two managing general
partners; Jack Z. Rabinowitz, 42, head of the firm's financial and
accounting operations; Charles M. Zarezcki, 40, Princeton-Newport's
chief trader; and Paul A. Berkman, 42, chief trader for a
Princeton-Newport subsidiary. Rabinowitz, Zarezcki and Berkman all
are from Princeton, N.J.
   Also: Princeton-Newport's comptroller, Steven B. Smotrich, 33, of
Belle Meade, N.J.; and Bruce Lee Newberg, 31, who worked in Drexel's
high-yield bond department, based in Beverly Hills, Calif., until
early 1988.
   All six previously were charged with one count each of
racketeering and conspiracy for alleged schemes to create bogus tax
gains and losses through sham securities sales between
Princeton-Newport and Drexel, and other phony sales from Drexel to
Princeton-Newport, to avoid regulatory requirements and stock
manipulation.
   All were charged additionally with numerous counts of signing or
aiding and abetting false tax returns for the partnership in
1984-1986.
   All six face maximum penalties of 20 years in prison and $250,000
in fines if convicted of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy,
the most serious charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
