<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Raytheon     01-19 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Raytheon,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raytheon's Profit Up 8 Percent in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytheon Co. on Thursday reported an 8
percent boost in its fourth-quarter earnings, which it attributed to
increased sales and lower U.S. taxes.
   The electronics giant said its earnings in the quarter ended Dec.
31 rose to $127.3 million, or $1.92 a share, from $117.9 million, or
$1.69 a share, in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 3.4 percent, to $2.21 billion from
$2.14 billion.
   Rising profits reflected increased sales with higher operating
income and a lower federal income tax rate, Raytheon said. Earnings
per share were boosted further because there were fewer shares
outstanding, the company said.
   Much of the sales increase occurred in Raytheon's electronics
division, which accounted for 61 percent of sales in 1988, compared
with 61.9 percent in 1987. Leading electronics sales was the Missile
Systems Division, the company said.
   For all of 1988, earnings increased 10 percent _ to $489.6
million, or $7.35 a share, from $445.1 million, or $6.12 a share, in
1987.
   Revenue for 1988 rose 7 percent, to $8.19 billion from $7.66
billion the year before.
   Raytheon's earnings per share were based on the average number of
shares outstanding during the period. In 1988, the average shares
outstanding came to 66.6 million, down from 72.8 million the year
before.
   In the fourth quarter, there was an average of 66.3 million
shares outstanding; in that period in 1987 the average was 70
million shares.
   Raytheon employs 76,200 people worldwide, including 31,000 in
Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
